<SLUG> BC-KWANZA-HOLIDAY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FESTIVAL FOCUSES ON FAMILY, CULTURE
</HEADLINE>
 (Editors, changes `Mediation' in 5th graf to `Meditation') 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Jesse Hiestand  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Emphasizing family, community and culture, the
seven-day Kwanzaa celebration that began Sunday leads
African-Americans through a deeply reflective week where family and
philosophy overshadow presents.
</P>
<P>
   The few gifts that grace the traditional Kwanzaa table in
celebrants' homes are highly symbolic: books and heritage symbols
showing appreciation for ancient African culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the heart of our celebration of Kwanzaa is the practice of
pausing and turning inward as persons and a people and thinking
deeply about the wonder and obligation of being African in the
world,'' said Maulana Karenga in his annual message.
</P>
<P>
   Karenga founded the celebration in 1966 as a black studies
professor at California State University, Long Beach. The festival
has grown in popularity and is now celebrated by more than 28
million people around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Kwanzaa ends Jan. 1 with a feast on the Day of Meditation, a
period of self-questioning that ideally should last throughout the
coming year, which according to the ancient Egyptian calendar is
the year 6240, according to Karenga.
</P>
<P>
   Though a relatively new cultural celebration, Kwanzaa draws on
ancient winter agricultural festivals marking the harvesting of
crops and sharing of good fortune.
</P>
<P>
   A modern-day emphasis on the environment preserves that legacy,
with some Kwanzaa observers using the occasion to clean up their
neighborhoods, parks or beaches, said Chimbuko Tembo of Us, the
nonprofit African-American cultural center which Karenga chairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a time we stop and take particular appreciation for all
the beauty we have around us in terms of creation and other
people,'' Tembo said. ``It's not a religious holiday, so people who
are followers of traditional African religions ... black Jews or
Muslims can all come together around our African-ness.''
</P>
<P>
   Kwanzaa, which means ``first fruits'' in Swahili, honors seven
principles: unity, self-determination, collective work and
responsibility, cooperative economics, purpose, creativity and
faith.
</P>
<P>
   Families mark the occasion with five activities, including
reinforcing their bonds, commemorating the past, recommitting to
cultural ideals and celebrating the good life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody of goodwill can certainly appreciate the aspects of
Kwanzaa,'' Tembo said.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional symbols of Kwanzaa are set up on a table that is
first covered with a straw mat symbolizing the foundations of
African culture.
</P>
<P>
   Fruits and vegetables represent crops and the rewards of
collective labor, she said.
</P>
<P>
   A candleholder symbolizes people who continue to live in Africa
and the seven candles represent the seven principles. Ears of corn
are laid out to symbolize children, and a unity cup honoring
ancestors is used to pour libations. Last, the table contains gifts
of books and heritage symbols.
</P>
<P>
   Kwanzaa, an African-American cultural celebration that runs from
Dec. 26 through Jan. 1, honors one of the following seven
principles, translated from Swahili, each night, with the lighting
of a candle:
</P>
<P>
   Umoja _ unity
</P>
<P>
   Kujichagulia _ self-determination
</P>
<P>
   Ujima _ collective work and responsibility
</P>
<P>
   Ujamaa _ cooperative economics
</P>
<P>
   Nia _ purpose
</P>
<P>
   Kuumba _ creativity
</P>
<P>
   Imani _ faith
</P>
<P>
   X X X  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
