<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 00:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9577 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-JAGUARS-TITANS-HN     12-27 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JAGUARS-TITANS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ For only the third time in franchise history,
the Tennessee Titans proved they are legitimate Super Bowl
contenders with the talent, confidence and momentum to become
champions.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Titans won't know until the playoffs if they can succeed
where the Houston Oilers failed during the Luv Ya Blue and
run-and-shoot eras, but if Sunday's powerful performance against
Jacksonville was an indication, Tennessee could be a team of
destiny.
</P>
<P>
   A three-point underdog in their home stadium, the Titans
annihilated the Jaguars 41-14 to sweep their AFC Central series and
improve their record to 12-3 entering the last game at Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans have defeated Jacksonville, the AFC's best team,
twice. And they beat St. Louis, the best team in the NFC.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said we had to take the next step, and we did, but we've
still got a long way to go to accomplish our goal,'' Titans coach
Jeff Fisher said. ``As a coach, you wish all games were like this,
but you know most of them aren't. It was a total team effort
against the best team in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Steve McNair was the Titan most responsible for
Sunday's domination of the team that entered the game with the
NFL's best record and No. 2 defense. Healthy for the first time
since the opening game, McNair threw a career-high five touchdown
passes _ one fewer than his season total _ and embarrassed the
league's second-ranked pass defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our defense was very poor,'' Jaguars coach Tom Coughlin said.
``We had no pass rush. We didn't stop the run. He was very much
under control, and he did what he wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair, who had been hampered by an ankle injury, completed 23
of 33 passes for 291 yards and touchdowns to tight end Mike Roan
(four yards), tight end Jackie Harris (62), receiver Yancey Thigpen
(two), receiver Isaac Byrd (65) and receiver Kevin Dyson (13).
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you get beat like this, it's embarrassing,'' Jaguars
offensive tackle Tony Boselli said. ``They answered the bell and
beat us to the punch. They just blew us out.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair didn't throw an interception, and he was not sacked by a
defense that entered the game leading the NFL in sacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just the tip of the iceberg for Steve,'' said running
back Eddie George, who contributed 102 yards rushing to the
season-high 476-yard performance. ``He couldn't have had a better
day against a great defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve was phenomenal after experiencing so much media
scrutiny. He never lost his composure, and I think you'll see him
have more days like this.''
</P>
<P>
   The Titans watched their quarterback put the ``Air'' back in
McNair against a defense that had been dubbed ``Dare McNair''
because the strategy was designed to stop the run and force him to
throw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't offended by that strategy, but it did present more of
a challenge,'' said McNair, who underwent back surgery early in the
season and suffered a badly sprained ankle when he returned. ``A
lot of teams have been daring us to throw the ball, and we haven't
been successful. Our passing game has struggled a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Until Sunday, when the Titans improved their AFC Central record
to 8-1.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee's defense knocked out quarterback Mark Brunell and
limited the Jaguars to 237 yards. The Jaguars trailed 17-7 when
Brunell left the game late in the second quarter with a sprained
medial collateral ligament in his left knee. He will undergo a
magnetic resonance imaging test to determine the extent of the
damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never want to see a player get hurt, but that did make a
difference in the second half,'' Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   Brunell was 4-of-11 for 95 yards with an interception. Jay
Fiedler finished 8-of-22 for 101 yards with two interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Titans cornerback Samari Rolle intercepted three passes. The
Titans registered four sacks, giving them 53, breaking the team
record of 52 set in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee limited Jacksonville to 65 yards rushing, including 44
by Fred Taylor, who averaged 2.8 yards on 16 carries.
</P>
<P>
   ``By getting a big lead, we made them a one-dimensional
offense,'' Fisher said. ``When we got them down 24-7 at the half,
they couldn't give the ball to Taylor like they wanted because they
were forced to throw.''
</P>
<P>
   Adelphia Coliseum has become an impenetrable fortress for the
Titans, who finished the regular season 8-0 at home for the first
time in franchise history. A record crowd of 66,641 watched them
tie a franchise record with 12 victories.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans could finish 13-3 and not win the division, even
though they beat Jacksonville twice.
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars, who haven't beaten a team with a winning record,
will win the AFC Central with a 14-2 record if they defeat
Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   It's a long shot, but the Titans still have a chance to win the
AFC Central for the first time since 1993 and earn the home-field
advantage throughout the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   If the Titans win at Pittsburgh, the Bengals win at Jacksonville
and the Colts lose at Buffalo, Tennessee will win the division and
secure the home-field advantage. Realistically, the Titans will
finish as the wild-card team with the best record and host a
first-round game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any explanations for it,'' Coughlin said.
``Obviously, one team came to play and the other didn't. We were
physically handled on both fronts. We never challenged them, and
the game was never in doubt, and I'm very disappointed about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
