<P>
   BURUNDI-RELOCATION (Bujumbura, Burundi) _ It would be hard to
name a place in the world where the forced relocation of a third of
a million people would not spark major international protest. But
this has not been so for Burundi, where in the last three months
the government has herded 350,000 people from their homes into
grubby camps. The government calls the camps a last resort to end a
series of guerrilla attacks. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Locator map
has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-TV-SHEEPDOG (London) _ If the BBC has its way, millions
of Britons will spend Monday evening watching a special edition of
``One Man And His Dog,'' a program in which a sheep running in the
wrong direction qualifies as high drama. Monday's episode is a
crucial test for ``One Man and His Dog,'' which was threatened with
cancellation last winter. But the threat caused such an uproar that
the BBC finally agreed to broadcast a special over Christmas. By
Sarah Lyall.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT6) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-PRESIDENT (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ Two months after
taking office, Indonesia's new president, Abdurrahman Wahid, seems
to be having a disconcertingly good time. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
