<P>
   SPEEDING-DRIVERS (Hartford, Conn.) _ Early last week, Mathew
Hennessy, mild-mannered computer programmer, was driving toward
Manhattan at 100 mph. He is one of a growing number of American
drivers who, according to traffic experts, are pushing highway
speeds to new heights. Steering bigger and more powerful cars and
exploiting increasingly lax police enforcement, more drivers than
ever are treating speed limits as suggestions, experts say. By Paul
Zielbauer.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT13) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   NEWEST-IMMIGRANTS (Bridgewater, N.J.) _ By leapfrogging to the
most desirable suburbs, many Asian immigrants are upending
stereotypes about new immigrants being poor and invisible, tethered
to ethnic neighborhoods, desperate to wriggle out of the city.
Instead, these newcomers are younger and more economically diverse,
equipped with graduate degrees and work visas, gifted in science
and technology. By David W. Chen.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT15,16,17,18,19[ have been sent to NYT photo
clients. Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CATHOLIC-UNIVERSITIES (Washington) _ When the nation's Roman
Catholic bishops voted in November to tie Catholic universities
more closely to the church, they left institutions like Georgetown
University with a lingering question. What will it mean for
Catholic theologians, teaching in Catholic universities, to have to
apply to their local bishop for a certification that they are
teaching ``authentic'' doctrine, a requirement laid out in the
document the bishops approved? By Gustav Niebuhr. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-BASE (Irvine, Calif.) _ Irvine is the United States'
largest master-planned community, a city with just the right number
of curves in its roads, just the right mix of single-family and
multiple-family housing, auto dealers and churches, carved out of
strawberry and tomato fields on a billiard-table-smooth parcel of
land. It is as calm as Los Angeles, the messy metropolis just to
the north, is tumultuous. One of Irvine's few long-term irritants
had been the adjacent and enormous El Toro Marine Corps Air
Station, where F-18s were screaming reminders of a troubled outside
world that many people had moved here to avoid. By James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT22) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   VATICAN-RADIOLINK (New York) _ About midnight on New Year's Eve,
the voice of Daisy Lopez _ Bronx teen-ager, Cathedral High School
student and loyal parishioner of St. Brendan's Church _ will travel
through telephone lines, across thousands of miles, and reverberate
in the Vatican. Some 18 relatives and hundreds of other
parishioners will be with her at St. Brendan's, in the Norwood
section of the Bronx, to celebrate not just the advent of a new
millennium, but a singular honor for their church. St. Brendan's
was the only Roman Catholic church in America to be chosen for a
24-hour, 24-country radio link to the Vatican. By Amy Waldman.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT25) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
