<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991227.0006 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9581 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GEN-HOUSTON-CENTURY-H     12-27 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-HOUSTON-CENTURY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAYNE CUSTRED  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
IT'S hard to imagine just where the time went. Without a single
major professional team before 1960, Houston has a busy, thriving
sports scene at the end of the century.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Building the Astrodome and changing the face of baseball took a
few years. Developing championship basketball teams took some more
time, as did the maturation of some of the greatest individual
athletes in a host of sports.
</P>
<P>
   But it seems like just yesterday that George Foreman was a buff
young man, getting ready for his first bout, and A.J. Foyt was
sliding behind the wheel of a race car for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Records were set, championships won, careers started and ended,
and Houston athletics continued to grow and change and prosper. And
now the future beckons, full of promise of things even grander and
greater for Houston sports fans.
</P>
<P>
   So with the new millennium upon us, here's a look back at 10 of
the Houston area's greatest sports memories and personalities.
</P>
<P>
   Inside and Artificial
</P>
<P>
   Nothing changed baseball more than the invention of AstroTurf
and the construction of the Astrodome, the world's first domed
stadium. Suddenly, neither rain nor snow nor sleet nor cold would
affect a baseball (or football) game, and plastic turf would give
athletes everywhere a level playing field. The brainchild of Judge
Roy Hofheinz, the ``Eighth Wonder of the World'' became an
attraction in its own right, and gave a new home to Houston's
major-league baseball team, the Astros. Although the Astrodome was
met with skepticism, it has become the model for domed stadiums
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Believe It
</P>
<P>
   Hakeem Olajuwon had long provided the thrill in Houston
basketball, first at the University of Houston and then for the
Rockets. But it wasn't until 1994 that the Dream would come true
for Houston basketball fans. Under the guidance of former Rockets
player Rudy Tomjanovich and led by an unstoppable Olajuwon, the
Rockets won back-to-back NBA titles in 1994 and 1995. In 1995, with
the midseason addition of Olajuwon's former UH teammate Clyde
Drexler, the Rockets swept the Orlando Magic in one of the dominant
performances in the history of the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Luv Ya Blue
</P>
<P>
   It began when the Oilers drafted running back Earl Campbell, who
ushered in Houston's love affair with its professional football
team that reached a fever pitch in the late 1970s and early 1980s.
Campbell thundered his way into the hearts of Houston fans and
stayed there, even though the Oilers never made it to the Super
Bowl. But by the early 1990s, the glow had worn off. At the 1993
Buffalo Bills-Oilers wild-card playoff game, the Oilers led 35-3
just minutes into the second half, but the Bills rallied for the
greatest comeback in NFL history, eventually winning 41-38 in
overtime. Four years later, owner Bud Adams would move the club to
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   No One Better
</P>
<P>
   The legend of Carl Lewis was born when he first stepped onto the
track at UH under the watchful eyes of coach Tom Tellez. An amazing
nine Olympic gold medals later, Lewis is simply the greatest track
and field athlete of all time. Beginning in 1981, Lewis won 65
consecutive long-jump titles, going 10 years without losing. Other
Houstonians have joined Lewis in bringing home Olympic gold,
including Mary Lou Retton in gymnastics and Tara Lipinski in figure
skating.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Upset
</P>
<P>
   It was on the floor of the Astrodome on Jan. 20, 1968, where a
college basketball game unlike any other ever seen was played
between No. 1-ranked UCLA and No. 2 Houston. UCLA, coached by the
legendary John Wooden, was known for its fast-break offense and
pressure defense. But the Cougars were ready to run as well, and
the game marked the emergence of the big-time college hoops we know
today. Elvin Hayes and UH beat UCLA 71-69.
</P>
<P>
   Oh So Close
</P>
<P>
   It was set up perfectly for the Astros to make their first trip
to the World Series. Leading the New York Mets 3-0 in Game 6 of the
1986 National League Championship Series, all the Astros had to do
was get three outs and the series would go to a seventh game. And
the Astros liked their chances with Cy Young Award winner Mike
Scott, who had beaten the Mets twice in the series, ready to pitch
that game. But the Mets rallied to send Game 6 into extra innings
and, despite a dramatic home run by Billy Hatcher in the 14th
inning, New York prevailed 7-6 in 16 innings to win the series. It
was one of the best playoff games in baseball history but a
frustrating result for a franchise that to this day has not won a
playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   Great George
</P>
<P>
   He was the ordained minister turned heavyweight champion who
captured the hearts of sports fans with his return to the top at
age 45. Foreman, the family man with the big appetite for
cheeseburgers, returned to the ring some 40 pounds heavier than his
original fighting weight. But that didn't slow him Nov. 5, 1994,
when he knocked out Michael Moorer, becoming the oldest man to win
a heavyweight crown in history. Twenty years after losing his title
to Muhammad Ali, Foreman was named Male Athlete of the Year. He
defended his title a year later against 26-year-old Axel Schulz,
then gave up the crown after refusing a rematch.
</P>
<P>
   The A.J. Way
</P>
<P>
   At the tender age of 26, the tough-talking Texan with the quick
temper was well on his way to making auto racing a mainstream
sport. He won his first Indianapolis 500 in 1961 and would take the
checkered flag at Indy a record three more times. In 1972, he added
the Daytona 500 to his list, running over anyone who got in his
way. The absolute need to finish first drove Foyt, who won his
fifth overall United States Auto Club crown in 1967 and was the
co-driver of the winning car in Europe's 24 Hours of Le Mans.
Refusing to give in to the wave of new technology sweeping the
sport, Foyt nevertheless continued to find ways to win until he
retired in 1993 to oversee a racing ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Running Wild
</P>
<P>
   It was the era of Phi Slama Jama, when Olajuwon and Drexler
joined forces to make University of Houston basketball the hottest
game in town. Their wide-open, high-scoring offense typified the
new athleticism of college hoops, thrilling fans in the process.
The Cougars dominated, charging to the Final Four three times and
to the final in 1983 and 1984. But Houston never brought home an
NCAA title _ the 1983 loss to North Carolina State on a shot at the
buzzer was especially hard to take _ but Phi Slama Jama made it
worth watching, win or lose.
</P>
<P>
   Shining Bright
</P>
<P>
   The birth of the WNBA brought a new team to Houston basketball,
and with the Comets it was nothing but championship basketball. In
the three years the league has been in existence, the Comets have
won the title each time. Led by two-time Most Valuable Player
Cynthia Cooper, the Comets have set the standard for all WNBA teams
with their gutsy play. Never was that more evident than in the 1999
season, when the Comets had to pull together after point guard Kim
Perrot, who had helped take them to two titles, succumbed to
cancer. This time around, Perrot's inspiration led the way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-99 0106EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
