u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BILLS-BO     12-27 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BILLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLOWN FIELD GOALS LEAVE PATRIOTS WIND-CHILLED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ It was garbage time in the most frustrating
of seasons. Nothing really mattered for the Patriots except pride,
playing the role of the spoiler, and finishing the season with a
winning record.
</P>
<P>
   It appears maintaining pride still may be possible, but playing
the spoiler and having a winning record no longer are possible
following a 13-10 overtime loss to the Buffalo Bills Sunday. It
dropped the Patriots to 7-8, their first sub-.500 mark since they
were 0-2 at the start of the 1996 season.
</P>
<P>
   The defense played very well, the offense (Drew Bledsoe's 101
passing yards were the worst in a game he started and finished
since his rookie season) sputtered, and Adam Vinatieri missed
another field goal(s) that could have won a game.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots played without wide receiver Terry Glenn, who
missed his first game of the season with the flu.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots fans became even more frustrated when Steve Christie
kicked a 23-yard field goal with 1:48 remaining in overtime, giving
the 10-5 Bills' playoff hopes life.
</P>
<P>
   Vinatieri had missed a 33-yarder for the win with six seconds
remaining in the game, a ball he badly mis-kicked. His attempt to
win the game in OT from 44 yards also fell short into a tough wind.
Vinatieri, who had made 22 of 26 field goals this season, was 1 for
4 on the day, and the final kicks were reminiscent of his 32-yarder
that hit the upright in Kansas City, which would have given the
Patriots the win and perhaps changed their disappointing season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I didn't hit it well,'' said Vinatieri of the missed
chip shot in regulation. ``I feel like I toed it a little. I knew I
didn't hit it very good.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots won the OT toss and chose to take the ball, but
they were going against the wind. Coach Pete Carroll said ``the
wind had died down a bit. It was definitely a consideration, but we
felt that Troy (Brown) was having a great day returning the ball
and we thought we could get good field position.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots had a chance to win it late in the fourth quarter
when Bledsoe took a page out of the Doug Flutie book, scampering
for a 25-yard gain, the longest run of his career, to the Bills 17.
</P>
<P>
   New England tried centering the ball with a couple of runs up
the middle by Terry Allen, and let the clock run down to six
seconds before Vinatieri attempted what looked like a sure winner.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of Vinatieri's teammates were sympathetic, even given
the wind. Certainly not defensive end Willie McGinest.
</P>
<P>
   ``What elements?'' said McGinest. ``That's his job. It's Adam's
job to make those field goals. I wished he would have made them. We
all had to play in the elements. The defense's job is to stop them.
I guess 13 points was too many today. I can only speak for myself,
but everyone is responsible for what they do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to lose anything. It's something I'll never get used
to. I hope guys from this team remember this feeling. That's the
key. If guys think this is OK, we've got to get them out of here.
Guys who are here who are fighters, those are the guys I want to
play with.''
</P>
<P>
   While the defense did a fine job containing Flutie, it did allow
168 yards on the ground and 206 in the air. The Patriots had one of
their better days rushing as Allen gained 126 yards on 27 carries
(the Patriots had a season-high 158 yards in all) and went on a
14-yard touchdown run with 12:15 left in the fourth quarter. That
came after Chad Eaton had forced a fumble of running back Jonathan
Linton, recovered it, and ran it 30 yards before being pulled down
by Flutie at the 14. Allen busted up the middle virtually untouched
to give the Patriots a 10-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   There was some question whether Linton actually had fumbled, or
whether Eaton was down on the spot. The play was reviewed and the
call was upheld by referee Mike Carey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the runner down with his elbow. The ball was not visible
until he rolled over and then the ball was visible on his chest,''
said Carey.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that the replay didn't show anyone touching Eaton
until Flutie tackled him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I picked it up, I knew somebody had to touch me,'' said
Eaton. When told that it was Flutie who had tackled him, he said,
``Don't remind me of that.''
</P>
<P>
   In OT, the Patriots took control at their 33 and a couple of big
plays _ a 20-yard pass to Ben Coates and a 12-yard run by Allen _
got the ball to the Bills 31. An offside penalty on Buffalo got it
to the 26, from where Vinatieri's 44-yarder died just before the
goal post.
</P>
<P>
   The Bills took over at their 34 and drove to the Patriots 19
when Eric Moulds, after catching a 19-yard pass from Flutie, took a
helmet hit to the midsection by free safety Tony George, who had
replaced the injured Chris Carter (hamstring), and fumbled. Tedy
Bruschi recovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tebucky (Jones) was in coverage, he slipped, and I looked back
to see Flutie eyeing the ball to Moulds,'' said George. ``I made my
break. He caught it but I put my hat on the ball and got it
loose.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots, who were held to a season-low 225 total net yards,
did nothing with that break.
</P>
<P>
   The Bills took control at their 42 and Flutie drove them.
Thurman Thomas broke their back with a 9-yard run to the New
England 6, from where the Bills kicked the winner.
</P>
<P>
   The teams played to a 3-3 tie in a boring first half marked by
offensive struggles. Vinatieri missed a 44-yarder in the first
quarter after a decent drive from the Patriots 31 to the Bills 26.
On the Bills' first possession, Christie kicked a 39-yarder to make
it 3-0. Vinatieri nailed a 38-yarder right before the end of the
half after the Patriots drove from their 35 to the Bills 15, the
big play a 29-yard pass from Bledsoe to Harold Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Patriots can hold on to the fact that they didn't
quit, what they don't have this morning is a winning record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully that affects a lot of guys,'' said McGinest. ``We're
not going out losing. We have to be at least 8-8. I don't think
we're surrounded by losers here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-99 0108EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
