<DOCNO> NYT19991227.0008 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9583 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GEN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     12-27 1375
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DALE ROBERTSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
IN less than a week, the new millennium is upon us. Although a lot
can happen in five days, it's unlikely anything of grand
consequence will, seeing as how the Rockets are lottery-bound, the
Astros have nobody left to trade and our as-of-yet unnamed NFL team
is roughly 1,000 days from its first kickoff.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But if Charles Barkley returns to play on one leg, or the Astros
decide Jeff Bagwell is expendable, too, I reserve the right to
amend the following, a final accounting, if you will, of the most
wonderful and the cruelest things to have occurred on the local
sports scene since the Brothers Allen made their way up Buffalo
Bayou some 164 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the smiley-face category, two lists follow. Why?
Because there are two distinct kinds of warm fuzzies to be
recognized from Houston's amazingly rich and storied past: those
that only made us shout, ``Yippee!'' and those that actually
altered the course of history, adding fresh brush strokes to
jockdom's Big Picture.
</P>
<P>
   Our 10 most significant sports moments:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1. Bud Adams and Lamar Hunt create the AFL  &LR; _ From that day
forward, Houston was officially a ``big-league'' city, but the real
importance of the event was that it ushered in the modern, golden
era of pro football, which is now our true national pastime. With
the advent of the American Football League, players' salary
escalation began, TV's role in the game mushroomed and the eventual
merging of the two leagues created the ultimate game, the Super
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2. The construction of the Astrodome  &LR; _ The ``Eighth Wonder of
the World'' became the planet's most famous, fabulous and
revolutionary sports venue. Suddenly, weather was removed from the
equation even in a reclaimed swamp like Houston.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 3. The invention of AstroTurf &LR;  _ Necessity was the mother of
invention, unfortunately. Outfielders couldn't see fly balls in the
Dome's blinding glare, and painting the glass panes killed the
grass. Plastic turf, odious though it might be in these retro
times, soon ``sprouted'' up everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 4. Warren McVea's receiving a football scholarship from the
University of Houston &LR;  _ A century after the Civil War, white kids
and a black kid would be teammates on a college football team in
Texas. All the dire, hateful predictions notwithstanding, the earth
did not cleave under the Cougars' cleats. Elvin Hayes and Don
Chaney soon joined the basketball program, and Houston entered the
20th century.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 5. The UH-UCLA basketball game &LR;  _ The Dome floor that night was
ground zero, the place where college hoops as we know the behemoth
today began. The Cougars' upset win was a bonus.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 6. The King-Riggs tennis match &LR;  _ Despite the many silly
trappings that surrounded Bobby Riggs' biggest hustle, Billie Jean
King's victory launched the tennis boom and changed the way the
world perceived women athletes. Such attitude adjustment shouldn't
have been necessary, of course, but it was.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 7. The Astros sign Nolan Ryan to a $1 million salary &LR;  _
Speaking of ground zero
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 8. The Carl Lewis-Tom Tellez partnership &LR;  _ Perhaps Carl Lewis
would have evolved into the greatest Olympic athlete of the century
no matter who coached him, but King Carl's decision to run for
Tellez at UH was where his glorious sprint, and leap, to global
icon status began.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 9. The birth of the Virginia Slims Tour at Houston Racquet
Club &LR;  _ Promoters laughed at Houston's Gladys Heldman when she
tried to convince them women should be paid to play tennis, so
Heldman started her own tour. Footnote: Upon her retirement this
year, Steffi Graf's career prize money had blown past $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 10. The '96 referendum  &LR; _ By approving the plan to fund new
baseball and football stadiums, voters kept the Astros in Houston,
made possible the NFL's return and, yes, moved Houston back to the
cutting edge in the sports facilities game. Name another city that
will possess two retractable-roof venues.
</P>
<P>
   Our 10 most satisfying sports moments:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1. The Rockets' first NBA title  &LR; _ Any arguments?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2. The Rockets' second NBA title &LR;  _ Nothing beats winning.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 3. The Rockets draft Hakeem Olajuwon  &LR; _ See above.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 4. The Oilers draft Earl Campbell  &LR; _ Campbell never got the
Oilers to the Super Bowl (those pesky Steelers kept getting in the
way), but he did enough to become the most beloved local jock hero
ever, Hakeem's own towering presence notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 5. Houston joins the National League  &LR; _ The Oilers predated the
Astros, but in those days you weren't really and truly a
major-league town until you had a major-league baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 6. Bob McNair brings the NFL back to Houston &LR;  _ And bless him
for it, given the $700 million price tag. Go, Bobcats!
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 7. Rice's 10-1 season in 1949  &LR; _ The Owls finished fifth in the
national rankings and whipped North Carolina in the Cotton Bowl.
Soon thereafter, a giant stadium worthy of Jess Neely's deserving
champions rose on the vacant land west of the campus.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 8. The Astros finally make the playoffs &LR;  _ After 18 also-ran
seasons, a pennant of some kind would finally hang from the Dome's
famous rafters.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 9. The Oilers beat the Steelers on  &LR; Monday Night Football _
With the Dome SRO and stuffed with pompoms, Luv Ya Blue was born on
this rowdy December night in 1979. No regular-season victory by any
of our teams felt better than this one did.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 10. The Comets' third WNBA title  &LR; _ First, they had to pay
their final respects to Kim Perrot, the scrappy point guard who had
helped lead them to the two previous championships. That is
overcoming adversity.
</P>
<P>
   Our 10 worst sports moments:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1. Buffalo 41, Houston 38  &LR; _ Hands down, the calamity to end
all calamities, final score-wise. By blowing a 35-3 lead, the
Oilers lost their best chance to go to the Super Bowl and thus
began the inexorable series of events that led Adams to take the
franchise to Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2. The Oilers leave town  &LR; _ It wouldn't have happened if the
aforementioned hadn't happened.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 3. Nolan Ryan signs with the Rangers  &LR; _ The disgust with John
McMullen for letting Ryan go launched a downward spiral in local
baseball interest that almost drove the Astros out of Houston, too.
Nolie's entering the Hall of Fame wearing a Rangers cap was the
final shot to our heart.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 4. North Carolina State upsets UH  &LR; _ Arguably the biggest
shocker in the history of college basketball's championship game.
The vastly superior Cougars choked up, slowed down and started
missing free throws, and with a lucky bucket at the finish, N.C.
State turned the late Jimmy Valvano into a crazy man. The loss
robbed Guy Lewis of his rightful place in the Basketball Hall of
Fame.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 5. Bum Phillips' firing  &LR; _ On New Year's Eve 1980, Adams dumped
the beloved folksy coach who had presided over Luv Ya Blue. In the
end, though, it would be only the second-worst thing he did to the
city.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 6. The Astros' 16-inning loss to the Mets  &LR; _ This most
spectacular of games was the closest the Astros have been to the
World Series. With the almost unhittable Mike Scott, of whom the
Mets stood terrified, set to start Game 7 of the National League
Championship Series, the Astros were a virtual lock to win the NL
pennant.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 7. Kim Perrot's death &LR;  _ Quite simply the most heartbreaking
sports story ever to unfold in our midst.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 8. Don Wilson's death  &LR; _ The no-hit pitcher was at the top of
his game when he died of carbon monoxide poisoning in his garage.
We still don't know why it happened.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 9. James Rodney Richards' stroke  &LR; _ Another superstar pitcher
cut down in his prime, although at least he survived.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 10. Tie: Astros lose to Padres; Oilers lose to Chiefs  &LR; _ With
Randy Johnson and a murderers' row batting order, the '98 Astros
were the best team in franchise history and should have blown away
the eventual NL champions. The '93 Oilers had won a
franchise-record 11 games in a row but, in a mini-repeat of the
Buffalo disaster, let Joe Montana overtake them in the fourth
quarter. The only reason the poor Bills could lose four consecutive
Super Bowls is because the Oilers gave them two free passes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
