<HEADER>
A9584 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS     12-27 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS' VINATIERI LEFT WITH COLD FEET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The suspended ceiling above his locker was
askew, one white panel hanging over his head like the sword of
Damocles. It seemed fitting to be dangling there because the roof
had just fallen in on Adam Vinatieri.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' usually reliable kicker had just missed three
field goals in a 3-point loss, one a 33-yard chip shot from
straight on with six seconds left in regulation that he simply
mis-hit and a 44-yarder in overtime that the God of the Winds blew
down to the ground even though it was well-stroked.
</P>
<P>
   The same thing had happened in the first quarter when he hit
another 44-yarder that took off like it intended to fly into the
stands but went down like a duck suddenly hit by buckshot just
before it reached the goal post. They were three kicks that
typified this sad Patriot season. Three kicks that, like the team
itself, didn't quite make it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put me in a dome and I'm 3 for 4 today but we're not in a
dome, we're in Foxborough,'' Vinatieri said sadly after those
misses led to the Patriots' 13-10 loss to the Buffalo Bills Sunday,
their sixth loss in the last seven weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the short one, I didn't hit it at all. It was like I left
the club open. I toed it a little and it went right. I was hoping
it was short enough that it wouldn't matter, but it did.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other two I felt I hit pretty good but Mother Nature beat
me there. Both of them looked good. They felt good. But they fell
short. We knew we had an 8- to 10-yard wind going there. If we'd
been going in the other direction it might have gone 10 yards
farther.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Patriots were going in the wrong direction Sunday, which
is the same direction they've been headed since their return from
the bye week oh so long ago, a week that turned into the bye-bye
week because they haven't been back since.
</P>
<P>
   Not back into the game. Not back into the playoffs. Not back
into anything but a U-Haul in seven more days.
</P>
<P>
   That's where most of them will have their possessions packed by
Sunday, when they end a meaningless season against the Baltimore
Ravens on this same field in a meaningless game between two
meaningless teams. End it without so much as a cameo appearance in
the playoffs for the first time since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   End it, more than likley, not with a bang but a whimper, the
same way things ended Sunday after Vinatieri's foot and the winter
winds conspired to make them losers again.
</P>
<P>
   It was Drew Bledsoe's worst passing day since his rookie year.
It was the offense's worst day this season, which includes more
than a few other awful days. And it was amiable Vinatieri's worst
day in a long time, a day in which wind, weather, and his own foot
conspired against him and his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   But when you are 7-8 and going nowhere, not everyone wants to
hear about the weather. They don't want to hear that the flu kept
Terry Glenn home in bed while others played hurt and they don't
want to hear that the wind was blowing from the southwest at 23
miles per hour, either. What they wanted to hear was what they did
not hear with two seconds left in regulation and Vinatieri stroking
what they believed so fervently would be a victory kick.
</P>
<P>
   They wanted to hear the crowd roar. Instead, all they heard was
the wind roar and then go out of their sails completely.
</P>
<P>
   ``What elements?'' an angry Willie McGinest snapped when asked
if he felt badly for his teammate's fate. ``That's his job. It's
Adam's job to make those field goals. I wished he would have made
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all had to play in the elements. The defense's job is to
stop them. I guess 13 points was too many today. I can only speak
for myself, but everyone is responsible for what they do.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, make the kick. Across the room, Vinatieri didn't
disagree.
</P>
<P>
   ``That one at the end of the fourth quarter was probably the
worst kick of my life,'' Vinatieri said of the errant 33-yarder.
``When I hit it, I knew I didn't hit it very well. I felt I crushed
the other two, but we knew about 43, 44 yards was by far the range.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this business you have to have a real short memory but this
is pretty disheartening. When I hit the one in overtime it felt for
sure like I had it but then I saw the ball starting to slow down
and then it just dipped down in front of the goal post and that was
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 33-yarder? You yank it and you know, `Wow, that's all me.'
The other two were more the elements but I don't know if there's an
easy miss. The kick falls short, it doesn't make it any easier
because the wind did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not any easier for Adam Vinatieri. Not any easier for Willie
McGinest. Not any easier for anyone in Foxborough, including the
man who seemed to move a foot closer to his final appearance there
when Vinatieri's kicks came up a foot short.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had two great chances to win the game,'' said beleaguered
coach Pete Carroll. ``Maybe one great chance and one hope with that
last kick. He kicks a great kick we win the game and we go home.
That was the thinking there. You're probably asking what would make
you think he could do that after missing the one before but, hey,
you never know. Adam's done a lot of good things for us, so we
wanted to give him a chance to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been killing the ball in practice the last few weeks. The
last kick, he pounded that kick, but it just wasn't enough. There
was just too much wind. Unfortunately, it didn't work out.''
</P>
<P>
   Like a lot of things in Foxborough these days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
