</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOSTON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIBLE GOT THE BOOK ON BC OFFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
 COLLEGE-BIBLE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ At first, Dana Bible didn't have the slightest idea who
would be called upon to execute the offense he planned to install
at Boston College, let alone what to call it. So, when the Eagles'
new offensive coordinator met with reporters for the first time
during BC's Media Day in August, Bible was peppered with questions
about the scheme he planned to implement.
</P>
<P>
   Would it be run-oriented? Run-and-shoot? Pro-style? Multiple?
Just what, exactly?
</P>
<P>
   Bible smiled politely. He tried to describe it, but stopped in
midsentence and shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know yet,'' he said. ``We're just going to try
and do the things that best suit the strengths of our personnel.''
</P>
<P>
   What those strengths were, Bible was not prepared to say at the
time. Nor was he prepared to put a name on his offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because it might not have been that,'' he said recently,
laughing at the recollection. ``I was as candid as I could be when
I said that we were going to play to the strengths of our players.
But we needed time to figure out what (they were). Really, there
were still seven or eight guys out there who really hadn't been the
guys. So who knew?''
</P>
<P>
   That much Bible understood when he inherited an offense that
lost eight starters from a 4-7 team, including three players who
went on to the NFL _ center Damien Woody, a first-round pick (No.
17 overall) by the Patriots; All-America running back Mike Cloud, a
second-round pick (No. 54 overall) by the Kansas City Chiefs; and
guard Doug Brzezinski, a third-round pick (No. 64) by the
Philadelphia Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early on, it was a work in progress,'' Bible said. ``We were
just trying to be solid, and as we got our feet under us, we
started to expand. That's the best way to describe it. If you look
at the kids who made up the offense, we weren't young, but we were
green with the upperclassmen because the class before had been very
talented and very productive and (had) very good players.''
</P>
<P>
   Bible put together an offense that was far from a finished work,
much less a masterpiece. He employed some creative brush strokes:
showing a few new wrinkles and virtually no tendencies in the first
three quarters against Miami, installing the option against
option-oriented Syracuse, and rallying from a 14-0 deficit in a
31-29 victory at Notre Dame with some bold moves that took the
fight right out of the Irish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he does an excellent job of game-planning each week,''
said junior quarterback Tim Hasselbeck. ``I don't know of a game
where we have seen a look that he's not prepared us for, by
watching film or in practice. We're never really guessing `What the
heck are they doing?' He does a great job of getting us ready each
week. We always do something different, but at the same time it's
something where we're still using the strengths of people on our
football team or on our offense, and that's a tribute to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, in the opener against Baylor, Bible admitted, ``In all my
career and in all my years of coaching, it was the very least that
I knew what we were going to do going into a season. I always look
for constants _ players or schemes or things that I know we can do,
something to hang your hat on. But I didn't know very much going
into the season.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until the emergence of Hasselbeck as the starting QB,
Cedric Washington as a 1,000-yard rusher, wide receiver Dedrick
DeWalt as the deep threat, and tight end Bryan Arndt as a steely
addition to the passing game that Bible was able to turn to the
pages of his good book and add new plays to the scheme.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we had evidence of what our kids could do, that
would allow us to evolve further or expand a little bit,'' Bible
said.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of his first season at BC, Bible has the Eagles
ranked third among Big East teams in total offense (380.6 yards per
game), first downs (225), and pass efficiency (126.1 rating), and
second in rushing offense 177.5 ypg). He has the offense of BC's
8-3 team preparing for a New Year's Eve showdown against Colorado
in the Insight.com Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   It was a far cry from the end of the spring game when BC coach
Tom O'Brien approached Bible and asked him for an evaluation of the
offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I let him get through the spring and then I asked him, `What
do you think?' and he said, `Well, I hope the freshman class is
good.' That was his initial statement,'' O'Brien said. ``Then he
said, `If they have the ``want to'' and want to work hard, if that
counts for anything, then we're going to be a good football team,
because these kids want to be great football players.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Bible, though, deflected any credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the culmination of a really talented group of players,
offensive coaches, and an outstanding head coach and his input that
makes this thing go,'' said Bible, a 46-year-old native of
Cincinnati who graduated in 1976 from the University of Cincinnati
and worked as a graduate assistant while earning an MBA at his alma
mater. ``I took the spring game as, `Let's try a little bit of
this, and let's try a little bit of that. I mean, in the middle of
the season I was still . . .'' he paused to search for the right
word.
</P>
<P>
   Experimenting?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes!'' he replied. ``It was like, `I didn't know he could do
that.' I had hoped, but you never know. That's the beauty of these
(bowl) practices is that we're still growing.''
</P>
<P>
   While Frank Spaziani benefited from the presence of six
battle-tested seniors to help in his transition from BC's running
backs coach to defensive coordinator, Bible faced a considerably
bigger challenge in integrating three new assistants, a slew of new
starters, and a new scheme into a cohesive offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it's probably easier for Frank, because he had some
lettermen and he had some experienced kids who had played for three
or four years,'' O'Brien said. ``The task he had was changing
defenses from a 3-4 to a 4-3 and then fitting the pieces of the
puzzle together. But he had some experience with some people who
had been in games, whereas Dana had a new quarterback, then he had
six other new starters on offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frank had been in the league, at least looking at it from the
other side of the football,'' O'Brien added, ``so he had some idea
of the personnel and the names and the way people played, but this
league was fresh and new to Dana.''
</P>
<P>
   No relation to the famous University of Texas football coach of
the same name, Bible came to The Heights after spending last season
as offensive coordinator of the Philadelphia Eagles, his second
tour of duty in the National Football League after a stint
(1990-92) as the Cincinnati Bengals' quarterbacks coach. In an odd
twist, Bible left the Eagles to coach the BC Eagles, replacing Jeff
Jagodzinski, who left the college ranks to become an NFL assistant
with the Green Bay Packers.
</P>
<P>
   A former offensive coordinator and quarterbacks coach at
Stanford (1995-97), Cincinnati (1994), Miami University (1989), San
Diego State (1986-88), and North Carolina State (1983-85), Bible
found the collegial atmosphere at BC more to his liking, but the
challenges were no less daunting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent my time not focused on that, because as a coach you
have to have tunnel vision on getting the pieces in place and being
single-minded about improving every single day,'' Bible said. ``I
didn't read any more into it than that. I didn't allow myself to
worry about the challenges or allow myself to dream about what
might be. I was very much (focused on) improvement, day-to-day,
that's all.''
</P>
<P>
   Which explained why, at the beginning of the season, finding a
label for BC's new offense was the least of his concerns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
