</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-ALLISON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLISON SIDELINED FOR TESTS ON WRIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, Mass. _ This season had all the potential to be
Jason Allison's best.
</P>
<P>
   So far, though, on a pain and frustration scale, it ranks right
up there with his worst.
</P>
<P>
   When the Bruins departed on their charter flight to Long Island
Sunday, the 24-year-old Allison remained behind and said he expects
to miss at least the next three games, and perhaps more, because of
his damaged right wrist.
</P>
<P>
   Allison is expected to undergo a test Monday or Tuesday that
should determine how long he will be out, whether he needs surgery,
or whether he can continue playing.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, after practicing with his teammates at the Ristuccia
Center, Allison appeared demoralized. He's tired of not being
healthy, of not being able to take faceoffs consistently, of being
sore and unable to play at full capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Short of a miracle cure, Allison said the best-case scenario
might be for him to put a cast on his wrist, sit out a month
without having surgery, and rest it. He said that if the doctors
told him he'd be 100 percent after that, he'd agree to it. In early
November, Allison was supposed to sit out three weeks. He ended up
sitting out one, missing two games. He said he wouldn't do it that
way this time because he's sick of the roller-coaster ride he's
been on.
</P>
<P>
   He said another scenario might be arthroscopic surgery to clean
up the wrist, sit out a while until it heals, and be able to finish
out most of the season and the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The worst-case scenario is surgery that would sideline him 3-4
months. But, Allison said, if he knew his wrist wasn't going to get
any worse, he'd nurse it through the year, take time off when he
needed it, and then have the major operation in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   The pain is unbearable at times, Allison said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's starting to scare me,'' he said. ``I want to play, and
that's the way I am, but I've got to be careful and make sure it
doesn't ruin my career. The way it's going now, the day after a
game I can't pick something up off the table . . . because of the
pain. It almost drops me. Two days later, it might feel good again.
Hopefully, that's a good sign and means it's something that just
keeps flaring up. That's why I kept playing, because it does get
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Allison said he just wants a resolution to a problem that first
reared its ugly head last February.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been maybe 10 games this year where I've felt
good,'' he said. ``The rest _ some nights have been better than
others, some nights have been awful. I can't go through that all
year. I said I wouldn't the last time it happened and I can't.
We'll see what they say. Basically, I'm going to let the
specialists make the decision for me rather than arguing with them
to play. If they told me that if I sit out a month then I'd be 100
percent, without it coming back, that would make me happy in a
way.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Christmas break, Allison already has had a few days
off. He said after having the test there was no sense trying to
rush back for the road trip that begins Monday night in Long
Island, continues in New Jersey Wednesday, and wraps up in Ottawa
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had three days off already,'' said Allison. ``It's a good
time right now to rest it. To have the test, it will be five days.
There's no sense in joining the team for two games (in two nights);
it's stupid. I'm going to give it a good week off anyway. After the
test, by Wednesday or Thursday, we should know what the plan is.''
</P>
<P>
   Allison's injury is rare, something you see in tennis but rarely
in other sports. He also said he's being told that it's not one
injury, it's different ones that have produced a domino effect on
his forearm and wrist.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one thing that has bothered me all year: (hearing),
`You have this a little bit, it might be a little bit of this or
that.' I don't want to take a month off and come back and have it
be hurting again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might take a week off and do that. I'd rather have surgery
and be out for three months than be out a month and come back and
rehurt it. Wrists are tricky things. Look what happened last year.
I had tendinitis and it turned into a torn forearm. Then I had torn
cartilage and a fracture from last year that were kind of related,
but they're not. The swelling and tiredness made another thing
happen. The tear healed in my forearm, but is it from that or from
last year? I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Nailing down the exact problem has, indeed, been difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're only going to check the tendon in the wrist and the
forearm,'' he said. ``If they fix the tendon, I'm sure they'll look
at the cartilage. If they tell me that if I take a month off and
it's not going to get better, then I have to make a decision
whether to have (arthroscopic) surgery now or wait until the end of
the year and take a week off here and there, which is what I would
have to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very frustrating for me. I haven't been able to battle
like I want to and take draws and shoot the puck as good as I'd
like. It's the NHL _ it's hard to get by if you're not 100
percent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
