<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO EGG ON FACE OF SCRAMBLING FLUTIE 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL McDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Doug Flutie walked onto the Foxboro Stadium
field at 11 Sunday morning, took one look at the flags flapping
loudly at the top of the stands, and thought he could deal with the
big problem of the day.
</P>
<P>
   The wind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will make a difference,'' he said. ``We'll have to be
careful. The thing (to worry about) is not turning it over. Field
position will be important.''
</P>
<P>
   The wind was unusually high for the stadium, gusting at more
than 25 miles per hour at times, creating havoc with passes and
kicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was playing a game in Winnipeg one time,'' said Flutie of
his time in the Canadian Football League, ``and the wind was
gusting up to 70 miles an hour. I went back one time, throwing into
it, I threw the ball as far as I could, and my wide receiver caught
it for an 8-yard gain. Threw it as hard as I could, but it only
went 8 yards.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots were talking about missed opportunities after their
13-10 overtime loss to the Bills. On the Buffalo side, they were
talking about Flutie's finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just got hot after the third period,'' said Bills offensive
coordinator Joe Pendry. ``We struggled on offense the first three
quarters. Doug made some bad reads, threw to the wrong guys. And
some of our other guys around him missed assignments and were
making mental errors.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the fourth period on into the overtime, we just got hot.
Doug made the plays and we moved the ball. The plays were there
earlier, we just killed ourselves with mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Flutie was cooking over the last 28 minutes, 15 in the fourth,
and 13 in OT. He completed 15 of 18 passes after going just 7 for
17 in the first 45 minutes. He converted nine of 17 third-down
situations, after struggling mightily on them early.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to run, to play-action, and stay away from
turnovers,'' said Pendry. ``That was what we told them before the
game. Then we had three fumbles on offense, plus a bunch of drops.
Guys were fighting the ball on account of the wind. They paid too
much attention to it. It became a mental thing. Then, at the end of
the game, everyone just seemed to settle down. Doug made some big
throws, and our guys started to hold onto the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for the turnovers, Buffalo dominated. They led the
Patriots in total offense, 374 yards to 225. They controlled the
ball for 42:32 to 30:40.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, they sacked New England quarterback Drew Bledsoe six
times (not uncommon this year) and held him to 67 net yards
passing. That is the fewest net yards passing by a Patriot QB since
1992 in a game against Cincinnati, when the immortal Jeff Carlson
threw for 60.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wind dictated how we played defense today,'' said Bills
defensive coordinator Ted Cottrell. ``When they were going into the
wind, we ran more eight-man fronts thinking they were going to try
to run more. Then when they had the wind at their backs, we blitzed
them more trying to get after their pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to give their running game some credit. At times they
hit our defense just right. Terry Allen was very effective. After
one series, one of our young linebackers says to me, `Hey that guy
can really run.' I said, `No kidding, he only ran for 1,500 yards a
few years ago.' ''
</P>
<P>
   All of the Bills thought they got jobbed by referee Mike Carey
on a critical play at the start of the fourth quarter when running
back Jonathan Linton, who had a terrible game, fumbled for the
second time. Chad Eaton picked up the ball at the Buffalo 44 and
ran it to the Bills' 14, setting up the Patriots' only touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like Linton fumbled, but the Patriots should have
had the ball right there,'' said Pendry. ``Eaton made contact with
our players when he was on the ground, and the play should have
ended (at the 44).'' The Bills were right. Even after looking at
the replay, Carey got it wrong.
</P>
<P>
   However, Buffalo, after sleepwalking on offense to that point,
met the challenge with the season on the line, and Flutie made all
of the big plays coming down the stretch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
