<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BILLS-FLUTIE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLUTIE'S AN OLDIE BUT A GOODIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Bruce Smith, another of the old guard and he
of the two sacks of Drew Bledsoe this day, chuckled as he got
dressed and prepared to leave Foxboro Stadium Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The subject of the moment was old favorite Doug Flutie, who led
the Buffalo Bills to a touchdown late in the fourth quarter to tie
the Patriots at 10-10. He then led them to Steve Christie's 23-yard
winning field goal late in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to the party,'' said Smith, Buffalo's defensive end,
with a big smile. ``None of us know what he's going to do. Not even
the offensive linemen. He made some good plays out there today.
It's exciting. It's exciting, but it can be nerve-wracking.''
</P>
<P>
   If it was nerve-wracking from the Buffalo sideline, imagine what
it was like from the Patriot viewpoint.
</P>
<P>
   Here were the Patriots shutting down Flutie and the Bills and
then taking a 10-3 lead early in the fourth quarter on a Terry
Allen touchdown that followed an odd, video-challenged runback of a
fumble recovery by Chad Eaton.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots held Flutie off again, but then the Bills held,
too, and here he was again.
</P>
<P>
   To this point, Flutie had scrambled for a couple of first downs,
but he had completed only 10 of 23 passes, and the Bills had scored
only a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   He hit Sam Gash for 5 yards and then for another 8. And now
Flutie, wearing gloves more to keep his hands from drying out in
the cold and wind than strictly for the cold, was heating up. He
hit Peerless Price for 24 yards and Eric Moulds for 19 and soon the
Bills had tied it with a 1-yard run.
</P>
<P>
   The Bills then watched while Adam Vinatieri missed a 33-yard
field goal to the right.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots won the OT coin toss and took the ball and started
down the field. Here was Vinatieri lining up again, this time from
44 yards into the wind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had no control over that, that's scary,'' Flutie said.
``But I honestly felt there was a good chance of him missing the
kick because of the wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Vinatieri was short on the second one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our defense shut them down enough so they had to try the
44-yarder into the wind,'' said Flutie.
</P>
<P>
   Flutie passed for 11 yards and Thurman Thomas _ remember him,
too? _ ran for 18 yards down the left sideline. But Moulds coughed
the ball up after a 17-yard reception and the Patriots got the ball
back.
</P>
<P>
   The Bills' defense held again and turned the ball over to Flutie
for the last time.
</P>
<P>
   He completed five passes around one Thomas run and then Thomas
ran up the middle for 9 yards and the Bills were in field goal
range.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thurman was amazing,'' said Flutie. ``He finds the smallest of
holes and slices through them. The one he slid through, if he
wasn't protecting the ball so hard, he probably would have
scored.''
</P>
<P>
   Not necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Christie came on and banged through a 23-yarder for the win.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, only a few games back after missing much of the season
with rib and spleen injuries, rushed 15 times for 84 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Flutie, who has been taking some heat in Buffalo for his
performances of late, completed his last 12 passes to tie a Bills
record (Jim Kelly put up the same number against the Patriots in a
1988 game) and finished 22 of 35 for 212 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Flutie, by the way, is 37. Smith is 36 and Thomas 33.
</P>
<P>
   Call it revenge of the old guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of makes up for last year,'' Flutie said. ``In our
minds, a little bit, we thought we had that game locked up last
year and they pulled it out of the hat.''
</P>
<P>
   In that one, Drew Bledsoe, playing with a pin in his finger,
threw a winning touchdown as the game ended.
</P>
<P>
   Not this time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
