<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BLEDSOE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLEDSOE STIL IN THROES OF SLUMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Sunday's was one of the ugliest games
Patriots quarterback Drew Bledsoe ever has played. He threw for
just 101 yards, completing 10 of 21 passes, with no touchdowns or
interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   His only worse games came in his rookie season, 1993. Against
the Phoenix Cardinals Bledsoe had 85 yards, hitting on 8 of 17
attempts, and against the Bills he had 96 yards, going 8 of 16.
</P>
<P>
   There was an explanation for Sunday's effort, however. Half the
game he was passing against a stiff wind.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe was 7 of 12 for 62 yards in the first half, with two
sacks. In the second half, he was 3 of 9 for 39 yards with four
sacks. The lone Patriots touchdown in the Bills' 13-10 overtime win
was on a 14-yard Terry Allen run up the middle in the fourth
period.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a strong wind, it's never really consistent,''
Bledsoe said. ``You've got a prevailing wind, but then it swirls at
times and so it makes it unpredictable a little bit. So the way
I've always counteracted it is to throw the ball a little harder
and take some air off the ball so it will go through the wind, so
it will end up somewhere it's supposed to be.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not the way it always works, though. For example, Bledsoe
tried to connect with wide receiver Shawn Jefferson up the sideline
on a third-down play, but the pass went out of bounds, instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was playing so the wind would knock the ball back a little
bit, and instead it pushed the ball out of bounds,'' Bledsoe said.
</P>
<P>
   One of Bledsoe's pleasant moments came on a run, in the fourth
quarter. The game was tied at 10, and it was first and 10 from the
Buffalo 42 with 1:19 remaining. Bledsoe saw an opening to the left
and went 25 yards, picking up a first down to the Bills 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initially, everybody was covered, they dropped into a two-deep
zone, and I was looking to check the ball to one of our backs,''
said Bledsoe. ``I saw there was nothing there but green grass, so I
took off. I don't know if I could have scored if I stayed on my
feet or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Bills free safety Kurt Schulz tackled Bledsoe inbounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was somebody that had an angle to knock me out of
bounds, I would have stepped on out, but I thought I'd get as much
as I could,'' Bledsoe said.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots kicker Adam Vinatieri soon attempted a 33-yard field
goal, but the kick was wide right.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have liked to have made another first down in that
situation and we would have liked to have gotten Adam closer,
especially kicking into the wind like he was forced to do, but we
felt like we were in the right situation,'' Bledsoe said. ``We
really didn't want to take a chance at that point, so we ran the
ball and unfortunately we didn't get close enough for him to get it
through.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bledsoe liked the Patriots' effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team, we're not going to quit, we have a lot of heart,''
he said. ``I don't think anybody on this team could have possibly
imagined that this could have happened to us, what has happened,
but by the same token, the guys have a lot of pride and they're
going to play hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said it before, and I will continue to say, through this
whole thing, I don't think there has been a lack of effort. There
has been some poor execution through the stretch, but when you have
some guys we have on this team, they're not going to (quit) on this
team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
