<HEADER>
A9594 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-DEFENSE-     12-27 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-DEFENSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSE LEFT HOLDING THE BAG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ For so long this season, the New England
defense has had to tote the heaviest of burdens _ its own offense _
yet week after week the defense became stronger as the offense grew
weaker.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday the defense's burden was twice as heavy _ it had to
carry the New Engand offense and its special teams. It was a load
much too heavy to bear.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like we're cursed,'' said linebacker Chris Slade. ``It
seems like everything that could go wrong has gone wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to remember this feeling,'' said defensive lineman
Willie McGinest after the Patriots lost in overtime to Buffalo,
13-10. ``Guys that say this is OK are guys that you've got to get
out of here.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pete Carroll said he was proud the Patriots showed up to
play, a week after New England played like a high school team and
eliminated itself from the playoffs. ``This meant a lot to me,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But what about the feeling mentioned by McGinest?
</P>
<P>
   It was an emptiness, symbolized by defensive lineman Chad Eaton
flinging his helmet across the turf when Steve Christie's chip shot
field goal went between the uprights with 1:48 left in OT.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defense has been playing well all year,'' said cornerback
Tebucky Jones, who was up to the task in his second start except
for one Doug Flutie pass to Eric Moulds that set up Buffalo's lone
TD. ``And one more game . . . we played well again.''
</P>
<P>
   The offense was its usual impotent self Sunday but the defense
kept Flutie and the Bills in check for virtually all of regulation.
True, Flutie completed 12 straight passes (seven in OT, five at the
end of regulation), tying Jim Kelly's team record, but the Patriot
defense twice came up with plays, one at the end of regulation and
the other in OT, that set up the offense with chances to end the
game early.
</P>
<P>
   And, significantly, the plays were made by two youngsters,
cornerback Kato Serwanga and rookie safety Tony George, who
mysteriously has been kept on the sideline while regular free
safety Chris Carter has done next to nothing all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a good call on the part of the coaches,'' said
Serwanga, who came in cleanly on a corner blitz on the first play
after the two-minute warning with the Bills facing third and 4 from
their 18-yard line. ``The coaches made a perfect call there and all
I had to do was execute it.''
</P>
<P>
   Serwanga, who also played well filling in at cornerback, dropped
Flutie for a 6-yard loss and the Bills were forced to punt. The
Patriot offense got the ball on the Bills' 42 with 1:19 left,
which, once upon a time, virtually would have guaranteed victory
for New England, its offense and its kicker once so dependable.
</P>
<P>
   But, as defensive lineman Chris Sullivan put it, ``early in the
season we always were so confident we were going to win close
games. But now? You just don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   An easy field goal was missed by New England's Adam Vinatieri,
sending the game into OT. But Vinatieri missed another field goal,
this a more difficult one from 44 yards into a strong wind, and it
seemed the Patriot defense now would both bend and break. Such a
result often follows when a team botches not one, but two, chances
to win.
</P>
<P>
   True enough, Flutie needed only three plays to move from his 34
to the New England 38 and then hit Moulds for a 17-yard gain to the
Patriots' 21, seemingly setting up an easy winning field goal. But
George still had a play to make.
</P>
<P>
   George displayed two instincts on the play, the first by
recognizing what was happening and getting into position to make a
play, and the second when he intentionally went after the ball and
tried to cause a fumble. Such instincts seldom have been seen from
Carter, who was forced out of Sunday's game with a lingering
hamstring pull.
</P>
<P>
   Jones was supposed to be on Moulds ``and I was supposed to push
over to the middle of the field and play the seam,'' explained
George. But the rookie saw immediately that ``Tebucky wasn't able
to get a good jam on Moulds and I saw Moulds run open, and I just
got over to make a play.''
</P>
<P>
   George not only made the tackle on Moulds ``but when I hit, I
always try to put the helmet on the ball because I've been taught
that so much.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' Tedy Bruschi recovered, and after Terry Allen
gained 20 yards on New England's first play, hinting that the
months-long slide by the offense just might be ending, the
Patriots' attack stepped back into the familiar quicksand. Three
more plays and out.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the defense folded under the burden of carrying the
team for 73 minutes. ``I could have been making these plays earlier
in the season,'' George said. But, with this Patriot offense, even
that might have made little difference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
