<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 01:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9599 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-CARROLL-     12-27 0261
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-CARROLL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIGNS POINTING TO CARROLL EXIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ There were two strong signs Sunday that
Patriots coach Pete Carroll believes he is gone.
</P>
<P>
   First, in an unprecedented move, Carroll took his players into
the visiting locker room at Foxborough Stadium Thursday and
addressed them.
</P>
<P>
   Reportedly there were no other coaches or team personnel
allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll reportedly told the players that he had tried to do
everything right, and he wanted them to perform in the last two
games the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Although he never told the players he thought he was going to be
fired, they came away with that feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said as much without saying it right out,'' said someone
who was familiar with what went on in the meeting. ``The players
that were in that meeting felt he was telling them that this was
going to be their last two games (with him), and that he was going
to coach as hard as he could and he wanted them to play with
pride.''
</P>
<P>
   It perhaps was not a coincidence, then, that Carroll said in his
postgame press conference that the players played ``with pride''
and ``played a prideful game.''
</P>
<P>
   The second sign?
</P>
<P>
   Solid ESPN reporter Sal Paolantonio said Carroll had phoned
agent Bob Lamothe in California and asked him to try to get Carroll
another head coaching job in the league. Lamothe is the agent for
Seattle coach Mike Holmgren, and has the reputation of being able
to help coaches get jobs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-99 0133EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
