r s BC-RAC-SANTAANITA-LADN     12-27 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-SANTAANITA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG CROWD FOR SANTA ANITA OPENER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA -- Drawn to Santa Anita by scenic weather, a program of
large fields and the chance to watch Breeders' Cup Classic winner
Cat Thief in action, 44,018 fans got more than expected on opening
day.
</P>
<P>
   They witnessed the last rides of Hall of Famer Gary Stevens, who
abruptly announced his retirement late Sunday afternoon, only 36
years old but unable to stand the pain in an arthritic knee.
</P>
<P>
   They saw a long-shot 8,845th victory by Hall of Famer Laffit
Pincay, who sets a new world record with every winner he rides.
And, along with those chapters in racing history, they saw Leonard
Dunc an saddle the 3-year-old gelding Love That Red to win a
three-horse photo finish over Straight Man and favored Cat Thief in
the $200,000 Malibu Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard who? Someday, the fans who made up the largest on-site
crowd in five years for a Santa Anita opener may look back and say
they were there when Dunca n won his first major race. A babyfaced
39-year-old who got his start as a trainer at Los Alamitos, Duncan
hopes to follow noted Los Al alumni D. Wayne Lukas and Bob Baffert
to glory at the major tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be successful, win Breeders' Cup races and make lots of
money? Hec k yeah, I'd like to do that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For one gloriously sunny afternoon, the Long Beach native was
excited just to be in a Grade I winner's circle for the first time
after Love That Red ($10.40) defeated horses trained by Baffert
(Straight Man and sixth-place Prime Timber) and Lukas (Cat Thief)
as well as big-name trainers Richard Mandella (fifth-place Desert
Hero) and Ron McAnally (seventh-place Painter).
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels incredible. It feels unexplainable,'' Duncan gushed.
</P>
<P>
   ``My knees are shaking,'' said his wife, Kathy.
</P>
<P>
   Garrett Gomez -- who rode two winners, as did Corey Nakatani and
Alex S olis -- sent Love That Red inside the hurried pace-setter
Five Star Day to take a short lead in mid-stretch, and held off
Straight Man by a neck with Cat Thief a head farther back.
</P>
<P>
   Cat Thief, shortening up to 7 furlongs in his first start since
winning the 1 1/4-mile Breeders' Cup Classic in November, ran well
despite going wide, and should be set for the 1 1/16-mile San
Fernando Stakes for 4-year-olds on Jan. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan said he'll resist the temptation to try the longer San
Fernando distance with Love That Red, who proved his sprinting
ability by winning the California Cup Sprint and three other short
stakes for breeder-owne r Terry Wells in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's absolutely better around one turn,'' Duncan said. He also
descri bed Love That Red as ``telepathic'' -- the gelding
communicates his mood to the trainer. Last time out, Love That Red
was cranky and finished se cond to Cliquot in the On Trust at
Hollywood Park. ``Today, he was absolutely perfect to saddle,
completely relaxed, and I told Terry in the paddock, `I just
saddled the winner,' '' Duncan said.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan, Wells and Gomez were among a handful of big winners on
Santa An ita's 63rd opening day, its second under owner Frank
Stronach, whose mak eover of the landmark track continued with
Sunday's opening of the 500-chair FrontRunners restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Chalk bettors started well as Fun Meeting You ($6) and Matt
Garcia won the first race in front-running style. McAnally-trained
Sam's ($37.20) snapped a more than year-long losing streak in the
second.
</P>
<P>
   Pincay gave his fans what they wanted in the fourth when a
couple of left-handed cracks of the whip sent Toqueville to a
maiden win that paid $ 59.60. Solis and Mandella teamed up to win
the day's other stakes, the Blue Norther for 2-year-old fillies on
turf, with Minor Details, half an hour after they combined to win
an optional claimer with Lake William.
</P>
<P>
   And David Flores launched defense of his 1998-99 riding title by
winning the nightcap on $48 Nates Colony to leave a single perfect
pick-six ticket worth $217,147.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-99 0213EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
