<DOCNO> NYT19991227.0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 02:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9620 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-RAC-STEVENS--LADN     12-27 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-STEVENS--LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOCKEY STEVENS RETIRES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA -- Midway through his mount aboard Desert Hero during
the featured $200,000 Malibu Stakes on opening day of Santa Anita's
winter/spring meeting -- Hall of fame jockey Gary Stevens told
himself, ``it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, a three-time Kentucky Derby champion who missed winning
the Triple Crown aboard Silver Charm by a nose in 1997 -- announced
his sudden retirement, Sunday -- ending a brilliant 20-year career
that began when he was 16.
</P>
<P>
   Arguably the best jockey over the last decade, Stevens said that
degenerative arthritis in his right knee has forced his career to
end prematurely.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month Stevens had arthroscopic surgery to remove
debris in his right knee -- but after returning to racing after a
30-day absence, he admitted he couldn't continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the eighth pole in the Malibu is when I said, `it's
over.''' said Stevens, who was 0-for-4 on the day. ``Before the
race was over with, I was a well-beaten fifth and I was praying for
the finish line to come just so I could stand up.''
</P>
<P>
   After his first mount in the second race aboard Naninja, Stevens
knew it was time to retire. He tried to finish his card -- but he
opted out of his last two mounts after his ride aboard Desert Hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``One hundred yards into the first race I rode, I knew this
would be my last day,'' he said. ``Today I was hoping for a
Christmas miracle. I was hoping to be able to do my job.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it wasn't fun anymore. It was time. There is bone on bone
and it's chipping away. I want to be able to walk later in life.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens leaves with six Triple Crown victories, with his other
two Kentucky Derby winners aboard Winning Colors in 1988 and
Thunder Gulch in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   He also won the 1997 Preakness with Silver Charm and the Belmont
with Thunder Gulch. His last Triple Crown victory aboard Victory
Gallop in 1998 spoiled Real Quiet's bid to become the first Triple
Crown winner since Affirmed in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, who also won seven Breeders' Cup titles, went on to
ride 4,512 winners in his career, earning a total of $187 million
in purses -- but injuries to both knee's over the last 10-years
made riding tough for the Eclipse Award winning jockey.
</P>
<P>
   ``The damage to my knee is irreparable and I was advised by my
doctors that I could carry on as long as I could withstand the
pain,'' said Stevens. ``I was hoping this last surgery would allow
me to be pain free enough to do my job and hopefully ride another
year -- but there was no way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last year and a half I've relied more on my mental savvy
than my physical savvy. But it's come to the point where I can't
rely on my smarts anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I could stick around for another year, but I realize
today that it's not fun to me anymore. It hasn't been fun the last
six months and I thought this clean up surgery would give me a
little more time.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one wants to admit when it's time to quit, but it's time.
It's a lot easier for me to say I'm not the rider that I was then
to hear it from somebody else. I can live with that, but I don't
think I can live with somebody else telling me that I'm not.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Baffert, the trainer that saddled Silver Charm and directed
his best stock in Stevens' direction -- said it's a tough loss for
racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always said he's the best rider I've ever thrown on the
back of one of my horses,'' said Baffert. ``He's one of those
riders that I had so much confidence in. I was never worried about
what kind of ride he would give the horse. I was worried whether I
would have the horse ready to run.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll always be indebted to him because he got me my first Ken &QL;
</P>
<P>
   tucky Derby -- but it's sad because there's nothing like
preparing for a big race and having Gary. Certain riders are fun to
win with and he was one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Jockey Laffit Pincay, who recently broke Bill Shoemaker's
all-time victory mark -- said Stevens was the best over the last 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure going to miss him,'' said Pincay. ``He's a champion.
I've seen him ride for many years and he's had this (knee) problem
for a long time but he never complained about it. He rode on heart
and that's what champions do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a loss because he had many good years ahead of him and he
was a gentleman and professional to be around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-99 0215EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
