<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 02:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9621 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LBPT     12-27 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS HOLD OFF CELTICS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just in time to help you squeeze into that millennium bio-hazard
suit, we're introducing a revolutionary Clipper workout called
``Ty-Mo.''
</P>
<P>
   The battle cry is easy:
</P>
<P>
   Know pain, know gain.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers, who are on a first-name basis with pain, also know
that Tyrone Nesby (22 points, 7 rebounds) and Maurice ``Mo'' Taylor
(26 points, 7 rebounds) enabled them to fatten their record (9-18)
during Sunday's 103-100 victory over the Boston Celtics in front of
12,039 at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``That isn't in my job description ... playin' the five,'' said
Taylor, who was hotter than a $50 Rolex during his 13-point fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five,'' by the way, is hoop code for center.
</P>
<P>
   Right, the 6-foot-8 Taylor was required to pull off that stunt
because regular cast member Michael Olowokandi (sore left knee)
joined a wounded list that has left the Clips about as deep as a
Pauly (cq) Shore flick.
</P>
<P>
   Left-ankle misery has made goners of Derek Anderson and Brian
Skinner, while reinforcement Marty Conlon (illness in the family)
has yet to play. Backup point guard Eric Murdock tweaked his left
ankle two minutes into his second-quarter appearance Sunday and
didn't return.
</P>
<P>
   The grief even reached Coach Chris Ford (lower back spasms), who
missed two heroic wins last week, but returned Sunday to direct his
team to victory over the franchise he coached and played for.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a great win,'' said Ford, whose team led by 13 in
the second quarter, but was outscored, 34-20, in the third. ``The
guys just found ways to make it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Not before negotiating even more twists in the minefield. The
Celtics (11-15) activated their best player, Paul Pierce (24
points) Sunday morning, and received 28 points from trash-talking
marvel Antoine Walker.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers still managed to post their third consecutive
victory - the fifth in seven games - and achieve a ninth win that
required 44 games to accomplish last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're definitely not worrying about what went on last year,''
said flu-damaged rookie Lamar Odom, who produced 15 points, a
game-high 11 rebounds, 3 assists, 5 steals, 3 blocked shots and a
game-high 6 fouls. ``But it is nice to see how we've improved over
last year ... we'll try and build from there.''
</P>
<P>
   It also was sort of pleasant watching Odom steal the ball and
finish the subsequent 2-on-1 dash with a runaway slam at 10:35 of
the fourth quarter. It was a galvanizing maneuver, trimming a
Boston lead that had grown to nine (61-52) down to 76-72.
</P>
<P>
   Odom took Pierce baseline to tie it at 78 with 7:38 remaining,
Taylor drilled an 18-footer for an 80-78 Clipper lead at 7:05, and
Nesby added a 3-pointer to make it 83-78, Clips, with 6:21 before
the final horn.
</P>
<P>
   With six seconds before closing, Boston's Tony Battie stepped to
the line for a pair of free throws and his team down, 101-99. He
made the first, missed the second, Clipper Troy Hudson (15 points,
9 assists) snagged the rebound, was fouled and clinched victory
with two free throws.
</P>
<P>
   Others sources of Clipper joy were provided by backup center
Keith Closs (7 points), backup combo guard Charles Jones (a crucial
3-pointer), guard Eric Piatkowski (15 points, 3 of 6 on 3s) and the
collective savvy to commit only 11 turnovers vs. Boston's pressure
defense.
</P>
<P>
   One of those errors was an incomplete inbound pass from Taylor
that occurred with 22.4 seconds left to play and Boston trailing by
a deuce.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just bugged out on the pass,'' Taylor admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Must be that millennium bug.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
