<HEADER>
A9624 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-KINGS-WRITETHRU-L     12-27 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS LOSE AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The symptoms of a five-game losing streak were
everywhere Sunday night at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   The winning goal for the Pacific Division-leading Phoenix
Coyotes in a 3-2 overtime victory actually was scored by Kings
center Bryan Smolinski.
</P>
<P>
   Luc Robitaille scored the tying goal midway through the third
period on his only shot of the night. After scoring 10 goals in the
first six games, he has two in the last 2{ months.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings irritated Phoenix's leading scorer, Jeremy Roenick,
into two major fighting penalties early in the game only to see him
credited with the game winner in OT.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're searching for answers right now,'' Smolinski said.
``It's tough, but you have to battle through times like this.
Sometimes games just have weird endings.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the disappointing loss, Sunday's game marked the first
time in more than two weeks the last-place Kings actually recorded
a point.
</P>
<P>
   They had been stuck on 39 longer than Jack Benny, but with the
new overtime rules, they got one for tying Phoenix in regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take it,'' said Kings coach Andy Murray, who watched his
team partially recover from three brutal losses with a respectable
2-1 loss last Wednesday in San Jose. ``All the games will be tough
from now on.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray could only shrug when asked about the winning goal that
started after Jyrki Lumme hit the post on a 15-foot wrist shot. The
puck sailed in the air and Roenick took a whack with what might
have been ruled a high stick. The puck hit Smolinski's stick and
trickled past Kings goaltender Stephane Fiset.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I hadn't touched it, it might have hit off Stephane and
gone in anyway,'' said Smolinski, his team now 0-2-6 in OT.
</P>
<P>
   Even more baffling might have been the recent performance of
Robitaille, who returned Dec. 3 after missing almost a month with a
broken left foot.
</P>
<P>
   When he was named NHL Player of the Week to open the season, he
looked a lot like someone who has more than 500 goals. Lately, he
has just looked lost.
</P>
<P>
   It can be argued that first-line center Jozef Stumpel was
playing just his second game Sunday after missing five weeks with
abdominal surgery. And right winger Ziggy Palffy has not picked up
his game since being sidelined two weeks ago with back spasms.
</P>
<P>
   But Robitaille shares the leadership role with captain Rob
Blake.
</P>
<P>
   After taking a pass from Stumpel behind the Phoenix defense, he
beat goaltender Bob Essensa with a wrist shot over the left
shoulder. Robitaille then skated past the Kings bench and each
player gave him a tap as if to say, `Welcome back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you score it feels great,'' Robitaille said. ``If we
continue to play like this we're going to be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings fell behind on two goals by Travis Green, the former
Mighty Ducks center. Green has 14 goals, one more than his career
high.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes did not take a shot on Fiset for the first nine
minutes of the game. But 15 seconds after the first, Green scored
on the power play.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes were coming off an 8-2 victory in Anaheim on
Wednesday but had dropped five of their past six. They also were
playing without captain Keith Tkachuk, who injured his back in
pre-game warmups.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of capitalizing, the Kings managed only a goal in two
periods, by Ian Laperriere, the third-line center who leads the NHL
in penalty minutes with 115.
</P>
<P>
   Twice the Kings had potential goals reviewed and rejected by
instant replay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the things that happen when you are going through a
losing streak,'' Robitaille said. ``What can you say, but you got
to keep playing hard and keep moving.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
