</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FEDERAL RESERVE'S Y2K COMMAND POST WILL WATCH BANKS AND
MARKETS 
</HEADLINE>
 (REPEATING FOR ALL NEEDING)  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, Dec. 26)   &HT;     (EDS: Filed in the ``w'' and ``f'' categories.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 &HT;     c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Although the Federal Reserve Board isn't expecting
any widespread Y2K problems, the Fed will operate a special
around-the-clock command post that will monitor banks and financial
markets for computer glitches beginning Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Reserve Board Governors Roger W. Ferguson and Edward W.
Kelley will work over the New Year's weekend, helping 100 staffers
at the command center keep track of each time zone's rollover into
the new year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't expecting major problems,'' said Federal Reserve
spokeswoman Rose Pianalto. The financial markets and the banking
industry _ particularly in the United States and major
industrialized countries_ started addressing the Y2K problem early.
As a result, American bankers predict their computers will work
without a hitch on Jan. 1 and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   The Y2K computer problem is the result of old programming that
expressed years with two digits, meaning that uncorrected computers
could interpret ``00'' as ``1900'' and crash, or garble data,
potentially disrupting everything from air travel to
telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's main focus will be to ensure that the U.S. banking
system survives the transition into the New Year.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed, which regulates about 1,500 U.S. banks, is requiring
the largest of them to do a ``health check'' on Saturday, Jan. 1 _
a day when most banks are traditionally closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will check the lights, the heat and the computers and
report to us,'' Pianalto said. The banks will report to one of the
Fed's 12 regional banks that are also running 24-hour Y2K centers.
The regional Fed banks will report into the Fed's headquarters in
Washington. That information, in turn, will be passed along to the
White House's Y2K command center.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed will also make sure that the nation's money system _ an
electronic network that moves money _ is working. The system helps
keep ATMs running and ensures that payments like paychecks are
correctly transferred from an employer's account to individual
employee accounts at various banks.
</P>
<P>
   Fed officials and bankers were once concerned that people would
withdraw huge sums of money and even close their accounts before
the New Year because of fears that their banks would be paralyzed
by Y2K problems.
</P>
<P>
   However, fear of an Y2K-inspired run on the banks was apparently
unfounded. Pianalto said bank customers appear to have taken out
more cash in anticipation of the New Year, but not enough to case
alarm.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, there was $530 billion in circulation, up 14 percent
over last November's figure of $464 billion, according to the Fed.
The amount of cash in circulation in November and December
typically increases by 7 percent annually, partly to accommodate
holiday spending, giving rise to the likelihood that only the other
7 percent hike represents withdrawals by customers concerned about
Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great economy,'' Pianalto said, explaining that part of
the increased cash can be attributed to strong holiday retail
sales. ``But some of it is probably Y2K.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's Y2K post is set up in the Federal Reserve's dining
room on the top floor of its five-story building on Constitution
Avenue and offers spectacular views of the Washington Monument and
the Lincoln and Jefferson Memorials.
</P>
<P>
   But other than the view, the center looks like dozens of other
government Y2K command centers sprinkled throughout the Washington
area. It is outfitted with about 100 computers that sit on small
desks with only enough room for the computer monitor and a phone.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed rented several televisions to follow Y2K news. Rented
clocks are set to local time in Hong Kong, London, Moscow, New York
and San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   New Zealand will be the first major country to enter into the
New Year at 6 a.m. Dec. 31. EST.
</P>
<P>
   The busiest day for the Fed will likely come on Monday, Jan. 3,
when banks and many world markets open for business. All U.S.
markets will be open then, though some markets in Japan and London
will be closed in observance of the New Year's holiday.
</P>
<P>
   During the early morning hours on Monday the Fed will check
markets in Hong Kong, Frankfurt, Germany and Paris to see how they
are doing. During the day on Monday, the 12 regional Fed banks will
call each private bank in their respective regions, again to see if
the lights, heat and computers are working. Banks are also required
to report any unusual behavior such as massive withdrawals of
funds.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Corbett Dooren can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at
the e-mail address jennifer &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-99 0826EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991227.0035 </DOCNO>
