</P>
<P>
   But other than the view, the center looks like dozens of other
government Y2K command centers sprinkled throughout the Washington
area. It is outfitted with about 100 computers that sit on small
desks with only enough room for the computer monitor and a phone.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed rented several televisions to follow Y2K news. Rented
clocks are set to local time in Hong Kong, London, Moscow, New York
and San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   New Zealand will be the first major country to enter into the
New Year at 6 a.m. Dec. 31. EST.
</P>
<P>
   The busiest day for the Fed will likely come on Monday, Jan. 3,
when banks and many world markets open for business. All U.S.
markets will be open then, though some markets in Japan and London
will be closed in observance of the New Year's holiday.
</P>
<P>
   During the early morning hours on Monday the Fed will check
markets in Hong Kong, Frankfurt, Germany and Paris to see how they
are doing. During the day on Monday, the 12 regional Fed banks will
call each private bank in their respective regions, again to see if
the lights, heat and computers are working. Banks are also required
to report any unusual behavior such as massive withdrawals of
funds.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Corbett Dooren can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at
the e-mail address jennifer &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
