<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 10:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9659 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-MILLENNIUM-TIME-REV     12-27 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-MILLENNIUM-TIME-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
 
 (Repeating for all needing.) 
 COUNTING THE YEARS TO MAKE SENSE OUT OF LIFE  (The Week in Review) 
(jw) 
 By EVA HOFFMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For all the hype, the panic and the prophecies, the occasion is
real. This New Year's Eve feels different, no matter how arbitrary
the date announcing the new millennium may be. The big round number
about to invade our diaries and our lives has an undeniable
symbolic force.
</P>
<P>
   Is this mere superstition, the kind that stops us from walking
under ladders? Perhaps not entirely, for while our systems for
measuring time may be arbitrary, they are also necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Living in seemingly infinite time and space, we humans are
mortal and finite, and we cannot get along without borders and
markers to make the world graspable to our minds.
</P>
<P>
   Sigmund Freud famously opined that ``There is no time in the
unconscious,'' but as soon as we gain consciousness, we begin to
sense and search for shapes and patterns in the continuum of time.
Some of these are determined, or at least strongly influenced by,
the nature of our nature. We experience divisions of time through
the progression of the sun, the alternation of night and day, the
rhythm of our heartbeats, the limits of human life. Richard Fortey,
a paleontologist at the Natural History Museum in London and the
author of ``Life: A Natural History of the First Four Billion
Years,'' believes that an experiential sense of time is encoded
into living creatures. Small mice, whose life spans are very short,
for example, probably ``perceive time in accelerated way,'' Fortey
said.
</P>
<P>
   The human ``appreciation of time,'' he notes, ``is still
governed by the old three-score and ten'' biblical life span and
that frame ``enables us to relate to time on a certain scale.''
</P>
<P>
   But while the tempo of human activity may be to some extent
determined by our bodies (although, as Fortey observes, some
hyperactive humans nowadays seem to live ``on mice-time''), our
conceptions of time are highly elastic, ranging from the light
speed of intuition to the poet's intimation of eternity. In our own
century, our awareness of time has undergone extreme contractions
and enormous expansions, as instruments for measuring time have
become ever more precise, and as our knowledge of the earth's
history continues to be extended. Fortey, who has called himself
``a historian of the last 200 million years,'' nevertheless admits
that the eons of geological and evolutionary time remain difficult
to comprehend even for him, and that he finds the names of
geological periods _ Cambrian, Ordovician, and so on _ helpful in
giving concreteness to the numbers he works with. To this, we might
add our increasing consciousness of the subatomic world and the
universe itself, with their units of time so unfathomably
infinitesimal and incomprehensibly immense as to bring the
imagination to a standstill.
</P>
<P>
   All the more reason, perhaps, why we need not only to measure
time but, in the words of Randall Styers, assistant professor of
philosophy of religion at the Union Theological Seminary, ``to
invest it with meaning.'' Styers notes that the function of the
liturgical calendar, of which the Christian calendar is just one
instance, is ``to give shape to the passing of time'' by endowing
certain days or phases of the year with special significance. The
importance of ritual dates such as Christmas or Easter, in Styers'
view, is not so much to commemorate real events _ the actual date
of Christ's birth, for example, is a matter of considerable dispute
_ as to ``reflect important moments for the community and take the
community through its story, its own self-definition.''
</P>
<P>
   The calendar, in any culture and tradition, delineates the
contours of seasonal and shared time. Art, and especially music, is
a more individual means of molding time and giving a kind of shape
and meaning to our thoughts and emotions. For Steve Reich, a
composer and an observant Jew, religious and musical understandings
of time are salient, and to some extent interconnected. For him,
the liturgical form of the week, particularly the culminating point
of the Sabbath, provides a spiritually refreshing counterpoint to
the hurly-burly of contemporary secular time. And, even without
overt religious content, the temporal form of music, he says, is
``what saves me and other composers from mental breakdown.'' The
underlying beat of any piece of music functions as ``an abstract
grid without which you would be sliding around in nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   What about the year 2000, then, what kind of a marker and
milestone is it? It suggests a measure and a meaning; and on both
these scores, it belongs to the scale of time, which for us is the
central one _ the scale of human history. It's true that the date
derives from what was originally the Christian calendar, which was
not established until the sixth century A.D. But the Common Era
calendar, as it has come to be known, was officially adopted by the
United Nations, and therefore has become, in effect, the global
standard. Within this context, 2000 no longer refers to the
cyclical, ritual time of a particular faith, but to the more linear
chronology of historical time.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, it is historians themselves, accustomed as they are
to the capriciousness of dating, who are often most resistant to
the fascination of round numbers. Norman Davies, the author of
``Europe'' and ``The Isles,'' notes that ``professional historians
now rarely pay attention'' to the commonplace divisions in their
structuring of the past. For example, the 19th century has been
called by some historians ``the long century,'' and has had its run
extended to 1914; while our own 20th has sometimes been shrunk to
``the short century,'' lasting from the outbreak of World War I in
1914 to the fall of the Soviet Union in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Historians, then, cannot quite do away with epochs or eras, even
if theirs are modifications of the popular versions. But it's the
ringing punctuations of decades, centuries and millennia that
resonate in the world. They help us locate and orient ourselves in
the ever lengthening progress of human history.
</P>
<P>
   A millennium, especially, is a span of time to encourage wonder
and contemplation of the centuries it contains. Without such
signposts, our accumulated heritage might scramble itself into an
indiscriminate mass of facts, or recede into Shakespeare's ``dark
backward and abysm of time.'' With their symbolic aid, we might
just be able to reflect on the patterns of the human past, and
therefore conceive of a plausible human future.
</P>
<P>
   Have a good one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-99 1023EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991227.0052 </DOCNO>
