<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 10:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9661 &Cx1f; tad-z
a w BC-Y2K-WATCH-1230-COX     12-27 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-WATCH-1230-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TRACKING THE ARRIVAL OF THE NEW MILLENNIUM: A GUIDE FOR Y2K
WATCHERS
 &HT;    Advance for release Thursday, Dec. 30
 &HT;    EDS: ``Today'' in the lede refers to Thursday.
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rest your eyeballs today. Tomorrow, you may be
wearing them out in front of the television.
</P>
<P>
   New Year's Eve typically is a quiet news day, with reporters
doing little but reviewing the year's events and updating party
stories. But this Dec. 31 could prove to be extremely news-filled
because of threats posed worldwide by computer software flaws and
terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   For those who don't want to miss any important stories, set the
alarm clock for 6 a.m. EST Friday. That's when New Zealand will
become the first major nation to face the so-called Y2K bug, a
software flaw that could cause computers to misunderstand the new
date and malfunction. If hidden Y2K bugs are going to trigger
serious problems, such as power grid failures and
telecommunications breakdowns, Aucklanders will be among the first
to know it.
</P>
<P>
   As the Earth continues its 24-hour rotation, the threats will
pass from one time zone to the next. For Americans in the U.S.
Eastern time zone, the most dramatic three-hour portion of the day
may begin in the late afternoon when 2000 rolls from Moscow,
through the Middle East and over to Western Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Midnight arrives in Moscow at 4 p.m. EST. Computer experts fear
Y2K flaws will cause failures in many of Russia's vital services,
such as power generation, telecommunications and transportation.
It's even possible that aging nuclear power plants could shut down
or become dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Worries are so great the State Department authorized the
voluntary departure of employees and family members at the U.S.
embassy, and urged Americans to avoid traveling to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   But while midnight in Moscow will be tense, the next hour may be
even more worrisome. At 5 p.m. EST, the religious pilgrims packing
Israel will welcome the 2,000th anniversary of the birth of Jesus.
Security officials warn that some Christian fanatics could cause
violence, in hopes of triggering the Apocalypse. Islamic terrorists
also are believed to be planning attacks.
</P>
<P>
   During that same hour, midnight will come to Eastern Europe. The
countries there that used to be part of the old Soviet Union may be
the riskiest places on Earth, in terms of Y2K bugs. Those areas
have interlocking power systems and aging computers. The State
Department has issued travel warnings for Ukraine, Moldova and
Belarus because of the high likelihood of dangerous disruptions in
heat and electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Then at 6 p.m. EST, the world will be watching Pope John Paul II
celebrate the beginning of the 3rd millennium of Christianity,
along with about a half-million visitors. Italy is widely
considered to be poorly prepared for Y2K bugs, giving rise to
concerns about blackouts and transportation failures.
</P>
<P>
   At 7 p.m. EST, aviators will be waiting to see whether anything
bad happens during this hour, which marks midnight in Greenwich,
England. Because airlines worldwide operate on Greenwich Mean Time,
this would be the hour when any Y2K bugs would make themselves
known in air traffic control systems.
</P>
<P>
   If no big news has broken out by 7:30 p.m. EST, you might as
well go to dinner; the midnight moment will be passing over the
sparsely populated Atlantic Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Then at midnight EST, all eyes will turn to the nation's two
biggest party centers: New York City and Washington, D.C. Both
cities are planning blowout celebrations with countdowns and
fireworks, and both fear being targeted by terrorists. It'll be
tough to fully relax until midnight has made its way past Seattle,
San Francisco and Los Angeles, and finally clears Hawaii at 5 a.m.
EST.
</P>
<P>
   And even then, don't expect the fat lady to sing.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K experts say that many software flaws may not become apparent
until Monday, Jan. 3, when factories and offices re-open for
regular business. Other bugs won't appear until companies have gone
through their first billing cycle and employees have gotten their
paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   Even after January, the coast won't be clear. That's because
this February happens to have 29 days. The long February in Leap
Years often confuses computers. Computer programmers say we can't
let down our guard until March.
</P>
<P>
   Which means the first day is the year 2000 is just the start of
a very long vigil. Happy New Year.
</P>
<P>
   (Marilyn Geewax can be reached by e-mail at:
mgeewax(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
