specialist at the Boston Consulting Group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-99 1024EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991227.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 10:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9663 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-EXCESS-REVIEW-ART-2     12-27 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-EXCESS-REVIEW-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE TRAIL OF THE SABLE AND LEARJET SET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(The Week in Review) 
(jw) 
 By MONIQUE P. YAZIGI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``To live on little, with contented mind,'' may be the
classically proper attitude toward wealth, but ``little'' and
``contented'' aren't seen together very much these days. A more
appropriate motto would be Oscar Wilde's ``Nothing succeeds like
excess.''
</P>
<P>
   Between the remarkable American economy, which has been growing
for almost nine years, and the dot-com tsunami, which has not yet
crested, the past decade has been a period of unprecedented wealth
creation. Consider that in 1989 there were an estimated 1.9 million
people in the country worth $1 million or more. Today that number
has jumped to about 8 million. The number of American households
worth $10 million or more has also quadrupled over the period,
jumping to 275,000 from 65,000, said Edward Wolff, a professor of
economics at New York University and an expert on wealth.
</P>
<P>
   So much money is sloshing around that it seems to have
overwhelmed the last vestiges of Puritan guilt over spending it. As
the stock market and corporate profits rise, charities nationwide
report that donations from both individuals and companies are
falling. The very idea of wretched excess, of buying as vulgar and
wealth as morally dangerous, has given way to a display-and-play
ethos.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all millionaires and billionaires by the time they're
30,'' said Leonard Ely, a 76-year-old Silicon Valley captain of
industry turned philanthropist. Ask them for a chunk of their
newfound wealth, he added, and ``They'd say, `Look, I don't have my
Ferrari and my place in Tahoe, and you're telling me I should give
money away?'''
</P>
<P>
   The new attitude was on parade at the holiday party thrown by
the society furrier Dennis Basso at the House of the Redeemer on
East 95th Street off Fifth Avenue in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Two rows of black, chauffeured cars lined the block outside the
candlelit Episcopal sanctuary, as guests nibbled caviar and ladies
with newly sculpted faces worshipped, well, fur. Upstairs, Blaine
and Robert Trump held court in the library of the former Vanderbilt
mansion, while Kathy Hilton, wife of an heir to the hotel fortune,
received rave reviews on her pink mink.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Ms. Hilton's coup, sable is de rigueur among the
pelt-wearing classes this year. ``Darling, this was the year of
sable,'' declared Basso. ``They all had to have one.'' Downstairs,
standing next to a cloakroom full of sable coats costing about
$150,000 each, Joan Collins, the former diva on ``Dynasty,'' stood
near several 30-something men in black-tie, who quietly questioned
whether her high cheekbones were real. And Michele Herbert, a Park
Avenue socialite, kissed Basso in gratitude for her $20,000
hand-beaded Russian broadtail suit.
</P>
<P>
   Even Locust Valley, N.Y., the capital of lockjaw and faded
chintz, has lost its bearings. The parking lot of the Piping Rock
Club, once filled with members' 10-year-old ``beater'' paneled
station wagons, now fills up with 3-year-old BMWs instead (and the
children own Porsches).
</P>
<P>
   Is it a new Gilded Age, with many thousands of robber barons,
instead of just a few dozen?
</P>
<P>
   ``There are striking parallels,'' said Jean Strouse, the author
of ``Morgan: American Financier'' (Random House, 1999), who spent
15 years writing and researching the biography of J.P. Morgan
(1837-1913). ``The Internet is very parallel to the building of the
railroads, the telegraph system, the transatlantic cable. People
were buying and building yachts. Enormous floating palaces.
Elaborate houses in Newport. It was an unbelievably lavish time.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an unbelievably lavish time now. ``People seem to be
shopping at two in the morning, three in the morning. That's when
they buy the expensive items,'' said James Finkelstein, the founder
of Luxuryfinder.com, an online merchant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sold out of pashmina blankets at $995 apiece,'' he said.
``We sold out of pashmina pillows for $335. We sold a lot of
caviar. A lot, a lot of caviar.'' The caviar costs $1,150 per 500
grams, but it comes with beautiful mother-of-pearl caviar spoons.
</P>
<P>
   One couple flies their palm trees from Southampton to Palm Beach
in the winter (to keep the trees warm). They also told their
decorator to put down black and white floor tiles to match the
coats of their terriers.
</P>
<P>
   Anastasia Soare, the owner of Anastasia's salon in Beverly
Hills, has grown accustomed to emergency calls from clients just in
from Europe who must have their eyebrows done at once.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was desperate,'' said Ms. Soare of one midnight call. In
response, Ms. Soare, whose shop also perfects the eyebrows of Naomi
Campbell, Jennifer Lopez, Lara Flynn Boyle and Kate Capshaw, packed
up tools in her own home in Benedict Canyon and drove across town
to her client's home. There, she performed an emergency pluck, cut
and wax. Charge: $400 to $3,000 (the latter price for flying cross
country) for as little as a five-minute session.
</P>
<P>
   Others fly their linens to Paris to be dry-cleaned. ``It's well
worth it,'' said one women at a Park Avenue cocktail party, as she
tossed her purple pashmina shawl around her shoulders. It better
be, since the tab in some homes runs to $6,000-a-month.
</P>
<P>
   It's exhausting, all this spending. Ms. Herbert, who is married
to the chairman of Pantone, a company specializing in color
graphics, talked about how hectic it is to keep up with everything.
``Let me put it this way, it would be easier if I had a job!'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   To help them keep up, the rich are hiring helpers, and even
helpers for their helpers. Mark Simone, a 44-year-old bachelor who
lives between New York and Greenwich, Conn., flipped through his
black book the other day and recited how many women he knows who
have multiple social secretaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you know how common it is for these women who do
nothing to have two secretaries,'' Simone said. ``I can think of 20
who have two.'' He equated it to having a cat. ``When you're not
home all day, you need to get another one to keep the first one
company.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the Hamptons, the magic number for summer help was four: A
houseman (to change the light bulbs and make sure there's Diet Coke
on ice), a laundress, a chef and a housekeeper.
</P>
<P>
   Children are equally the beneficiaries of excess. It's there to
be seen on any rainy day outside Nightingale-Bamford, an all-girls
private school on the Upper East Side. Ten-year-olds stand in
front, calling their very own town cars on their very own cellular
phones. An entire seventh-grade class at another New York private
school flew to Barbados for a birthday weekend. And a doting father
recently paid $17,000 to rent the F.A.O. Schwarz flagship toy store
on Fifth Avenue for his 12-year-old daughter's birthday slumber
party.
</P>
<P>
   At 3 a.m. one 12-year-old turned to another, both dressed in
flannel feetsy pajamas, and said ``We'll be in business together.''
Her friend said, ``We'll be Greenberg and Leff.'' And they would
make lots of money because the first girl knew all the ``lawyer
words.'' She recited: ``Malpractice, liability.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Malpractice, liability,'' repeated her friend.
</P>
<P>
   One young woman, who spent 13 years in the New York private
school system and is a freshman at Cornell University, pointed out
the importance of the status of such things. ``Cell phones, town
cars, country houses, and kids whose parents who have really cool
jobs have no problem making friends,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said that vacations were really important, too. ``If you go
to Florida for vacation you're not going away,'' the girl said.
Why? ``On a vacation you have to see clear water; in Florida, the
water is murky.''
</P>
<P>
   So, the rich at least, have got what they wished for. Which is
exactly what the gods are supposed to give us _ before they drive
us mad.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-99 1030EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991227.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 10:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1261 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-EXCESS-REVIEW-ART-2     12-27 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-EXCESS-REVIEW-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE TRAIL OF THE SABLE AND LEARJET SET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(The Week in Review) 
(jw) 
 By MONIQUE P. YAZIGI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``To live on little, with contented mind,'' may be the
classically proper attitude toward wealth, but ``little'' and
``contented'' aren't seen together very much these days. A more
appropriate motto would be Oscar Wilde's ``Nothing succeeds like
excess.''
</P>
<P>
   Between the remarkable American economy, which has been growing
for almost nine years, and the dot-com tsunami, which has not yet
crested, the past decade has been a period of unprecedented wealth
creation. Consider that in 1989 there were an estimated 1.9 million
people in the country worth $1 million or more. Today that number
has jumped to about 8 million. The number of American households
worth $10 million or more has also quadrupled over the period,
jumping to 275,000 from 65,000, said Edward Wolff, a professor of
economics at New York University and an expert on wealth.
</P>
<P>
   So much money is sloshing around that it seems to have
overwhelmed the last vestiges of Puritan guilt over spending it. As
the stock market and corporate profits rise, charities nationwide
report that donations from both individuals and companies are
falling. The very idea of wretched excess, of buying as vulgar and
wealth as morally dangerous, has given way to a display-and-play
ethos.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all millionaires and billionaires by the time they're
30,'' said Leonard Ely, a 76-year-old Silicon Valley captain of
industry turned philanthropist. Ask them for a chunk of their
newfound wealth, he added, and ``They'd say, `Look, I don't have my
Ferrari and my place in Tahoe, and you're telling me I should give
money away?'''
</P>
<P>
   The new attitude was on parade at the holiday party thrown by
the society furrier Dennis Basso at the House of the Redeemer on
East 95th Street off Fifth Avenue in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Two rows of black, chauffeured cars lined the block outside the
candlelit Episcopal sanctuary, as guests nibbled caviar and ladies
with newly sculpted faces worshipped, well, fur. Upstairs, Blaine
and Robert Trump held court in the library of the former Vanderbilt
mansion, while Kathy Hilton, wife of an heir to the hotel fortune,
received rave reviews on her pink mink.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Ms. Hilton's coup, sable is de rigueur among the
pelt-wearing classes this year. ``Darling, this was the year of
sable,'' declared Basso. ``They all had to have one.'' Downstairs,
standing next to a cloakroom full of sable coats costing about
$150,000 each, Joan Collins, the former diva on ``Dynasty,'' stood
near several 30-something men in black-tie, who quietly questioned
whether her high cheekbones were real. And Michele Herbert, a Park
Avenue socialite, kissed Basso in gratitude for her $20,000
hand-beaded Russian broadtail suit.
</P>
<P>
   Even Locust Valley, N.Y., the capital of lockjaw and faded
chintz, has lost its bearings. The parking lot of the Piping Rock
Club, once filled with members' 10-year-old ``beater'' paneled
station wagons, now fills up with 3-year-old BMWs instead (and the
children own Porsches).
</P>
<P>
   Is it a new Gilded Age, with many thousands of robber barons,
instead of just a few dozen?
</P>
<P>
   ``There are striking parallels,'' said Jean Strouse, the author
of ``Morgan: American Financier'' (Random House, 1999), who spent
15 years writing and researching the biography of J.P. Morgan
(1837-1913). ``The Internet is very parallel to the building of the
railroads, the telegraph system, the transatlantic cable. People
were buying and building yachts. Enormous floating palaces.
Elaborate houses in Newport. It was an unbelievably lavish time.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an unbelievably lavish time now. ``People seem to be
shopping at two in the morning, three in the morning. That's when
they buy the expensive items,'' said James Finkelstein, the founder
of Luxuryfinder.com, an online merchant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sold out of pashmina blankets at $995 apiece,'' he said.
``We sold out of pashmina pillows for $335. We sold a lot of
caviar. A lot, a lot of caviar.'' The caviar costs $1,150 per 500
grams, but it comes with beautiful mother-of-pearl caviar spoons.
</P>
<P>
   One couple flies their palm trees from Southampton to Palm Beach
in the winter (to keep the trees warm). They also told their
decorator to put down black and white floor tiles to match the
coats of their terriers.
</P>
<P>
   Anastasia Soare, the owner of Anastasia's salon in Beverly
Hills, has grown accustomed to emergency calls from clients just in
from Europe who must have their eyebrows done at once.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was desperate,'' said Ms. Soare of one midnight call. In
response, Ms. Soare, whose shop also perfects the eyebrows of Naomi
Campbell, Jennifer Lopez, Lara Flynn Boyle and Kate Capshaw, packed
up tools in her own home in Benedict Canyon and drove across town
to her client's home. There, she performed an emergency pluck, cut
and wax. Charge: $400 to $3,000 (the latter price for flying cross
country) for as little as a five-minute session.
</P>
<P>
   Others fly their linens to Paris to be dry-cleaned. ``It's well
worth it,'' said one women at a Park Avenue cocktail party, as she
tossed her purple pashmina shawl around her shoulders. It better
be, since the tab in some homes runs to $6,000-a-month.
</P>
<P>
   It's exhausting, all this spending. Ms. Herbert, who is married
to the chairman of Pantone, a company specializing in color
graphics, talked about how hectic it is to keep up with everything.
``Let me put it this way, it would be easier if I had a job!'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   To help them keep up, the rich are hiring helpers, and even
helpers for their helpers. Mark Simone, a 44-year-old bachelor who
lives between New York and Greenwich, Conn., flipped through his
black book the other day and recited how many women he knows who
have multiple social secretaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you know how common it is for these women who do
nothing to have two secretaries,'' Simone said. ``I can think of 20
who have two.'' He equated it to having a cat. ``When you're not
home all day, you need to get another one to keep the first one
company.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the Hamptons, the magic number for summer help was four: A
houseman (to change the light bulbs and make sure there's Diet Coke
on ice), a laundress, a chef and a housekeeper.
</P>
<P>
   Children are equally the beneficiaries of excess. It's there to
be seen on any rainy day outside Nightingale-Bamford, an all-girls
private school on the Upper East Side. Ten-year-olds stand in
front, calling their very own town cars on their very own cellular
phones. An entire seventh-grade class at another New York private
school flew to Barbados for a birthday weekend. And a doting father
recently paid $17,000 to rent the F.A.O. Schwarz flagship toy store
on Fifth Avenue for his 12-year-old daughter's birthday slumber
party.
</P>
<P>
   At 3 a.m. one 12-year-old turned to another, both dressed in
flannel feetsy pajamas, and said ``We'll be in business together.''
Her friend said, ``We'll be Greenberg and Leff.'' And they would
make lots of money because the first girl knew all the ``lawyer
words.'' She recited: ``Malpractice, liability.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Malpractice, liability,'' repeated her friend.
</P>
<P>
   One young woman, who spent 13 years in the New York private
school system and is a freshman at Cornell University, pointed out
the importance of the status of such things. ``Cell phones, town
cars, country houses, and kids whose parents who have really cool
jobs have no problem making friends,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said that vacations were really important, too. ``If you go
to Florida for vacation you're not going away,'' the girl said.
Why? ``On a vacation you have to see clear water; in Florida, the
water is murky.''
</P>
<P>
   So, the rich at least, have got what they wished for. Which is
exactly what the gods are supposed to give us _ before they drive
us mad.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-99 1031EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
