<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 10:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9665 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-CAMPAIGN-DEBATES-AD     12-27 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CAMPAIGN-DEBATES-ADS-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT IF BRADLEY HAD CALLED GORE'S BLUFF? 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(jw) 
 By ADAM CLYMER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ On one level, Vice President Al Gore's
proposal to scrap all 30-second television spots in favor of
twice-weekly debates with former Sen. Bill Bradley was just what
the senator said it was: a campaign ploy. To be sure, it was a
modestly imaginative gambit that seemed to annoy Bradley by making
him defend the political system he prefers to deplore.
</P>
<P>
   But the idea is worth thinking about in two other contexts: as a
way of communicating with voters, and as a campaign spending
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   These days the only way most voters hear about Gov. George W.
Bush's views on education is by watching images of cute children
while listening to him promise local control, ``charters and
choice'' and phonics to teach reading. But if Gore's idea were
taken up, voters could hear candidates explain in depth what local
school boards should control and how much new plans would cost.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the Supreme Court banned campaign spending limits in
1976 as a violation of free speech, critics have sought indirect
ways to curb the spiraling costs of running for office.
</P>
<P>
   Their efforts became particularly urgent after politicians came
up with the idea of ``soft money'' donations in 1988. These are the
unlimited contributions made to party organizations by fat cats,
corporations and unions. The remaining contribution limits that the
Supreme Court had allowed became meaningless, and as a result
presidential elections today are hardly more regulated than they
were when the Watergate scandals led to the 1974 Federal Election
Campaign Act.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the dominant approach in Congress, backed by both
Democratic presidential candidates, is to ban soft money, which
theoretically goes to party building, but in fact buys thousands of
30-second spots _ both positive and negative _ about candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Legislation prohibiting soft money commands majority support in
Congress, but Republican filibusters in the Senate have killed it
twice since 1997. Meanwhile, both parties are raking in soft money
as fast as they can.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' claim to virtue, based on their votes against the
filibusters, is no stronger in practice than the Republicans', as
evidenced by last week's disclosure that Democratic Party officials
had set up committees to funnel such donations into several Senate
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's challenge to Bradley last week is another indirect
approach to a spending curb. He would forswear the most costly way
to spend campaign cash: the 30-second television spots, whose price
rises sharply each election cycle. If nobody bought 30-second spots
praising or condemning candidates like competing brands of laundry
detergent, campaign costs would drop dramatically _ and the level
of political discourse might rise.
</P>
<P>
   But nobody expects that to happen.
</P>
<P>
   In this campaign, Bradley, after three years out of politics,
plainly needs television ads to introduce himself to voters. And in
subsequent campaigns, at least one side will surely see the need
for commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, perhaps not. Look at the history of presidential
debates. After the Kennedy-Nixon encounters of 1960, there were no
presidential debates in 1964, 1968 or 1972. In each of those
election years, one candidate held a big lead and saw no point in
legitimizing his rivals by sharing a television screen. The
conventional wisdom at the time was that somebody would always have
an advantage, and so no presidential candidates would ever debate
again.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, Jimmy Carter was up about 30 points in the polls after
the Republican convention. But his campaign managers thought the
lead was anything but solid and figured that debates could show
Carter had the stature to be president. So when President Ford
challenged him to debate, Carter accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Today, general election debates are regular parts of
presidential campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, it is not easy to visualize a situation in which
both sides would reject campaign advertising. Even the spots people
say they hate _ the attack ads that Gore has promised not to use in
any event _ are effective. They help politicians get elected.
</P>
<P>
   Critics like Fred Wertheimer argue, though, that those ads also
make it harder for politicians to govern because of the cynicism
the spots engender. And Robert Teeter, a Republican consultant, is
among those who argue that the public may be getting fed up, that
it wants to hear directly from candidates through debates,
interviews, short speeches _ almost any forum where the candidate
is talking live without production gimmicks.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who insists he has not given up on the idea, said last
week: ``I think the American people would love it. I think they
find the current way of doing things pretty boring.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-99 1032EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
