<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 10:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9666 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN29-CO     12-27 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Racist profiling at work
 &HT;    (For release Dec. 29, 1999.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ It really isn't ``racial profiling'' so much as it is
``racist profiling,'' a far harsher term but one richly earned. The
oft-repeated incidents of singling out minorities, particularly
blacks, for immoderate exclusion or scrutiny hangs like an
albatross around the neck of this democracy-for-some.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the premier example of racist profiling is the case of
brothers, one 23 and the other 19, killed last month in an
automobile accident on an interstate highway near Fort Lauderdale.
Highway patrol officers on the scene reported that the brothers,
who were black, were traveling in the wrong direction and ran
headfirst into another car traveling in the correct direction. They
also suggested the dead may have been drunk or on drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The person in the other car was white and an FBI agent. He
lived.
</P>
<P>
   There was nobody to tell the Florida Highway Patrol which car
was traveling in the wrong direction; it was just an assumption
distorted as actuality; i.e., if there are two young black men and
a white guy in an accident, then the black men must have caused it.
</P>
<P>
   A month later, after their distraught mother's persistent
defense of her sons _ one was studying to be a computer engineer,
the other was dreaming of opening his own church _ plus some
scrutiny about how the officers on the scene came to make their
judgment, the story turned 180 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Now the facts are in, and the police have embarrassed
themselves. It was the FBI agent, with a blood-alcohol level twice
the legal limit, who wandered into the wrong lane and killed the
young brothers.
</P>
<P>
   The police were quick to call it ``an honest mistake.'' I would
agree, so long as the police concede that this type of ``honest
mistake'' is made often when it comes to determining culpability
between whites and blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Not far from there, in Miami Beach, a black couple having dinner
in a Thai restaurant saw there was a 15 percent service charge
added to their dinner bill. There was no such inclusion on bills
for whites at the next table. The owner of the establishment
claimed that blacks don't tip well and that's why the 15 percent is
on the checks of black customers.
</P>
<P>
   That's racist profiling. The owner and victims will meet next in
civil court.
</P>
<P>
   A little less conspicuous but an inequity nevertheless was an
incident I witnessed at a National Hockey League game in Sunrise,
Fla., three nights before Christmas Eve.
</P>
<P>
   As fans enter their sections of the arena, ushers require them
to show their ticket stubs. No problem there. But between periods,
most of those fans move back and forth to concession stands,
restrooms, etc. On the way back, it is rare _ very rare, almost
never _ that the usher will ask to see the ticket stub again.
</P>
<P>
   This night he did, to a 14-year-old or so black male. The
youngster produced the stub and continued on to his $60 seat below
me, joining his mother, father and brother. I don't know if he said
anything about the episode to his folks, and I suspect he didn't,
racist profiling being a fact of life for young blacks.
</P>
<P>
   I write of this, not so much to condemn the South Florida area
as a hotbed of racist profiling _ there's voluminous competition
around the rest of the country _ but to cite three incidents in
just one month's time that were visible. Imagine how much goes on
that we don't see or hear.
</P>
<P>
   More than 60 years ago, Miami Beach acquired a reputation that
blacks in the city after sundown had to produce identification or
be shuffled off to jail. The timeworn legend was that this was the
law.
</P>
<P>
   After diligent research and the finding of the actual 1936 city
ordinance, it is clear that all persons, black or white, working in
tourist-oriented jobs had to have the ID. Blacks, Negroes or
coloreds are not mentioned in the ordinance.
</P>
<P>
   But the rub was this: Blacks seen on the street after dark were
asked by police to produce their ID, whites weren't. The assumption
was that blacks had no business in the resort area unless they were
waiting tables or washing dishes.
</P>
<P>
   It was racist profiling in its early stages, backed by a
statewide policy of segregation. That buttressing element,
segregation, has been dissolved, but racist profiling seems to have
a life of its own.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
