<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 10:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9667 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-PREDICTIONS-REVIEW-     12-27 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-PREDICTIONS-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORGET THE MILLENNIUM. TRY TO PREDICT ONE WEEK.
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review) 
(jw) 
 By JENNY LYN BADER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Six shopping days left until the century cusp, and the average
shopper has stopped ordering bulk shipments of mineral water and
started making lunch dates for January. Pundits who spent the fall
debating portents of doom have begun making predictions about the
next hundred years and the next thousand.
</P>
<P>
   Awaiting the apocalypse couldn't have remained a national sport
for long. After all, the whole fun of a national sport is rooting
for some guy, no matter how messed up he is, and wondering whether
he'll prevail against incredible odds. If the Messiah showed up He
would just prevail. What fun is that? The final weeks of most
centuries have been more nerve-racking than the denouement of this
one.
</P>
<P>
   The first time a century ended, members of a desert religious
sect got themselves buried in Qumran with their graves facing north
so they could greet the Messiah when He resurrected them. He didn't
show.
</P>
<P>
   In the 990s, Christian priests took the Vikings to be the
biblical destroyers from Gog and Magog bringing the end of the
world. Turned out they were just Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   Today the world is still intact, despite gloomy predictions from
the heavy hitters of prophecy. The mystic Edgar Cayce, who
accurately predicted the stock market crash of 1929, predicted that
the American coasts would flood in 1998. Jeane Dixon, the
astrologer who foresaw John F. Kennedy's assassination, thought a
world war would be fought in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Most notably the world was supposed to explode this past July,
according to Nostradamus, who wrote cryptic prophetic verses in
1555 and usually hated to give a verifiable date. But he liked it
when numbers came in threes, so in one of his rare specific moods
he foretold the Great Fire of 1666: ``The blood of the just will be
required in London/burned by fire in thrice twenty and six.''
</P>
<P>
   In another precise moment, he pinpointed this past July as a
time of war and heaven-sent destruction: ``In the year 1999 seven
months,/From the sky will come a great King of Terror. ... Before
and afterwards Mars rules happily.'' Interpreters of the verse have
seen the King of Terror as a fusion weapon, a nuclear warhead or a
spaceship due to land around Independence Day. (Could he have been
anticipating the movie?)
</P>
<P>
   After July came and went, fans of eschatological prophecy calmed
down a bit. But the big breakthrough came in September, the start
of the academic year, with the arrival of next year's day planners,
the Filofaxes and the art calendars in stationery stores. Ancient
mystics did not have stationery stores and could remain riled up
for longer. Contemporary mystics had to face facts. How could time
both be ending and also be mapped out on so many glossy sheets of
cardboard? Anticipating the end suddenly seemed not a sign of faith
and imagination but just a good excuse to put off one's car
payments.
</P>
<P>
   But now that the mood has changed from predicting the end to
predicting the future, the time frame seems too long term. How can
we think about the next century or the next millennium, when it's
hard enough to tell what's going to happen this week?
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry. A round-up of predictions for the coming week
appears below. Unlike predictions for the year 3000, these can be
verified. Just keep this newspaper around until next Sunday.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
