<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 10:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9672 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-NEWYEAR-WARNINGS-TE     12-27 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NEWYEAR-WARNINGS-TEXT-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) 
 FLYING CORKS, KILLER POINSETTIAS AND OTHER HOLIDAY HAZARDS  (The
Week in Review) 
(jw) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the peak of the holiday season, and the air is filled with
apocalyptic warnings tied to the turn of the millennium. But there
is plenty more to worry about than serious threats like terrorism,
doomsday cults and Y2K calamities.
</P>
<P>
   As usual at this time of year, the perennial peril profiteers,
seasonal scolds and year-end yentas are busy issuing warnings and
advice on more mundane dangers. And with the clock winding down on
the century, the worry warts are in full throat, as evidenced by
the following alarming bulletins culled from recent press releases
and news reports.
</P>
<P>
   _ JOE SHARKEY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   YOU COULD POKE YOUR EYE OUT
</P>
<P>
   Is your Champagne Y2K ready? Before you open a bottle of your
favorite bubbly to toast the promise of a new millennium this New
Year's Eve, make sure it's cold.
</P>
<P>
   The American Academy of Ophthalmology, the world's largest
association of eye M.D.s (ophthalmologists), wants to remind you
that warm bottles of Champagne, coupled with bad technique, are
responsible for causing serious, blinding injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Every few months, academy spokesperson Anne Sumers M.D. sees the
devastating results: ... ruptured eyeballs, detached retinas, the
loss of an eye. Contrary to popular belief, Sumers says her
patients were not fooling around, recklessly aiming bottles at
people, but had simply reached for a warm bottle and popped the
cork.
</P>
<P>
   ``It usually doesn't happen with the first bottle of Champagne,
because it has been on ice, but with a third or fourth bottle that
hasn't been fully chilled. A warm bottle explodes much sooner and
with greater force than a cold bottle,'' said Sumers.
</P>
<P>
   And once it explodes, it's like a bullet.
</P>
<P>
   _ Press release from the American Academy of Ophthalmology &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WHY NOT STUFF THE TURKEY WITH OATMEAL
</P>
<P>
   How many times have you made a New Year's resolution to lose
five to 10 pounds that you gained during the holiday season? ...
New research suggests a novel strategy: eating a bowl of oatmeal
for breakfast might make it easier to stuff the turkey and not
yourself this holiday season. ..
</P>
<P>
   Death rates from heart attacks are relatively steady through
November and shoot up after Thanksgiving through Christmas, peaking
around the first of the year. This could be attributed to increased
food, alcohol and salt consumption and increased stress. ...
</P>
<P>
   _ Press release from the Quaker Oats Co. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NO HOLIDAY FOR JUNIOR
</P>
<P>
   With the hustle and bustle of the holiday season, parents toilet
training their toddlers may be tempted to put it on hold until
January. ``Don't give up,'' said Dr. Timothy Schum, lead researcher
on the most comprehensive toilet-training study ... ``Our research
shows that once you've moved a child out of diapers and into
disposable training pants, cloth training pants or underwear, you
can keep making progress. No matter how much the holidays disrupt
your schedule, hang in there and you'll keep moving forward.
Remember that the holidays are a time for family and memories and
even toilet training.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Press release from Kimberly-Clark, makers of Pull-Ups training
pants. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PET PERILS
</P>
<P>
   New Year's brings in a brand new year filled with the promise of
hope, prosperity, health and happiness. But be alert to any pet
hazards such as fun noisemakers [which) can frighten your pet,
causing your pet to bolt out an open door or window. ...
</P>
<P>
   Caution: Those adorable holiday costumes for your pets may be
cute at get-togethers or in family photos, but pet owners should be
wary of costumes which have rubber bands to keep them securely in
place. ... If rubber bands are accidentally left on the pet after
the fun of dressing up is over, the pet could chew off and swallow
them, causing choking. ... Resist the temptation to tie ribbons
around pets' necks for the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   -- From the Web site of Pawprints and Purrs, an animal welfare
organization (www.sniksnak.com/holidays.html) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don't let the family dog take a bite out of your special
occasion. Even a friendly dog can be overwhelmed and stressed out
with all the holiday excitement, says C.W. Meisterfeld Ph.D.,
canine psychoanalyst based in PETaluma, Calif. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Should your dog express any warning signs towards your guests
DON'T try to force the dog to socialize. It is far more prudent to
put Fido away until all guests have left,'' says Meisterfeld.
</P>
<P>
   _ Press release for Meisterfeld's School for Canine Training &AMP;
Education &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An unprecedented 62 percent of Americans buy gifts for their
pets. ... ``The holidays are the perfect time to think about
protecting your pet from accidents and illnesses,'' says Dr. Jim
Humphries, author and leading authority on veterinary care. ``One
trip to the emergency clinic for a pet who requires surgery after
ingesting tinsel or a toy is all it takes to understand the value
of Veterinary Pet Insurance.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Press release for Veterinary Pet Insurance &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
