</P>
<P>
   _ Press release for Veterinary Pet Insurance &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   I'LL BE IN A HOME FOR CHRISTMAS
</P>
<P>
   For many adults, those holiday visits to the old homestead that
are supposed to look like a Norman Rockwell painting end up feeling
more like ``The Scream.'' That's because the opening of gifts is
often accompanied by the opening of old wounds, grudges and
longstanding family arguments.
</P>
<P>
   However, area therapists and counselors specializing in family
issues say adults can take steps to minimize the chance for
conflict during holiday visits.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Harrisburg Patriot, Dec. 20 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TIME TO STOCK UP ON SLURPEES
</P>
<P>
   While 7-Eleven will offer its typical products, the company has
chosen to increase its order of certain items to reflect the Y2K
preparation guidelines from the American Red Cross and the
President's Council on the Year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The American Red Cross recommends that people prepare for Y2K
like they would for a serious storm, stocking up on bottled water,
batteries, candles, firewood, first-aid kits, flashlights, paper
products and nonperishable foods.
</P>
<P>
   _ Press release from 7-Eleven Inc. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GEEZ, DOC, ANYTHING ELSE TO WORRY ABOUT?
</P>
<P>
   It's holiday time! It's fun. And, as the song says, it's the
most wonderful time of the year. But beware! It can be the most
dangerous time of the year, too. ...
</P>
<P>
   Food that is not prepared properly or left on buffet tables too
long can become a breeding ground for deadly bacteria. ...
Half-consumed holiday drinks, especially a pretty punch that looks
like juice, can be very tempting to a child who may be up before
you the next morning. But just a few gulps of a holiday beverage
with alcohol in it can poison a child. .... Cigarette butts,
sometimes left in ashtrays or drink glasses after a holiday party,
can be toxic to little children.
</P>
<P>
   Holiday plants lend a festive mood to your home, but many plants
are a danger to children who may be curious about their taste.
</P>
<P>
   Spending time with family and special friends is my favorite
part of the holidays. But holiday visitors may bring personal care
products and medicines. ...
</P>
<P>
   Brightly colored pills and vitamins are very attractive to
children. Please, take the extra precautions if you have young ones
in your house, so you can all enjoy the holiday celebrations, the
family gatherings, the spirit of the season. Happy, healthy
holidays to all!
</P>
<P>
   _ Dr. Hank Clever, ``The Doctor Is In'' column, The St. Louis
Post-Dispatch &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-99 1039EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
