A9674 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN28-COX     12-27 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Progress seems to pass me by
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Progress, as far as I'm concerned, is a dirty
word, and planning ahead runs a close second. I'm just not good at
it.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, I seem to have spent most of my life playing catch-up.
Like the time my mother threw a Burdine's bag with two bras in it
on the bed and ordered me to put one of them on and I refused
saying I wasn't ready for that kind of stuff. I reminded her I was,
after all, (SET ITAL)only(END ITAL) 15.
</P>
<P>
   The reason the march of time always catches me flat-footed, I
suspect, is because I loathe change. Had it been left up to me,
Henry Ford would never have built the Model-T because there
wouldn't have been any of those round things for it to roll on.
</P>
<P>
   While all of my friends are experimenting with DVD and eBay, I'm
still happy with a cable-unready television and a 20-year-old VCR
that quit recording in 1983. And as for shopping the Internet?
Forget it. My L.L.Bean catalog has never let me down and when I
call them, a real person answers.
</P>
<P>
   I was barely 5 the morning my mother dressed me up, pinned a
handkerchief to my jumper, and dragged me kicking and screaming to
kindergarten. School didn't coincide with my plans for that day, I
complained. I wasn't ready. Some things in life are not optional,
she explained.
</P>
<P>
   And just about the time I found myself easing into the school
groove, somebody told me I was graduating. Say what? Sorry, I said,
I'm not ready to leave.
</P>
<P>
   GO! I was told. I went, but I had no idea what came next.
College, my mother said. Not ready, I said. Then, get a job, she
said. A WHAT?
</P>
<P>
   Soon my friends were settling down with husbands and learning to
cook. I was still trying to decide on a university. About the time
they were starting families, I was looking for a job.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, I came up with a husband of my own (SET ITAL)and(END
ITAL) a stove, but I still didn't get it. And then my son came
along. One day he was 21-inches long and I was wrapping him in
flannel jammies _ the next he was 6 feet 5 and we couldn't find
jeans long enough for his legs. One day he was this spiffed-up
little kid climbing the too-tall stairs of a big blue schoolbus,
and the next he was standing in a garden promising to love, honor,
and obey while I wondered if he had enough clean clothes for the
honeymoon.
</P>
<P>
   And now an entire century has gotten away from me and once
again, I've been caught with my plans down. There is no time to
build a backyard bunker and stock it with automatic weapons so I
can shoot the neighbors if they try to steal my food and water. Nor
is there time to withdraw my life savings and stuff it into the
mattress.
</P>
<P>
   This morning a friend called to ask if my computer was
2000-ready. I told him I didn't know and asked what it might take
to accomplish that. An ominous cluck was his reply followed by a
suggestion that if I had to ask, it was probably already too late.
And when I told him the Underwood had a new ribbon in it he asked
me how I planned to get online with a 1938 typewriter.
</P>
<P>
   I do have a month's supply of cat food in the pantry, however,
and four 5-gallon jugs of water the Culligan man left in the
basement last week. And if the power goes off and with it the
boiler that heats the house, I still have the gas logs in the
fireplace. And should the natural gas flow be interrupted, then I
guess the cat and I will go sit in the car with the heater running
until it comes back on ... or until we run out of gas because the
pumps at Tom's Sunoco have glitched.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, the whole millenium thing has passed me by so I've
decided not to worry about any of it. My plan is to take the cat
and go to bed early on the 31st and set the alarm for July, by
which time the entire mess will have straightened itself out and no
one will discover that, as usual, I've turned up a day late and a
dollar short.
</P>
<P>
   Happy 2000!
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison,
</P>
<P>
   Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
