<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 10:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9676 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-INTERNET-FUTURE28-COX     12-27 1657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-FUTURE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Taking the Internet out of `the dark ages'
 &HT;    By Heather Cocks
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Above Alan Tannenbaum's desk, overlooking his
high-tech gadgets and powerful computers, hangs an eerily prescient
picture.
</P>
<P>
   The illustration depicts a woman wearing her World Wide Web
browser. A portable computer connected to a headset projects a tiny
computer screen in front of her eye, letting her see and surf
simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   As Tannenbaum talks, the picture seems increasingly like a nod
to his vision of the Internet's evolution. He predicts the Internet
will ascend to a technological level totally free of the clunky
computers and tangle of wires that bound _ and still bind _ this
waning decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in the dark ages, we really are,'' said
Tannenbaum, senior technical staff member for IBM Corp.'s corporate
Ease-of-Use group in Austin. ``Wireless will be the key. We're
going to see computing shrink and disappear into other devices,
letting us get at the Internet through things we can't even imagine
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   His words echo the pie-in-the-sky idealism of early 1990s
Internet users, who rang in the decade enamored of the then-private
computer network and the vast, mysterious promise it held. Even so,
few expected the Internet to explode like it has.
</P>
<P>
   Global business-to-consumer sales over the Internet surged 179
percent this year, becoming a $31.2 billion industry on pace to top
$380 billion in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   And with 160 million global users and climbing, the Internet has
blossomed from a private playground into a diverse hybrid medium _
part information hotbed, part economic model _ that analysts say
will become increasingly pervasive in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   They might not don cyborg-chic headgear like the woman gracing
Tannenbaum's wall, but many of the 500 million people expected to
connect to the Internet in 2003 will do so on devices less
conventional than today's personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   Computer makers are already trading traditional, fully-loaded
beige boxes for stylish designs that encase very basic,
Internet-centric machines. Austin-based Netpliance Inc. and Pacific
Bell took it a step further this year, unveiling small portable
machines just for e-mailing and limited online shopping. Prototypes
have appeared for Internet-ready refrigerators and cars.
</P>
<P>
   Tannenbaum, who in 25 years at IBM has literally witnessed the
Internet's development, predicts the fashion industry will shrink
Web connections even further. In New York City this past October,
InfoCharm Inc. staged a fashion show where statuesque models
strutted the catwalk wearing Web connections and keyboards sewn
into shirts, pants and jackets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fashion will be a critical part of the success of Internet
devices,'' Tannenbaum said. ``Once people start wearing these tools
built into our belts and watches and shoes, then no one will want
to walk around with just the standard watch or shoe any more. The
computer industry will take that into account.'' Some claim content
will again reign supreme, at the expense of traditional media.
Other pundits espouse Tannenbaum's belief that wireless Web access
will define the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   At work, where a wall of framed patents and awards herald his
IBM career, Tannenbaum is already part of the way there.
</P>
<P>
   A small antenna turns his laptop into a wireless device, which
he totes through the hallways without severing his Internet
connection. A second laptop sits idly on his desk, its sole
function to forward important e-mails to Tannenbaum's pager when he
is away from the office.
</P>
<P>
   One spiral notebook and a thin stack of papers sit nearby, tidy
relics of an age when paper memos provided the most important link
between corporate departments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ordinary correspondence is a thing of the past,'' Tannenbaum
said. ``When we had big documents to print, everyone would worry
about how it looked on paper, but today paper itself is unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not the Internet turns the paperless office into a
worldwide reality, most analysts agree that it will continue to
spur a total shift in the way people view computing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very exciting energy,'' said Barry Parr, an analyst
withresearch company International Data Corp. ``The Internet has
become an honest-to-God mainstream thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different world even from last year, and we realize
it's just at the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   A GLOBAL KISS
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to my page! I kiss you!!'' proclaims the large black
text on the Web site of Mahir, a Turkish man whose goofy,
self-promoting page has became an Internet phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   Mahir's site is representative of a familiar Internet
occurrence: Surfers stumbled on his Web site and e-mailed their
friends. Like wildfire, word of the site swept the globe, spawning
at least 15 parodies and enticing millions _ for no particular
reason other than curiosity _ to e-mail Mahir or check out photos
of him posing by his car, sunbathing, or engrossed in ping-pong.
His site now accepts advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a modern miracle,'' Parr said. ``We've entered this age
where people become Internet celebrities not based on anything but
that they did something mildly amusing.''
</P>
<P>
   In this decade, arguably the most essential societal turning
point was the invention of the Web, an easy-to-use graphic
interface that triggered the Internet's explosion in 1995 and
propelled it into popular consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Mahir's sudden stardom also exemplifies the Internet's
extraordinary use as a forum for meeting and communicating with new
people. Today roughly 10 percent of Internet users have their own
home page, and 25 percent have at least one close friend they've
met online, Parr said.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, PC prices have plummeted, and customers can get
three-figure rebates _ sometimes free PCs _ in exchange for signing
long-term contracts with various Internet service providers. Still,
increasingly cognizant of the Internet's undying consumer appeal,
this year a host of computer companies began making machines geared
toward simplifying network access.
</P>
<P>
   In late November, Dell released its Webpc, a stripped-down
computer optimized for Internet use. That and the similar iPaq from
Compaq Computer Corp., Dell's Houston-based rival, are the latest
entries in a market evolution sparked in 1998 by Apple Computer
Corp.'s plug-and-play iMac.
</P>
<P>
   To Parr, that underscores the degree to which the Internet's
popularity will shape the computer industry. While shopping for the
right machine for his mother, Parr realized hardware is a headache
for most people _ they just want simple devices that access the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are buying computers because they want to get onto the
Net, not because they actually want computers,'' said the analyst.
``My mother doesn't want a 'technology solution,' she just wants to
e-mail and play bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   E-COMMERCE PLAYS BIG ROLE
</P>
<P>
   If you did any holiday shopping online this year, you helped
spur the fastest growing sector of the Internet economy:
e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Since last year, the number of e-commerce companies has doubled
and their revenues swelled 127 percent, according to a study by the
Center for Research in Electronic Commerce at the University of
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   This holiday season alone, e-commerce companies are expected to
take in between $6 billion and $15 billion in revenues _ a
phenomenal amount of money for a sector that barely registered two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Tannenbaum of IBM readily admits to feeding into the frenzy. An
avid collector of antique books _ his passion is Lewis Carroll _ he
traded piles of catalogs and snail-mail missives for online
auctions, chat rooms, libraries and e-mail networks. Through
browsing and buying online, Tannenbaum quickly built his collection
to 2,000 items.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world is a marketplace,'' Tannenbaum said. ``I even have a
Mastercard that's just for Internet shopping.''
</P>
<P>
   Parr said he hopes the new decade quiets the e-commerce buzz,
molding the network back into a true information medium and less of
a shopping tool.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope we stop talking about it, because there's so much more
to the Internet than that,'' Parr said. ``It's like when the
telephone comes along and all anyone can talk about is
telemarketing. Content should be king.''
</P>
<P>
   If that transformation happens, it will hinge on wireless
technology, according to both Tannenbaum and UT professor Andrew
Whinston, who heads the school's e-commerce research efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Mobile phones with built-in Internet browsers are already
becoming a bridge between the wired world and the wearable Web,
delivering information with a portable immediacy desktop computers
currently lack. As constant connectivity becomes ubiquitous,
Whinston said he expects to see more books, newspapers and
magazines published entirely online, redefining traditional
perceptions of news and information.
</P>
<P>
   It's hardly a new idea _ pundits envisioned the death of
traditional media earlier in the decade when the Web rose to
prominence. But wireless adds a critical dimension to the debate
that Whinston claims changes it from theory into inevitability.
</P>
<P>
   ``The view will be, what happened six hours ago is history,''
Whinston said. ``If you want to know what's happening right this
minute, you want information delivered to a wireless device. If
companies can't respond to that need, they'll lose ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, spending too much time predicting the Internet's future
can be futile.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the online innovations achieved in the past five
years were largely unforeseen _ and unprecedented _ when the decade
began.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years out is too far to predict,'' Tannenbaum said. ``Five
years is too far. Every year we get more advanced, but more
possibilities crop up.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 10 years, we'll probably look back and laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
