<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Yahoo's magazine rings in '00 by picking best of Web
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Given the approaching end of the year and century,
it's time for ``best of'' lists. Yahoo Internet Life features in
its January issue a ``Top of the Net'' list of the 100 best Web
sites for 2000. There are also several stories that look back on
the year online and forward to the coming year, as well as
examining the most popular sites now and for the future. You'll
find few surprises in what's been popular among sites. Topping the
list of Internet sites this past year was, for example, the one
promoting the film ``Star Wars: Episode I.''
</P>
<P>
   ON CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   The holiday season brings the release of computer CD games
ranging from classic to modern. In the classic category is the
latest version of mah-jongg, published by Activision as ``Shanghai:
Second Dynasty.'' This version includes a vast assortment of
mah-jongg games. You can play against the clock or against
opponents. ``Second Dynasty'' is available for both Macs and PCs.
</P>
<P>
   For those with modern tastes, Activision has also released the
latest version of ``Quake,'' called ``Quake III.'' This is a very
violent game, so parents and those who find this genre offensive
beware. What's new is the number of warriors players can choose
from and the graphics. Everything now, of course, is 3-D. ``Quake
III'' is available only for PCs with Windows 95 or higher.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE
</P>
<P>
   Now for something completely different. If you're sick of all
the celebrity hype, check out a site called Quirked. The site
features pictures of celebrities distorted through Kai's Power Goo.
You'll find, for example, Al Gore twisted into the Joker. Another
favorite is Leonardo DiCaprio converted into a Spock look-alike. Or
how about John Travolta with a head like Jabba the Hut? You get the
idea. You'll find Quirked at www.quirked.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
