<SLUG> BC-CYBERSCENE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Need some tech support? If you can
 &HT;    get online, sites are filled with advice
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As sure as Christmas, some of you will have trouble
with that new computer you got as a holiday gift.
</P>
<P>
   If it's the only way you have of getting onto the World Wide
Web, you'll have to make do with help from friends or dial the
company's support line by telephone. But if you have another
computer and can get on the Web, there are literally dozens of free
sites that offer computer advice and help.
</P>
<P>
   We'll start with PC Help Desk, a really fine service offered
from the site located at www
</P>
<P>
   .pc-helpdesk.com/.
</P>
<P>
   There are rich databases of information, arranged by category,
on this page, so you may be able to find the answer simply by
clicking your mouse. But there are many other ways of getting help
here, including real-time online chat with other users and by
e-mail. You'll also find Y2K advice, just in case the bug bites you
New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   The e-mail service probably is the most valuable, since you can
ask a specific question and get the answer by mail.
</P>
<P>
   CyberNet Information Station at www.cyberpc.com/ seems to be
geared toward offering help with Internet and Web questions. But
there also are databases that offer to help with Microsoft Windows.
This site also has a download section where you can find updates
for the programs you use, drivers (the small software programs used
by devices such as printers and modems) and utility programs that
help you make adjustments to Windows.
</P>
<P>
   TipWorld has nothing at all to do with horse racing. It is a
good bet, however, that you'll get help at
www.tipworld.com/0,2724,,0.html for your PC woes. The best feature
of this site is its organization. The PC tips are organized into
logical areas such as operating systems, the Internet, graphics,
computer care and networks.
</P>
<P>
   As is true with the previous site, you'll find a download area
for shareware and freeware programs.
</P>
<P>
   While many other sites offer general computer help, some of the
best advice comes directly from the source: the company that sold
you the computer or software. Almost certainly you'll find the Web
address in the manuals that came with your programs and computer.
Try those sites first.
</P>
<P>
   Also remember that the Microsoft site is massive and _ if your
questions or problems concern Windows or another Microsoft program
_ it's an excellent resource. The site is located at
www.microsoft.com. But since there is so much information stored
here, you'll almost certainly need to use the search feature at the
site.
</P>
<P>
   Intel, which makes the chips that power many PCs, has a site at
www.intel.com. As is true with the Microsoft site, you'll find
helpful information here. If your computer is powered by the AMD
chip _ which competes with Intel chips _ go to the site at
www.amd.com.
</P>
<P>
   Apple Macintosh owners can find help and an excellent source of
information at www.apple
</P>
<P>
   .com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
