<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAC-REPORT28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Take care: Shareware might not be Y2K-ready
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's true that most Macs are Y2K-compliant, but some
may still experience problems with the coming ofthe new year.
</P>
<P>
   The problem isn't with the Mac per se but with the software that
runs on it. Specifically, all that shareware you've been
downloading through the years.
</P>
<P>
   Think about it. Much of this stuff has been discontinued or not
upgraded for months, if not years. It's this type of unsupported
software that could trip up many a Mac user.
</P>
<P>
   A suggestion: Clean out any shareware program, be it a solitaire
game or battle tanks, that you're not absolutely sure has been
upgraded for Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   You can always download another version after the new year when
programmers will be re-releasing rewritten software.
</P>
<P>
   A bit extreme? Perhaps. But in this case it's better to be safe
than sorry.
</P>
<P>
   Another potential problem is using files originally formatted in
PC applications. These files can't take advantage of Macs' built-in
Y2K savvy. No one knows exactly what these files might do to your
Mac, but it sure won't be pretty.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just PC files that could mess with your Mac's brain.
There are plenty of shareware and custom scripts written for big
programs such as Word, Excel and FileMaker that very well might not
be designed to handle 2000.
</P>
<P>
   If you depend on any such scripts or shareware, be sure to
double-check them to make sure they're Y2K-compliant.
Unfortunately, that's no easy task _ especially if you receive this
stuff from a friend of a friend.
</P>
<P>
   The message here is not to panic but to be alert. Seek out
patches online for your favorite shareware and scripts. If you can
afford to, dump the stuff you can't upgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that the Mac itself can process dates after the
beginning of the New Year. How far ahead they can read future dates
varies, though, depending on what operating system your Mac is
running.
</P>
<P>
   The operating system is the software that comes inside your Mac,
controlling everything from the way the screen looks to how
software runs. The original Mac systems can read dates through Feb.
6, 2040. The newer systems can read dates through 29940.
</P>
<P>
   Apple has been trumpeting the Y2K compliance of its machines
since the Super Bowl, when it ran ads pointing out this fact.
</P>
<P>
   The company has also assembled online a formidable database
about what machines and components it has tested to date. You'll
find this site at www.apple.com
</P>
<P>
   /about/year2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
