<HEADER>
A9696 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-NETWATCH28-COX     12-27 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Companies' core values ring true
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Time magazine calls it dotcommunism.
</P>
<P>
   Others, like Amazon.com's Jeff Bezos and MindSpring's Charles
Brewer, prefer to call it ``core values and beliefs.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a set of principles that guide the direction of a company.
Other online companies have similar core values _ or at least they
say they do. It's trendy in the dot-com business to say your
company has core values written down somewhere. At the turn of the
last century, many millionaires of the industrial age had just one
guiding principle: Make as much money as possible, as quickly as
possible. But the online world is a kinder, gentler place, if you
believe everything you read.
</P>
<P>
   Out at Amazon's Coffeyville, Kan., distribution center, Time
reports that huge banners hang from the ceiling with phrases like
``Our vision is the world's most customer-centric company.''
Another banner is devoted to the company's six core values:
Customer obsession, ownership, bias for action, frugality, high
hiring bar and innovation.
</P>
<P>
   WINNING FORMULA
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile in Atlanta, Internet service provider MindSpring has
been winning over subscribers and employees with its 10 core values
and beliefs, or the ``cv&AMP;b's'' as they are known to staffers.
</P>
<P>
   They also decorate the walls and even the business cards of
MindSpring employees. At the last MindSpring shareholders meeting,
each of the company's executives took turns reading the core values
out loud.
</P>
<P>
   EarthLink, the Internet service provider that will merge with
MindSpring early next year, has its own list of values and beliefs.
Even the kids working on that Internet start-up venture in the
garage down the street from your house probably try to work the
phrase ``core values'' into a sentence when describing their Web
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   This idea of putting the customer first, honoring commitments
and thinking of ways to make your customers happy is kind of sweet.
</P>
<P>
   In the boom economy of the '90s, the notion of core values seems
kind of quaint _ like something out of a Frank Capra movie from the
1930s. Imagine Jimmy Stewart as the head of an online business
lecturing his handful of loyal staffers and his director of
marketing (Donna Reed or Maureen O'Hara, perhaps) on the importance
of promptly answering every e-mail and keeping every customer
happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gosh darn it!'' Stewart would have yelled at his
earnest-looking group of Web designers, coders and programmers.
``If we don't put the customer first, we'll never be able to take
this company public! Now everybody go have some more free lattes
and get back to work!''
</P>
<P>
   The thing with the dot-com companies and their core values is
that they mean what they say. Even the most hard-boiled Wall Street
analyst will tell you these companies aren't kidding when they tell
CNBC or Time the customer is always right.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the idea of following the Golden Rule is a throwback to
the days when these companies didn't have a hope or a share of
stock in the world. When Brewer began MindSpring in 1993, he said
he wanted to start the kind of company he'd want to work for and
drew up the original core values that are now part of MindSpring's
legend.
</P>
<P>
   But when you hit the big time, with its initial public
offerings, sky-high stock prices, and offices, call centers and
distribution centers all over the country, it's harder to have
thousands of employees who are all fervent believers in one set of
principles. And cynics will say having a guiding set of principles
is just a gimmick and, at the very worst, a cheap way to motivate
employees into believing their hard work is for the greater good,
not simply to line the pockets of the founder and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com was a crazy scheme Bezos cooked up with just a 30
percent chance of making it big. Brewer had no idea he'd be the
chairman of the nation's second-largest ISP. Maybe they just
decided if they were going to go for broke, they might as well do
it with a little class.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
