<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RocketChips blasts speeds to megabits
 &HT;    By Kirk Ladendorf
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ You've got to like the name: RocketChips Inc. is
way cool.
</P>
<P>
   But the name isn't why Moises Robinson wanted to work for the
tiny chip startup based in Minneapolis. He liked the vision and the
high-growth markets the company was attacking, along with the
chance to get in with a promising company before a public stock
offering.
</P>
<P>
   So Robinson, a 31-year-old native of Panama and an engineering
graduate of Texas A&AMP;M University, left a job with Oak Technology in
Austin in 1998 to start the Austin office of RocketChips.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a year and a half later, the Austin design office has
15 employees and is nearing completion of its first chip _ a
communications chip based on a high-speed connection technology,
called FireWire, that joins computers and other products such as
digital camcorders.
</P>
<P>
   RocketChips brags that it designs the hard stuff _
communications chips that employ mixed-signal designs, with both
digital and analog circuits on the same chip.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are doing some of the difficult things'' in communications
chip design, Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Added company Chief Executive Ray Johnson, ``The drug of choice
today is bandwidth, and we are one of the pushers.''
</P>
<P>
   The chip was designed for Faraday Technology Corp. of Taiwan,
which wants to break into the emerging FireWire connectivity
market, but RocketChips can sell the chip _ or part of it _ to
other companies.
</P>
<P>
   Privately held RocketChips guards its financial information
closely. It has raised $15 million in venture capital and it has
received licensing revenues from other electronics companies. Its
first three designs are still several months away from going into
volume production.
</P>
<P>
   FireWire looks like a good market to play in. The high-speed
connectivity technology was invented by Apple Computer Inc. and
became a public standard in 1995. Research firm Cahners In-Stat
Group predicts the market is about to explode, from shipments of
about 10 million units in 1999 to nearly 200 million units
(including computers, video camcorders and printers) in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   The current version of FireWire is very quick _ it can move data
at speeds ranging from 100 megabits per second to 400 megabits per
second. And there is an even faster version of the technology is in
the works.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a high-bandwidth application, particularly if you
have audio and video content, then FireWire is a very elegant
solution,'' said Mark Kirstein, vice president of research at
Cahners In-Stat.
</P>
<P>
   FireWire is fast and it is also ``peer-to-peer.'' That means
that a digital video camcorder with a FireWire connection can
communicate directly with a printer with the same connection
without going through a computer.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of startup companies are working on FireWire-related
chips, Kirstein said, but RocketChips is the only one that has
taken on the analog part of the solution.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's next challenge is to double the size of the Austin
design center in the next year so the company can turn out more
designs. RocketChips also has design centers in Minneapolis and in
Ames, Iowa, where it has a close relationship with Iowa State
University. The design teams are connected by high-speed telephone
lines so engineers can ship complex computer files back and forth.
</P>
<P>
   Mixed-signal design capabilities are going to be crucial for
high-speed communications chips, Robinson said, so his company
already is attracting the interest of other chip companies that
want to partner with it new chip designs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people rooting for us in the industry,''
Robinson said. ``I think we have something big going on here.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
