<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-TRENDS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pass the popcorn: '99 movie trends
 &HT;    By Robert Sims
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _
</P>
<P>
   Now selling licenses for Gungan hunting season: Jar Jar Binks _
perceived racial stereotype and subject of numerous Internet death
threats _ symbolized the aggressively infantile nature of ``Star
Wars Episode 1: The Phantom Menace.'' And this prequel's long
stretches of mundane exposition and overwhelming emphasis on
special effects revealed that George Lucas has lost his touch after
a 22-year sabbatical from directing.
</P>
<P>
   Best-kept secret: Know anyone who spilled the beans after
experiencing ``The Sixth Sense''?
</P>
<P>
   Two reasons for the Academy of Motions Pictures and Sciences to
create a special Best Adolescent acting category: Kimberly J. Brown
in ``Tumbleweeds'' and Haley Joel Osment in ``The Sixth Sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Time to invest $400 in a camcorder: ``The Blair Witch Project,''
a creepy tale shakily shot on video for less than the price of a
new car, raked in $140 million at the box office this past summer.
</P>
<P>
   Been There, Seen That, Enough Already: Hollywood churned out the
unnecessary remakes ``Jakob the Liar,'' ``The Out-of-Towners,''
``The Haunting,'' ``The House on Haunted Hill,'' ``The King and
I,'' ``Anna and the King'' and ``The Thomas Crown Affair.'' And
attempts to bring TV rerun staples ``My Favorite Martian,''
``Inspector Gadget'' and ``Wild, Wild West'' to the silver screen
proved less entertaining than a Ron Popeil infomerical.
</P>
<P>
   Much ado about nothing: The relatives of David Berkowitz's
victims condemned Spike Lee for employing the Son of Sam murders as
a backdrop to ``Summer of Sam,'' but Lee neither trivialized the
killing spree nor painted Berkowitz as anything other than a
callous and unbalanced murderer. Then Catholic protesters declared
blasphemous ``Dogma,'' a comedy starring buddies Ben Affleck and
Matt Damon as exiled angels looking for a way back to Heaven.
``Dogma'' director Kevin Smith certainly dissed organized religion,
especially Catholicism, but the film unfolded as a more
faith-affirming experience than a sermon belted out by any
silver-tongued televangelist.
</P>
<P>
   Parent of the Year: In ``October Sky,'' Chris Cooper urges his
son to follow him down the mine rather than pursue his dream to
become a rocket scientist. In ``American Beauty,'' Cooper resorts
to beating some sense into his wayward son while harboring his own
darks secrets and desires.
</P>
<P>
   Smells too much like teen spirit: Generation Y chose to make
successes of ``Varsity Blues,'' ``She's All That,'' ``Cruel
Intentions,'' ``Never Been Kissed'' and ``American Pie'' while
rejecting the smart and tart-tongued ``Rushmore,'' ``Go'' and
``Election.'' Makes you wonder about our future generation of
politicians and business leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But will they regret it in the morning?: Members of the Academy
for the Arts and Sciences surprised everyone most conspicuously
director Steven Spielberg by handing the Best Picture Oscar to the
delightfully witty ``Shakespeare in Love'' and not Spielberg's
bloody but pragmatic portrait of men in war, ``Saving Private
Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   Eeriest time to pass on the exploding Omega watch: Desmond
Llewelyn, aka Q, died this month in a car crash soon after
introducing 007 to his assistant, played by John Cleese, in ``The
World Is Not Enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Drum roll please: The winner of the Gene Hackman/Michael Caine
Ubiquity Award goes to Julianne Moore for ``Cookie's Fortune,''
``An Ideal Husband,'' ``Magnolia,'' ``The End of the Affair'' and
``Map of the World.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
