<SLUG> BC-NFK-FEATURES-RECORD28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Will this be on my permanent record?
 &HT;    By Keith Still
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ What lists your grades, might tell whether you've been
naughty or nice and will be around for 100 years? No, it's not some
list Santa is keeping. It's your permanent academic record, and
it's on file right now at your school or school system's office.
</P>
<P>
   Don't panic yet. While state law says that your ``permanent''
record is just that, the files are used mainly for administrative
purposes. They can be passed from school to school as you move.
</P>
<P>
   ``The school administration can look at your records, and if
they see you're not doing well in reading, they'll try to work out
a program to help,'' said Spencer Ragsdale, public information
director for DeKalb County Schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a big flurry of use in the first year or two after
graduation, when colleges need students' records. After that, not
much is done with them.''
</P>
<P>
   So what exactly goes in these records and why do schools keep
them so long? The state requires that your records be retained
permanently for student use and for historical purposes, said Peter
Schinkel, retention schedule program manager at the Georgia
Archives.
</P>
<P>
   Your grades, the classes you took, standardized test scores,
academic achievements and awards, special education documentation,
Social Security number and other personal identifying information
are usually in your permanent record.
</P>
<P>
   However, individual school systems might add other details. Some
systems may keep your immunization records, birth certificate
copies or even your disciplinary history.
</P>
<P>
   Don't fret, though. Most discipline offenses, unless they are
out-of-school suspensions, won't be etched into your permanent
record, says Melanie Stockwell, state Department of Education legal
services director. However, Stockwell noted, it does depend on the
individual school system.
</P>
<P>
   Still worried about what might be lurking on your files? This
isn't an X-File. Your parents or legal guardian, and in some
instances, you, can take a peek _ no sneaking around required.
While school systems by law must keep your records confidential,
your parents have every right to look at your personal file, at
least until you turn 18.
</P>
<P>
   If there's something on your record that you think is incorrect
or unfair, you can dispute it. Individual schools may have
different procedures, Stockwell says. But you're generally
guaranteed a hearing if you disagree with what's in the school's
files.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
