<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rocker says he's not racist
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta Braves pitcher John Rocker says he's sorry for
saying mean things about immigrants and gay people in New York. The
pitcher taunted New York Mets fans during the playoffs this year
and added more negative comments about New Yorkers in an interview
with Sports Illustrated.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker told Sports Illustrated he would retire before ever
playing for a New York team. Then added: ``The biggest thing I
don't like about New York are the foreigners. You can walk an
entire block in Times Square and not hear anybody speaking
English.''
</P>
<P>
   When the article was published, Rocker tried to apologize.
``Even though it might appear otherwise from what I've said, I am
not a racist,'' he said in a statement. ``I should not have said
what I did because it is not what I believe in my heart. ... I
recognize that I have gone way too far in my competitive zeal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves and Major League Baseball are deciding if they should
punish Rocker for his comments.
</P>
<P>
   Government warns of terrorist acts
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government is asking people to be calm but to keep
their eyes open for anything suspicious during the holidays. The
government is concerned about terrorists hurting Americans overseas
and at home.
</P>
<P>
   Airports and border guards have stepped up security measures.
Based on FBI warnings, the U.S. Postal Inspection Service is
X-raying some mail and packages from Germany for bombs.
</P>
<P>
   The government says to be suspicious of mail that you weren't
expecting or of packages left unattended in public places.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 14, an Algerian was arrested in Washington after
bomb-making materials allegedly were found in his car.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. authorities warn that a suspected Islamic terrorist has
issued calls to action to hurt U.S. citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
