</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   Q: Don't laugh _ this is a serious problem for my friends and my
big mouth. I need to know who to contact about a problem with the
background music on ``As the World Turns.'' The music is so loud
you cannot hear the dialogue sometimes. Can you find an address?
The local television station could not help me.
</P>
<P>
   _ Skip Duncan
</P>
<P>
   A: You and your buddies are not the only soap fans who have been
missing key lines uttered in the fictional town of Oakdale due to
ATWT's loud music. Add your voices to the chorus complaining to CBS
and, who knows, they might just listen. Send a letter _ or several
_ to Chris Goutman, Executive Producer, ATWT, CBS Broadcast Center,
524 W. 57th St., New York, NY 10019.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Nine years ago, we purchased a Hallmark motion ornament (the
kind that plugs into a Christmas light socket) of a train going
around and through a tunnel. One of the cars fell off, causing the
train to jam, and we haven't been able to use it since. Does
Hallmark have some place we can send it to be repaired? It's
completely enclosed with no way to open it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kevin &AMP; Diana Gray
</P>
<P>
   A: No, no repair facility. The Hallmark ornament warranty lasts
only three years. Ornaments still under warranty in need of repair
may be returned to Hallmark Fulfillment Center-001, 3640 Market
St., St. Louis, MO 63110-1218. Hallmark will replace the ornament
or reimburse you and return the broken ornament if you would like.
Hallmark customer service advises customers to insure ornaments
when shipping. Sounds like the best bet is to replace it with a new
one. Contact Ornament Trader Magazine at (800) 441-1551 for
assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am trying to get in touch with the grandparents of the boy
in Tennessee in the national news. The boy's mother died and he
spent a month with her body in an apartment. I was hoping our
church could start a college fund for him.
</P>
<P>
   _ Johnny Williamson
</P>
<P>
   A: One has already been started for 9-year-old Travis Butler. To
contribute or to send words of encouragement, write in care of the
Travis Butler Fund, National Bank of Commerce, 910 Madison Ave.,
Memphis, TN 38103.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I was completely frustrated at being forced to use a 900
number for passport renewal information and outraged at the
$1.05-per-minute charge. Who exactly profits from this practice and
how can our State Department justify taking advantage of U.S.
citizens in such a way? _ L.S.
</P>
<P>
   A: The U.S. State Department contracts with an agency to handle
the fee-based calls instead of hiring more people to answer
questions. The National Passport Information Center is paid for
with user fees. The State Department receives no money. By the
mid-1990s, the department was unable to answer phones and issue
passports because workload had increased more than 70 percent.
Customers were put on hold for 15 to 30 minutes (usually not
toll-free) and disconnects were common _ as were unhappy customers.
The 900 system works much better. The information is also available
on the Web at travel.state.gov. Q: My granddaughter would like a
crystal growing kit. Toys ``R'' Us had none. _ M.K.W.A: Neither
does any other retailer I contacted. Order all the ingredients for
$9 (except food coloring) by calling Mrs. Stewart's at Luther, Ford
and Co., (800) 325-7785 or check the Web site at
www.mrsstewart.com. Or make your own with Mrs. Stewart's Bluing.
For complete instructions, send me a stamped self-addressed
envelope or an e-mail request. In addition to the bluing, you will
need a glass or plastic bowl, pieces of coal, tile, porous brick or
sponge, water, table salt, Mercurochrome, vegetable coloring or
ink. When you are finished with the project, toss the container.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig, author of ``Thanks for Asking,'' at P.O. Box
670, Austin, TX 78767; (512) 445-3697; e-mail
jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968. Due to the number of
inquiries, not all questions can be answered or acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
