<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 10:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9705 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-HIGHSMITH28-COX     12-27 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIGHSMITH28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Author found drama in the dark side
 &HT;    By Laura Dempsey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ To read a mystery is to know with general
certainty that the crime _ murder, most likely _ will be solved and
the killer exposed and punished. It's a large part of the reason
for the genre's enduring popularity: In fiction, no one sins with
impunity.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Highsmith knew better. She knew from a tender age that
killers walk among us, that pyromaniacs and kleptomaniacs and
sociopaths of every order live just down the street. She knew that
chance and chance alone kept the world in check, and that one small
rumble could start a landslide from which no one would be safe. To
read Highsmith is to be reminded of this, again and again, in pages
of disarmingly simple prose that mask the deep, disturbing message
of her work: Given half a chance, me-first trumps morality. Every
time.
</P>
<P>
   Highsmith's characters, most notably the enduringly creepy Tom
Ripley, are rightfully paranoid and unconscionably free of guilt.
If, like Ripley, they're murderers, they are afraid only of getting
caught. The deed doesn't haunt them, and no tell-tale heart will
ever force a confession.
</P>
<P>
   Highsmith's first book, ``Strangers on a Train,'' was published
in 1950. Alfred Hitchcock turned the story into a movie a year
later in what would seem to be a meeting of like minds, artists of
the dark side. The film, a necessarily watered-down version of the
novel, featured Robert Walker as Bruno, who proposes a brilliant
tit-for-tat murder scheme with a less-willing Guy, played by Farley
Granger.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 50 years later, another of Highsmith's novels has been
adapted by a classic filmmaker: Anthony Minghella, who won awards
with his screen version of Michael Ondaatje's seemingly unfilmmable
novel, ``The English Patient,'' has taken on ``The Talented Mr.
Ripley,'' Highsmith's 1955 classic. The film will _ and should _
stand alone, as movies must follow a different set of rules
regarding their heroes. Matt Damon's Ripley shows a tender, nearly
sweet nature that works well for the film, but which fans of
Highsmith's books will find highly uncharacteristic. The movie
Ripley is tearful and emotional as he bludgeons his best friend to
death. The book Ripley just gets tired.
</P>
<P>
   Highsmith was born in Texas in 1921. She was raised in New York,
graduated from Barnard College and made a lasting move to Europe in
1963, living in England, Italy and France before settling in
Switzerland in 1981. She died there in 1995 at the age of 74. She
lived with only a cat, preferring animals to humans and deftly
reflecting recurring inquiries about her sexual orientation _ her
second novel, ``The Price of Salt,'' was a happy-ending story of a
lesbian couple, published under the pseudonym Claire Morgan (Naiad
Press reissued the book in 1984, under Highsmith's name but
retitled ``Carol''), and several books, including the Ripley
stories, have a homosexual undercurrent impossible to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   She was reclusive, granting the occasional begrudging interview
as a duty to publishers and fans, who were largely European _
Americans never quite caught on. Graham Greene and Gore Vidal were
ardent admirers, The New York Times wrote glowing reviews, and
Highsmith wrote prodigiously, leaving 21 novels and seven
short-story collections. Five books featured Ripley, with the last,
``Ripley Under Water,'' being published in 1993. There have been
several other movie adaptations, most notably Alain Delon as Ripley
in the French film version of ``The Talented Mr. Ripley,'' titled
``Plein Soleil,'' and a boyish Dennis Hopper in the role in Wim
Wenders' ``The American Friend,'' based on ``Ripley's Game.''
</P>
<P>
   Her books are usually classified as mysteries, but they are
never tales of detection or crime-solving. Usually, it's more a
case of cat-and-mouse, where the sympathy lies with the hunted.
Highsmith was a master of dark psychology, often crediting her
childhood reading of ``The Human Mind'' by Karl Menninger, which
laid out case studies of the famous psychiatrist's patients _
twisted minds of every category. ``Edith's Diary,'' one of her few
books that doesn't feature a brutal murder or two, is a brilliant
depiction of a mind going slowly insane, written with unerring
logic under a canopy of impending doom. ``Those Who Walk Away'' is
the story of two Americans playing deadly hide-and-seek in Europe,
its impetus the suicide (was it really?) of one's daughter _ the
other's wife.
</P>
<P>
   The genius of Highsmith is her ability to make the unthinkable
become reasonable. Even Ripley, who kills and kills and profits
mightily, becomes the man with whom we identify, and it isn't until
the stories are over that we realize what she's done. We root for
the murderer, and it's not necessarily empathy or understanding
that drags us into his corner: It's good storytelling.
</P>
<P>
   Everyman's Library has packaged the first three Ripley books _
``The Talented Mr. Ripley,'' ``Ripley Under Ground'' and ``Ripley's
Game'' _ into one, fat $26 package, and the movie has prompted a
Vintage Crime re-issue of ``The Talented Mr. Ripley'' as a $13
paperback. They are deceptively easy reads, but beware: Highsmith's
world is deep and quite dark, and once entered, it's impossible to
ignore life's shadows. Even _ especially _ under a high-noon sun.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
