<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Tuesday, December
28, 1999, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   So specialty editors can focus on one day's budget, CoxNet
produces themed features budgets each day. Here is the schedule:
</P>
<P>
   TODAY: Technology
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday for Wednesday: Automotive, personal finance and home &AMP;
garden
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday for Thursday: Food, CD reviews, video reviews
</P>
<P>
   Thursday for Friday: Movie reviews, travel, books and fashion
</P>
<P>
   Friday for Saturday: Religion and science &AMP; health
</P>
<P>
   In addition, separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports,
business and commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. An ETA is given if a
story will move after 8 p.m. Eastern.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   LOOK ON THE WEB: Stories marked as a CoxNet layout are available
for purchase in paginated form: http://nytsyn.com/syndicate/pageex
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-FUTURE _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Above Alan Tannenbaum's desk,
overlooking his high-tech gadgets and powerful computers, hangs an
eerily prescient picture. The illustration depicts a woman wearing
her World Wide Web browser. A portable computer connected to a
headset projects a tiny computer screen in front of her eye,
letting her see and surf simultaneously. As Tannenbaum talks, the
picture seems increasingly like a nod to his vision of the
Internet's evolution. He predicts the Internet will ascend to a
technological level totally free of the clunky computers and tangle
of wires that bound _ and still bind _ this waning decade. (Cocks,
Austin American-Statesman). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-TOOLS _ Software reviews. This week: Learning some history
with a CD-ROM by DK Interactive Learning called 20th Century Day by
Day. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCH _ What's new on the Web. This week: Internet companies'
core values and beliefs. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSCENE _ What's new on the Web. This week: tech support on
the Web. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-MEDIA _ What the tech magazines are writing about. (Haddad,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MAC-REPORT _ News on Apple and its products. This week: Beware _
sharware may not be Y2K-compliant. (Haddad, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-HOTCOMPANY _ This week: RocketChips. (Ladendorf, Austin
American-Statesman). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-PLAYGEAR _ AUSTIN, Texas _ This week: The latest
incarnation of the Taxi Wand is remonikered the Millennium Wand
2000. (Kallenberg, Austin American-Statesman). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-WEBSHOP _ This week: spun.com and mercata.com. (Austin
American-Statesman). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-LINK _ A rundown of good Web sites. (Gallaga, Austin
American-Statesman). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-GAMER _ The latest in games. (Austin American-Statesman).
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
