<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 10:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9713 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-THISWEEK-REVIEW-NYT     12-27 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-THISWEEK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGHLIGHTS OF THE PAST WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arrest at the U.S. Border Points to a Terrorist Ring
</P>
<P>
   When a customs agent began asking questions at a remote ferry
boat border crossing near Seattle, the nervous driver, Ahmed
Ressam, bolted. His car contained timing devices and enough
explosive chemicals to level a building. By the week's end, the
Algerian from Canada's immigrant underground was at the center of a
spreading international investigation of an Islamic
gangster-terrorist ring.
</P>
<P>
   _ JOHN KIFNER
</P>
<P>
   Violent Siege Ends
</P>
<P>
   Only days after ending a hostage siege at a Louisiana prison,
six hostage-takers _ all of them Cuban inmates awaiting deportation
_ got their wish: a return flight home.
</P>
<P>
   Local prosecutors criticized the deal, saying it would encourage
similar uprisings by other Cubans imprisoned while Cuba decides
whether to accept them. But the Clinton administration insisted
that the unusual agreement with Fidel Castro ended a siege that had
threatened to turn bloody. A seventh Cuban hostage-taker was
detained after a woman inmate taken hostage said she had been
raped.
</P>
<P>
   _ PHILIP SHENON
</P>
<P>
   School Vouchers Found Unconstitutional
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge has ruled that a program in which 3,761
Cleveland schoolchildren receive up to $2,500 in taxpayer money to
attend private schools violates the constitutional separation of
church and state.
</P>
<P>
   The students will be allowed to continue attending classes until
the decision is reconsidered by an appeals court, and the closely
watched case _ which has already been discussed in the presidential
campaign _ is considered likely to be accepted for review by the
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   _ JODI WILGOREN
</P>
<P>
   Have Wrench, Will Travel, Once Again to the Hubble
</P>
<P>
   America's eye to the universe is opening again. The Hubble Space
Telescope is fixed and should be back in business shortly after the
first of the year, project officials say. Teams of spacewalking
astronauts from the shuttle Discovery swarmed over the observatory.
They replaced the faulty gyroscopes that last month forced Hubble
into hibernation when it couldn't point itself properly, and
updated other equipment. After a rocky year, NASA was ending the
millennium with a success.
</P>
<P>
   _ WARREN E. LEARY
</P>
<P>
   HUD, the Homeless and the Mayor
</P>
<P>
   Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo said his agency would take
control of $60 million in federal funds for homeless services in
New York because Mayor Rudolph Giuliani could not be trusted to
distribute the money equitably. A federal judge ruled last month
that the city blocked access to the funds to punish a group
critical of the mayor. Giuliani accused Cuomo of playing politics,
noting his ties to Hillary Rodham Clinton, who is running for the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   _ DAVID M. HERSZENHORN
</P>
<P>
   Tracking Bullets
</P>
<P>
   Gun advocates like to say that it's people who kill, not guns.
Others say it's bullets that kill: If you can trace them, you might
find the shooters. The White House has advocated the creation of a
computerized catalog of the distinctive markings that each gun
leaves on discharged shell casings. Such a system ``has the
potential to do for gun crime what fingerprints have done for
forensics,'' said Bruce Reed, the administration's domestic policy
adviser.
</P>
<P>
   _ HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   Rails From Canada to U.S.
</P>
<P>
   Rail barons have created a mighty transcontinental railroad,
North American Railways, with the proposed $6 billion merger of the
Burlington Northern Santa Fe and the Canadian National Railway. The
combined 50,000 miles of track would stretch from Nova Scotia to
the Gulf of Mexico, linking lumber and coal markets in Canada to
oil and chemical plants in Texas. Robert Krebs, chairman of
Burlington Northern, said consumers will benefit from lower costs
because of the combined company's ability to send goods nonstop
over long distances.
</P>
<P>
   _ CHARLES V. BAGLI
</P>
<P>
   A New Internet Face
</P>
<P>
   General Electric is famous for only wanting to compete in
markets where it can be a top player. So it was odd that its NBC
unit said it would back Telocity, a Silicon Valley start-up
offering Internet access to homes. America Online now reaches 20
million subscribers, 10 times more than the nearest rival. But
Telocity is 30 times faster than AOL _ fast enough to offer
Internet television programs, an area where NBC is still on top.
</P>
<P>
   _ SAUL HANSELL
</P>
<P>
   A Monitor for the Law
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department's decision to appoint a monitor to
oversee the New Jersey State Police sends a resounding message to
dozens of other law enforcement agencies accused of racial
discrimination. Among them is the New York City Police Department,
which is now negotiating with the federal department and hoping to
avert outside oversight.
</P>
<P>
   _ DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI
</P>
<P>
   Cleaner Fumes
</P>
<P>
   The Environmental Protection Administration issued regulations
intended to clean up the air in 2010 and 2020 by setting new
tailpipe standards for vehicles, including light trucks, sold in
the 2004 model year and beyond. Gas will have less sulfur, so
catalytic converters can work better.
</P>
<P>
   _ MATTHEW L. WALD
</P>
<P>
   A Schools Chief Ousted
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Charging that Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew had grown
too ambivalent about his job, the New York City Board of Education
voted 4-3 not to renew his contract when it expires in June.
</P>
<P>
   Crew's once-close relationship with Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
deteriorated last spring after the two battled over school
vouchers, and Crew's allies on the board accused Giuliani of
orchestrating his ouster. Three of the four members voting to end
Crew's tenure were close allies of the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   _ ABBY GOODNOUGH
</P>
<P>
   Flooding in Venezuela
</P>
<P>
   Instead of celebrating the adoption of a new Constitution,
Venezuela spent the week digging out from under the worst natural
disaster in its modern history. Massive landslides and flooding
brought on by torrential rains displaced more than 150,000 people,
but with so many still missing, the death toll from the calamity
may never be known: the government's own estimates range from less
than 500 to more than 25,000 dead.
</P>
<P>
   _ LARRY ROHTER
</P>
<P>
   Open Mouth, Insert Foot
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Braves pitcher John Rocker achieved notoriety after
making a slew of ethnically and racially offensive remarks about
New Yorkers. His views were published in Sports Illustrated, and
calls for his ouster from the team quickly followed. Hank Aaron,
the Braves' senior vice president, said he was sickened by the
comments and questioned how Rocker could remain in baseball.
Reacting to the uproar, Rocker said, ``I am contrite.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-99 1051EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
