<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 11:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9759 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-EMILY-WATSON-IN-ANGEL     12-27 1439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMILY-WATSON-IN-ANGELAS-ASHES-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUCHED BY `ANGELA': EMILY WATSON STIRS `ANGELA'S ASHES' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Emily Watson in a scene from ``Angela's
Ashes.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Emily Watson smiles _ details at 11!
 &HT;    The British actress has portrayed serious, damaged characters so
often _ most notably in the Danish film ``Breaking the Waves''
(1995), the Irish-troubles drama ``The Boxer'' (1997) and the
classical-music tragedy ``Hilary and Jackie'' (1998) _ that
audiences across the globe believe that dark clouds accompany her
everywhere and that she breaks into tears on an hourly basis.
 &HT;    At the moment, though, striding into a suite room at Manhattan's
Essex House to discuss her latest celluloid sobfest, Alan Parker's
adaptation of Frank McCourt's best-selling childhood memoir
``Angela's Ashes,'' Watson is ... grinning from ear to ear.
 &HT;    And why not? The two-time Oscar nominee loves ``Angela's
Ashes,'' and has flown in from the Budapest set of her next movie
specifically to talk about it.
 &HT;    Set in the grim, sodden slums of Limerick, Ireland, the
just-released drama casts Watson as Angela McCourt, put-upon mother
of Frank (played at different ages by three young actors) and his
assorted siblings, and wife of Malachy (Robert Carlyle), a
well-meaning alcoholic who can't keep a job and eventually abandons
the family.
 &HT;    Much of ``Angela's Ashes'' was shot on location in Ireland, and
Watson acknowledges that she often ``got a bit low'' during the
filming. Angela's silent suffering made it all the easier to
succumb.
 &HT;    ``On the other films I'd done, like `Breaking the Waves' and
`Hilary and Jackie,' there were very heightened emotional
circumstances,'' Watson says. ``They were like actor's workouts.
Angela wasn't like that _ there's not a scene where she goes,
`That's it! I've had enough!' That's not the nature of the story.
 &HT;    ``It was quite strange,'' she says, ``because there wasn't a
scene where I could let it all out and vent.''
 &HT;    Instead, says the actress, casually dressed in slacks, with a
black-leather jacket over a pink sweater, she had to craft the
character through continuity and subtle interpretive touches.
 &HT;    ``Most parts are joining the dots between events,'' she says.
``You're telling a story through the thread of events _ you try to
find your way as the character feels through that.
 &HT;    ``There were obviously very strong events in Angela's life,''
she continues, ``but she's just got a much less expressed emotional
(range). I don't know if she ever really knew how to grieve, or if
she did grieve but wasn't handed any of the tools of modern
psychology to say, `Your life is a disaster _ do this and do that.'
 &HT;    ``Everything is a disaster, in a way,'' the actress says.
``She's married to an alcoholic. She's lost lots of her children.
The family lived in poverty.''
 &HT;    And then, improbably, Watson smiles.
 &HT;    ``I don't know what I'm saying, really,'' she says, laughing
easily at herself.
 &HT;    Much easier to take was the company of the many children she
worked with while making ``Angela's Ashes.'' There were the boys
who played Frank, as well as the babies and other tykes who
portrayed the McCourt children who died as babies and infants.
 &HT;    ``It was, in a sense, a very straightforward process of getting
right in there for this role,'' she says. ``As soon as I was on the
set, there were usually seven children wanting my attention.
 &HT;    ``There was only so much the assistant directors could do,'' she
adds, ``so I had to be in control of the situation. I had to
marshal them and explain things. They were all desperately excited
and didn't really understand what was going on.
 &HT;    ``The wee little ones never really clicked,'' Watson admits.
``They'd suddenly do things in the middle of a take, like start
chatting away and then turn around as if nothing happened.
 &HT;    ``But they were all terribly, terribly sweet,'' she says. ``The
older ones were a bright bunch, really lovely.''
 &HT;    Considering the somber tone of the film and the glut of
Oscar-worthy serious fare now in theaters, industry observers have
wondered if ``Angela's Ashes'' will connect with a broad audience,
especially those who haven't read the original book. But Watson
seems unconcerned, in part because she doesn't see the film as a
downer.
 &HT;    ``In a way, this is the ultimate American dream,'' she says.
``It's about somebody who lives in terrible poverty in a hovel
somewhere in Europe, used to pray to the Statue of Liberty and
winds up breaking free and going to New York. America represents
salvation.
 &HT;    ``I think it's a real uplifting tale, full of hope,'' Watson
says. ``Frank gets away, and he served the community as a school
teacher. Then he simply wrote down his story, and now he's a
millionaire.
 &HT;    ``That's a great story.''
 &HT;    Watson's own story isn't bad, either. Besides ``Angela's
Ashes,'' she's currently onscreen in ``Cradle Will Rock,'' the
based-on-fact Tim Robbins drama in which she plays an aspiring
actress, and will soon be seen in ``Trixie'' and ``The Luzhin
Defense.'' The last-named film, co-starring ``Cradle'' colleague
John Turturro, is what takes her to Budapest.
 &HT;    ``Trixie,'' it should be noted, is a comedy _ which begs a
question: Did Watson sign on simply to prove to herself, or to the
moviegoing public, that she had it in her to be funny?
 &HT;    ``It's a bit of both,'' the actress says. ``There is that fear
of being typecast. You can't keep on doing the same things, because
if you do too much of that it becomes about your technique rather
than about you serving the story.
 &HT;    ``I did want to look around for something different,'' she says.
``I was reading romantic comedies with names attached, to play the
girl. I was going, `Ohhhh ... ' I'm not obvious casting for
those.''
 &HT;    And then along came ``Trixie.''
 &HT;    ``I read this script from Alan Rudolph, which was just
crazy-mad,'' Watson recalls. ``I play this girl who wants to be a
private detective. She just has a loop missing, and speaks in mixed
metaphors all the time.
 &HT;    ``I just fell in love with it, but I didn't know if I could do
it at all,'' adds the actress, who co-stars in ``Trixie'' with Nick
Nolte, Will Patton and Dermot Mulroney. ``It did have a similarity
to the other things I'd done in that she's a very strong character,
very far removed from who I am.''
 &HT;    Who she is and where she comes from, Watson says, not only keep
her grounded but also prevent her from relocating to Los Angeles.
She prefers the familiarity and relative anonymity of London, where
she lives with her husband.
 &HT;    ``For me to live in London and do the work I do is just
essential,'' she says. ``Some people love (Hollywood) and it suits
them very well, but I don't think I'd take to being in that
lifestyle and having that pressure all the time.
 &HT;    ``I've done all right so far,'' she says softly. ``I'm in a very
fortunate situation, just in the way I went sideways into the
industry, via Denmark _ I've never had to go and knock on film
doors. I did as a theater actress when I was younger, but I did
`Breaking the Waves' and scripts started coming my way.
 &HT;    ``It's probably quite unusual,'' Watson admits, ``and I thank my
lucky stars I'm in this position. I think I'd be a lot tougher and
wiser had I done it another way.''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
