<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETHAN-HAWKE-IN-SNOW-FALLING-ON-CEDARS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ETHAN HAWKE AND A STRANGE KIND OF LOVE STORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Ethan Hawke with Youki Kudoh in a scene
from ``Snow Falling on Cedars.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Ethan Hawke knows about love stories.
 &HT;    Onscreen, he's starred in two defining 1990s young-love stories,
``Reality Bites'' (1994) and ``Before Sunrise'' (1995), as well as
the upcoming `Snow Falling on Cedars,'' which opens Jan. 7
nationwide.
 &HT;    And offscreen ... well, that's an even better love story.
 &HT;    Hawke first met actress Uma Thurman six years ago, at a bank
machine in Manhattan's East Village. He was immediately smitten _
but there were some problems.
 &HT;    For one thing, she was with ``some really scummy-looking guy,''
Hawke recalls. For another, she ignored his attempts to strike up a
conversation.
 &HT;    They wouldn't meet again until 1996, when they were cast
opposite one another in the sci-fi flick ``Gattaca.'' Hawke was
smitten all over again, but it still wasn't easy.
 &HT;    ``She was shockingly intimidating at first,'' the actor admits.
``She's 6 feet tall and very beautiful. She's intelligent. Wouldn't
you be afraid?''
 &HT;    He persevered, however, and today the two are married and the
parents of a beautiful baby girl.
 &HT;    To judge by his appearance as he settles into a suite at
Toronto's Four Seasons hotel to promote ``Snow Falling on Cedars,''
domesticity suits the former slacker poster boy. Dressed in dark
slacks and a fawn-colored corduroy shirt, he's relaxed and quick to
laugh _ befitting an actor whose film is getting Oscar-caliber
buzz.
 &HT;    Hawke says he identified with the story, based on David
Guterson's best-selling novel, about a pre-World War II teen
(Hawke) who falls in love with a Japanese girl (Youki Kudoh). Years
later, after her family has survived wartime internment camps, she
marries a Japanese man _ and, when her husband is accused of
murder, calls on Hawke's character and begs him to help.
 &HT;    ``There was just something about the story that I found
incredibly moving,'' he says. ``I connected with the subtle way the
story is told. I also like the main idea, which is universal _ it's
about the one love who got away.''
 &HT;    He laughs.
 &HT;    ``Now that I'm happily married, I think about the 40 that get
away every minute,'' he jokes. ``I was sitting in the Four Seasons
bar last night and I thought, `God, life is so different now _ I'm
really going to go home. I'm going to put on Spectravision and
watch some John Travolta movie for a bit.'''
 &HT;    Seriously, though, he admits that his new life is daunting.
 &HT;    ``Being a parent is so incredibly humbling,'' he says. ``The
biggest thing about it is that it's a job that doesn't stop.
 &HT;    ``For the first three months,'' he recalls, ``I was so gung-ho.
I was like, `I'm going to be Superdad!' And then finally it was
just a wash. I was so depressed _ I thought, `I'm a loser, a
terrible dad. I don't get any sleep. I don't work anymore.'
 &HT;    ``But now I've reached some middle ground,'' Hawke says. ``I
realize being a dad is the most average, common thing you can do _
and it's the most exciting.''
 &HT;    Life on the baby track isn't that bad for an actor who never
really wanted everything that came with stardom.
 &HT;    ``I hated the idea of being some teen hunk,'' says Hawke, who
was 18 when ``Dead Poets Society'' (1989) made him a star. ``I
couldn't imagine waking up going, `Who loves me? Who? Who?' ... I
never thought about that sex-symbol stuff. I just wanted to act.''
 &HT;    And indeed Hawke avoided the Brat Pack route of many of his
peers, searching for high-quality films that offered acting
challenges. He played Winona Ryder's slacker boyfriend in the
innovative ``Reality Bites'' (1994), and then after ``Before
Sunrise'' (1995) _ in which he and Julie Delpy spent a talkative
night walking the streets of Vienna _ he took several years off,
devoting himself to stage work and writing.
 &HT;    ``I tried to be careful,'' Hawke says. ``There are a lot of
people who had a big hit movie when they were 18. They aren't
acting at 30. You have to be choosy _ you have to do things you
believe in.
 &HT;    ``I mean, I don't want to sit here and huckster a piece of
crap,'' he adds. ``I don't want to be sitting in a coffee shop with
my friends and not be able to look them in the eye because my
latest movie is a piece of garbage.
 &HT;    ``I'm quite comfortable in the self-esteem department _ I don't
need to see my name over the title of some $100 million movie.''
 &HT;    That self-esteem was tested early. Born in Austin, Texas, Hawke
was raised in West Windsor, N.J., as a shy boy who found an outlet
in the theater.
 &HT;    ``My first play was `The Seagull,' with Tyne Daly and Jon
Voight,'' Hawke recalls. ``I still remember the review: `Ethan
Hawke is more concerned with his pimples than his prose.'
 &HT;    ``The other one was, `The most interesting conversation to have
after watching ``The Seagull'' is, who was worse: Ethan Hawke, Tyne
Daly or Jon Voight? They were all so bad.'
 &HT;    ``I felt like, `Hey, this is so unfair.'''
 &HT;    But the lesson came in handy when ``Dead Poets Society'' made
him an overnight star.
 &HT;    ``It's a very weird experience to be 18 and in a movie that's
nominated for Oscars and grossing hundreds of millions of dollars
worldwide,'' he explains. ``There you are, being flown all over the
world to do press. I couldn't help thinking from that moment on,
`Ethan, you are a made man.'
 &HT;    ``I thought, `OK, so it's nominated for best picture. So next
year I'll be nominated. Three years later, I'll win. And 40 years
later I'll be president of the United States.'''
 &HT;    Nowadays, those dreams are far from his mind. At 28, in fact,
the actor is exploring other fields and re-examining everything in
his life.
 &HT;    Do people have midlife crises at 28?
 &HT;    ``It's not a midlife crisis,'' Hawke says. ``But a lot of people
who have been professionally acting for 16 years are like 36 years
old or 38 now _ they tell me they're bored with it. So I feel
sometimes like, `Gosh, what am I going to do to make this fresh for
myself?'
 &HT;    ``But that's a great place to be as a new parent,'' he adds,
``because I'm ready to dedicate some time. Parenthood is so new and
exciting for me.''
 &HT;    So Hawke moonlights. In 1996 he published his first novel, ``The
Hottest State,'' and he continues to serve as artistic director for
the Malaparte Theater Group, of which he is a founding member. And
he deals with the diapers, too.
 &HT;    And, yes, he admits that finding the time isn't easy.
 &HT;    ``It gets harder when you get older,'' he says. ``Suddenly
everyone starts having children, and it's not quite as much fun to
hang out in the basement talking to your acting friends.''
 &HT;    If all else fails, there's always his wife. The two read each
other's scripts and offer advice, solicited or not.
 &HT;    ``We're very opinionated people,'' Hawke says. ``We're also
different, but I think differences are what make us interesting.
 &HT;    ``We both hate people who go around saying, `I wish I were this,
I wish I were that,''' he adds. ``That's what wrong with life. An
oak tree doesn't wish it was a maple or a cedar.''
 c.1999 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
