<HEADER>
A9765 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a BC-WILLIAM-H-MACY-IN-MAG     12-27 1433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILLIAM-H-MACY-IN-MAGNOLIA-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAM H. MACY: AN ACTOR'S ACTOR BLOSSOMS IN `MAGNOLIA' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of William H. Macy with Craig Kvinsland and
Henry Gibson in a scene from ``Magnolia.'') 
 By JEANNE WOLF and SHEP MORGAN  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    William H. Macy's face is so familiar on screens big and small
that he can't go anywhere without being ... well, almost
recognized.
 &HT;    ``People think I went to high school or college with them,'' he
says, smiling. ``Then I'll get nailed by someone as that guy from
`Fargo' or `E.R.'''
 &HT;    Macy, who began his career on stage in ``American Buffalo,''
written by his buddy David Mamet, has become one of film's
hardest-working men, following a nonstop work ethic that kept him
on location for most of 1999, making movies as diverse as the
quirky ``Happy, Texas'' and the mainstream spoof ``Mystery Men.''
Even so, it was an off year _ he was in seven 1998 films, and only
five in 1999.
 &HT;    His latest film is ``Magnolia,'' which reunites him with
writer/director Paul Thomas Anderson of ``Boogie Nights'' (1997).
Macy plays Donnie Smith, an aging former television quiz kid whose
brief youthful celebrity has been replaced by a mundane job in an
appliance store.
 &HT;    Macy, whose stock in Hollywood got a major boost after he was
Oscar-nominated as Best Supporting Actor in ``Fargo'' (1996),
didn't hesitate to take a relatively small role in an ensemble cast
that ranges from Tom Cruise and Julianne Moore to Jason Robards and
Philip Seymour Hoffman, directed by a virtual newcomer.
 &HT;    ``Paul Thomas Anderson kept calling me up while he was writing
the script,'' Macy recalls. ``He said, `You're going to be playing
this famous kid who grew up to become anonymous.' That's the way he
is _ Paul tailors almost every role to the actor that he wants to
play it.
 &HT;    ``I'm ready to keep on doing any film he directs, because he's
the real deal,'' the actor says. ``I've got socks older than Paul,
but he has more self-assuredness than somebody twice his age. He's
the kind of director who doesn't look back _ he doesn't hedge his
bets.
 &HT;    ``Once he gets an idea, he goes with it,'' Macy adds. ``It may
fail, but nobody is going to stop him from putting it on the
screen. And nothing will make him compromise _ no producer, no
box-office considerations, no agonizing over whether the audience
will get it.
 &HT;    ``I think he and Mamet are peas in a pod, distinctive voices.''
 &HT;    To get ready for his role as Donnie, a gay man stuck living in
his past, Macy simply took a look around his own world.
 &HT;    ``I marvel at kids in Hollywood who are 20 and get Oscar
nominations and make millions of dollars and are on the cover of
every magazine,'' he says. ``The problem is that, eventually,
they're going to reach 30. If they're still sane, that is a
testament to how strong they are _ fame and celebrity and starpower
are just completely dangerous two-edged swords.
 &HT;    ``My success has come along a lot later,'' the 49-year-old actor
says. ``If you get it when you're young and then have to face
living without it, it can be devastating.''
 &HT;    Macy has somehow found time to make a series of guest
appearances with his wife, Felicity Huffman, on her ABC series
``Sports Night,'' and he and Huffman also starred in TNT's ``A
Slight Case of Murder'' (1999), which he wrote.
 &HT;    ``The past year has been tough,'' he admits with a touch of
weariness. ``It's an unusually long stretch that I don't think will
be repeated. I don't ever want to do it again.''
 &HT;    Besides, Macy says, he's not one of those actors who doesn't
know what to do with himself when he's not on a set.
 &HT;    ``I have a little cabin in the Vermont woods,'' he says. ``I go
there whenever I can and turn bowls _ I have this killer wood shop,
full of all these great tools. Mostly I make bowls from cherry,
maple, birch and silver birch.
 &HT;    ``I don't sell them,'' he adds. ``I give them away _ you won't
find an agent, a director or anyone who's worked with me who
probably doesn't have one.''
 &HT;    It's been more than a quarter-century since the 22-year-old Macy
first caught the public eye in Chicago, playing Bobby in Mamet's
``American Buffalo.'' They're still talking about his incredible
knack for merging into a character, any character.
 &HT;    ``Becoming a character is a big fat trick,'' he says. ``I'd even
call it a cheap trick. Now you see more and more actors buying into
false teeth, dyed hair, glasses, stuff like that to create an
image. It's seductive, and I succumb to it as much as anybody else.
If you dress me up like King Henry, then I'm the king.
 &HT;    ``But the acting part comes from somewhere else,'' he says,
``and that's what makes the best performances a little more
mysterious.
 &HT;    ``You might be doing a love scene with an actress,'' Macy
continues. ``You're supposed to be head over heels in love with
her, but the reality is that you find her annoying. As a person,
you can't stand her.
 &HT;    ``The great actor will combine those emotions _ his real dislike
with the love he's supposed to be feeling in the scene,'' he says.
``The bad actor will try to pretend that he doesn't find her
annoying at all _ but the audiences are so smart that they'll see
that pretending every time.''
 &HT;    As for research and immersing himself in the world of each
character he plays, Macy leaves that to others.
 &HT;    ``I used to do tons of research,'' he says. ``I would even have
a fake wallet with photo IDs of my character. I finally started
asking myself, `Does the audience care about this? Does it make any
difference?' I say no. But I know actors who are hooked on it.
 &HT;    ``Here's the funny part,'' he adds. ``They do all this
preparation _ and they don't know their lines. They can tell what
kind of plants are growing in their imaginary front yard, and they
can't remember their freaking lines.''
 &HT;    It's ironic that Macy has lately been so convincing as two gay
characters _ the sheriff in ``Happy, Texas'' and Donnie in
``Magnolia'' _ because he's nonetheless managed to create a minor
controversy in the gay community with a single misunderstood
comment.
 &HT;    ``I told an interviewer for The Advocate,'' he says with a sigh,
``that I would find it daunting to actually have to play a love
scene with a guy on film.''
 &HT;    He pauses, searching for the right words to explain himself,
then shrugs.
 &HT;    ``I'd say that again,'' he says. ``I would find it daunting _
but I find it daunting to do scenes with women, too. It's just that
men have beards and women don't. The thought of kissing someone
with a beard doesn't appeal to me _ I prefer kissing someone with
breasts.
 &HT;    ``But loves scenes are just icky,'' he concludes. ``It's hard to
stay serious beyond the first couple of takes. You're making out
with someone while the whole crew is watching you. It's weird.''
 &HT;    He stops, still trying to get something out.
 &HT;    ``A lot of my friends are gay,'' he adds after a moment, ``and I
have a pretty short fuse when it comes to gay-bashing _ playing gay
characters has made me realize how insidious it is.
 &HT;    ``But I'd like to think that both characters were, first of all,
real people,'' he says. ``What they did wasn't about their being
gay, it was about trying to do the right thing or trying to find
love or whatever.''
 c.1999 Pentacom Productions  
<TEXT>
