<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 11:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9766 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a BC-THE-TOPS-IN-TELEVISIO     12-27 1556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THE-TOPS-IN-TELEVISION-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOPS ON THE TUBE: THE 20TH CENTURY'S GREATEST TELEVISION 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Lucille Ball in a scene from ``I Love
Lucy.'') 
 c.1999 TV Guide Canada  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a new millennium begins, television looks back on its first
one _ well, all right, its first century. OK, its first
half-century.
</P>
<P>
   But there've still been some memorable moments, as the staff of
TV Guide Canada captures in this salute to the best of 20th-century
television. &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; TOP STARS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   + Lucille Ball.
</P>
<P>
   By her own admission, Ball didn't think funny. She never wrote
her own material or even suggested comic bits. She had impeccable
timing and a flair for physical comedy, but she knew her weaknesses
_ which is why she demanded the best writers, directors and
co-stars.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, though, she worked harder than anyone on
television, before or since, to please her audience. Which is why
Lucy remains the standard against which all others are measured.
</P>
<P>
   + Johnny Carson.
</P>
<P>
   For 30 years, Johnny Carson made everyone's bedroom a little
cozier. His show was comfortably middlebrow. Guests from Zsa Zsa
Gabor to Bette Midler had nothing to fear from him _ he cared only
about keeping them, himself and his viewers amused.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he retired, Carson had won four Emmys and left three
generations happy as they put out the lights.
</P>
<P>
   + Bill Cosby.
</P>
<P>
   The first black comic to achieve mainstream acceptance, Cosby
broke television's color barrier in 1965, co-starring with Robert
Culp in the hip, irreverent ``I Spy.'' Two decades later he
resuscitated NBC with ``Cosby,'' proving that a sitcom about an
upscale black family could capture America's heart. A jazz
connoisseur, gifted educator and devout humanitarian, he remains,
above all, a true gentleman _ and a Cos to believe in.
</P>
<P>
   + Mary Tyler Moore.
</P>
<P>
   Some people are born comics, some are natural straight men.
Precious few can be both.
</P>
<P>
   On ``The Dick Van Dyke Show'' Moore elevated saucy suburban
silliness to sexy new heights, holding her own against a team of
seasoned veterans and serving as the perfect comic foil for the
arrow-straight Van Dyke. Five years later, on ``The Mary Tyler
Moore Show,'' she proved herself equally charming as the calm
center of a comic maelstrom.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, we've known that when Mary's on the scene, love
is all around.
</P>
<P>
   + Carol Burnett.
</P>
<P>
   Television hasn't been the same since ``The Carol Burnett Show''
ended its 11-season run in 1978. A carrot-topped clown in Bob
Mackie sequins, Burnett sang, danced, mugged shamelessly, screamed
out a Tarzan yell _ anything to keep audiences laughing. But, fun
as they were, Burnett's gallery of unforgettable characters had a
real undercurrent of pathos.
</P>
<P>
   Her warm human touch, as much as her undeniable humor, is the
reason we still love Carol Burnett.
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; TOP CHARACTERS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   + Archie Bunker.
</P>
<P>
   As portrayed by Carroll O'Connor, ``All in the Family's'' Archie
was the epitome of blue-collar angst and the definition of social
intolerance _ unabashedly bigoted and unafraid to say so. To him,
blacks were ``spades'' or ``jungle bunnies,'' Puerto Ricans were
``spics'' and his son-in-law was ``a dumb Polack.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor's great gift was the ability to convey Archie's soft
side _ especially when daughter Gloria (Sally Struthers) lost her
baby or wife Edith (Jean Stapleton) was almost raped, but even in
the show's everyday moments.
</P>
<P>
   If there's such a thing as a lovable bigot, it was Archie.
</P>
<P>
   + Lucy Ricardo.
</P>
<P>
   She could be selfish, conniving and even a little cruel. She was
ineptness personified. So why did we love Lucy?
</P>
<P>
   Guts, for one thing _ who else would disguise a 25-pound cheese
as a baby to smuggle it aboard an airplane, or tango with a blouse
full of freshly laid eggs?
</P>
<P>
   We knew each carefully hatched scheme would backfire. We knew
each celebrity encounter would end in disaster. And we always knew
that in the end she'd pick herself up, dust herself off and start
all over again.
</P>
<P>
   + J.R. Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   Described by Time magazine as ``that human oil slick,'' J.R.
(Larry Hagman) was television's all-time greatest bad guy,
power-hungry, unscrupulous, conniving and ruthless. When he was
shot by an unknown assailant at the end of the 1979/80 season, we
couldn't help getting caught up in the mystery: He had so many
enemies that it was impossible to guess who'd actually pulled the
trigger.
</P>
<P>
   + Arthur ``Fonzie'' Fonzarelli.
</P>
<P>
   With apologies to Vinnie Barbarino, the Fonz was the coolest
dude to grace the television screen, clear and simple. He was the
best thing about ``Happy Days,'' and the main reason we tuned in
for 10 years. The producers had envisioned him as a bit player, a
two-dimensional, greasy-haired biker, but Henry Winkler fooled them
_ he made the Fonz someone we all wanted to be.
</P>
<P>
   + Cosmo Kramer.
</P>
<P>
   Television has had its share of wacky sidekicks, but none like
``Seinfeld's'' Kramer. Not so much dancing to the beat of a
different drummer as plugged into another dimension entirely, the
enigmatic Kramer (Michael Richards) defied traditional logic while
creating his own entirely plausible version of it. His cult began
with his trademark door openings, but went on to his
money-saving/making scams, his obsessions with everything from
fried chicken to Merv Griffin and more.
</P>
<P>
   And everyone knows that, if his coffee-table book about coffee
tables had ever really been published, it would have been a
best-seller. &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; TOP MOMENTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   + Neil Armstrong's moon walk.
</P>
<P>
   On July 20, 1969, 600 million television viewers _ almost one
quarter of the world's population _ watched a glowing figure
descend a ladder and step onto sand. The broadcast, made possible
by a live camera set up on the lunar surface, remains a triumph of
television news reporting.
</P>
<P>
   With him aboard Apollo XI were Edwin E. ``Buzz'' Aldrin Jr. and
Michael Collins, but Armstrong stole the show with his comment as
he planted the first footprint on the moon: ``That's one small step
for man, one giant leap for mankind!''
</P>
<P>
   + The Kennedy assassination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Totally unconfirmed,'' Walter Cronkite said on Nov. 22, 1963,
as the first reports of President John F. Kennedy's assassination
came in from Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Thus began four days of pandemonium that pushed television's
news capabilities to the limit. Long before CNN turned newscasting
into a high-tech art, bulky cameras, long-distance phone hookups
and 16-millimeter-film crews had to suffice. Unedited footage was
thrown on the air, yet somehow the networks stayed in control.
</P>
<P>
   When 3-year-old John-John saluted his father's coffin for the
cameras, the ``boob tube'' reached a poetic height.
</P>
<P>
   + The Royal Wedding.
</P>
<P>
   On July 29, 1981, an estimated 750 million people got up as
early as 1:30 a.m. to watch softspoken Lady Diana Spencer become
the Princess of Wales. It was perfect even when it was imperfect _
when a nervous Diana stumbled over Charles' many names, audiences
everywhere laughed in support, then dabbed away a happy tear.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen years later, her funeral would bring an era to a sad
close.
</P>
<P>
   + The end of ``M*A*S*H.''
</P>
<P>
   When ``M*A*S*H'' took its final bow on February 28, 1983, after
11 seasons, it proved to be the last great television blockbuster.
Soon the arrival of multichannel cable would severely splinter
network viewership, and even ``Seinfeld's'' farewell would draw
only a fraction of the audience that tuned in for ``M*A*S*H's''
two-and-a-half-hour-long sendoff.
</P>
<P>
   At episode's end, after numerous celebrations and still
unresolved tensions, viewers watched tearfully as Hawkeye Pierce
(Alan Alda) gazed down at the 4077th for the last time from the
chopper that was taking him home, and saw that, on the ground
below, B.J. Hunnicut (Mike Farrell) had used rocks to spell out the
word ``GOODBYE.''
</P>
<P>
   + The Challenger explosion.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 28, 1986, 73 seconds after liftoff from the Kennedy
Space Center, an explosion ripped the space shuttle Challenger to
pieces and killed the seven-person crew, including teacher Christa
McAuliffe.
</P>
<P>
   Carried live on CNN, it was a new generation's Zapruder film _
sickening and unforgettable. &QL; 
 &UR; EDITOR: Don't forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Website
at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
