<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 12:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9832 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s BC-GUGLIOTTA-SEIZURE-AZR     12-27 1688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUGLIOTTA-SEIZURE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOENIX SUNS' GUGLIOTTA TOOK SUPPLEMENT BEFORE SEIZURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - On the night he suffered a seizure that caused him to
stop breathing, Suns forward Tom Gugliotta ingested a supplement
that has been tied to the collapse of a 16-year-old Peoria, Ariz.,
boy and at least one death, ``The Arizona Republic'' has learned.
</P>
<P>
   The compound, furanone di-hydro, is a legal, over-the-counter
substance marketed as an herbal supplement that is designed to
improve sleep and aid in muscle recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Furanone is one chemical name for gamma butyrolactone. The U.S.
Food and Drug Administration at the beginning of this year asked
companies that manufacture products containing the chemical to
voluntarily recall them.
</P>
<P>
   The supplement is marketed under a variety of brand names and
has been linked to the nearly fatal collapse of the Peoria teen on
Dec. 2.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone conversation with ``The Republic'' on Sunday,
Gugliotta and Dr. Richard Emerson, the Suns' physician, confirmed
that Gugliotta had taken the furanone di-hydro supplement after a
Dec. 17 game in Portland, Ore., before boarding the team's bus.
</P>
<P>
   A short time after getting on the bus, Gugliotta suffered a
seizure. With Gugliotta's permission, Emerson revealed for the
first time Sunday that the 6-foot-10, 30-year-old player stopped
breathing en route to the hospital and in the emergency room there.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said my heart never stopped, but I wasn't breathing,''
Gugliotta added.
</P>
<P>
   Emerson said that the supplement container was found, and that
doctors were able to treat Gugliotta with counteractive drugs,
``which probably saved Tom's life.''
</P>
<P>
   Emerson said the team's medical staff is making no assumptions
that the supplement is the definite cause of the seizure, and
Gugliotta is scheduled to undergo more tests. But Gugliotta's
symptoms are consistent with other reported seizures and collapses
linked to furanone di-hydro products.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Internist) Dr. Craig Phelps, (team nutritionist) Doug Grant
and myself have been doing a lot of research, and while (furanone)
is highly suspect, we can't assume anything,'' Emerson said.
``There is a family history of seizure as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Emerson said the substance is not banned by the NBA, nor does he
believe it will endanger Gugliotta's eligibility for the 2000
Olympics in Sydney, Australia, where he will be a member of the
U.S. Dream Team.
</P>
<P>
   Gugliotta said he wanted to emphasize that he did not get the
supplement from any members of the team's medical, training or
strength staff or from Grant. He said none were aware he was taking
it. And Emerson said no other Phoenix player has used the
supplement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard about it through a friend of mine from high school,''
said Gugliotta, who would not identify the friend and was advised
not to identify the product brand name. ``We were just talking and
I told him I hadn't been sleeping very well.
</P>
<P>
   ``He brought this up. It is supposed to promote terrific sleep
and also help your body recover from extreme activity _ like
playing an NBA basketball game. It sounded pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Emerson said, that often is the case with
unregulated herbal-based supplements that are readily available
over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is being marketed as a safe herbal supplement,'' he said.
``This product is fairly unstable. Even changes in the body's pH,
or even a can of soda can change the chemistry. It can transform to
more unstable products within the body. It's a pretty dangerous
substance.''
</P>
<P>
   Gugliotta said he had no idea when he took the supplement that
it was any more dangerous than other over-the-counter vitamins and
herbal supplements he has taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have any idea something like this could happen,'' he
said. ``I nearly lost my life. You would have to be totally crazy
to take it if you knew beforehand what could happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never worried about going to the store for vitamins over
the counter. I've never heard of anybody getting sick from
something like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Gugliotta said he hopes others, particularly young athletes,
will learn from his mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you read some of the stuff, it sounds like it's a miracle
or something,'' he said. ``After seeing some of the research done
on the medical side, you think the exact opposite. After reading
that, you would want to at least talk to somebody before taking it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping something good can come out of it other than my
recovery. If anybody is even thinking about this stuff, there is no
way the positives _ if there are any _ can outweigh what can
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the brand names the supplement is marketed under are
ReActive, Verve, SomatoPro, Blue Nitro and Regenerize, all of which
are readily available over the Internet. There are restrictions on
its distribution in Texas, California and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Food and Drug Administration has cautioned against the
use of products containing furanone di-hydro. But the FDA regulates
mostly pharmaceuticals and does not approve or disapprove herbal
compounds.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA, however, has documented 55 adverse effects tied to
furanone di-hydro, including a death in Florida and at least 19
individuals who became unconscious or comatose after taking it.
Several of those required intubation to assist breathing, insertion
of a tube into the airway. At least five victims were 18 years old
or younger.
</P>
<P>
   Other reported effects have included seizures, vomiting, severe
headaches, slowed breathing and slowed heart rate.
</P>
<P>
   The 16-year-old Centennial High School student from Peoria
collapsed Dec. 2 during a school gym class after taking Verve _ a
furanone-based product. The student, whose name was withheld by
authorities because he is a minor, lost consciousness and had to be
resuscitated by paramedics.
</P>
<P>
   ``He stopped breathing several times. It was a very scary
situation,'' said Dudley Butts, principal of Centennial High.
</P>
<P>
   ``There should be a lot of outrage that this stuff is on the
market. The FDA hasn't approved it. But it has been approved as an
industrial solvent.''
</P>
<P>
   In the body, furanone di-hydro is rapidly converted into
gamma-hydroxybutyric Acid (GHB), which has been associated at high
levels with several deaths in California since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Gugliotta said he took the recommended dosage of a liquid
furanone product and washed it down with a soft drink before
getting on the bus. It was the second time he had used the product,
and he said there were no adverse effects the first time.
</P>
<P>
   In Portland, he began sweating profusely and his head rolled
back on the bus seat. He was on a cell phone speaking with his
wife, Nikki, when he suffered the seizure.
</P>
<P>
   Teammate Toby Bailey spotted Gugliotta in trouble and alerted
Robin Pound, the club's strength and conditioning coach. Pound sent
Bailey to find the paramedics that are on duty at NBA games, and
Pound tried to keep Gugliotta awake.
</P>
<P>
   The paramedics had not left the arena, nor had Portland's
internist, Dr. Tom Reis. They responded, and Gugliotta was
transported to a hospital just blocks from the Rose Garden arena.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns forward was on a respirator to aid his breathing in the
intensive care unit and was listed in serious condition that night.
He awoke at about 4 a.m. the next day and told ``The Arizona
Republic'' he thought at first he was in his own bed.
</P>
<P>
   Emerson later said that had Gugliotta suffered the seizure while
the team was in flight to Phoenix, he might not have survived it.
There was no equipment aboard the plane to intubate a patient who
could not breathe, and there was no one on the aircraft trained to
perform an intubation.
</P>
<P>
   Promoters of products that contain furanone di-hydro suggest
that the product can stimulate muscle recovery and growth but warn
that it can be dangerous if not taken properly.
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to reach manufacturers of the substance on Sunday were
unsuccessful. Promotional material for the various brands of the
supplement are similar and describe a compound that is supposed to
promote a deep sleep. Some furanone products are marketed as sleep
aids. Others also suggest that the products will aid muscle
recovery and growth.
</P>
<P>
   In a deep state of sleep, the promotions say, the body's
pituitary gland is more active in producing human growth hormone
(HGH), which is supposed to aid in muscle recovery and growth.
</P>
<P>
   Heath Brittan, manager of Hi Health World of Nutrition in
Arizona Mills mall in Tempe, Ariz., said the supplement's most
common form, Verve, has made very little impact on the buying
public. Brittan said all the buzz now is about a growth hormone he
calls Zen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had just a handful of people come in to the store the
last six to eight months asking for Verve. We don't stock it for
that reason,'' Brittan said.
</P>
<P>
   Brittan said he had talked to quite a few bodybuilder types at
the gymnasium in which he works out about Verve, the product which
the 16-year-old took and which is a furanone di-hydro product like
the one Gugliotta ingested.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those people said that Verve didn't work well for them,''
Brittan said. ``Usually, something that works well hits fast and
spreads like wildfire. But Verve is definitely not one of those
kinds of stimulants.''
</P>
<P>
   Gugliotta said Sunday he finally had gone most of the day
without the recurring headaches he has suffered since the episode.
He hopes to return to the club's lineup soon, when testing is
completed.
</P>
<P>
   Emerson said it is ironic that Gugliotta was caught off guard
because he is one of the most conscientious athletes he has dealt
with when it comes to medications and supplements.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what's bizarre, I guess,'' Gugliotta said. ``I won't
even take Advil painkillers if I can help it because I've heard
they can be bad for your kidneys and liver if you take too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think it was anything more dangerous than a vitamin.
I know it sounds ridiculous now, but that was my mind-set.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Republic writers Mark Shaffer and Brent Whiting contributed to this
article. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
