<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 12:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9843 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-Y2KLIST-1228-COX     12-27 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2KLIST-1228-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LAST MINUTE PRECAUTIONS TO TAKE BEFORE THE Y2K BUG BITES
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    EDS: Bulleted ``do'' and ``don't'' list at bottom of story can
also be used as graphics material.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - Procrastinators, this is your week.
</P>
<P>
   For months, government and Red Cross officials have been urging
Americans to take moderate precautions in case the Y2K computer bug
interrupts essential services after Jan. 1. But those warnings
appear to have stirred relatively few people to action.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with just four days left before the Y2K bug bites, people
still have time ``to take simple, common sense steps to prepare,''
said American Red Cross spokeswoman Leslie Credit. In fact, many of
the items you may need, such as flashlights, warm blankets and
plastic containers for water, ``you probably already have in your
home; it's just a matter to getting things together,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities say computer glitches will not cause any major
disruptions to the nation's basic infrastructure, such as the power
grids or telecommunications systems. But some communities may
experience localized problems, and no one is sure where those spot
outages might occur. So the Red Cross is urging each household to
be prepared for at least three days of inconveniences.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the concern is the Y2K software flaw that could
cause some older computers to misunderstand the date rollover from
1999 to 2000. Before the mid-1990s, many computers were programmed
to read only two digits of the year. So it's possible ``00'' will
be misread as 1900, triggering equipment malfunctions.
</P>
<P>
   While the biggest bugs have been eradicated, Americans could see
problems. Timed traffic lights could malfunction and cause traffic
tie-ups, for example. Or, computerized pharmacy records could get
confused, making it difficult to refill prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid problems in early January, authorities recommend taking
these steps now:
</P>
<P>
   _ Rinse out two-liter soda bottles or similar plastic containers
and fill them with clean tap water. Put the cap on tightly and
store out of direct sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make sure you have some ready-to-eat foods on hand in case
stores are closed. Peanut butter, canned tuna, granola bars, canned
hams and fresh fruits are good choices.
</P>
<P>
   _ Check your medications and refill any prescriptions that might
run out during the first week of January.
</P>
<P>
   _ Round up your flashlights and check the batteries.
</P>
<P>
   _ Know where you have your warm blankets, coats, gloves and hats
in case the heat goes out.
</P>
<P>
   But just as important as the ``do'' list is the ``don't'' list,
authorities say. Some actions should not be taken because they may
endanger your family or the greater community. Foolish actions to
avoid include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Buying a gun at the last minute. You don't have time to learn
to use it to safely.
</P>
<P>
   _ Waiting until Friday evening to go to an ATM for cash. You
could become a robbery target.
</P>
<P>
   _ Topping off the tank of every vehicle on Friday. If everyone
does that, shortages will hit gas stations and create a panicky
atmosphere on New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make plans to start calling everyone you know at 12:01 a.m.
Jan. 1. Phone companies say a vast surge in calls at the same time
will jam circuits.
</P>
<P>
   (Marilyn Geewax can be reached by e-mail at:
mgeewax(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
