<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 12:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9851 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-GERMS-ON-ALL-SURFACES     12-27 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMS-ON-ALL-SURFACES-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T TOUCH THAT: EVERYDAY OBJECTS SPREAD DISEASE-CAUSING GERMS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 By HEATHER ROSS  
 c.1999 HealthSurfing.com  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Inside and out, the body is a walking zoo, home to billions of
bacteria and countless viruses.
</P>
<P>
   Most microscopic hitchhikers are harmless creatures, even
helpful. Bacteria help digest food, clot blood, and keep harmful
germs out. But a few disease-causing organisms can cause serious
illness and sometimes death.
</P>
<P>
   The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention lists infectious
disease as the No.3 killer of Americans. By understanding how
disease-causing germs travel through air, water, food, and between
people, one can protect oneself from these unseen enemies.
</P>
<P>
   New research adds commonly-touched objects to the list of germ
hideouts.
</P>
<P>
   University of Arizona environmental microbiologist Charles
Gerba, Ph.D., has made a career out of understanding and
publicizing the chain of transmission of germs. In the latest
project, his researcher team set out across the cityscapes of
Chicago, Tucson and San Francisco to determine the degree to which
bodily fluids are present on commonly-touched objects.
Disease-causing germs in bodily fluids can survive for hours or
days on inanimate objects.
</P>
<P>
   Swabbing some 800 surfaces, researchers measured general
cleanliness and tested for the presence of blood, urine, saliva and
sweat. If any human protein with a potential to transmit germs
could be detected, a site was considered unhygienic.
</P>
<P>
   At malls, grocery stores, banks, vending machines, and copy
centers, 44 percent of all surfaces tested were considered
unhygienic. Twenty-one percent of objects tested carried traces of
bodily fluids.
</P>
<P>
   Shopping malls and banks were the most contaminated, with nearly
half of all surfaces failing the general hygiene test. Bodily
fluids were detected on about 27 percent of surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Banks and copy centers surprised me a lot. These are areas
that don't get a lot of cleaning or disinfecting'' says Dr. Gerba.
``I'm going to bring my own pen into the bank. The pen was one of
the worst. If you think about how many people use that pen.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerba says a person is at risk with every contact: ``If I put my
hand on a surface, I could pick up the cold virus that you left
there. Surfaces are really important to cold transmission. You
literally pick up colds all the time. We're not just talking about
colds and flus. Some of the other illnesses you can get are
diarrhea, infectious hepatitis, fevers, and hand foot and mouth
disease.''
</P>
<P>
   The top contaminated surfaces in the study:
</P>
<P>
   --Public telephones
</P>
<P>
   --Public restroom surfaces
</P>
<P>
   --Counter pens
</P>
<P>
   --Chair armrests
</P>
<P>
   --Elevator buttons
</P>
<P>
   --Escalator handrails
</P>
<P>
   --Shopping cart handles
</P>
<P>
   --Grocery refrigerator handles
</P>
<P>
   Gerba's studies show that cleaning can actually make matters
worse. ``We've done studies that show when you clean a bathroom,
you (can) spread more germs around than you're actually killing,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   In Phase 2 of the study, researchers showed that germs on
objects or on the hands can spread easily from outside to inside
the home. A telephone, a bathroom faucet, and a door handle from
three offices were ``contaminated'' with an invisible product that
glows under black light.
</P>
<P>
   The fluorescent dye, known commercially as ``Glow Germ,'' allows
researchers to trace a simulated germ's chain of transmission, and
educators and trainers in schools, food service, and healthcare to
demonstrate disease transmission.
</P>
<P>
   After 30 minutes of normal office routine, with workers
performing regular duties using shared equipment, the product had
spread to copy machines and copied papers, keyboards and mouses,
typewriters, hands, faces, telephones, hair, ears, desktops,
drinking cups, clothes, computers, door knobs, pens, glasses and a
water fountain.
</P>
<P>
   Selected workers were followed home after touching a doorknob
brushed with Glo Germ. In the case of one woman, prior to leaving
the office the traceable dust was found on her hands, shoulder,
hair clip, back pack, sunglasses, purse and keys. In the course of
driving home the product was transferred to the steering wheel,
gear shift, radio dial, door handle, and seat belt.
</P>
<P>
   Within 20 minutes of arrival at home, Glo Germ was found on the
woman's front door, phone, light switch, and drinking mug.
</P>
<P>
   As disturbing as these studies are, Gerba says the point is not
to make people germ-paranoid, but germ-wise.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always playing Russian roulette every time you touch a
surface,'' he says, ``If there's a germ there, you may or may not
get ill. You can't avoid touching these surfaces all day so you've
got to wash your hands as frequently as makes sense or use those
alcohol gels. Wash your hands and disinfect surfaces.''
</P>
<P>
   Since people come in contact with countless germs, the real
wonder is that humans aren't sick all the time. The human body has
many ``germ warfare'' strategies including...germs. Harmless
bacteria coat the skin producing substances that prevent harmful
germs from invading. Skin also forms a protective barrier. Germs
usually can't enter the skin unless it's through a cut, or an
opening like the eyes, nose, mouth, or genitals. Even then, the
body's immune system attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The immune system is an intricate network of bone marrow, blood,
the lymph nodes and vessels, tonsils, adenoids, the thymus gland
and mucous. It works best when a person is rested and eats healthy
foods.
</P>
<P>
   When a person's immune system is compromised because of young
age, old age, genetics, other illness, drug use, or even an organ
transplant, a person has more difficulty fighting off invading
germs. That's why someone with an impaired immune system is at
higher risk for germs contracted in the environment.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Arizona germ research project was funded by
the Clorox Company, makers of Clorox bleach.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (The HealthSurfing.com Web site is at http://healthsurfing.com)
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)
</P>
