<P>
   MILITIA-Y2K (San Francisco) _ The militiamen called them the
``twin sisters'' _ giant steel tanks in rural Sacramento County
that hold enough liquid propane to immolate every living thing for
five miles if they somehow were to explode. For more than a year, a
loose-knit band of survivalists, illegal firearms traders and
right-wing revolutionaries allegedly plotted to detonate the tanks,
perhaps with the same sort of fertilizer bomb used in the 1995
attack on the federal
</P>
<P>
   building in Oklahoma City. But one of the conspirators turned
out to be a shadowy informant whom the FBI had recruited with money
and the hope
</P>
<P>
   Of leniency on a weapons charge. By LANCE WILLIAMS.
</P>
<P>
   WRONG-PREDICTIONS (San Francisco) _ The future isn't what it
used to be. In the 1950s and 1960s, the most upbeat visionaries
imagined 2000 as a chrome-plated Tomorrowland with flying cars,
lunar cities and cancer cures. The most downbeat predicted nuclear
wars, gasoline lines a mile long, and widespread starvation. These
are among many incorrect forecasts about what life would be like at
the end of the century. By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   FUTURISTS (San Francisco) _ A few years ago, the Futurist, a
journal published by the 30,000-member World Future Society,
received an article discussing the coming threat of the Y2K virus.
They rejected it. That decision epitomizes the hazards of
forecasting the future over the long and the short term. By KEAY
DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   CUSTOMS-TRAVELERS (San Francisco) _ Though U.S. Customs
examinations are designed primarily to catch drug smugglers _ who
often resort to extreme measures, such as swallowing condoms filled
with drugs or hiding heroin in surgical wounds or hollow legs _
most of what gets
</P>
<P>
   confiscated on a daily basis is far less dramatic. By ANASTASIA
HENDRIX.
</P>
<P>
   PLAGIARISM.ORG (Berkeley, Calif.) _ Thanks to a former teaching
assistant at UC-Berkeley, there's a new weapon to catch students
who would rather surf the Web for a paper than write their own.
John Barrie, a neurobiology Ph.D. candidate at Cal, launched an
online service for professors and instructors suspicious of their
students' work. It's called Plagiarism.org. By MATTHEW YI.
</P>
<P>
   CUSTOMS-TONE (San Francisco) _ As of Oct. 1, a series of new
traveler-friendly policies has been in place at the U.S. Customs
Service, a change the agency hopes will help soften its reputation
for conducting overzealous and intrusive searches or targeting a
disproportionate number of women and minorities for scrutiny. By
ANASTASIA HENDRIX.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ Texas officials say the state is
prepared
</P>
<P>
   for the so-called Y2K bug. But just in case something does
happens,
</P>
<P>
   hundreds of state employees will be on duty _ and thousands more
will be on call New Year's Eve and New Year's Day _ to carry out
contingency
</P>
<P>
   plans patterned after hurricane response procedures. By JOHN
GONZALEZ.
</P>
