<DOCNO> NYT19991227.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 13:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9865 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-MAINTAINING-MEMORY-NY     12-27 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAINTAINING-MEMORY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCH AIMS AT EARLY INTERVENTION TO SLOW ALZHEIMER'S  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 By SHAWN O'LEARY  
 c.1999 HealthSurfing.com  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kurt and Betty Reichert love to reminisce about days gone by
when they rivaled Hepburn and Bogart with their globe-trotting
escapades. The Reicherts have spent a lifetime trekking, sailing
and flying to the four corners of the globe.
</P>
<P>
   For Betty, who has been diagnosed with Alzheimer's disease (AD),
nostalgia serves as a memory exercise. Although still spry at 83,
Kurt says he's also losing his memory: ``I'm to the point where I
have to write little notes to myself not to forget what I was going
to do upstairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Kurt's waning memory worries him enough to get tested.
Researchers at the Mayo Clinic say it's a legitimate concern in
light of research identifying a distinct type of memory loss called
mild cognitive impairment, or MCI.
</P>
<P>
   Alzheimer's specialist Dr. Leo Thal says that people with the
condition have chronic memory problems but, generally speaking, no
other symptoms of Alzheimer's such as impaired perception, language
difficulty, disorientation, or sleeping problems:
</P>
<P>
   ``Their spatial relations are fine, their speech is fine, their
language is fine, their ability to navigate is fine. They're
functioning not perfectly normally, but pretty normally,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   HALTING PROGRESSION
</P>
<P>
   Thal estimates three million Americans have mild cognitive
impairment, and 2.5 to 5 million people have Alzheimer's. One
hundred thousand people die from AD each year. He is anxious to
find drugs that will help curb the progression of MCI to
Alzheimer's as his generation--Baby Boomers--moves on to
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Says Thal: ``We think if you're going to develop Alzheimer's
disease, patients will go through this phase. But it's not
generally recognized because individuals who have this syndrome
generally don't present themselves for medical attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Memory loss hasn't stopped the Reicherts from collecting more
memories in the present, most recently touring Europe, from
Normandy to Vienna. Says Keith, ``We travel, we go to water
aerobics, we go to plays, to concerts, to the zoo. We have lots of
friends, we have house guests. We're having a good time.''
</P>
<P>
   But the effort doesn't come easily, Keith notes, especially for
Betty: ``It's a struggle in self-discipline. Much of her struggle
goes on subtly, inside, in ways that I can only fathom that she
doesn't enunciate.''
</P>
<P>
   With MCI, information in the brain isn't reached slowly; the
information vanishes.
</P>
<P>
   Past Mayo Clinic research shows mild cognitive impairment
frequently leads to Alzheimer's disease. Says Thal, ``After three
years, we anticipate that 45 percent of subjects will develop
Alzheimer's disease, after seven years over 70 percent will.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast only 1 percent of the general population in the same
age group develop AD.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL DRUG TRIALS
</P>
<P>
   The National Institute on Aging (NIA), as outlined in the March
15, 1999 issue of the journal Archives of Neurology, is
investigating a drug called Aricept (generic name: donepezil) to
see if it can improve memory in MCI patients. Donepezil is a
cholinesterase inhibitor. Research was half funded by NIA and half
funded by the marketer and manufacturer of Aricept, Eisai Inc. and
Pfizer Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Donepezil increases the amount of the neurotransmitter
acetylcholine, which controls memory and other brain functions, and
reduces anxiety and depression, common in AD patients.
</P>
<P>
   NIA is also trying to determine whether large doses of vitamin E
can delay the onset of Alzheimer's in this risk group. Vitamin E is
thought to neutralize cell-damaging free radicals produced by the
buildup of plaques in the brain, a key characteristic of
Alzheimer's.
</P>
<P>
   Past research found that AD sufferers who added large quantities
of vitamin E to their diets took approximately eight months longer
to progress to a more serious level of the disease. A serious side
effect of taking high levels of vitamin E is internal bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   Other drugs are also being researched, including Vioxx, an
anti-inflammatory, nonsteroidal, COX-2 inhibitor, generically known
as rofecoxib.
</P>
<P>
   From the medical community's standpoint, the goal of early
intervention is to keep people out of nursing homes, saving
billions in healthcare costs.
</P>
<P>
   Says Thal, ``At some point we may change the criteria at which
we diagnose Alzheimer's disease, but we're certainly not ready to
do so at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   There are other goals connected to this research, more personal
ones. Kurt says staying independent and together is his family's
top health priority: ``Betty and I consider ourselves very
fortunate--taking the Alzheimer's as a given--in the way we can
work around it, work with it, and cope with it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's at ``home sweet home''--not at a care facility--where Keith
and Betty feel they can best take their trips down Memory Lane, and
plan for their next voyage.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (The HealthSurfing.com Web site is at http://healthsurfing.com)
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)
</P>
</TEXT>
