<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9877 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r i BC-MEXICO-VANWRECK-3000(     12-27 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-VANWRECK-3000(3TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY DEVASTATED BY LOSS OF 9 IN WRECK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REBECA RODRIGUEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEOCALTICHE, Mexico _ Inside the warm, bright kitchen, women
chattered as tamales stuffed with meat and sweet fruits steamed in
huge pots. Outside, the men watched sausages and strips of pork
roast, their eyes glowing with the heat of the fire.
</P>
<P>
   The lively din of children peppered the air.
</P>
<P>
   Then the clock struck midnight and the hugs began.
</P>
<P>
   ``Feliz Navidad,'' they told one another, somberly. ``Merry
Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   Christmas came to this central Mexican home this year, but it
brought little joy. One week earlier, nine members of this family
perished on a dark Mexican highway as they headed south for the
holidays from their home in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Six were children, ages 1 to 16. Only one person, Jose Carvajal,
24, survived. The truck driver who collided with the family's
Suburban fled and still eludes police.
</P>
<P>
   Killed in the crash were siblings Javier, 1, and Cecilia
Delgadillo, 4, and their cousin Cindy Delgadillo, 6. Also dead are
six brothers and sisters: Filiberta Carvajal Delgadillo, 29, Javier
and Cecilia's mother; and Maria, 11, Silvano, 13, Eva, 16, Noel,
who turned 22 the day he died, and Sofia Carvajal, 29.
</P>
<P>
   The tragedy has scarred many in the three communities that the
Carvajal and Delgadillo families called home: Fort Worth, where
they had lived for several years; the small Mexican town of
Teocaltiche; and the small ranch in central Mexico called Lo de
Carrera, about 260 miles northwest of Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, thousands lined the stone streets of Teocaltiche in
mourning. They packed the Cementerio de Los Angeles, the final
resting place for all nine. At a time typically marked by joyful
family gatherings, relatives in all three communities can only
wonder why life has brought them so much death.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just can't understand how life could do this,'' said
Prudencia Gonzalez Jimenez, an aunt to many of the dead.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Behind the white steel doors at 96 Juan A. Garcia St., the
shuffling of footsteps on the concrete floor signals the start of a
new day.
</P>
<P>
   Floors are swept; breakfast is cooked. The strong smell of
varnish pickles the air as the 30-year-old family business of
making wooden chess sets churns on. A small plastic Christmas tree
sits in one corner of the front sitting room. It appears to be a
typical Mexican home the week before Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   But life here changed dramatically a week ago. Normally the
family gathering place for festivities, the home of Prudencia and
Juan Gonzalez Jimenez is a site of mourning. On Wednesday, Elida
Carvajal Delgadillo looked at a Fort Worth Star-Telegram from last
week and saw a picture of her 6-year-old daughter, Cindy, who died
in the wreck.
</P>
<P>
   Her hand flew to her mouth and tears began to flow freely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ay, mi nina,'' she cried softly.
</P>
<P>
   Elida Carvajal Delgadillo and her husband, Epifanio Delgadillo,
had left Fort Worth for Mexico and were eager to be reunited with
their little girl. Now, Elida is the last remaining daughter in the
family.
</P>
<P>
   As the day wore on, brothers, cousins and grandparents filled
the home, whispering and hugging. Some shed tears; others prayed.
</P>
<P>
   A child's squeal came from the bedroom as Elida Delgadillo's
3-year-old son, Erik, tore into a box of brand-new toy cars. He was
once one of four grandchildren in the Carvajal and Delgadillo
families, which are related by marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is the only one.
</P>
<P>
   He can't understand why his sister isn't around to celebrate
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asks me, `Where is she, papa? D''nde est , Cindy?' '' his
father said. ``I bought something for him the other day and he said
I should buy something for Cindy, too. He's too young to
understand.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Christmas was on the horizon when the Carvajal and Delgadillo
families loaded the Suburban in south Fort Worth on Dec. 17. Some
family members had left for Mexico days or weeks earlier, and this
would be the last batch of passengers to make the trip. Six of them
were children who had to stay in school until that Friday.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 15, Jose Carvajal flew to Ciudad Juarez, picked up the
Suburban and drove it to Fort Worth. There, nine others boarded,
gifts in tow, and headed for Mexico about 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   They planned to make the trip in 13 hours, stopping only when
necessary. It started out happily, Jose Carvajal said. Brother Noel
Carvajal had turned 22 that day and, by Saturday morning, all would
be home for the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Because he had driven so much already, Jose Carvajal fell asleep
in the passenger's seat during the trip. He was still asleep at 3
a.m. when he awoke to the sound of steel crashing against steel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disoriented and I barely remember what happened,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   His eyes lower when he thinks about what happened next. His
brothers and sisters were in pain, as he was, having broken his
left arm. There was chaos inside the van as people tried to move
around, to quell the pain.
</P>
<P>
   The youngest children cried, and 13-year-old Silvano said his
leg hurt. Yards away, the steel mill truck that hit them was turned
on its side, but Jose Carvajal could not read the name or the
license plates.
</P>
<P>
   A third vehicle, also from Fort Worth, was reportedly involved
in the accident, but relatives said the family was released by
police and left the scene.
</P>
<P>
   On the highway, no one passed by for what seemed like forever.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, at least an hour later, Jose Carvajal said, a car
stopped and some people covered the injured with blankets, and then
left to call help. Eventually, ambulances arrived and Jose Carvajal
was whisked off to a hospital nearby, where a doctor set his arm
and gave him painkillers.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't know it then, but the nine others were dead.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Carvajal survived, but the pain of losing six brothers and
sisters, two nieces and a nephew is visible in his eyes, his
hunched frame, his drawn lips. What haunts him most is that some of
the nine _ he doesn't know which _ were still alive for some time
after the accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``If help had arrived more quickly, some of my brothers and
sisters could have survived,'' he said. ``They were alive for a
while after the wreck, but help didn't come in time.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Jose Carvajal was born and raised on Lo de Carrera, the small
ranch named for those who set up a home there more than a century
ago. Today, the rural ranch is a world away from bustling Fort
Worth.
</P>
<P>
   The dusty, bumpy ride from Teocaltiche to Lo de Carrera takes
close to an hour, even though they are only about 10 miles apart.
Along the way, travelers cross from Jalisco state into Zacatecas
state.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Carvajal knows the way with his eyes closed. He lived on
the ranch for his first 20 years and returns frequently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Left at the fork, right at the road paved with stones, and
here we are,'' he said, as the car rounded a curve. Below, laid out
like living carpet, was the ranch. Small brick homes dot its
surface, and steel-blue mountains line the horizon. At the fenced
entrance to the ranch, a sleepy cow chews and stares, a benign
gatekeeper.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's beautiful here,'' Carvajal said. ``Here we work, plant
crops, cultivate the land, and you never go hungry.''
</P>
<P>
   The air is pure. During the day, the sun beats down on old men
working in the fields, their sandals caked with dust.
</P>
<P>
   Burros carry loads of hay, roosters crow and women hang clothes
to dry. The low-wattage lights from inside the many farmhouses are
swallowed by the night.
</P>
<P>
   It is a land of leathery hands and deeply creased faces, where
manual labor is valued and the strength of community upheld. For
the Carvajal and Delgadillo families, most of whom were born and
raised here, Lo de Carrera is without question the place they call
home.
</P>
<P>
   Candido and Maria Concepcion Carvajal, the patriarch and
matriarch, both grew up on the ranch in the 1930s and '40s. They
raised crops, as their families had done before them, and bore 11
children.
</P>
<P>
   On 5 hectares (about 12 acres) of fertile land, they built a
brick home and began their life together raising corn, beans and
squash. Decades later, wearing high-dollar sneakers and an ESPN
ball cap, Jose Carvajal remembers his childhood as a happy,
innocent time.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were growing up, we were extremely poor,'' he said.
``We never had toys, so we played with our shoes, with rocks,
whatever we found.''
</P>
<P>
   When the children got older, they put on work boots or durable
leather sandals and a hat and worked the fields, planting and
harvesting the family crops. When things got dull, there was always
the nearby town of Teocaltiche.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as now, the senses came alive with the scent of roasting
corn, the rumble of trucks coughing out plumes of black smoke, and
the blare of Mexican ranchera music from cheap speakers in store
doorways.
</P>
<P>
   That was life for Jose and his 10 brothers and sisters.
</P>
<P>
   Then, people began leaving to ``el norte.''
</P>
<P>
   Jose Carvajal remembers hearing the stories as a young child.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the United States was the best, and it was my dream
to go there,'' he said. ``People who went there said you could make
a lot of money and live well.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven years ago, his older sister Elida and her husband moved to
the south side of Fort Worth in search of work. They chose Fort
Worth because Epifanio Delgadillo had cousins already living and
working there who could help them get on their feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard, and scary, to go where you don't know
anyone,'' said Epifanio Delgadillo, who works in a pepperoni
factory in Fort Worth. ``When you go, you look for your own kind.
We stick together and help each other out.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   Cesareo Delgadillo, Epifanio's brother, also lives in Fort Worth
and works on conversion vans. He said he is offended when people
accuse Mexicans and other immigrants of being welfare freeloaders
in search of free health care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Immigrants built the United States,'' he said. ``If it weren't
for immigrants, the U.S. economy would not be as strong as it is.
When we go there, we buy houses, we pay taxes and we work, often
for very little.''
</P>
<P>
   After Epifanio and Cesareo Delgadillo moved to the south side of
Fort Worth, the exodus from Lo de Carrera continued. Now, several
dozen people from the same ranch live and work there, returning
home only for the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   They help one another find work, act as translators, and pool
resources to rent and buy homes.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Carvajal had been living in Mexico most of this year
because of an illness, but he, too, makes his home in Fort Worth,
where he works for Mike Cancos' carpentry company. Another brother,
Cirilo Carvajal, 19, lives in Fort Worth, and a third, Margarito
Carvajal, 23, lives in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The last remaining brother, Adan Gonzalez Carvajal, lives in
Fort Lauderdale, Fla., and works as an assistant to the famous
Mexican singer Juan Gabriel.
</P>
<P>
   Adan Carvajal's work has allowed him to buy a home for his
family in Fort Worth. And in one room of the ranch house at Lo de
Carrera sits a new computer with the Windows 98 operating system
and a scanner.
</P>
<P>
   ``One can get ahead in the United States more than here,'' Adan
Gonzalez Carvajal said. ``The schools are better and more
opportunities are available. And children learn English, which will
probably be the world language one day.''
</P>
<P>
   The migration has changed Lo de Carrera. Older people, like
Candido Carvajal, still work their land as was done at the turn of
the century.
</P>
<P>
   But many of the houses are empty, their doors locked and their
occupants working in cities like Fort Worth, Los Angeles, Chicago
and Fort Lauderdale. A drive through the ranch's center reveals few
young children.
</P>
<P>
   Still, La Navidad remains a time to return to Mexico to enjoy
the posadas, eat Christmas meals and be with family. In
Teocaltiche, it appears that every fourth car or truck bears Texas
license plates, with a few from California, Illinois, Nevada and
New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Down Ninos Heroes street, past the cathedral, is the Cementerio
de Los Angeles. Hundreds of elaborate monuments to the town's dead
stand inside its gated walls. The placid eyes of La Virgen de
Guadalupe and Jesucristo stare timelessly into space. Everywhere,
bright flowers are a reminder that the dead are not forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Between two monuments lies a mountain of funeral wreaths bearing
messages like ``For Javier'' or ``From the Gonzalez Gonzalez
family.''
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the wreaths, the nine are buried, together in death as
in life. It is a public display of mourning and connects the whole
town to this tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   But a far greater pain takes place in private.
</P>
<P>
   Since the accident, Maria Concepcion Carvajal has been in
seclusion at the home of her sister, Prudencia Gonzalez Jimenez.
The loss of six of her 11 children has cast her into deep despair,
and she is not eating.
</P>
<P>
   Her family fears that she may not survive the tragedy. Her son
Adan wants her to live with him in Fort Lauderdale.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Candido Carvajal, is a man of few words. At age 69,
he still gets up every morning and heads for the fields of Lo de
Carrera. There he stays, day in and day out. His horse has no name,
but they are partners nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   And he seems strangely unlike a man who lost six children and
three grandchildren a week ago. But beneath his stoic exterior, one
senses a deep pain that only he can feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Angels, all of them,'' he said, a distant smile on his brown
wrinkled face. ``Now, they're in Heaven, and we have to keep on
living. I have to be strong for those who remain.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
