<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9881 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-BOOKS-BREAKINGTHROUGH     12-27 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-BREAKINGTHROUGH-2000(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK BUSINESS IS GOOD, BUT IT'S HARD FOR AUTHORS TO GET NOTICED
</HEADLINE>
 
(Accompanied by BC-BOOKS-MUSTREAD) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even though Americans are reading more _ book sales are up
nearly 15 percent in the '90s, according to industry surveys _ the
chances of talented, lesser-known writers becoming bestselling
superstars are worse than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a deadly combination of things _ the changing nature of
the publishing industry, the tastes of bookstore patrons, and the
kinds of books and authors the media chooses to publicize, when
they do publicize books at all,'' says Kenneth Kirkland, an
independent publishing-industry analyst based in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's put it this way: In some months, as many as 5,000 books
are published in America. Each month, Oprah Winfrey chooses one
book to feature in her book club. Five thousand-to-one is about the
correct odds for a really gifted writer to break out into the Tom
Clancy-Anne Rice-Stephen King stratosphere of being popular enough
to guarantee huge sales,'' Kirkland says.
</P>
<P>
   New Mexico's Tony Hillerman, whose first mystery novels cracked
bestseller lists in the early 1970s, is more succinct:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad I'm not trying to make a name for myself now,''
Hillerman says. ``It's just about impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   The primary reason, analysts and authors agree, is the business
philosophy of major publishing companies. Most are part of
diversified corporate conglomerates whose mission is to make as
much money as possible for shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a numbers-crunching business now,'' says Texas author
Carlton Stowers, who has won two prestigious Edgar awards for best
true crime writing. ``Take Random House,'' Stowers says. ``Now
they're run by this big German outfit who are huge in the auto
industry. They know how to make money selling cars, so they run
their new book business like a car dealership. The big names get
all the attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirkland says that publishers put their muscle behind Stephen
King or Anne Rice because the profits subsidize the other books
being published.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, when publicists contact TV and radio talk-show
hosts and print journalists urging interviews with authors, their
first efforts concentrate on the big names.
</P>
<P>
   But when they tout lesser-known but gifted writers to the media,
the media aren't interested.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is frustrating,'' says Norton publicist Catherine Melnicki.
``Usually to break out an author, it takes major media hits
(coverage), but most of the (media) people we contact just want the
big names. Well, they want ratings or lots of readers, and the big
names bring that. Everyone works by the rules of a
capitalism-driven marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   To save money, many publishers are cutting back on the number of
``midlist'' authors, whose work doesn't make the bestseller lists.
</P>
<P>
   Novelists are in the highest risk category. ``Up until the '60s
and '70s, the book industry was driven by fiction,'' Kirkland says.
``But titles like `In Cold Blood' (by Truman Capote) and `Helter
Skelter' (by Vincent Bugliosi) changed that. It has evolved to a
point where I'd estimate two-thirds of the titles sold each year
are nonfiction. Bookstores, which are now mostly huge chains like
Barnes &AMP; Noble, push those.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado writer Pam Houston's first two books, ``Cowboys Are My
Weakness'' and ``Waltzing the Cat,'' were composed of short
stories. Each received critical kudos but sold modestly. At the
strong suggestion of her publisher, Houston's third collection, ``A
Little More About Me,'' is a series of first-person essays, many of
which appeared in magazines Houston writes for to augment her
income.
</P>
<P>
   ``The publisher tells me this is what I need to do if I want to
become well-known enough for my fiction to sell,'' Houston says.
``I understand and I'll try it. But my fiction means so much more
to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``kind'' of nonfiction most popular with readers also
hampers fine writers in search of recognition.
</P>
<P>
   ``So-called self-help books are classified as nonfiction, and
those are often written by psychologists, professors, professionals
who couldn't or shouldn't write books about anything other than
their area of specialization,'' Kirkland says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do they sell millions of books while much more talented
writers sell in the few thousands? Of course they do,'' Kirkland
says. ``Publishers are marketing books to a society in search of
quick fixes to personal problems.''
</P>
<P>
   All of which leaves most lesser-known writers with one shining
hope: Oprah Winfrey.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could get one of my books on `Oprah,' I would pay my own
way to get there,'' Stowers says.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   Since 1996, when she endorsed the novel ``The Deep End of the
Ocean'' by then-unknown Jacquelyn Mitchard, Winfrey has selected
one book a month and invited its author to appear on her nationally
syndicated TV show. Bestsellerdom is not guaranteed as a result _
Sheri Reynolds' ``The Rapture of Canaan'' and Ernest J. Gaines' ``A
Lesson Before Dying'' were never bestsellers. Sometimes Winfrey
selects books that have long been in print, such as Toni Morrison's
``Song of Solomon.''
</P>
<P>
   But Winfrey made stars of Mitchard and Wally Lamb (''I Know This
Much Is True''), while helping Anna Quindlen (''Black and Blue: A
Novel,'' Jane Hamilton (''The Book of Ruth''), Maeve Binchy (''Tara
Road'') and Alice Hoffman (''Here on Earth'') move up on the
celebrity author ladder.
</P>
<P>
   Failing Oprah, Kirkland concludes, the best, if near-miraculous,
way for an unknown author to break into bestsellerdom ``is still
word of mouth by people who work in bookstores. Charles Frazier's
``Cold Mountain'' became a bestseller that way, with somebody
suggesting the book, somebody buying it and then recommending it to
friends. Kent Haruf's ``Plainsong,'' too. That kind of thing still
happens. It just doesn't happen much.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is books editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Contact him at (817) 390-7720 or e-mail:
jguinn(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
