<DOCNO> NYT19991227.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9884 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-BOOKS-MUSTREAD-TEX     12-27 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MUSTREAD-TEX </SLUG>
 
(Accompanies BC-BOOKS-BREAKINGTHROUGH) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Few modern American authors are household names _ industry
analyst Kenneth Kirkland says the modern-day ``famous writer'' list
``probably consists of John Grisham, Tom Clancy, Patricia Cornwell,
Stephen King, Toni Morrison, Anne Rice, Tom Wolfe and maybe John
Updike, with people like Dave Barry, Mary Higgins Clark, Tony
Hillerman and Sandra Brown on the next rung under that.''
</P>
<P>
   Following are four of America's finest, if not best-known,
current writers. One is a publishing veteran, one has just
published her third title, and two are relative rookies.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bryson: The crusty Iowa native is wrongly categorized as a
travel writer. In fact, his on-the-road rants offer both belly
laughs and thoughtful criticisms of modern culture.
</P>
<P>
   Best book: ``A Walk in the Woods'' (Broadway Books, $25), which
chronicles Bryson's disastrous attempt to hike the Appalachian
Trail. An imaginary scene where Bryson is set upon by bears may be
the funniest moment in modern American literature.
</P>
<P>
   In his own words: ``When you write for a living, you want as
wide an audience as possible. It's human instinct to crave success.
But actually, one of the nicest things about not being well-known
is it spares you the downside of celebrity. I would hate to be
recognized when I walk down the street.''
</P>
<P>
   Eric Garcia: Still in his 20s, Garcia has a college degree in
creative writing and film. While working as a screenwriter in Los
Angeles, Garcia decided to try his hand at a novel. The spectacular
result failed to reach a wide audience, but gained sufficient
critical praise to ensure that his second book will be widely
reviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Best book: ``Anonymous Rex: A Detective Story'' (Villard, $23)
stands the hoary mystery genre on its literary ear. Garcia's
protagonist, LA gumshoe Vincent Rubio, is a velociraptor disguised
as a human. The book's sequel, ``Casual Rex,'' should be published
in 2000 or 2001.
</P>
<P>
   In his own words: ``I got the idea while watching a documentary
(about dinosaurs) on television. My hope is to write novels, and to
be able to try different things from other books that are out
there. Certainly I hope for a wide audience; I'm trying to
entertain as many people as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Pam Houston: The Colorado writer divides her time between
crafting short stories and engaging in life-threatening wilderness
adventures, many of which she writes about for outdoor magazines.
Novelist Pat Conroy says he ``loves and adores'' Houston's work.
Mystery writer James Lee Burke considers Houston ``one of the best
I've ever read.''
</P>
<P>
   Best book: While publisher Norton hopes the nonfiction ``A
Little More About Me'' will finally gain Houston the audience she
deserves, ``Cowboys Are My Weakness'' (Washington Square Press, $14
in paperback) is the short-story collection that cemented Houston's
reputation. It is a priceless example of just how compelling short
fiction can be.
</P>
<P>
   In her own words: ``It means so much to me, whenvever I do book
signings, when people come up to me and start talking like they're
friends, because they feel they know me from reading my books. That
kind of connection with readers _ it's what writing is about. I
hope my books become better known, of course, but it's the writing
itself that I care about most _ doing the best I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Karla Kuban: A native of Minnesota who now lives in New Mexico,
Kuban is the product of several distinguished writing programs,
including a stint as a James A. Michener Fellow at the University
of Texas at Austin. After winning several awards for short stories,
Kuban attempted a novel _ and what a novel ``Marchlands'' was.
Critics swooned, but as a first-time author, Kuban received minimal
publicity, and the book failed to ``earn back its advance'' for
publisher Scribner. Kuban is working on her second novel.
</P>
<P>
   Best book: ``Marchlands: A Novel'' (Scribner, $23) is a
coming-of-age story, set on a western sheep ranch, in which Kuban
evokes the best writing of Ivan Doig (character development) and
Larry McMurtry (sense of place).
</P>
<P>
   In her own words: ``A first-time author like me can't expect to
be instantly known, to become a household name right away, if ever.
I am only slightly frustrated that my book didn't achieve higher
sales figures. In the end, I am grateful that it has been
published, thankful to be making a living as a writer.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
