<HEADLINE>
N.E. UTILITIES, OTHER SECTORS SAY Y2K PLANS ARE IN ORDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ After years of work by New England's big utilities,
phone companies, and government agencies to solve the Y2K computer
glitch, it is hard to make a case for major infrastructure
disruptions at midnight Friday.
</P>
<P>
   As the final week of 1999 begins, power providers, including
Boston Edison and New England Electric, say their systems are in
order; banks, including Fleet Boston Corp., say they've got Y2K
covered.
</P>
<P>
   A key water supplier, the Massachusetts Water Resources
Authority, received a mostly healthy audit report earlier this
month on its Y2K readiness. In New Hampshire, a consultant found
the state's main power companies to have a low risk of disruption,
although some smaller water and telephone companies were judged to
have a ``moderate'' risk of problems.
</P>
<P>
   At the national level, ``We have no indications there are
problems that were overlooked or not paid attention to,'' John
Koskinen, President Clinton's top Y2K adviser, said in an interview
late last week.
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen and others make fewer promises about what might happen
overseas, but most domestic worries now center on what might occur
as businesses and stock exchanges open Monday, Jan. 3, when
thousands of minor failures could add up to significant
difficulties. That's still progress, considering how much
hand-wringing there was at the start of 1999 that major systems
wouldn't be fixed in time.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Goldberg, a computer consultant who advises a dozen
clients on Y2K matters, said he still expects some problems in the
first few weeks of January but credits ``economic self-interest''
for motivating many companies to speed up their preparations during
the past 12 months. ``Nobody can afford to take the
public-relations hit of a Y2K failure,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials can't know for sure what will happen when the clock
strikes midnight, but they have developed plenty of plans to limit
the impact of any problems.
</P>
<P>
   Where available, some of these documents are sobering. The MWRA,
for example, imagines a worst-case scenario in which ``regional
power and/or communications may be lost for up to three consecutive
days and unstable conditions may persist for up to 14 days.''
</P>
<P>
   The MWRA says it could keep operating under such circumstances,
a good thing considering the White House estimates that only 15 to
20 percent of US households have stockpiled supplies.
</P>
<P>
   But planners are paid for their pessimism, and overall, ``things
look good,'' said Jim Sinclair, spokesman for ISO New England Inc.
in Holyoke, the region's bulk electric power-distribution
organization.
</P>
<P>
   In July, the organization's largest member utilities, including
New England Electric and Northeast Utilities, parent of Western
Mass. Electric and Public Service Co. of New Hampshire, said they
had completed upgrades of their most important systems.
</P>
<P>
   These companies declined to release internal audits they have
commissioned of their preparations, prompting criticism. On Dec.
20, ISO New England did release the results of a spot-check of 13
power generation, transmission, and control facilities done by Duke
Engineering &AMP; Services, although the power companies that
participated were allowed to select which of their systems were
checked.
</P>
<P>
   Out of 425 items that were surveyed, utilities were able to
produce documents showing a successful fix in 423 cases. Both
exceptions related to purchase orders, a result the Massachusetts
Department of Telecommunications and Energy says is sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   Another worry was that many large-power consumers would fire up
their own emergency generators over New Year's weekend, creating an
imbalance between the amount of power demanded and the amount
produced.
</P>
<P>
   But after hearing this concern at an industry meeting in August,
major transmission companies surveyed their big customers and know
of only a few that plan to use their own power this weekend. New
England Electric has received commitments from its 3,100 large
commercial and industrial consumers that they will remain ``on the
grid,'' said spokeswoman Karen Berardino. ``Everybody agreed to
cooperate.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinclair, the ISO's spokesman, said the organization's members
typically generate about 10,000 megawatts of power during New
Year's weekend; based on recent surveys the group expects to
produce about 12,000 megawatts this year, mostly to accommodate the
extra office workers many companies expect to have on duty.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those will be employees of Bell Atlantic, the dominant
phone company in 13 Northeastern states. It will have 20,000
employees on duty Friday night, 5,000 more than usual.
</P>
<P>
   For the MWRA, which supplies water and sewer services to about
2.6 million people in Eastern Massachusetts, service disruptions
could lead to public-health concerns. But the agency says it is set
to handle any contingency related to Y2K after spending $4.3
million on software upgrades and extra supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Of that, $600,000 has been spent on new electric generators in
case they are needed to pump water to communities. But the
authority says water systems serving 85 percent of its customers
are driven by gravity and don't require power to operate.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the power companies, the water authority did agree to
share the results of an outside review of its preparations.
</P>
<P>
   The review by the state, released by State Auditor Joseph
DeNucci's office Dec. 8, states that ``it appears that the
authority will be well-positioned to ensure continued provision of
its critical business operations up to, during, and after the year
changeover.''
</P>
<P>
   DeNucci's report raised several concerns about the authority's
contingency plans for continuing operations in case of power
disruptions. In particular, the auditors cited concerns about
whether the MWRA could obtain enough fuel to run all of its back-up
generators for three straight days, since the fuel tanks of some
would need frequent refills.
</P>
<P>
   That could prove confusing amid competing demands for fuel
``between public and private sector entities,'' the auditor's
report states, sounding more like a plan for civil defense.
</P>
<P>
   Greg DeFronzo, who heads the MWRA's Y2K readiness efforts, said
it has since clarified its refueling plans with its vendors.
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire, the state's public utilities commission this
month released a consultant's report stating that ``the state's
utilites are well-positioned'' to cope with Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   The auditors gave good marks to the state's electric and gas
utilities and to Bell Atlantic, which serves 94 percent of New
Hampshire. They assigned a ``moderate'' risk rating to many smaller
telecommunications and water systems in places such as Hanover.
</P>
<P>
   But the consultants said that overall, most of the water
companies ``have exhibited diligence in performance of their Y2K
programs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
