<SLUG> BC-CHANGING-NAMES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`2000' MAY SOON BECOME A THING OF THE PAST FOR MARKETERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For now, you can find the number ``2000'' attached to the names
of everything from breath mints to government reports to an escort
service on the World Wide Web _ generally meant to suggest a
product is new and nifty.
</P>
<P>
   But seen in that light, the imminent arrival of Jan. 1, 2000,
represents a marketing catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   Who wants to be associated with the past?
</P>
<P>
   ``Once New Year's Eve comes and goes, anything that says `2000'
on it could seem backward-looking,'' said Richard Schreuer of
Chadwick Martin Bailey, a Boston consulting firm that helps
companies come up with product names.
</P>
<P>
   Enough already, said Patrick Devine, whose Amsterdam, N.Y.,
company recently quit selling its Concept 2000 woodworking tool.
Once, the name seemed innovative, he said, but lately, ``You want
to stick your finger down your throat anytime you hear a
reference'' to 2000.
</P>
<P>
   PC maker Gateway 2000 also has dropped the number from its
corporate name and now goes by Gateway Inc. And Shell Oil Co. has
quit selling its SU2000 gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   A fast-food unit of ConAgra Brands is about to change the name
of its ``2000'' microwaveable popcorn brand to ``Extreme Butter,''
thinking it more up-to-date.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a better way to hit that teenage boy market,''
marketing manager Dan O'Connor said. ``We don't want to seem
passe.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the children's book hero Harry Potter has upgraded from the
``Nimbus Two Thousand'' flying broomstick he once used. In the most
recent volume, young Potter rides a ``Firebolt,'' which, compared
with the older model, boasts ``superbly smooth action.''
</P>
<P>
   2000, some agree, isn't all it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was this nice, round number, a universal symbol that
conjured up a future we could all relate to,'' Schreuer said. After
Jan. 1, ``I don't know what the shorthand for the future is going
to be,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``2000 isn't what's relevant to people anymore,'' said Eric
Keshin, manager of the McCann-Erickson Worldwide ad agency, which
helped Gateway pick its new name.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, 2000 still has its boosters, such as software and
car companies that use it to designate model years. Other backers
include several hair salons in New England, which call themselves
Hair 2000. ``It's futuristic. It shows we're thinking ahead,''
explained John Marnelakis, who owns a Hair 2000 shop in Indian
Orchard.
</P>
<P>
   The name, he said, was partly inspired by a device called the
``Perm 2000,'' which calculated the amount of chemicals needed for
a particular customer's hair type. But many customers have
suggested he find a new commercial identity. ``They're saying I'll
be backdated,'' Marnelakis said.
</P>
<P>
   Once, there was little argument that 2000 stood for progress and
achievement. The number reached an apex in 1989, when it was used
as part of ``Goals 2000,'' an education initiative by the nation's
governors and then-president George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, 2000 seemed to represent ``something bold,''
recalled Jennifer Davis, now an aide to Mayor Thomas M. Menino and
previously a planner for the National Governors Association. ``What
we came out with had to be very high-minded and visible and
visionary. 2000 is all those things, or at least it used to be,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Doubts about ``2000's'' potential first began to emerge in 1975
when producer Roger Corman released ``Death Race 2000,'' an
unfortunate movie involving a fatal sports-car competition. Jeb
Brody, a curator at the American Museum of the Moving Image in New
York, said it was among the first films ``that didn't invoke a
Utopian feel for 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Another early skeptic was Marc Abrahams, editor of the ``Annals
of Improbable Research'' parody magazine in Cambridge. In 1994,
Abrahams began surveying his readers for mentions of 2000 and
estimates he has since received more than 10,000 nominations.
</P>
<P>
   Examples include the Ultra Gel 2000 air freshener, the Apotheke
2000 drugstore in Switzerland, the Dating 2000 service, and the
Snore Stop 2000 nose clip.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, Abrahams said he is puzzled by the
popularity of the term but declined to criticize companies
specifically. ``It's minimal work and possibly maximal payback when
you slap it on,'' he said. ``And let's face it, everybody else is
doing it, too!''
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't quite the case in 1987 when American Tool Companies
Inc. of Vernon Hills, Ill., introduced the first of its ``Speedbor
2000'' drill bits. Manager John Sara said the name was picked to
suggest the product's ``futuristic'' innovations, such as a pair of
small spurs on the cutting edge. A previous bit, the Speedbor 88,
was named after an Oldsmobile.
</P>
<P>
   But now 2000's days are numbered, and American Tool plans to
phase in a version known as the ``Speedbor Lock-N-Load'' because it
is easier to change.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping the old name ``might seem seem dated, like calling it
the Speedbor 1776,'' Sara said. ``Nobody thinks about the old days
anymore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
