<DOCNO> NYT19991227.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9898 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-CENTURY-NOVEL-BOS &LR;      12-27 1751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENTURY-NOVEL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SHOCK OF THE NOVEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is a truth universally acknowledged, that a reader in
possession of time's fortune, must be in want of a novel. And so it
is that we return to that foreign country of the past, where the
nights were always dark and stormy, the dawns rosy-fingered, and
the readers gentle _ where every flight of the imagination began,
in a certain corner of la Mancha, with ``once upon a time.'' Surely
it was the best and worst of times, the season of Light and the
season of Darkness, the spring of hope and the winter of despair _
in short, the period was so far like the present period, when we
wait for the clocks to strike 13 and take us into a new age.
</P>
<P>
   Thus poised at this artificial precipice of Not Really the
Millennium, we contemplate the near-infinite bounty of our literary
history by examining the novel's extended family tree. In a
thousand years, the novel has developed from fireside diversion
into a form of such aesthetic magnitude as to define entire
cultures; in its myriad efforts to secure a particular moment in
art or history, it has on occasion transformed both. And while
happy families may all be alike, the bastards, misfits, grumpy old
aunts, wicked step-siblings, and prodigal sons that make up this
particular genealogy _ from Chaucer to hypertext _ are a far more
fascinating tribe.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is theirs exactly the saddest story I have ever heard.
Instead it is fabulous and tawdry, desultory and checkered, and the
trail it blazes through the centuries has more than its share of
breathtaking vistas. For anyone who worries from time to time that
the novel is dead or even suffering from chronic fatigue, a gaze
into the past thousand years _ however absurd or short-handed that
notion _ offers both vast perspective and enormous consolation. If
we have indeed managed to arrive here all the way from the dark,
preliterate insularity of the Middle Ages and, despite countless
efforts to destroy ourselves, lived to tell the tale, then we may
actually find a way to navigate the future.
</P>
<P>
   One may as well begin with the Battle of Hastings, which in 1066
redefined the lands and laws and language of the earth as we know
it. Much sacking and pillaging from there on out, and for a while
there was rarely the time or climatic conditions for art to
flourish. The novel, of course, was still centuries away from being
born, but its ancestral tale _ the very human notion of one's
imagination encapsulating, then superseding reality _ is at least
as old as material culture itself. (What else is a hieroglyphic or
a cave painting but a really tight plot?) Most roads in the West
lead back to the twin towers of Homer and the Bible, and so it is
with literature _ the novel, recognized in English Lit courses
across the land to have begun in 1605 with Cervantes's ``Don
Quixote,'' has its earlier roots in epic poetry and scripture. But
Chaucer, writing in the 14th century, also knew how to handle the
big scene, and his ``Canterbury Tales,'' a movable feast of
invention to rival ``The Arabian Nights,'' gave us the first
glimmers of modern character development.
</P>
<P>
   Petrarch climbed that seminal mountain just to get the view
roughly around the same time; a recorded act that, along with
Dante's ``The Divine Comedy,'' corresponds to the beginnings of an
inner life in narrative. It's simple enough to draw a timeline
linking the greats of history; more striking in some ways is to
consider what they were up against. The celebrated moments of
literature are scattered through centuries of disease, violence,
and darkness; if a man was fortunate enough to live out his life
span of 30 or 40 years, he did so within the essential realm of
trying to feed himself and his family and avoid the calamities of
plague or of being bludgeoned by his neighbor. The radius of his
entire life was tantamount to our own distance to and from Home
Depot; had he ever seen a book or known what to do with it, chances
are that it was chained to a podium, and a priest had the key.
</P>
<P>
   A man named Johannes Gutenberg changed all this, and then a man
named Martin Luther became the Johnny Appleseed of Gutenberg's
invention. Muslims had established the first known European
papermaking mill in Spain in the late 11th century, and movable
type first appeared in Korea some 50 years ahead of the West. But
when Gutenberg developed a movable-type printing press in Germany
in the 1450s, then used it to print the Bible, those actions were
far more revolutionary than any cyberhead's wildest pipe dream. The
world broke apart in 1452 or thereabouts, and despite countless
religious and political efforts to destroy what Gutenberg had
wrought _ book burnings and translation bannings and published
indexes of forbidden books _ civilization is unimaginable without
those portable pieces of metal font.
</P>
<P>
   Aesthetically and globally, we had great distances ahead. The
first grammar written in one language about another was published
in 1591, around the same time as Shakespeare's ``Henry VI''; now it
was possible to hear genius on the Elizabethan stage and also to
conceive of it in translation. Though the cost of books would
remain steep, even prohibitive, until the advent of circulating
libraries in the 18th century, at least they were no longer a
sovereign domain under holy guard.
</P>
<P>
   An indicator of the value of a commodity is a despot's attempts
to forbid it: ``A circulating library in a town,'' said one
character on the Irish stage in the 1700s, ``is an ever-green tree
of diabolical knowledge!'' The fruits remained diabolical; one of
the worst punishable acts an American slave could commit was
learning to read. But however much the ruling classes (and gender)
struggled to maintain their literary dominion, the cat was long out
of the bag. If you could think, you could learn to read, and if you
could read you could listen to the firebrands who could write. The
history of literacy is a great story of populism's triumph _ when
men and women might not only read their way into fighting for
freedom or getting the vote, but, harder to quantify, blow open the
ceilings of a fixed worldview long enough to envision something
larger.
</P>
<P>
   So this story inevitably becomes a history of consciousness,
when civilization imagined, recorded, and collaborated upon an
aesthetic conspiracy to raise the roofbeams high. Once we emerge
into the light of the 17th and early 18th centuries, culture itself
begins to accelerate: from Shakespeare and Galileo to Rembrandt,
Donne, Milton. The modern English novel slouched toward London, and
all its progenitors were in place: Swift, Pope, Pepys, Johnson,
Defoe. ``Robinson Crusoe'' in 1719; seven years later, ``Gulliver's
Travels.'' In 1740, Samuel Richardson's work as a printer inspired
him to throw aside the manual he was crafting and write ``Pamela'';
with Henry Fielding, he paved the way for the subsequent explosion
in the novel form, culminating with Sterne and then Austen. If the
first modern novels delivered a vastly imagined and populated world
with its own systemic laws and structural integrity, Jane Austen
imploded that self-contained universe _ giving us, in her ``little
bit (two Inches wide) of ivory,'' human nature itself.
</P>
<P>
   The rest, as they say, was up to God and progress, and several
volumes would be required to chart the arc of the novel over the
next two centuries. But as we craft this family portrait of the
greats at the dinner table, leave us not forget the ribald and
slovenly relatives munching on a chicken leg and stealing from the
larder; they also warrant a place at the gathering. With its wanton
lack of morals and religious instruction, the novel in its early
popular form was considered base, sentimental, and even depraved;
reading it could curdle the brain and puncture the spirit, and of
course people flocked in droves to do just that. It would take the
panoramic trinity of Dickens, Melville, and Tolstoi to elevate the
form beyond its critics and naysayers into eternal eminence; on the
other side of the horizon, Flaubert, Eliot, and James were
concerning themselves with, instead of vastness, mere perfection.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the novel's Golden Age, from ``Moby-Dick'' and
``Middlemarch'' and ``The Portrait of a Lady'' on to the rise of
the modernist masters, the wholesale enterprise of experience would
be fought over, reinterpreted, fragmented, improved upon,
transcended. Art would replace God, and the triumph of the self
would replace both; if Einstein helped to shatter the nature of
time and reality in the novel, Freud went on to have a hand in
murdering the omniscient narrator. ``Life is not a series of gig
lamps symmetrically arranged,'' Virginia Woolf wrote famously in
1919, ``but a luminous halo, a semi-transparent envelope
surrounding us from the beginning of consciousness to the end. . .
. Let us record the atoms as they fall upon the mind in the order
in which they fall.'' She could have been describing ``Ulysses,''
``Absalom, Absalom!'' or her own ``To the Lighthouse,'' all of
which appeared, a few years later and from three different
countries, within time's mere gasp of one another.
</P>
<P>
   Until a century ago, it used to be said, a reader could make do
with a library consisting of no more than 500 books _ all of which,
it must be added, had to be the right 500 books, a decree of
election which itself has come under fire in recent years. However
great the temptation to rue the passing of that era, with all its
towering novelistic edifices of strength and splendor, those salad
days (both safe and certain, in retrospect) are irrefutably behind
us.
</P>
<P>
   We are left instead with the particular beauties of the
contemporary novel, as well as the cruelties peculiar to the age _
among them, an infinite cyber-strip-mall where anyone can publish
anything, in a world where meaning itself threatens to lose its
meaning. But as long as human consciousness draws breath, there
will be plenty of souls who long for that essential journey that
the novel has always promised; for this abiding reason, there will
always be a story to be told, and someone whose life work will be
to tell it. And the novel itself, that wily old witness, lurks
patiently in the wings and listens for its cue. So yes, says the
novel, waiting to be born: yes I said yes I will Yes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Gail Caldwell is the chief book critic of the Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-99 1341EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991227.0160 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9900 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-YEAR-MUSIC-WOODSTOCK-     12-27 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YEAR-MUSIC-WOODSTOCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCK'S UNDERGROUND BREAKS THROUGH AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How different these year-end stories would be if the rain had
poured at Woodstock '99. A storm missed the Woodstock concert site
by just a few miles during the closing set by the Red Hot Chili
Peppers, thus enabling some rowdies to set fires that would have
been impossible to start had rain dampened the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, we have endless stories about how Woodstock's
peace-and-love era went up in flames, replaced by anger over
expensive bottles of water and food (not everything was
high-priced, though cynics would have you believe that). Promoters
caught blame, and so did the fans and bands smeared by association.
That was particularly true for easily targeted acts like Rage
Against the Machine, prompting Rage guitarist Tom Morello to decry
the ``horrific youth-bashing'' that took place after Woodstock.
Rarely have so many been blamed for the actions of so few.
</P>
<P>
   Rock has been in retreat from the media ever since, but you know
what? Rock had an incredible comeback year _ regaining a sense of
rebellion that many feared was lost, and stealing thunder from the
rappers who thought they held the cutting edge. Sales figures this
year showed a dramatic increase for rock as albums by Rage Against
the Machine, Korn, Limp Bizkit, and others shot to No. 1 in their
first week.
</P>
<P>
   Rock's underground became mainstream _ and shook up the
establishment in the process.
</P>
<P>
   What better example than the ``guerrilla tour'' by Limp Bizkit,
which previewed its new album with a week of unlicensed,
police-baiting shows. This included a late-afternoon sneak concert
on a rooftop in Kenmore Square, where several thousand fans, after
hearing an announcement on WAAF (107.3 FM) just minutes before,
caught Bizkit rocking hard for 20 minutes before Boston police shut
them down. The band had hired a private security team to monitor
the crowd (and the moshers), so the scene wasn't as reckless as the
police might have thought. Score a definite victory for the people
_ and a connection to earlier days, when the Beatles played on a
roof in London and U2 did the same in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Not that all of this year's breakthrough bands were saints. Far
from it. Korn wallowed in angst, Bizkit had a misogynist streak,
and Kid Rock never met a swear word he didn't like. But in their
updating of rock, often with mind-searing guitars and a streetwise
rap element, they made some of the most exciting music of the year.
You might not have been able to dance to it all the time, but its
in-your-face roar and unsettling lyrics reminded listeners of what
rock was always about.
</P>
<P>
   Hard-rocking bands multiplied in this pedal-to-the-metal
millennial year _ Godsmack, Buckcherry, Creed, Sevendust, Staind,
Oleander, System of a Down, Static-X, they just kept coming. And
many of these grew by word of mouth, just as the neohippie trend
developed such stars as the Dave Matthews Band (the only act to
play two nights at Foxboro Stadium this year) and New England's
Phish.
</P>
<P>
   The most meaningful band of the year, by far, was Rage Against
the Machine, which restored a political purpose to the music. They
rapped and raged about economic oppression, racial prejudice, and
Third World abuse _ a stunning troika that was matched only by the
ferocity of the music.
</P>
<P>
   The most meaningful solo artist of the year was Bruce
Springsteen, who proved that loyalty still exists in the crazy
market-driven mess known as today's music. Whether fans will follow
Rage, Korn, and Bizkit in 10 years remains to be seen. But
Springsteen's fans rallied to see him in unprecedented numbers.
Five sold-out shows at the FleetCenter? No problem. And his fifth
show at the Fleet was the best show I heard all year. He went for
broke and got there, while his E Street Band colleagues were right
with him. Brotherhood revived _ and sisterhood, too, considering
how well Springsteen's wife, Patti Scialfa, performed that night.
</P>
<P>
   OK, there was a lot not to like in 1999, too. Corporate mergers
induced a malaise, as many bands were dropped and many labels
folded into others _ such as Salem's feisty Rykodisc, which had to
relocate to New York under the wing of the Palm Pictures label run
by Chris Blackwell.
</P>
<P>
   And what can you say about the spread of watered-down,
hunk-du-jour teeny-bop bands? The two best-selling recording acts
were Britney Spears and the Backstreet Boys, whose albums both
topped 9 million sales. The backlash was best expressed by punk
rockers the Offspring, whose spirited Woodstock show was capped by
the singer clubbing life-size balloon replicas of the Backstreet
Boys as the crowd howled.
</P>
<P>
   It was a year of digital downloading and on-line retail gains, a
year of revivals (the J. Geils Band stood out), a year of sadness
(the tragic death of Morphine's Mark Sandman in Italy), of great
tour packages (Paul Simon with Bob Dylan and Emmylou Harris with
Linda Ronstadt), of Latin stars new and old (Ricky Martin and
Carlos Santana), of posthumous rap albums (another by the Notorious
B.I.G.), of gospel going mainstream (a great FleetCenter show by
the Rev. Kirk Franklin), of classic entertainers returning (Bette
Midler was never funnier), of emerging Boston acts (Godsmack,
Guster, Susan Tedeschi, the Push Stars, Mr. Lif), and of continued
high ticket prices ($300 to see the Stones at the FleetCenter).
</P>
<P>
   But despite merger mania and ample greed from the corporate
offices down to the dressing rooms, there was still enough street
cred to suggest hope for the future.
</P>
<P>
   R.I.P.: Gwen Guthrie, Charles Brown, Dusty Springfield, Lowell
Fulson, Skip Spence, Roger Troutman, Bruce Fairbairn, Augustus
Pablo, Lord Sutch, Dennis Brown, Mark Sandman, Guy Mitchell, Anita
Carter, Roy Wiggins, Bobby Sheehan, Brewer Phillips, Beau Jocque,
Katie Webster, Hoyt Axton, Donald Mills, Lester Bowie, Doug Sahm,
Rick Danko, Hank Snow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
