<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEIGE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELCOME, AMERICA, TO YOUR POST-BEIGE WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JAIMEE ROSE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
PHOENIX - The real trouble of the year Two Thousand is the tired,
bland-chicken, dusty-beige realization that we're facing The Future
and we've been beaten by our own cartoon.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Because meet George Jetson.
</P>
<P>
   And get over his flying car.
</P>
<P>
   And, while you're at it, get over his thinking computer and his
meals-in-a-pill. Because ``The Jetsons'' is what we wanted, but
``The Simpsons'' is all we've got.
</P>
<P>
   We wanted a world of purple spacestations in the sky with
aerodynamic curves that looked like Mr. Spacely designed them.
</P>
<P>
   We have a world of beige stucco suburbs and Homer Simpson as our
national icon, who is appreciative of the flying saucer shape only
because it looks like a jelly doughnut.
</P>
<P>
   We can't be the futuristic cartoon, so we've decided to look
like it instead.
</P>
<P>
   Our computers don't think, but Apple's iMac computer looks as
though we could confide in it. Our cars don't fly, but we'd expect
to see Astro hanging out the curvaceous windows of the new
Volkswagen Beetle. The blue M&AMP;M isn't a meal in a candy-coated
pill, but in 1995, the little sucker ousted beige from the M&AMP;M bag.
</P>
<P>
   The iMac, new Beetle, the blue M&AMP;M: Welcome to the new
post-beige America. You might want to paint your house.
</P>
<P>
   When the new Beetle hit the streets in 1998, everyone was crazy
for it; there weren't enough of them; and a besotted woman in Ohio
even trailed a Beetle transport truck until it stopped and then
bought one on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   People were willing to pay double. There were fights at the
dealerships. There was even Beetle scalping.
</P>
<P>
   It was a hip, curvy, friendly little number that came in lemon
yellow and even had a bud vase on the dash.
</P>
<P>
   It was old and new at the same time, rooted in the past with all
the security that brought, but its shape announced The Future (in
case we weren't sure). This made us feel comfortable, yet confident
that surely we were evolving as a people.
</P>
<P>
   The professionals, such as Margaret Walch, director of the Color
Association in New York City, agree. (These are the people who
track and dictate fashionable colors, the ones that turned the
world teal green, the folks who tell us we can't have gold because
it's a silver year.)
</P>
<P>
   ``This roundness is a part of the whole fascination with the
'50s and those amoeboid-like shapes. It has to do with that revival
feeling,'' she says. ``But we're also trying to go forward. There's
a lot in the past that we want to take along with us, and the
future's unknown, so we go slowly into it.''
</P>
<P>
   We certainly didn't go slowly into the iMac, which hit the
country just months after the Beetle.
</P>
<P>
   It debuted in the stores at 8 a.m. on a Sunday and sold out by
9. It was cheap and round and came in bright blue, ``Bondi blue,''
named after the waters off Bondi Beach in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Apple formally christened it blueberry. The company wanted us to
think of fruit, and not beige, camel, taupe or off-white. (Now, we
even have it in raspberry, tangerine, grape and lime.)
</P>
<P>
   The iMac instantly was compared with the Beetle by salivating
writers at the ``Washington Post,'' ``Time`` magazine, even
Salon.com. They called it a gumdrop, a gummy bear, the Bondi blue
bubble that replaced the beige box.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fast Company'' just wanted to tickle it under its chin.
</P>
<P>
   The iMac sold more than 2 million models in its first year. Most
of the time, it was the top-selling computer in America.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of hours were spent trying to figure this out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time'' considered postmodernism, that esoteric catchall phrase
for things we know are now!, but don't quite understand.
</P>
<P>
   So ``Time'' asked Steve Jobs, the chief guy at Apple:
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you call it postmodern?''
</P>
<P>
   Nope.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call it post-beige.''
</P>
<P>
   And when Jobs told lead iMac designer Jonathan Ive (he used to
do toilets) what he wanted for the iMac, it was this: He wanted the
computer the Jetsons would use.
</P>
<P>
   Even before that, though, before beige was nixed in computers
and cars, we wanted it out of our candy.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, M&AMP;M/Mars decided to have a public poll. Should the tan
M&AMP;M, a part of the ``plain'' mix since 1949, live on?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the least likely color to be popular,'' said Marilyn
Bertille, M&AMP;M talkie.
</P>
<P>
   Four percent of voters said tan should stay. Fifty-four percent
said it would be better in blue.
</P>
<P>
   So that was the end of beige in the bag, and the Empire State
Building in New York City was illuminated in blue for one evening
to honor the occasion. &QL; 
All of this because we're bored with beige.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been beiged to death,'' says Walch, that woman behind
teal. ``It's boring. It's grandma's stocking color. In an era of
complication, it is too simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an era of great specificity, it just doesn't tell you
much.''
</P>
<P>
   This holy post-beige trinity makes us feel connected to the
things we rely on most in a complicated, rush-hour online world:
cars, computers, candy from the vending machine.
</P>
<P>
   Take Sam, a man in Sydney, Australia, who logged onto Apple.com
to confess that his green iMac makes him do something that's maybe
about connecting, or maybe just weird.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll let you in on a secret,'' Sam Icklow wrote. `` Every time
I sit down in front of my lime little wonder, I sit for a second
and reach out and touch it. Yum.''
</P>
<P>
   (That ``yum'' is because the iMac looks like candy, and that's
because designer Jonathan Ive actually inteviewed candymakers to
make sure he got the translucence just right.)
</P>
<P>
   Jill Morton, a Hawaii-based color consultant, says that Sam's
reaction really isn't that far off (or far out).
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to live in a colorful world, but now we live in
offices,'' Morton says. ``iMac colors make you feel like you don't
have to be a technophobe anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   They also make you feel unique, because color says something
about you that beige doesn't. Perhaps we're beginning to tire of
the Gap's khaki country, of Calvin Klein's minimalism, and of
having to choose among taupe, buff, putty, light brown, mocha,
linen and almond (or camel, toast, sand, stone, oatmeal, ecru and
bone).
</P>
<P>
   We're maybe tired of listening to Donna Karan tell about how
everyone in New York wears black, when we just want to be like
California.
</P>
<P>
   Everything colorful starts in California. For that is where Cher
is. Yes, if post-beige were a person, it would be Cher, rooted in
the past but imminently futuristic. If it were a pizza, they'd
serve it, cheeseless, at one of Wolfgang Puck's restaurants (this
is about being different). If it were a film, it would be ``Being
John Malkovich'' (this is also about being postmodern).
</P>
<P>
   If post-beige were on the shelves at Target, it would be Sony's
transparent blue CD player. In fact, so many things on the shelves
right now are, at their heart, post-beige: the Nokia cellular phone
with removable, colorful covers; printers in Bondi blue; scanners
in clear lime green.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone wants things that create an illusion of a desk, a
street, maybe even a world that is friendly, warm and fuzzy,
because what is color if not good cheer?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, along with the Jetsons, we're missing the fuzzy, friendly
days of the Beatles and the Yellow Submarine, the days when we were
in love with Jerry Garcia (who never was neutral).
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we miss the times before Jerry and the Jetsons faded into
the khakis and camouflage of the Vietnam War, when we struggled
with ourselves, against ourselves, fighting a dusty, impenetrable
cloud of dead soldiers and government distrust that descended over
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   (That cloud has only been eclipsed by a new generation that
can't understand, or care, really, how it got there in the first
place.)
</P>
<P>
   So maybe post-beige is really just a fun trend, but maybe it's
actually a call for peace. Maybe the new, colorful America is the
signal of a renaissance, a coming together of a nation that's
celebrating the possibilities of a new century and a new president
and a new color palette.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we'll even catch up to the Jetsons, because what is a zero
if not a fresh start?
</P>
<P>
   And in 2000, we've got three. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach Jaimee Rose at Jaimee.Rose(at)arizonarepublic.com or at (602)
444-7975. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-99 1345EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991227.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9905 &Cx1f; tdt-z
