<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTOR'S EXPECTATIONS ARE TOO HIGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am 58 with 25 years on my job. I am faced with an option to
retire. I have approximately $300,000 in my company's pension plan,
and another $300,000 in my 401(k). Of the latter, approximately
$50,000 is in Allstate and Sears common stock. I would like to know
where I can put the money at a low risk that will give me at least
a 10 percent to 15 percent return until I am 59 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   R.B., Wiggins, Miss. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I hate to be a grouch, especially at this time of year, but
there is no such thing as a low-risk investment that will deliver
at least 10 percent to 15 percent annual returns.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in normal historical investment climates, people who
aim for just 15 percent returns, disregarding the ``at least,'' are
usually regarded as speculators who are willing to assume high
risks for the prospect of getting to their target.
</P>
<P>
   I don't want to bawl you out too much: My mailbag recently has
been full of letters from people who don't take a historical
perspective of the market and who are counting on handsome
double-digit investment returns for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is that we are now in one of the greatest bull markets
of our nation's economic history. The equally inexorable fact is
that eventually this will come to an end, and investors will once
again set their sights on targets in the 8 percent to 10 percent
range, knowing that even those goals will involve shouldering
market risk.
</P>
<P>
   End of lecture.
</P>
<P>
   If you have an 18-month investment time frame, I would advise
that you put the lion's share of your money in conservative
fixed-income holdings, ranging from money market funds and CDs at
the most cautious to GNMA and other US government securities funds
at the most aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   You wouldn't even come close to the level of returns you mention
_ probably a return in the area of 6 percent to 6.5 percent would
be more likely. But it would be fairly low-risk.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My wife and I are both 30 and have saved $31,000 and $7,000
respectively in our 401(k) plans. We also have $10,000 in an IRA
account from my wife's previous job. All of these are invested in
various stock funds with the exception of $6,000 worth of AT&AMP;T
stock. For non-retirement savings, we have $45,000 in Fidelity's
U.S. Government Reserves, which we want to keep for emergencies
that may arise because of rental properties. Our annual earnings
are about $100,000, and we plan to put $10,000 a year into our
401(k) plans until retiring at age 60. Assuming an 8 percent return
on our retirement investments and a 5 percent return on our
non-retirement savings, how much will we have saved at age 60?
Also, we are expecting a baby. If we invested $2,000 a year in a
Roth IRA that was invested in an aggressive mutual fund, what would
be the accumulation in 18 years? Can you recommend an aggressive
fund?
</P>
<P>
   L.M., Shrewsbury, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. If you continue with monthly contributions of $833.33 to your
401(k) plans for 30 years, the accumulation (including the funds in
your IRA) would amount to $1,656,938 after 30 years of growth at an
8 percent average rate of return.
</P>
<P>
   As for your emergency savings, that account would grow to
$194,487 after 30 years with 5 percent growth and no contributions.
Of course, if you continue putting 10 percent of your earnings into
your retirement savings, the contributions would advance each time
you got a raise, and the accumulation would be likely to be much
greater.
</P>
<P>
   Why is this important? Because that grand total of $1,851,425
would have the buying power of a little less than $660,000 in
today's money if inflation averages at 3.5 percent during those 30
years. So it's important that even if you don't save more that you
do maintain savings as a percentage of earnings rather than at a
flat dollar level.
</P>
<P>
   The simple answer to your question about the Roth IRA is that if
you made $2,000 annual contributions to a fund that generated
average returns of 10 percent for 18 years, you would accumulate
$95,377.
</P>
<P>
   Since you juxtapose that question with the happy news that you
are expecting a child, I am thinking that you are considering this
as an investment vehicle for a child's educational savings account.
</P>
<P>
   But when the child is 18 you will be only 48 years old _ 10 1/2
years before you can take distributions from a Roth IRA without
taxes and penalties. So you would be better off keeping such
savings in a taxable account in your own names.
</P>
<P>
   If I were looking for an aggressive investment with an 18-year
time frame, I would pick Fidelity Specialized Health Care fund for
the purpose. If I were being a little less aggressive, because it's
never a good idea to put all of your eggs in one speculative
basket, I'd put half in the health care fund and the rest in a
Standard &AMP; Poor's index fund.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am 65 and plan to work another five years. I take home
about $3,200 a month after various deductions, including
contributions to various pension, savings, and deferred
compensation plans. I have no more wife or dependent kids at home.
At retirement, I would have about $1,100 a month from Social
Security, another $1,100 a month from my current pension account,
and a military pension of $800. I have the opportunity to buy in
some additional retirement years by adding $1,300 a month to my
defined benefit pension account. The effect of this would be to
increase my pension benefit by $1,000 a month at age 70. Are there
other equally safe investments which will return the same or
greater benefit at less cost?
</P>
<P>
   B.C., Santa Anita, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, let's look at what would happen if you went it on your
own, investing $1,300 a month for five years. If you achieved
average annual returns of 8 percent, you would amass $94,876. The
figure would be lower if you withdrew funds from the account to
deal with the tax liabilities that resulted from it.
</P>
<P>
   But if you paid the taxes from other funds, what would the
$94,876 then bring you? If it were then invested in a fixed-income
account, earning average returns of 6.5 percent, you could withdraw
$1,000 a month for a little less than 11 years before the account
went dry.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, we should examine that assumption of 8 percent returns.
We have been experiencing a bull market of almost unprecedented
scope. It seems likely that it will soon end, so I would be loath
to suggest that an expectation of 8 percent returns over the
relatively short-term period of five years is something that you
should bank on.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, by investing in the pension, you won't have
to worry about markets or taxes, and you will be assured from the
start what the benefit will be. The only question that remains is
whether you will live long enough to take financial advantage of
the benefit you will have earned.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, investing in the improved pension is a bet that you
will live long enough to take out more than $130,000 from this
segment of the pension.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, if you take the route of investing on your own, you
are not only placing the bet that your investments will earn good
returns, but you're betting against yourself _ you're effectively
betting that you will die before depleting the fund, and, unlike
the pension, the balance of the money will go to your estate.
</P>
<P>
   I don't like the idea of a person betting against himself,
especially if the payoff requires his or her early demise, so I am
in favor of investing in the higher pension. I know the actuaries
will say I'm wrong, that on average people retiring at 70 can
expect to live about nine more years. But who cares about averages?
</P>
<P>
   Consider how you'd feel if you went with the independent
investment plan and found yourself at age 81, taking a
$1,000-a-month hit to your income stream, which doubtless would
already have felt the pinch of inflation? The pension is certain,
and that's the path I suggest you take.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
