<SLUG> BC-SCI-SALMON-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MAINE, DISPUTE OVER SALMON IS A REAL FISH FIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST ORLAND, Maine _ The next generation of Atlantic salmon that
will swim in this state's rivers are tucked up in little blue
drawers at the Craig Brook National Fish Hatchery here. In each
one, thousands of pink pearl-size eggs are piled together in a
freshwater bath like some strange casserole.
</P>
<P>
   Once abundant in New England rivers from the Connecticut to the
St. Croix, Atlantic salmon were nearly wiped out in the United
States by scores of dams that block the path to their spawning
grounds. Today, this hatchery at the end of a dirt road incubates
up to 95 percent of the salmon in Maine's salmon streams.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the heroic efforts, however, the decline continues:
fewer than 150 adult salmon returned this year to spawn in eight
key rivers in eastern Maine, among the last rivers in America where
humans never completely drove them out.
</P>
<P>
   But this handful of survivors has stirred not sympathy but
powerful fears among Maine political and business leaders, who
bitterly oppose a Clinton Administration proposal to add the
Atlantic salmon to the endangered species list. They say that the
fish could become another ``spotted owl,'' referring to the
reclusive bird whose protection closed millions of acres of federal
land in the Pacific Northwest to logging.
</P>
<P>
   Maine Governor Angus King has taken personal control of the
opposition, branding the salmon protection plan the biggest
immediate threat to his state's prosperity. Because federal
biologists name everything from the herbicides used on blueberries
to logging along riverbanks as potential threats to the salmon,
King worries that these industries would be vulnerable to
strangling regulations in the name of salmon protection.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, King is concerned about the state's $65 million
aquaculture industry, a promising new business where fish farmers
raise salmon for food in pens near the mouth of several salmon
rivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will kill (the aquaculture) industry dead. D_E_A_D, dead.
That's why I'm so upset about the proposed listing of the Atlantic
salmon,'' said King in an interview. ``We have to be sure that we
are allowed to have economic growth like everyone else,'' adding
that the state should not be seen as ``a park for somebody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists and federal biologists say King's grim
predictions are exaggerated, noting that other animals such as bald
eagles have been declared endangered without hurting Maine's
economy. Moreover, they say the aquaculture industry has helped
create the crisis atmosphere by doing little to prevent the
farm-bred salmon from escaping and breeding with native salmon,
despite months of prodding from federal officials to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Federal biologists say such breeding poses a major threat to the
wild fish by introducing genes that could weaken their offspring's
ability to survive a demanding life cycle that includes a trip to
Greenland and back, followed by an upstream swim to spawning
grounds.
</P>
<P>
   More important, biologists from both the US Fish and Wildlife
Service and the National Marine Fisheries Service say King misses
the significance of this dwindling band of fish, and the federal
government's $11 million expansion of the Craig Brook hatchery to
help them.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are other Atlantic salmon around, from the
fish-farm salmon that wind up on restaurant plates to the
hatchery-raised fish that have been reintroduced to the Connecticut
River, the salmon from these eastern Maine rivers may be the last
in America that reproduce in the wild despite the incredible odds
against them.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Governor King's own senior salmon biologist Ed Baum
argues that the eastern Maine fish should be treated as a
``treasure of national significance'' whose ability to survive has
proven their genes are worth preserving.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real question is whether we want Atlantic salmon in Maine
rivers or not,'' said David Carle of the Conservation Action
Project, one of several groups whose lawsuit against federal
wildlife agencies prompted the Clinton Administration proposal to
declare the salmon endangered.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the angry rhetoric is a difficult question in an age in
which humans increasingly play a decisive role in the fate of
animals, from airlifting wolves to Yellowstone National Park to
raising condors in zoos: At what point are animals no longer really
``wild'' at all but products of human engineering?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is vital in deciding whether to apply the Endangered
Species Act, a law so strict that it stopped a multi-billion dam in
Tennessee in the 1970s to protect an obscure fish called the snail
darter.
</P>
<P>
   Maine officials argue that the hatchery at Craig Brook has
released so many salmon into the rivers over the last century that
they have swamped the tiny wild population. In particular, the
mixing of salmon from various rivers, King asserts, eliminated the
unique genes that evolved as salmon families returned to the same
spawning ground, generation after generation.
</P>
<P>
   The salmon in eastern Maine, said King, ``are the product of
more than 50 years of hatchery stocking from a variety of sources,
including several in Canada, and are therefore no more (genetically
pure) than I am a purebred Scot, with my English, German, and
God-knows-what-else ancestors.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, King argues, the Endangered Species Act doesn't
apply to salmon because the eastern Maine variety are no more
valuable than the tens of thousands that spawn in Canada or even
the millions in aquaculture pens. The animals deserve protection,
King said, but they are far from an endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for me to understand how an animal that numbers in
the millions can possibly be in danger of extinction,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But environmentalist Doug Watts believes the salmon behind his
house, just a mile from King's office, prove the governor wrong. A
few salmon return each year to Bond Brook in Augusta although no
one ever stocked the stream. Since salmon are famously loyal to the
stream where they spend their first two years, Watts believes they
are truly ``wild.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The way the governor has conducted himself comes down to:
`Don't confuse me with the facts,' '' complains Watts, president of
Friends of the Kennebec River Salmon.
</P>
<P>
   Geneticists at the US Geological Survey, called in to take a
closer look at the Maine salmon, believe that remnants of the wild
salmon population similarly survived in eight rivers in eastern
Maine that endured fewer dams and other human insults. They're
still studying the Bond Brook fish.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the federal hatchery has released hundreds of
thousands of young salmon even into these supposedly ``wild''
rivers, including salmon from Canada as well as various Maine
rivers. However, federal biologists believe that the overwhelming
majority of these stocked fish died without reproducing, perhaps
because they lacked the genetic programming to return to the same
river.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't believe there's a pure 100 percent wild strain out
there. We're not that idealistic, but we do believe there is a wild
gene pool worth saving,'' said Tom King, biologist at the Craig
Brook Hatchery.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Brook continues to extensively stock the eight rivers, but
with an important difference since 1992. Now, the hatchery only
releases salmon into the rivers their parents came from, ending the
old practice of capturing breeding fish from one river, then
releasing their young into another. Today, hatchery workers round
up eggs after they have already been laid by the females in rivers,
using the hatchery as an incubator and nursery to improve their
survival chances.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, federal wildlife officials don't have black and
white rules on how much cross-breeding is too much for the
Endangered Species Act. For instance, panthers in Florida get full
endangered-species protection even though biologists have crossbred
them with Texas lions to increase their numbers. On the other hand,
wolves brought from Canada to Yellowstone National Park are treated
as ``experimental'' animals that can be shot if they threaten
cattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Endangered Species Act does not draw that line'' where
human breeding of animals has so damaged a species' genetic
integrity that it can no longer be protected, said Martin Miller,
deputy chief of the endangered species division at US Fish and
Wildlife. ``It comes down to using the best available science.''
</P>
<P>
   It also comes down to politics. Federal biologists concluded
four years ago that the Maine salmon were so depleted that they
should be declared endangered, but memos show top Clinton
Administration officials backed off under pressure from
then-Senator William Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when the Endangered Species Act was under fire from
the new Republican majority in Congress, the moderate Cohen
threatened to ``rethink his position on the Endangered Species
Act'' if Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt went ahead with the
endangered species listing of salmon, according to a 1995 memo from
Chris Mantzaris of the National Marine Fisheries Service.
</P>
<P>
   To the consternation of the biologists, Babbitt, along with the
late Commerce Secretary Ronald Brown, the Cabinet secretary in
charge of the National Marine Fisheries Service, postponed and
finally withdrew the proposal to protect the salmon, allowing Maine
to come up with its own conservation plan instead.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, the federal biologists saw even more problems
with the salmon, such as new diseases, and more evidence that the
Maine salmon are genetically unique. While praising Maine
conservation efforts _ and admitting that not enough time had
passed for them to pay off _ the biologists said in July that
federal action was needed to save the fish.
</P>
<P>
   The biologists' recommendation set off panic among coastal
industries near the salmon streams. Aquaculture officials face the
most direct threat _ federal biologists have said they should stop
using imported, faster-growing European salmon unless they can
guarantee the fish won't escape _ but a Biological Review Team
report also said water and chemical use of blueberry and cranberry
growers as well as logging practices need to be reviewed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big worry about listing (salmon) is that any group for
just about any reason can file a lawsuit'' to eliminate what they
regard as threats to the salmon, said Clyde MacDonald, executive
director of the Maine Cranberry Growers' Association.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of listing the salmon wish King would listen to Baum,
a longtime biologist at the state Atlantic Salmon Commission, who
believes that King's fears and those in industry are misplaced.
Based on federal handling of other endangered species, Baum
believes the government would simply accelerate state conservation
efforts without damaging industries.
</P>
<P>
   However, given the ambiguity surrounding the salmon's genetic
makeup, the debate may finally come down to values as much as
science. And King is convinced that the cost of protecting a few
particular salmon is too high, especially when the effort could
fail anyway because of dangers the fish face at sea.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could close all of Washington and Penobscot Counties, send
everyone home and turn out the lights, and still not bring the fish
back,'' said King.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
