<HEADLINE>
DID THE WISE MEN SEE AN ACTUAL STAR? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. What's the star that led the Wise Men to Bethlehem, and
what's the best guess as to when it actually appeared?
</P>
<P>
   B.A., Wellesley &UR; , Mass. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. According to astrophysicist Mark Kidger, author of the
recently published ``The Star of Bethlehem,'' the wise men probably
saw a nova, the birth of a new star, in 5 BC. His theory isn't new.
The exhaustive research behind it is.
</P>
<P>
   Kidger says Chinese records note that in March of 5 BC,
astronomers one night observed a new object in the sky. The called
it a ``Po Hsing,'' a bushy star, to the north of the constellation
Capricorn. The records say the object was seen in the same spot for
two and a half months. It didn't move, as a comet would have. After
a while, it faded from view.
</P>
<P>
   Checking back in time with computer planetarium programs that
have only been developed in the past few years, Kidger found a star
that would have been at that spot in the sky, at that time. Novas
do sometimes look a little bushy when they first appear, and they
do sometimes fade.
</P>
<P>
   He also found that Jupiter and Saturn, two planets that at times
appear as very bright stars, were close together three times in the
night sky in the seven months before March of 5 BC.
</P>
<P>
   Then, one night, the Wise Men, the Magi, who were probably
astrologers, looked up and saw a star that hadn't been there the
night before. They might well have called it a miracle.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would certainly have been quite amazed by it,'' Kidger
says.
</P>
<P>
   But where were they when they saw it? Kidger ran his planetarium
programs and found that the nova would have appeared to the west of
anyone in Persia, now Iran, exactly where some historians think the
Magi were from.
</P>
<P>
   What about the part of the story in which the star moves across
the sky, leading the Wise Men to the manger? Novas don't move
across the sky, at least not in one night. But they do move across
the sky in successive nights, as the earth's orbit gradually
changes the position of every star as the days and nights pass.
Kidger argues that the Magi headed west, the direction of the star,
to Jerusalem. Each night the star moved a bit in that direction,
leading them on.
</P>
<P>
   How could a celestial object observed five years before Christ
be the star that led the Magi to the birth of Jesus? Kidger says
there are many biblical scholars who agree the precise date of
Jesus' birth is open to interpretation. The modern calendar setting
Christ's birth date as time 0 wasn't set until 6 centuries later.
And bible stories of Herod trying to find Jesus date to 4 BC.
</P>
<P>
   Kidger admits that 2000 years later the records are so old,
incomplete, and circumstantial that we may never be able to read
them correctly. But it's a very nice theory. Whether you're looking
for a scientific explanation or you're a practicing Christian who
believes this was a miracle, you can square this theory with your
beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write to
How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
