<HEADLINE>
STATE OF THE NATION'S HEALTH: NEEDS IMPROVEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since 1990, Americans overall have become less likely to die
from cancer, heart disease, and homicide, but they're more
overweight and more likely to develop diabetes, according to a
once-in-a-decade US health report card.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, black Americans continue to have higher rates
of infant mortality and many other indicators of poor health
compared to the US average. And American Indians, Hispanics, and
Asian Americans and Pacific Islanders still have higher rates of
such diseases as diabetes and tuberculosis than the general
population.
</P>
<P>
   This latest health status tally _ part of a report card called
``Healthy People 2000'' _ shows that 60 percent of the public
health targets set a decade ago to improve America's well-being
will be met next year, but others will fall short.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to take those targets we will fail to meet in 2000 and
put them again before the American people and policymakers'' and
address them in the coming decade, said Deborah Maiese, senior
prevention policy adviser to the US Department of Health and Human
Services, who is involved in establishing the objectives for 2010.
</P>
<P>
   But the most ambitious goal of ``Healthy People 2010'' is the
elimination of racial disparities in preventing and treating
disease. Aside from calling for better data collection and
research, however, there are few specifics in the 2010 draft report
about how the government hopes to achieve this goal. A final
report, which is expected to contain more description, will be
released January 25 by US Secretary of Health and Human Services
Donna Shalala and US Surgeon General David Satcher.
</P>
<P>
   Public health officials attribute the historic racial
disparities in disease rates to poverty, lack of access to care,
and discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials representing black, Asian American, and
Hispanic communities called the goal of eliminating racial gaps a
laudable one, although they said it will take a major public health
commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a great idea,'' said Azzie Young, executive
director of Mattapan Community Health Center, which serves a
population at higher risk of everything from infant mortality to
breast cancer death. ``I think the goal is achievable provided we
have the political will to address the issues. Some of them are
going to be very tough.''
</P>
<P>
   The decennial ``Healthy People'' initiative began two decades
ago to encourage healthy behaviors and track the nation's progress
in public health; the program began under then-US Surgeon General
Julius B. Richmond, a professor emeritus at Harvard Medical School
and the School of Public Health.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we began to see, and what encouraged me to start to set
goals for a 10-year period, was that we were beginning to see
progress in. . .the chronic disorders that don't have a single
cause like infectious disease, but multiple causes, like heart
disease, stroke, cancer,'' said Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   The death rate from those chronic diseases continued to decline
throughout the 1990s, according to the most recent progress review
for Healthy People 2000. It is a trend that public health officials
attribute to better prevention, earlier detection, and improved
treatment of disease.
</P>
<P>
   In cancer, the overall decrease is largely a result of early
detection, ``particularly for the ones we talk about most _ breast,
prostate, and colorectal cancers,'' said Dr. John Rich, medical
director for the Boston Public Health Commission, which is working
with the American Cancer Society on a ``cancer crusade'' to
emphasize the importance of early detection and treatment to all
city residents.
</P>
<P>
   For lung cancer, a decrease in death rates among men was
attributed to a reduction in smoking, but the rates among women
have stagnated, according to public health officals.
</P>
<P>
   But the latest Healthy People 2000 review shows that the numbers
have been going in the wrong direction over the last decade in
diabetes, obesity, and sedentary lifestyle, which tend to be
related to one another.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the US prevalence of diabetes has increased from
an average of 26 cases for every 1,000 people in 1990 to 31 in
1996, while the year 2000 target was to reduce the number to 25
cases for every 1,000 people. Adult-onset diabetes, also known as
type 2 diabetes, the more prevalent form of the disease, is linked
to obesity.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Marian Parrott, vice president of clinical affairs for the
American Diabetes Association, said these numers show diabetes is a
``public health epidemic.''
</P>
<P>
   The diabetes numbers, which are considered poor across the
board, are worse for minorities than for whites. For instance, the
prevalence among blacks shot up from 36 cases for every 1,000
people in 1990 to 44 in 1996, while for American Indians, it
increased from 67 in 1990 to 73 in 1994, according to the latest
data available. The numbers also went in the wrong direction for
both blacks and whites for such diabetes-related complications as
amputations of toes or feet.
</P>
<P>
   Up until now, US health officials have only aimed to reduce
racial disparities in health _ not eliminate them _ by establishing
one goal for the US average and then another for blacks and, if
there were enough data, for other minorities.
</P>
<P>
   For example, while the overall US goal was to reduce diabetes
prevalence in all Americans to 25 cases for every 1,000 people by
the year 2000, a 3.8 percent reduction from the 1990 figure, the
goal for blacks was to cut it to 32, an 11 percent reduction, and
for American Indians, to 62, a 7.5 percent reduction.
</P>
<P>
   The 2010 goal of eliminating racial disparities calls for
setting one target for everyone, so that in the case of diabetes,
the aim is to get the prevalence for everyone down to less than 25
cases for every 1,000 people, according to the draft Healthy People
2010 report.
</P>
<P>
   But not every minority health official supports the idea of
doing away with separate, more immediately attainable targets.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Namais, director of community health programs for the
North American Indian Center of Boston, said she was skeptical,
considering the failure to meet the Healthy People 2000 targets for
American Indians, who have among the worst statistics of all, in
everything from smoking to alcoholism to diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't even meet those goals,'' said Namais, a St. Regis
Mohawk, whose federally funded community health programs provided
more than 5,800 services to nearly 300 American Indians in the
greater Boston area last year. ``There's no impact in Indian
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Another first for Healthy People 2010 is the acknowledgment that
gays and lesbians have special health concerns, according to
Patricia Dunn, director of public policy for the San
Francisco-based Gay and Lesbian Medical Association, and US health
official Maiese. There are no specifics about goals for this
population in the draft report.
</P>
<P>
   While the once-a-decade process of updating the Healthy People
report card has led to some progress and more ambitious goals for
the nation, Mattapan's Young said that by 2010, ``I hope we're not
having the same conversation. I do hope the conversation has
changed, so that we're talking more about our success stories.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-99 1355EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
