<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991227.0171 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9924 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-STEM-RESEARCH-BOS &LR;      12-27 1672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEM-RESEARCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEBATE LOOMS OVER STEM CELL FUNDS, RESEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Reopening some of the wrenching moral questions of
the abortion fight, Congress is preparing to debate whether to fund
research that may rely on destroying embryos in order to find cures
for disease.
</P>
<P>
   The debate, which lawmakers are expected to take up early next
year, arises from a breakthrough 13 months ago in isolating human
``stem cells.'' These cells, which appear early in an embryo's
development, can grow to become anything in the body, including
heart, kidney, blood and bone marrow cells that could be
transplanted into people whose own organs are not functioning
properly.
</P>
<P>
   But an embryo is destroyed in the process of harvesting its stem
cells, raising thorny questions about whether it is proper to end
one form of human life to benefit another.
</P>
<P>
   The debate is being prodded by the National Institutes of
Health, which this month laid out guidelines for funding stem cell
research that would use embryos produced by couples during
infertility treatments but not used. The NIH says its plan is
legal, but some lawmakers said it violates a congressional ban on
spending federal money for research that destroys embryos.
</P>
<P>
   House members who support the ban will likely challenge the NIH
early next year. ``Something is going to be done one way or
another, in the courts or in Congress,'' said Representative Jay
Dickey, an Arkansas Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Senate supporters of the stem cell research said Majority Leader
Trent Lott has promised a debate on whether to give the NIH
explicit authority to proceed. The NIH is taking public comments on
its proposal through Jan. 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``To what extent can we profit from things that some people
think are morally questionable?'' asked Ronald M. Green, professor
of ethics at Dartmouth College. ``How do we determine where life
begins? I think stem cell research raises some of the most
important moral questions of our time.''
</P>
<P>
   Stem cells develop when embryos are only a few days old and have
only 15 or 20 cells. Some of those cells are destined to form the
heart, others to form bones or blood. But they have not yet
``committed'' to any part of the body, and they have the ability to
become part of almost any organ system.
</P>
<P>
   Using private funds, scientists from the University of Wisconsin
in Madison last year were able to grow embryonic stem cells for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers obtained the cells from embryos that couples had
created during fertility treatments and that were going to be
discarded. Couples routinely make more embryos than they use in
trying to produce a child, leaving thousands of frozen embryos
around the country that the potential parents may use later,
destroy or preserve indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   The number of frozen embryos in the United States is estimated
at 150,000, though no one knows for sure. While more are created
each year, their legal and moral status remains unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Under Roe v. Wade, life in the womb has no legal status that
outweighs a woman's right to end her pregnancy, though in the third
trimester states may protect a fetus by restricting abortion. Now,
the nation must consider whether early human life has value that
outweighs a scientist's research proposal or a patient's desire for
new cures.
</P>
<P>
   Many patient-advocate groups say the potential benefit to
millions of people makes the research essential. But for
Christopher Currie, 37, whose diabetes is damaging his eyesight,
kidneys and nervous system, embryonic stem cell research crosses a
clear moral line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could not carry the burden of adding years to my life at the
cost of causing someone else to perish,'' said Currie, a Catholic
and college philosophy major, who also opposes abortion. ``It
scares me to think I could be faced with the decision'' to accept a
stem cell treatment. ``I would look at my wife and daughter, and it
would rip my guts apart.''
</P>
<P>
   However, opinions on abortion are proving to be only a limited
guide in the stem cell debate. In a little noted development,
opponents of the research have grown to include some people outside
the antiabortion camp. They argue that a woman should have the
right to end her own pregnancy, but also that human embryos have
enough innate value that they should not be used as experimental
material.
</P>
<P>
   That is the position of the United Methodist Church, which has
8.5 million members. ``We are not saying that an embryo is the same
thing as human life, but we are saying that it deserves special
consideration,'' said Jaydee Hanson, of the church's Board of
Church and Society.
</P>
<P>
   Some scientists hold the same view. ``To acknowledge the right
of somebody not to be a parent is not the same as saying we can do
anything we want with human embryos,'' said Stuart Newman, a
developmental biologist at New York Medical College in Valhalla,
N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Newman concedes the stem cell debate could prompt some people to
revise their view of abortion. ``A mother's right not to proceed
with a pregnancy is not so much based on biology as on a social
contract,'' he said. ``But to draw attention to the basic humanity,
the biological humanity, of her pregnancy kind of corrupts the
whole contract and shows it to be something that is purely
practical.''
</P>
<P>
   While the nature of the research forces the NIH to confront
tough ethical questions, the agency's political situation makes the
landscape even trickier.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Congress approved language that barred federal funding
for any ``research in which a human embryo or embryos are
destroyed.'' The law does not prohibit privately funded research,
though some states regulate or bar it.
</P>
<P>
   The NIH, after obtaining a legal opinion early this year from
the Department of Health and Human Services, said that it had the
authority to fund stem cell research, as long as taxpayer money did
not pay for the process of extracting the cells from embryos.
</P>
<P>
   Now, even some supporters of the agency said that reasoning is
strained. If a lab somewhere destroys embryos on behalf of a stem
cell researcher, they said, that researcher cannot claim to have
had no role in the destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Green, the Dartmouth ethicist, said this was similar to the
unresolved question facing scientists today of whether to use
research conducted on Nazi death camp inmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``This touches on one of the most fascinating moral question of
our century: At what point does cooperating with moral wrongdoing
begin?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Raising another question, the new NIH guidelines say that
researchers may use only stem cells taken from embryos created
during infertility treatments. Scientists may not create new human
embryos in order to produce stem cells.
</P>
<P>
   But NIH critics say an embryo either has moral value or it does
not, independent of why it was created.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's not human life, why is it a bad thing to create it?''
asked Maggie Wynne, staff member of the House Prolife Caucus, which
opposes the research. Rather than using rigid logic, she said, the
NIH ``is gauging things on the `yuck factor,' on what the general
public will accept before they get the idea that the NIH is out of
control and starting to play around with human life.''
</P>
<P>
   More questions arise from the fact that scientists are learning
new ways to produce tissues and whole organisms from a single cell.
Canadian scientsts in 1993 reported producing entire mice from stem
cells, and it could be possible to produce a person from a single
human cell. For some people, this feat raises the question of
whether a single cell carries the same moral value as a person,
even though it would need extraordinary care to complete its
growth.
</P>
<P>
   A Worcester, Mass. company, Advanced Cell Technology, has
suggested one way to circumvent some moral questions, only to raise
another. It claims to have fused a human cell and a cow cell,
creating a hybrid that produces human stem cells, but could never
grow to be a person. The company says it later added a jellyfish
gene to the hybrid in a first step toward learning how to guide the
development of stem cells into specialized cells.
</P>
<P>
   However, many people recoiled at the thought of crossing species
lines, and the NIH explicitly barred that type of project from
receiving federal funds.
</P>
<P>
   Some scientists believe the day will come when society assigns a
different status to an embryo based on its stage of development.
</P>
<P>
   In the first 14 days of life, the embryo has not yet developed a
``primitive streak,'' the precursor to a backbone. Once a backbone
develops, the embryo can no longer split and become twins, and will
grow as a single being.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cells have not decided to become an individual yet,'' said
Michael West, chief executive of Advanced Cell Technology.
``There's no person at this point.'' West suggested that any type
of research be permitted on embryos before 14 days and that
research be barred or regulated after that point.
</P>
<P>
   For Currie, the easiest solution is for Congress to continue its
bar on embryo destruction while funding other promising
possibilities. Neural stem cells taken from adults, for example,
may prove to be more useful in some treatments than those from
embryos.
</P>
<P>
   Stem cells have also been isolated in tissue from aborted
fetuses, which may raise fewer qualms because the research itself
did not cause the human life to end.
</P>
<P>
   But it is unclear whether these stem cells have the same powers
as embryonic stem cells, and scientists want to continue both lines
of research.
</P>
<P>
   Overwhelmingly, families with sick children favor research that
can lead to cures, even if it involves embryonic stem cells.
</P>
<P>
   Said Dr. Evan Snyder, a neurobiologist at Children's Hospital in
Boston: ``I can't tell you how many phone calls I get from families
waiting for cures from this for their children. It would make you
go home and hug your kids 1,000 times.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
