<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEM-RESEARCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEBATE LOOMS OVER STEM CELL FUNDS, RESEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Reopening some of the wrenching moral questions of
the abortion fight, Congress is preparing to debate whether to fund
research that may rely on destroying embryos in order to find cures
for disease.
</P>
<P>
   The debate, which lawmakers are expected to take up early next
year, arises from a breakthrough 13 months ago in isolating human
``stem cells.'' These cells, which appear early in an embryo's
development, can grow to become anything in the body, including
heart, kidney, blood and bone marrow cells that could be
transplanted into people whose own organs are not functioning
properly.
</P>
<P>
   But an embryo is destroyed in the process of harvesting its stem
cells, raising thorny questions about whether it is proper to end
one form of human life to benefit another.
</P>
<P>
   The debate is being prodded by the National Institutes of
Health, which this month laid out guidelines for funding stem cell
research that would use embryos produced by couples during
infertility treatments but not used. The NIH says its plan is
legal, but some lawmakers said it violates a congressional ban on
spending federal money for research that destroys embryos.
</P>
<P>
   House members who support the ban will likely challenge the NIH
early next year. ``Something is going to be done one way or
another, in the courts or in Congress,'' said Representative Jay
Dickey, an Arkansas Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Senate supporters of the stem cell research said Majority Leader
Trent Lott has promised a debate on whether to give the NIH
explicit authority to proceed. The NIH is taking public comments on
its proposal through Jan. 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``To what extent can we profit from things that some people
think are morally questionable?'' asked Ronald M. Green, professor
of ethics at Dartmouth College. ``How do we determine where life
begins? I think stem cell research raises some of the most
important moral questions of our time.''
</P>
<P>
   Stem cells develop when embryos are only a few days old and have
only 15 or 20 cells. Some of those cells are destined to form the
heart, others to form bones or blood. But they have not yet
``committed'' to any part of the body, and they have the ability to
become part of almost any organ system.
</P>
<P>
   Using private funds, scientists from the University of Wisconsin
in Madison last year were able to grow embryonic stem cells for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers obtained the cells from embryos that couples had
created during fertility treatments and that were going to be
discarded. Couples routinely make more embryos than they use in
trying to produce a child, leaving thousands of frozen embryos
around the country that the potential parents may use later,
destroy or preserve indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   The number of frozen embryos in the United States is estimated
at 150,000, though no one knows for sure. While more are created
each year, their legal and moral status remains unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Under Roe v. Wade, life in the womb has no legal status that
outweighs a woman's right to end her pregnancy, though in the third
trimester states may protect a fetus by restricting abortion. Now,
the nation must consider whether early human life has value that
