new cures.
</P>
<P>
   Many patient-advocate groups say the potential benefit to
millions of people makes the research essential. But for
Christopher Currie, 37, whose diabetes is damaging his eyesight,
kidneys and nervous system, embryonic stem cell research crosses a
clear moral line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could not carry the burden of adding years to my life at the
cost of causing someone else to perish,'' said Currie, a Catholic
and college philosophy major, who also opposes abortion. ``It
scares me to think I could be faced with the decision'' to accept a
