would rip my guts apart.''
</P>
<P>
   However, opinions on abortion are proving to be only a limited
guide in the stem cell debate. In a little noted development,
opponents of the research have grown to include some people outside
the antiabortion camp. They argue that a woman should have the
right to end her own pregnancy, but also that human embryos have
enough innate value that they should not be used as experimental
material.
</P>
<P>
   That is the position of the United Methodist Church, which has
8.5 million members. ``We are not saying that an embryo is the same
thing as human life, but we are saying that it deserves special
consideration,'' said Jaydee Hanson, of the church's Board of
Church and Society.
</P>
<P>
   Some scientists hold the same view. ``To acknowledge the right
of somebody not to be a parent is not the same as saying we can do
anything we want with human embryos,'' said Stuart Newman, a
developmental biologist at New York Medical College in Valhalla,
N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Newman concedes the stem cell debate could prompt some people to
revise their view of abortion. ``A mother's right not to proceed
with a pregnancy is not so much based on biology as on a social
contract,'' he said. ``But to draw attention to the basic humanity,
the biological humanity, of her pregnancy kind of corrupts the
whole contract and shows it to be something that is purely
practical.''
</P>
<P>
   While the nature of the research forces the NIH to confront
tough ethical questions, the agency's political situation makes the
landscape even trickier.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Congress approved language that barred federal funding
for any ``research in which a human embryo or embryos are
