though some states regulate or bar it.
</P>
<P>
   The NIH, after obtaining a legal opinion early this year from
the Department of Health and Human Services, said that it had the
authority to fund stem cell research, as long as taxpayer money did
not pay for the process of extracting the cells from embryos.
</P>
<P>
   Now, even some supporters of the agency said that reasoning is
strained. If a lab somewhere destroys embryos on behalf of a stem
cell researcher, they said, that researcher cannot claim to have
had no role in the destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Green, the Dartmouth ethicist, said this was similar to the
unresolved question facing scientists today of whether to use
research conducted on Nazi death camp inmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``This touches on one of the most fascinating moral question of
our century: At what point does cooperating with moral wrongdoing
begin?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Raising another question, the new NIH guidelines say that
researchers may use only stem cells taken from embryos created
during infertility treatments. Scientists may not create new human
embryos in order to produce stem cells.
</P>
<P>
   But NIH critics say an embryo either has moral value or it does
not, independent of why it was created.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's not human life, why is it a bad thing to create it?''
asked Maggie Wynne, staff member of the House Prolife Caucus, which
opposes the research. Rather than using rigid logic, she said, the
NIH ``is gauging things on the `yuck factor,' on what the general
public will accept before they get the idea that the NIH is out of
control and starting to play around with human life.''
</P>
<P>
   More questions arise from the fact that scientists are learning
new ways to produce tissues and whole organisms from a single cell.
Canadian scientsts in 1993 reported producing entire mice from stem
cells, and it could be possible to produce a person from a single
human cell. For some people, this feat raises the question of
whether a single cell carries the same moral value as a person,
even though it would need extraordinary care to complete its
growth.
</P>
<P>
   A Worcester, Mass. company, Advanced Cell Technology, has
suggested one way to circumvent some moral questions, only to raise
another. It claims to have fused a human cell and a cow cell,
creating a hybrid that produces human stem cells, but could never
grow to be a person. The company says it later added a jellyfish
gene to the hybrid in a first step toward learning how to guide the
development of stem cells into specialized cells.
</P>
<P>
   However, many people recoiled at the thought of crossing species
lines, and the NIH explicitly barred that type of project from
receiving federal funds.
</P>
<P>
   Some scientists believe the day will come when society assigns a
different status to an embryo based on its stage of development.
</P>
<P>
   In the first 14 days of life, the embryo has not yet developed a
``primitive streak,'' the precursor to a backbone. Once a backbone
develops, the embryo can no longer split and become twins, and will
grow as a single being.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cells have not decided to become an individual yet,'' said
Michael West, chief executive of Advanced Cell Technology.
``There's no person at this point.'' West suggested that any type
of research be permitted on embryos before 14 days and that
research be barred or regulated after that point.
</P>
<P>
   For Currie, the easiest solution is for Congress to continue its
bar on embryo destruction while funding other promising
possibilities. Neural stem cells taken from adults, for example,
may prove to be more useful in some treatments than those from
embryos.
</P>
<P>
   Stem cells have also been isolated in tissue from aborted
fetuses, which may raise fewer qualms because the research itself
did not cause the human life to end.
</P>
<P>
   But it is unclear whether these stem cells have the same powers
as embryonic stem cells, and scientists want to continue both lines
of research.
</P>
<P>
   Overwhelmingly, families with sick children favor research that
can lead to cures, even if it involves embryonic stem cells.
</P>
<P>
   Said Dr. Evan Snyder, a neurobiologist at Children's Hospital in
Boston: ``I can't tell you how many phone calls I get from families
waiting for cures from this for their children. It would make you
go home and hug your kids 1,000 times.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
