<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9929 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-ESSAY-TIME-BOS &LR;      12-27 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESSAY-TIME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE COUNTING'S WRONG, BUT THE TIMING'S RIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scully: ``But, Mulder, the millennium doesn't start until
January 2001.''
</P>
<P>
   Mulder: ``Nobody likes a math nerd, Scully.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; --``The X-Files,'' Nov. 28 episode &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the past few years, longer than Agent Scully, I
have been grinding countless social occasions to a mirthless halt
whenever somebody in the room says the millennium begins on New
Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   On all historical and logical grounds, these people have got it
wrong. The reason is simple: There was no Year Zero. Thus, the
first millennium lasted from Year 1 to 1000, the second from 1001
to 2000, and so the third won't start till 2001.
</P>
<P>
   If mathematics didn't convince, there was history, including
local lore. Consider, I would say, the Twentieth Century Club of
Boston, which held its end-of-the-century bash not on New Year's
Eve 1899 (as we'll be celebrating ours on New Year's Eve 1999), but
rather in the final moments of Dec. 31, 1900.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty-thousand people gathered before the State House. Edward
Everett Hale read the Nineteenth Psalm,'' wrote historian Hillel
Schwartz in ``Century's End.'' As the clock struck midnight, ``the
trumpeters trumpeted, church bells pealed, chimes rang,'' and ``the
assembled thousands sang one of the national anthems.''
</P>
<P>
   And Boston was not eccentric on this point. ``Every major
newspaper and magazine officially welcomed the new century with
their first issue of January 1901,'' writes Stephen Jay Gould, the
Harvard University scientist, in ``Questioning the Millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   All told, it's clear we should not be celebrating the new
millennium this week. And yet, in recent weeks, I've been changing
my mind _ or, rather, expanding my perspective _ to the point where
I am no longer hostile to the popular view. In fact, I even feel
comfortable celebrating.
</P>
<P>
   Why? A better question might be: Why not? For, sweep away the
grand edifice of centurion or millennial time and it becomes clear
that the foundations of time as we know it are mere daydreams.
</P>
<P>
   Most units of time are grounded in nature. A day is defined by
the rotation of the earth. A month is set (more or less) by the
phases of the moon, a year (give or take a few hours) by the
earth's revolution around the sun.
</P>
<P>
   But the decade, the century, and the millennium have no basis in
nature whatever. They do have one thing in common: They are all
based on the number 10. And why is 10 the key number in human
counting? Why is our numeric system a base 10 system? Because we
have 10 fingers.
</P>
<P>
   If we had been born without pinkies (or worse, without thumbs),
we would probably have a base 8 numeric system (that is, the number
we now call 8 would be called 10, our 16 would be called 20, and so
forth). And in this frame of mind, we would not be thinking about
centuries or millennia at all right now. In a base 8 world, the
year that our decimal-driven culture calls 2000 would be known as
3720. The base 8 world's Year 2000 would have taken place back in
1024.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the measure and the very concept of centuries
and millennia are rooted in the chance material of human
experience.
</P>
<P>
   This raises another question: Why should anybody care when a
century or millennium begins or ends? Why should arguments over the
issue excite the passion they often do?
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz, in surveying past century-ends, offers an interesting
angle. He notes that the span of history was first laid out in
terms of centuries in the 13-volume ``Magdeburg Centuries,''
published in the late 1500s _ roughly coinciding with the
propagation of the Gregorian calendar, another new way of viewing
time.
</P>
<P>
   Both of these tools, Schwartz writes, were ``expressions of a
new anxiety over the passage of time,'' set in motion by
``Calvinist and proto-capitalist notions of thrift, economy, and
efficiency.''
</P>
<P>
   The emphasis on objective time, and our impulse to connect it to
the passage of personal time, solidified over the years (quite
apart from the tendency, in apocalyptic circles, to link the end of
centuries to the end of the world). By 1700, people started to
celebrate birthdays _ a product of the increasingly common usage of
calendar-dates in business, reinforced by the spread of household
clocks and pocket watches, which made possible and stiffened the
demands for punctuality.
</P>
<P>
   By the late 18th century, the measurements of time took on their
own character. The German word Zeitgeist _ ``spirit of the time'' _
first appeared around then.
</P>
<P>
   ``Centuries were, so to speak, Doppelgangers,'' Schwartz writes,
``coherent cultural entities in whose person and personality men
and women might recognize themselves.'' Knowing when exactly the
18th century ended and the 19th began became a matter of personal,
even spiritual importance _ a way for people to orient themselves,
and feel grounded, in the world and the universe.
</P>
<P>
   In still another sense, then, time and its divisions _
especially the most arbitrary divisions, decades and centuries _
are thought of and visualized in terms of how they are experienced.
</P>
<P>
   If the turning of a century is a profound occurrence, the
turning of a millennium is a monumental one. It is arguably even an
unprecedented one: In the 10th century, the last time this
happened, the world had no uniform calendar, no sense of centuries,
no agreed-upon New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   And so, at the end of this century and this millennium, what
will trigger the most powerful, the most palpably shuddering
experience of a change taking place in the annals of human events?
Not the transition from 2000 to 2001 (except, maybe, for Stanley
Kubrick fans). Rather, it's some cosmic blowup of the sensation
that comes with the repositioning of all the bits on a digital
clock, the rotation of all the numbers on a car's odometer: the
transformation from 1999 to 2000.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way the century should end, not with a whimper but a
bang.
</P>
<P>
   Party on, Mulder.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Fred Kaplan writes from The Globe's New York bureau.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-99 1401EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
