A9932 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-HORSES-BOS &LR;      12-27 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-HORSES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HORSEMAN'S MATURE ESSAYS HONOR THE NOBLE BEAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
SOME HORSES 
By Thomas McGuane 
Lyons, 176 pp., illustrated, $22.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years, I had difficulty warming up to Thomas McGuane. While
his themes of macho disaffection and alienation in ``Ninety-two in
the Shade'' and ``The Bushwacked Piano'' are appealing, he worked
so hard on his sentences they broke out in the sweats. That was the
Tom McGuane of the Montana movie mafia who hung around with Peter
Fonda and Warren Oates and married actress Elizabeth Ashley and
wrote the original screenplay for ``The Missouri Breaks.'' He
played at being a cowboy. Now, he is one.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Some Horses,'' a brilliantly relaxed collection of nine
essays revolving around the author's dealings with cow ponies, the
mature McGuane exhibits a reportorial sense, allowing his subjects
center stage. And he's done a masterful job of presenting their
stories.
</P>
<P>
   McGuane is a sharp, observant lover of horses. As a writer, he
accomplishes the very difficult task of presenting these gifted
animals in all their glory without ever crossing over into
sentimentality.
</P>
<P>
   ``A horse can already do many of the things we require of it, if
we would just get out of the way and let them do it,'' he writes.
McGuane goes on to quote a friend from Oklahoma who said, ``God
made a perfect world but he would like one chance to redesign the
horse.'' Instead of simply leaving that statement to sit on its
own, McGuane elaborates, ``Certainly, some work could be done with
feet, hooks, suspensory tendons, navicular bones, all of which seem
far too delicate for the speed and weight of the horse. And too
often, the fifty feet of unsupported intestine acquires a simple
loop and kills the horse. If a horse were a Ford, the species would
vanish beneath lawsuits engendered by consumer-protection laws.''
</P>
<P>
   In many of the essays (several of which were previously
published in magazines), McGuane returns to the theme of man's
relationship to the horse, and how that connection implies a
certain philosophy of life earned by long hours in their company
and longer ones in front of a typewriter. Some trainers still
believe in ``breaking'' a horse _ that is, making the animal's life
so miserable that the poor beast eventually surrenders. McGuane
believes that method, aside from being cruel, also destroys the
horse's spirit.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Buster,'' a profile of Buster Welch, McGuane says that he
gave a copy of Eugen Herrigel's ``Zen in the Art of Archery'' to
the horseman. Buster ``concluded that its application to
horsemanship was that if you are thinking about your riding you are
interfering with your horse.''
</P>
<P>
   The domination of man over the horse, as exemplified by most
cowboy movies, is an idea whose time has passed. McGuane, in
writing about trainers and riders, weaves this theme seamlessly
through all the essays. Whether describing a rodeo competition or
the birth of a foal, McGuane never missteps. Through characters
with names such as Windy Spurgeon and places called Sweet Grass
County, Montana _ where McGuane lives with his wife and three
children _ he takes us through a world far from the movies and
publishing where he makes his living.
</P>
<P>
   These essays were not anthologized to make money _ neither the
subject matter nor the form screams best-seller list _ but to
suggest a way of doing things where money and status are not the
measure of a successful life. What matters most to McGuane is not
man's capacity to use intelligence and power to force an animal
into subservience, but the possibility that they can be used to
allow the horse to be a horse. Through a series of compromises and
understandings, horse and rider reach some sort of agreement that
may, given time and patience, evolve into friendship.
</P>
<P>
   An added touch are the black-and-white etchings by an artist
named Buckeye Black, which find the visual equivalent of McGuane's
prose. The angle of vision comes from an artist who has clearly
spent years transforming his impressions of horses into images of
forthright clarity.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't sense a kind of magic watching a horse take two
steps or put his nose under water or switch flies, there's no real
point,'' writes McGuane. If that sentence doesn't move you, don't
bother with this book. There's no real point.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
