<HEADLINE>
BOOKS RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Fortune's Rocks'' by Anita Shreve (Little, Brown, $24.95). A
page-turner about a girl who has a tragic affair with an older
man. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Anne Morrow Lindbergh'' by Susan Hertog (Nan A.
Talese/Doubleday, $30). In search of a living moral example, the
biographer finds a woman who married the century's preeminent
public hero but who craved privacy and silence. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Flu'' by Gina Kolata (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $25). A
masterly recounting of medical history, and a good mystery story
about the pandemic of 1918-19. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeats's Ghosts: The Secret Life of W. B. Yeats'' by Brenda
Maddox (HarperCollins, $32). How the spirit world, and a spirited
woman, aided the great Irish poet. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Rembrandt's Eyes'' by Simon Schama (Knopf, $50). A lively and
wide-ranging biography/appreciation of the original Dutch master. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Plainsong'' by Kent Haruf (Knopf, $24). An outcast girl in a
Colorado town finds love and care on the farm of two eccentric
brothers.
</P>
</TEXT>
