<HEADER>
A9935 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOKS-MYSTERY-BOS &LR;      12-27 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MYSTERY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE COUNTS THE WAYS HE LOVES CRIME FICTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBIN W. WINKS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reviewers are busily compiling lists this time of year: best
books of the year, the decade, even the millennium; books attached
to a list of resolutions or the New Year; and among the
Anglophiles, most likely, sly notices about Boxing Day. This is a
mug's game, and while thinking about playing it, I fell into a a
reverie about why I continue to read crime fiction when so much of
it is, to tell the truth, so bad. Why do I have an old creamery
house full of 8,000 titles which, I allege, are the books that have
most significantly shaped the genre? Why do I care?
</P>
<P>
   Of course there are dozens of plausible answers, and on an
Oxford evening, as the dark settled in (at 4:30 this time of year),
some of them occur to me without much thought. There is, for
example, propinquity: reading books based on where you are, more or
less, right now, or at least on places one knows very well. In the
States I find I don't much enjoy Frances Fyfield: her attitudes are
so very English. But read in England they seem much better, for
they don't so much remind as explain. ``Staring at The Light''
(Viking, $23.95) is vintage Fyfield (if one may use such a term for
only a 10th book). Here we have a beautiful London lawyer, all
strong on the outside, inclined to be weak on the inside, tossing
about among lovers, working to help a man who is not likable, a man
who is threatened by his twin brother, Johnnyboy, who fears nothing
save the dentist's chair. Everyone speaks preciously and an air of
hauteur smothers the proceedings: ``Guy Fawkes favoured gunpowder
because that was what he knew. An artist, after his fashion.'' If
you like that opening, you'll probably like this book.
</P>
<P>
   Clive Egleton writes very British spy thrillers, and ``Dead
Reckoning'' (St. Martin's, $24.95) is quite good of its kind. The
pace is slow, careful, considered; the plot is entirely plausible,
even likely. A woman killed in a clinical psychiatrist's waiting
room in London's Holland Park section turns out to be using the
name of the wife of an SIS agent. This leads to the discovery that
the intelligence agency's personnel files have been accessed by a
hacker. A complex story involving Northern Ireland, the Russians,
and in-house rivalries comfortably covers le Carre territory
without becoming disturbing. One feels one knows these people, they
sit next to one at high table, and they seldom mean precisely what
they say, though by propinquity we may learn how to translate
behavior with more understanding.
</P>
<P>
   Displacement is another reason I, at least, read this stuff. If
three months of rain, very narrow roads, and train seats subtly too
small for the average human body begin to pall, one can visit Texas
for a while, the better to return to all the things about Britain
that truly are wonderful _ the pubs, the cheese courses, the
restaurants (yes, the restaurants). This wet month I was made dry
by Rick Riordan's ``The Last King of Texas'' (Bantam, $23.95,
forthcoming next month in the States), about how Tres Navarre,
private eye with a mouth, who improbably holds a PhD from the
University of California, sits down in the chair of a murdered
professor of English at the University of Texas, and tries to
figure out what is going on. The dead man was a medievalist, the
scene is San Antonio, and while there is many a person here who
doesn't mean what he or she says, they do it differently in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Frederic Bean's ``Murder at the Spirit Cave'' (Bantam, $8.99)
moves a little west and south, to Terrell County, a real-life place
which is one of those counties about the size of Wales and with a
population of maybe 2,000, and brings on the first woman to be
permitted to join the Texas Rangers. A young man's body is found in
a cave, scalped and mutilated, and an old Apache is accused. All of
this sounds quite predictable, and it proves to be so in the way
Fyfield and Egleton were predictable, and it's a comfort, for the
story is well told and, I suspect, were it to be read by a visiting
English scholar at, say, the University of Texas, that scholar
would find the whole mess very American and very irritating.
</P>
<P>
   One reads to be informed, naturally, and perhaps to kick-start a
piece of one's own writing. Stuck in an essay on environmental
history, I tried to rev up the motor with ``Habitat'' by Skye
Kathleen Moody (St. Martin's, $24.95). Here the investigator is
working for the US Fish and Wildlife Service. The scene is an
island off the coast of Washington State and the issue is the
saving of endangered species by cloning the embryos of rare
animals. The writing is a bit didactic but given my interests,
consistently intriguing; only the conclusion lets one down, but by
then I was up and back at my own writing, so I don't care.
</P>
<P>
   And one reads as vicarious experience, one form of which is
forewarning. Anyone who writes, and has ever been stuck in one
place, can take a lesson from ``The Mentor'' by Sebastian Stuart
(Bantam, $22.95). A writer whose first novel has carried him for 25
years is handed by his wife a research assistant about whom neither
of them knows anything like enough. The assistant wants to write,
and does, and the famous writer begins to help her. I have never
believed in having a research assistant and this book confirms
everything I have ever suspected. The story is compelling, sad, and
instructive, and a fine debut, but it has carried me back to
Britain in mind, where I am in body, ready to imitate those old
sidewalk artists who would draw in chalk a fantastic scene and then
write, usually in a circle nearby, ``All My Own Work.'' Always a
good idea, I think.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-99 1407EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991227.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9936 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-YEAR-ESSAY-BOS &LR;      12-27 1827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YEAR-ESSAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE YEAR OF LISTING OBSESSIVELY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Poor 1999. Its biggest event may have been its very demise, the
turn of the you-know-what, the numerical phenomenon that happens
every 100 or 1,000 years or so. Event movies? There were plenty,
most notably `` Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace,'' which
took home $429 million in the states despite its dearth of heart
and soul. Event television? Oh, just about every week, particularly
when a nutty mensch named Regis Philbin was busy popping that
iconic, apocalyptic question: ``Is that your final answer?'' Event
pop music? Indeed. BRITNEY NEW QUEEN OF BUBBLEGUM! LATIN MUSIC
INVADES U.S.! BECK IS BACK! WOODSTOCK OR RAPESTOCK?
</P>
<P>
   But in 1999, an abundance of our cultural lives were spent
counting the days, listing the titles, chronicling the eras. We
were like Dustin Hoffman's autistic savant in ``Rain Man,''
obsessed with the importance of numbers, memory, order. A
psychologist might say we wanted to exert control over time. And
the world of entertainment accompanied us far into our
preoccupation, and I'm not talking about the Backstreet Boys'
massive ``Millennium,'' or that cheezy Ken Olin TV dud, ``Y2K.'' In
recent months, there were more classifications, reevaluations, and
celebrations of the past than seemed possible. In 1999, the Age of
Too Much Information and the Millennium met cute, and suddenly Kurt
Cobain and Andy Warhol and Albert Einstein and Jesus Christ were
everywhere, even on the glossies, with the list-o-maniacal
Entertainment Weekly devoting fat issues to ``The 100 Greatest
Moments'' in movies, TV, pop music, and celebrity. Naturally, TV's
savvy VH1 devised an addictive who's-the-best-ever series called
``The List'' to capitalize on the timely countdown.
</P>
<P>
   But 1999 was a fascinating period in pop culture, even if we've
looked back at it as little as we've read Tina Brown's magazine,
Talk, since its August launch. Will it help to begin the year
retrospective from a numerical point of view? George Clooney left
``ER'' after five seasons, and 36 million viewers watched. Monica
Lewinsky went on ``20/20'' for a one-on-one about the 42d
president, and 70 million watched. Stanley Kubrick's 13th feature,
``Eyes Wide Shut,'' was altered to avoid an NC-17, but took home
only $55.6 million. Fiona Apple released a celebrated second album
with a 90-word title. J. K. Rawling, age 34, enjoyed a massive cult
among Muggles with her Harry Potter books, of which there are 17.4
million in print. Susan Lucci won a Daytime Emmy after 18
nominations and 18 losses. Howard and Alison Stern split after 21
years. Pamela Anderson had 10-year-old implants removed, bringing
her from a 34D to a 34C. Oh, and the ``World'' ended _ ``Another
World,'' that is _ after 35 years.
</P>
<P>
   Of course the year's most interesting events escaped easy logic
and simple math. In 1999, new rules and new polarities seemed to be
emerging in music, movies, and TV, as pop culture continued to
frustrate the arrogant entertainment honchos who like everything
preordained. It was a year that encompassed a different set of
extremes from 1998, with Ricky Martin vs. Limp Bizkit, ``The
Phantom Menace'' vs. ``The Blair Witch Project,'' and ``Who Wants
to Be a Millionaire'' vs. ``The Sopranos.''
</P>
<P>
   At the movies, paint-by-number blockbusters did take their
predictable journeys to the top of the box-office charts. There
were flops _ Will Smith's ``Wild Wild West,'' Harrison Ford's
``Random Hearts'' _ but most of the high-profile projects paid off
big time, from the ``Phantom Menace'' to Julia Roberts's romantic
pair, ``Notting Hill'' and ``Runaway Bride.'' And ``The Thomas
Crown Affair,'' ``The World Is Not Enough,'' and ``Double
Jeopardy'' all performed as hoped.
</P>
<P>
   But still, the movies everyone talked about in 1999, the movies
that captured younger generations, the movies that studios lusted
after, were not made from the traditional Hollywood mold. They were
anything but formulaic, as they embraced the influence of video
games and the Internet, and their popularity seemed to prove our
willingness for more surprise and recklessness in our cineplex
affairs. Their motto could be this line from ``The Matrix'':
``Buckle your seat belt, Dorothy, because Kansas is about to go
bye-bye.'' And their poster boy could be Spike Jonze, the
music-video director whose first feature, ``Being John Malkovich,''
was applauded for its Kafkaesque originality. The enigmatic Jonze
also did an acting turn in ``Three Kings,'' another of the year's
acclaimed, disorienting movies, in which the Gulf War and global TV
culture merge.
</P>
<P>
   Of course the most debated of the newfangled crop of 1999 was
``The Blair Witch Project,'' the under-$100,000 production that
proved the power of simple storytelling and Internet promotion as
it went on to gross $140 million domestically. No high-tech horror
flick, it depended only on grainy hand-held camerawork and pure
dread for its thrill quotient. Despite a complicated plot about
virtual reality and the future, ``The Matrix'' also became a
surprise grosser at the box office, just as the mysterious, slowly
paced ``The Sixth Sense'' managed to draw huge audiences.
</P>
<P>
   You have to note a difference in a year when the most
Oscar-buzzed movie is ``American Beauty,'' a biting look at
suburban angst that features haunting metaphysical flourishes.
Let's just say it's not ``Father of the Bride.'' Meanwhile, a
director who once unfailingly met with critical embrace, Martin
Scorsese, seemed to fall by the wayside this year with his
``Bringing Out the Dead.''
</P>
<P>
   The world of television also underwent some tectonic activity in
1999. Oh sure, there were the usual TV ills _ the newsmagazines as
artificial as Diane Sawyer's smile, the overcoverage of tragedies
like the death of JFK Jr., and David E. Kelley's provocation
fixation, which brought us some hammy romantic kissing between Ally
and Ling on ``Ally McBeal.'' With only a few exceptions, sitcoms
were as brash and dumb as ever, showing no sign of shaking off
their post-``Seinfeld'' malaise. And wrestling continued to conquer
the world with ``WWF Smackdown!,'' the series that has kept the UPN
network afloat. The drone of racy TV was so constant that the
moralists and cranks neglected to put CBS on their redial button in
October when Mark Harmon used the ``S'' word on ``Chicago Hope''
for the first time ever on network TV. The moment passed unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
   And once ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' mania and Philbin
fever erupted, the networks became preoccupied with the simplistic,
retro game-show format. The ``Millionaire'' phenomenon brought new
life to ABC in 1999, as it became the first series to outperform
NBC's Must-See Thursday night comedies in over a decade. A knockoff
of a British quiz show, it gave us easy questions, real people, and
Regis without the insipid Kathie Lee Gifford. Naturally, the other
networks cemented plans to imitate ABC shamelessly into the new
century, with Dick Clark set to host CBS's ``Winning Lines'' and
Maury Povich set for NBC's ``Twenty-One.''
</P>
<P>
   But quality TV still managed to rear its head and roar in 1999.
Despite dire predictions about the shrinking attention spans of
viewers, and despite a fall season that appeared to be solely
targeted to young people, the hourlong adult drama took over
prime-time series TV in 1999. The hits included ``Providence,''
``Family Law,'' ``The West Wing,'' ``Once and Again,'' ``Law &AMP;
Order,'' ``The Practice,'' ``Now and Again,'' ``Third Watch,''
``ER,'' and ``Judging Amy,'' a top-15 show that no one expected to
survive. The roster of successful drama was so crowded that, in a
controversial move, ABC decided to bump ``NYPD Blue'' to midseason
to milk the popularity of ``Once and Again,'' which occupied the
Tuesday-night slot. Steven Bochco was not pleased, to say the
least.
</P>
<P>
   The best drama of all was ``The Sopranos,'' which had an
important impact on TV beyond raising the creative bar. As critical
acclaim and word-of-mouth spread, the HBO series brought once
cablephobic viewers into the new world. It also struck fear in the
hearts of the networks, as it won 16 Emmy nominations in their
coveted series-TV categories. The networks long ago ceded the movie
Emmys to cable channels, but the specter of losing the most TV of
TV awards to cable did not go unnoticed. In the future, we may look
back at ``The Sopranos'' as one of the first serious cable
takeovers of series TV.
</P>
<P>
   The wave of young adult TV dramas in 1999 _ ``Roswell,''
``Freaks and Geeks,'' ``Popular,'' and ``Angel,'' to name a few _
failed to change the face of TV, as many critics expected. But teen
tastes played a huge role in pop music 1999, as a quick glance at
the grunge-free MTV would have revealed. There were new kids on the
block, and they were dancing their heads off.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, news from the hormonally charged pop world seemed to
pull in opposite directions. One minute, sex was selling harmless
teeny-bopper fantasies. The pretty Spice Boys (`N Sync, the
Backstreet Boys, 98 Degrees) and their pretty disco-ish
counterparts (Britney Spears and Christina Aguilara) were moving
lots of butt _ and record amounts of product. And sweet-tempered
Ricky Martin became a new sex symbol, as he sold more than 6
million albums and ignited a Latin-music invasion (along with
Jennifer Lopez, Marc Anthony, and Enrique Iglesias). The only
shadow on this candy-coated world was the disturbing rumor that
former Mouseketeer Spears, now 18, had undergone breast enhancement
to boost her career.
</P>
<P>
   But the next minute, sex was selling violence and misogyny, as
macho rap rockers like Limp Bizkit were moving impressionable lads
to be less than friendly to the opposite sex, memorably at
Woodstock '99, which reportedly turned into three days of sexual
harassment, fire, and rape. Amid appearances by Korn and Kid Rock
at the MTV Music Video Awards, a now grown-up Beastie Boy Adam
Horovitz accepted the award for best hip-hop video with a
condemnation of the treatment of women at Woodstock. Didn't folks
know that Spears was referring to the truth _ and not knuckles _
when she sang, ``Hit me baby one more time''? In between these pop
extremes, the year did see the release of plenty of good,
controversy-free music, ranging from Nine Inch Nails' ``The
Fragile'' and Chris Cornell's ``Euphoria Morning'' to Tom Waits's
``Mule Variations.''
</P>
<P>
   Will the same tensions mark the year 2000? Oh, the larger themes
_ money and quality _ are probably eternal, but the faces and
stories will surely change, just as last year's biggies _
``Titanic,'' Madonna's ``Ray of Light,'' the record payday for
``ER'' _ long ago receded into the woodwork. On the eve of the new
decade, the new century, and the new millennium, pop culture moves
at the speed of light. Next Big Things: You can count on 'em.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-99 1408EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
