u e BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS &LR;      12-27 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIES RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   !!! 1/2 ``All About My Mother'' Pedro Almodovar's genuflection
to the staying power and coping abilities of women. Mischievously
blurring sexual lines, it's loaded with Almodovar's trademark
saturated color and farcical rambunctiousness. A terrific ensemble
_ Cecilia Roth, Marisa Paredes, Penelope Cruz, Antonia San Juan _
keeps the screwball soap opera humming. (R)
</P>
<P>
   !!! 1/2 ``Anne Frank's Diary'' This superb animated version of
the familiar story celebrates the young diarist but doesn't put her
on a pedestal. It will educate young viewers about the Holocaust
and World War II; at the same time, it is a rich, personal story
that will appeal to all ages. The animation style is simple yet
gorgeous, with compositions that are always interesting. (Unrated)
(Betsy Sherman)
</P>
<P>
   !! 1/2 ``Any Given Sunday'' You practically need a face mask to
sit through Oliver Stone's sentimentalization of the macho clashes
built into pro football. It keeps coming at you, keeps hammering
you, and has no business being as entertaining as it is. It's too
long, and plays like a hard-fought win in the mud, but Al Pacino's
coaching throwback and Cameron Diaz's bottom-line-driven owner help
keep things lively. (R)
</P>
<P>
   (FR) !! 1/2 ``The End of the Affair'' Exquisitely crafted but
frustratingly waterlogged. It's based on Graham Greene's
semiautobiographical novel about a sexy affair during World War II:
Ralph Fiennes plays the novelist and Julianne Moore the woman
trapped in a passionless marriage. The story really heats up when
he obsesses over the reason she inexplicably breaks off the
romance, but Neil Jordan's sensitive adaptation and the handsomely
modulated acting never succeed in igniting it. (R)
</P>
<P>
   !!! 1/2 ``42 UP'' Michael Apted began interviewing 14 British
schoolchildren in 1962, when they were 7, and has gone back to
update their stories every seven years. This sixth installment,
benefiting from the cumulative weight of our longstanding
acquaintance with them, deepens our respect for the resilience of
the 11 still on board. Some began as friends. Some became friends.
And now they're our friends, too. (Unrated)
</P>
<P>
   !!! 1/2 ``Cradle Will Rock'' Tim Robbins goes back to the '30s
to evoke a time when art and politics and passion fused as never
before. The story, featuring such period notables as Orson Welles
and Nelson Rockefeller, is red-blooded and committed as it turns
the premiere of an agitprop opera and the destruction of an
anti-capitalist mural into vibrant political cartooning. (R)
</P>
<P>
   !!! ``Galaxy Quest'' This clever, affectionate sendup of ``Star
Trek'' writes in Trekkies, too. Menaced aliens spacejack actors
whose series was canceled, believing they're real intergalactic
heroes. Tim Allen as the Kirk figure, Alan Rickman as a Spock with
a Klingon look, and Sigourney Weaver as a space babe deliver
heads-up performances. The bad guys look like angry lobsters; the
good aliens are sweetly goofy. (PG)
</P>
<P>
   !! 1/2 ``Man on the Moon'' Skilled mimic that he is, Jim Carrey
delivers a superb impersonation of envelope-pushing comic Andy
Kaufman, who before his 1984 death opened the door to comedy's
mainstreaming of alienation. But this biofilm by Milos Forman never
gets beneath the skin in which Kaufman was so uncomfortable: We
never get the inner Kaufman. (R)
</P>
<P>
   !! 1/2 ``Sweet and Lowdown'' Woody Allen's string of riffs on
the theme that living with a genius is not an emotionally rewarding
proposition (a notion that's not exactly new, if you've been
watching his recent movies). Although the concept is big, the film
_ which owes a lot to Fellini's ``La Strada'' _ seems slight. It's
worth watching mainly for the resourcefulness Sean Penn brings to
the central role of a Depression-era jazz guitarist, cocky on the
outside, frightened on the inside, running from intimacy, heartsick
because he knows he'll never match his hero, Django Reinhardt.
(PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   !!! 1/2 ``The Talented Mr. Ripley'' Anthony Minghella's slick,
twisty, top-of-the-line crime thriller has seductively sensual
textures and richly faceted performances. Foremost among them is
Matt Damon's, as a scheming social climber with a homosexual crush
on Jude Law's rich contemporary in Italy in the late '50s, when la
vita was dolce. Gwyneth Paltrow's betrayed fiancee, Cate
Blanchett's rich girl craving social entree, and Philip Seymour
Hoffman's moneyed sadist add to the malignant glitter of this dark
entertainment, which knows the anatomy of corruption. (R)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
