<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Tuesday, Dec. 28,
1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   Y2KLIST _ WASHINGTON _ A quick checklist of good and bad ideas
for the final four days of 1999. Bad ideas: Stockpile gasoline; buy
guns; take out a huge pile of cash that could be stolen; make plans
to call everyone you know at 12:01 a.m. Jan. 1. Good ideas: If you
need cash for the long weekend, get it now and not on Friday
evening in the dark at an ATM; fill up several clean containers
with tap water; make sure the batteries in your flashlights are
working; check your prescriptions so you don't run out of important
medications on Jan. 1. (Geewax, Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   Y2KMEDIA _ WASHINGTON _ John Kosinen, chairman of the
President's Council on Year 2000 Conversion, holds a briefing on
the Y2K Council's process for gathering information and making it
available to the press and public. (Geewax, Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-MEDICINE _ WASHINGTON - The Pentagon's strapped medical
care program, which received an emergency $600 million
appropriation in the middle of the fiscal year that ended in
September, has been quietly shifting costs from military hospitals
to Tricare contractors, the companies that provide medical care for
active duty and retired personnel and dependents. This means that
after it spent the extra $600 million the military medical system
is between $500 million and $1 billion in arrears and will go broke
if it does not receive an additional shot in the fiscal arm.
(Nesmith, Cox News Service). 30.
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-VIRUS _ As the Y2K bug takes center stage, computer mistfits
are spawing another concern for computer users: y2k-related
viruses. We look at what they are, how they work and how to ward
them off. (Cocks, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   FLA-MILLENNIUM _ Florida, the ``Land of Flowers,'' seems nakedly
new, built yesterday or the day before. In fact we are in our
10,000th year of human habitation, our 486th year of recorded
history, our 154th year of statehood. But much of Florida's history
over the past 1,000 years must be re-created, re-enacted, to be
seen. Outside of St. Augustine, outside of some old towns in North
Florida where the light of elder days still shines on old
brick-faced downtowns and oak-shaded graveyards, our yesterdays
have been scanted for our big tomorrows. Here is a brief, backward
glance, a small photo album of our comings and goings. Much has
come and gone, never to come again. (Browning, Palm Beach Post).
240.
</P>
