<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUSTOMS-TRAVELERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CUSTOMS WORLD REVOLVES AROUND DRUGS, BUT ALSO BEANIE BABIES AND
BODY PARTS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ANASTASIA HENDRIX  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Though U.S. Customs examinations are designed
primarily to catch smugglers of illicit drugs, much of what is
confiscated on a daily basis is far less dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   Most citations issued at San Francisco International Airport are
to passengers with an excess of undeclared items, such as Beanie
Babies or fake designer purses, or carrying exotic foods or
medicinal products.
</P>
<P>
   Meats, meat products and other food are heavily restricted and
regulated by the U.S. Department of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   Confiscated foods are taken to a makeshift lab in a back office
of the Customs area at the airport. Dozens of green peppers were
sliced open and left in large glass jugs of water to see if pests
emerged. Flowers were placed under a warming light to check for
bugs, which could only escape through a funnel into a test tube of
alcohol, which kills them instantly.
</P>
<P>
   USDA officials collect enough fruits and vegetables every day to
fill four or five industrial-size plastic garbage cans _ enough to
leave a lingering and pungent scent in the tiny office. Medfly
larvae are found about twice a week, said John Nelson, an agency
supervisor. The garbage is taken away by a company that first
steam-sterilizes it at 212 degrees Fahrenheit for two hours.
</P>
<P>
   The most eye-catching and unusual examples of what has been
confiscated over the years can be found in a wooden curio cabinet
near the front of the agency's airport office.
</P>
<P>
   The collection includes hundreds of items, mostly meat or
meat-related. A tin of something labeled ``pork floss'' sits next
to the leathery remains of a deer penis and two shriveled,
blackened gallbladders of a small antelope, both imported for Asian
herbal medicinal purposes. A small plastic box of dried animal
blood chips was ``donated'' by a passenger who intended to use them
as an aphrodisiac.
</P>
<P>
   The most common item people get caught with: Cuban cigars.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to bring in a few,'' said Mike Freitas, a U.S.
Customs spokesman in San Francisco. ``It's just a sexy thing to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, a Barbados pet store owner was caught with
55 red-footed tortoises in his pants when he arrived at Miami
International Airport. He apparently intended to sell them for $75
each. He was charged with smuggling and violating a treaty
prohibiting transportation of endangered species, and the tortoises
were given to the U.S. Fish &AMP; Wildlife Service.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a collector caught the attention of Customs
investigators when he brought a Soviet-era Scud missile into a
Ventura County airport. Officials believed it had not been properly
demilitarized.
</P>
<P>
   Even Beanie Babies can be taken away if someone has more than
three of one kind or is bringing them from countries known to
produce counterfeits.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the garbage, everything _ from cocaine to Cohibas _
is transferred to a warehouse in downtown San Francisco and
appraised. Drugs and illegal contraband are often held as evidence
for criminal prosecution in the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Items like the cigars are torn apart or destroyed in front of a
witness to ensure that no one else uses them. More mundane objects,
such as shoes and rugs, are sold at auction.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said that confiscation can be upsetting, or even
downright traumatizing, for passengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be a real negative learning experience,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The worst things to take away, Nelson said, are items with great
personal or religious significance.
</P>
<P>
   For example, many veterans who went to Europe in 1994 to
commemorate the 50th anniversary of the D-day invasion brought back
soil from the graves of war buddies or sand from Omaha Beach. Sand
is OK, but soil is not allowed because it can harbor pests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually they let us take it and give it a heat treatment, and
so we don't have to take it away,'' Nelson said. The ``heat
treatment'' is a five-minute cycle in one of the two microwaves in
the office.
</P>
<P>
   Untreated hunting trophies, such as heads of deer, boar or other
animals, must be immediately sent to a taxidermist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
