<HEADER>
A9956 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-27 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WHAT'S PAST IS PROLOGUE FOR GIANT ELKS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TOM STIENSTRA  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ What happened to the largest recognized tule elk
in California history?
</P>
<P>
   A. After the head was mounted, it fell out of a pick-up truck
bed from a bump on Highway 101, then was run over by a semi-truck.
</P>
<P>
   B. It died of old age last year at Point Reyes National
Seashore, was then recovered and mounted, and is the new featured
exhibit at the state's wildlife museum.
</P>
<P>
   C. It was taken by a hunter three years ago at Grizzly Island
Wildlife Area, and after photographing it, the hunter then took the
meat home and is still eating elk steaks every Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   D. It was mounted and auctioned off for $17,000 at the banquet
for the Elk Foundation, with all the money going to the elk habitat
restoration program. Last summer, the head mount was stolen from
the buyer's home in Los Altos Hills.
</P>
<P>
   The answer to this question is in a yarn that starts in the
Valley of the Giants in Northern California, a place named for its
ability to produce giant elk.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring of 1985, an elk was born, the son of the largest
tule elk recognized in modern times. The parent bull was named
Stud, with antlers that were measured and scored at 392.
</P>
<P>
   When Stud died of old age in 1991 in the Valley of the Giants,
federal wildlife biologist Gary Zahm took the head and had it
mounted, then moved it to the U.S. Fish and Wildlife office in Los
Banos. It is still there on display for visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the progeny of Stud started growing. In three years,
this elk was named Son of Stud because he had the near-identical
antler configuration as his father. In 1994, however, Son of Stud
was not the master bull in the Valley of the Giants. There were two
larger elk, named Monarch and Extra Points. Monarch was 10 years
old, when elk typically have their largest antler racks, and
measured 380, while Extra Point was nearly 10 and measured 375.
</P>
<P>
   Son of Stud, now 8 years old, measured 332.
</P>
<P>
   J.J. McBride of Glen Ellen, a recognized authority on wildlife
in North America, had started tracking and photographing this elk
herd. Then in February 1995, Son of Stud, along with two others, No
Point and Unknown Elk, were relocated by the Department of Fish and
Game to Grizzly Island Wildlife Area near Fairfield in the San
Francisco Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   They were transported for one reason: To freshen up the gene
pool of the herd of 80 elk at Grizzly Island. But instead, these
three transplants turned into loners and refused to mix with the
herd.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1995, Son of Stud swam across Montezuma Slough and took
up residence as a loner on an island in the Lower Delta. A month
later, Son of Stud apparently decided to swim back _ but drowned.
His body was discovered by the Coast Guard in Honker Bay on June
10, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The elk was so big that the Coast Guard proclaimed it a
navigational hazard and after notifying Fish and Game, dispatched a
team that removed its head and sank the carcass.
</P>
<P>
   That head was then transported to the state Department of Fish
and Game regional office in Yountville. McBride was notified.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within a day, I identified it as Son of Stud,'' McBride said.
``I told them, `This is such an outstanding specimen, I'll mount it
for you.' They didn't have any money to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The first thing McBride noticed was that the antlers of Son of
Stud were still covered in velvet, which means they were still
growing. The antlers of an elk will continue to grow into July,
after which the velvet is then stripped off by the elk rubbing the
antlers against young trees and brush.
</P>
<P>
   The mount was completed by December 1995 by taxidermist Bob
White of San Martin. In the meantime, McBride scored the antlers at
403, using what is known as the Roosevelt Method.
</P>
<P>
   That made it the largest tule elk ever known, even bigger than
his father, Stud, by 11 points, even though the antlers were in
velvet and not fully grown.
</P>
<P>
   There was such an uproar over this elk that McBride took the
mount on a tour of North America at sports shows. ``I was never
paid for this and that's not a complaint,'' McBride said. ``I did
it because I love what I do.''
</P>
<P>
   After the tour, the mount was returned to the Fish and Game
regional headquarters, and there it became something of an
attraction for employees of the agency from across the state.
</P>
<P>
   Alongside Son of Stud was a full-mount standing polar bear and a
beautiful shoulder mount of a Rocky Mountain elk.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the bomb.
</P>
<P>
   To help raise money at dinners for the Rocky Mountain Elk
Foundation, the Department of Fish and Game permitted Son of Stud
to be taken to fund-raising banquets and be displayed. In March of
this year, after such a dinner in Ukiah, Son of Stud was being
driven in a pick-up truck to be returned to the Fish and Game
office in Yountville. His crate, however, was not lashed down, and
in addition, there were tremendous winds at the time, estimated at
35 to 40 mph. At one critical moment, the pick-up truck hit a big
bump right when a howling gust ripped across the highway _ and in
that instant, the crate bounced out of the truck and on to the
road.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, an 18-wheeler semi-truck plowed right through it,
and Son of Stud was broken into dozens of pieces.
</P>
<P>
   The pieces were retrieved and taken back to Yountville, and
McBride was notified.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so broken up that it was almost beyond recognition,''
McBride said. ``I was in an utter state of shock.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, after examining the remnants, he discovered the tag that
he had placed on the back of the mount. He held it in his fingers,
turned it over, and saw his signature verifying that this was Son
of Stud.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I had lost a child,'' McBride said. ``I had
video-taped him and tracked this animal for five years. We watched
him grow. We'd sneak on him. We could recognize his unique walk.''
</P>
<P>
   Son of Stud had one offspring, named Reno, who lives in the
Valley of the Giants. Reno has antlers with 12 points one side, 7
on the other, scoring at 350. In addition, Reno has had two
offspring _ now just youngsters, still unnamed that McBride and
others are tracking _ and thus this saga will never end.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
