<SLUG> BC-STORAGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TIPS ON STORING, PACKING HOUSEHOLD GOODS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are tips for caring for furniture and other household items
while in storage:
</P>
<P>
   For wood furniture, choose old blankets over plastic drop cloths
as a cover, because any dust that gets in between plastic and the
wood can rub off the furniture finish.
</P>
<P>
   Stacked, bulging boxes can tip over easily, and partially filled
boxes tend to collapse. To guard against this, fill boxes tightly
with bubble wrap and packing paper to fill empty spaces.
</P>
<P>
   Apply a few drops of machine oil on clean surfaces before
storing bicycles and other metal items, to retard rust.
</P>
<P>
   When packing dishes, all plates, platters and saucers should be
stored on edge. Nest cups and bowls. A layer of packing material
should be placed on the bottom of the box first and one over the
top before closing the box.
</P>
<P>
   Any closet can become more efficient if you install closet
organizers. Some are relatively inexpensive to install, such as
vinyl-coated wire styles. Be sure to measure carefully to see that
they fit. Always check with your landlord before attaching shelving
to walls.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
