<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following  &UR; Science
Times &LR;  stories for papers of Tuesday, Dec. 28:
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EGYPTOLOGY (Undated) _ The prodigious explorations of the
last two centuries, beginning with the discovery of the Rosetta
Stone, have only whetted public and professional appetites, making
Egyptology one of the most robust endeavors of archaeologists. New
discoveries have pushed back the beginnings of Egyptian history.
New interpretations of earlier findings have refined thinking about
the lives of pharaohs and their subjects, the origins and richness
of the language and the philosophy of life and death that inspired
the pyramids. Yet mysteries abound, driving further searches among
the ruins. By John Noble Wilford. (2100 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo and map.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FERMILAB (Batavia, Ill.) _ The Fermi National Accelerator
Laboratory has for three decades played a pivotal role in the quest
to understand the ultimate nature of matter. Fermilab still houses
the most powerful particle accelerator in the world, four miles
around and capable of accelerating protons and antiprotons to
energies of a trillion volts and then smashing them together, but
the laboratory is showing signs of age. The cutting edge of
high-energy physics is moving to Europe, and Fermilab's next decade
could prove to be the laboratory's last hurrah. By Malcolm W.
Browne. (1470 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AUTISM (Undated) _ Inspired by new findings on how animal
brains develop before and after birth, scientists are developing
provocative new theories to explain autism _ a mysterious brain
abnormality that prevents human infants from developing normal
social and cognitive skills. By Sandra Blakeslee. (1800 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-RESEARCH-SPENDING (Undated) _ American industry is pouring
extraordinary sums of money into research and development in an
effort to nurture strong growth, private and federal officials are
reporting. By William J. Broad. (750 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HUGHES-INSTITUTE (Undated) _ The Howard Hughes Medical
Institute has emerged only recently from its shadowy role as a tax
shelter to become a major player in biological research. It has
become the chief dispenser of the fortune that Howard Hughes
protected for 23 years and major universities and scientists vie
for its largesse. By Nicholas Wade. (1400 words)
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HUGHES-CECH (Undated) _ Mini-profile of Dr. Thomas R. Cech,
a chemist and RNA expert, who is taking over the Hughes Medical
Institute. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-OXYGEN (Undated) _ The many and varied forms of oxygen and
other elements, superhot to supercold and under extreme pressure,
provide ample areas of explorations for students and scientists. An
essay by Malcolm W. Browne. (1150 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ News and notes on science: Items on a
growth hormone in plants, a new kind of rocket engine and a more
efficient photography process. By Henry Fountain. (700 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FITNESS-MODELS (Undated) _ Models for fitness and even
aerobics instructors are now coming in larger sizes, reflecting the
diversity of their classes, with men who never will have 30 inch
waists and women will never see a size 2. By Mary Duffy. (1470
words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SURGICAL-ZIPPER (Undated) _ Some doctors now are using the
surgical zipper in lieu of stitches or staples. It has an adhesive
that attaches to the skin on each side, and then zips. One big
advantage is that it peels off in the shower. By Keith Mulvihill.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DEMENTIA (Undated) _ The AMA has released ``Dementia: A
Practical Guide for Primary Care Physicians.'' The guide is set up
to help doctors diagnose dementia and plan treatment options for
patients with the diagnosis. It also addresses the treatment of
cognitive problems and behavioral symptoms, issues of family care
giving, safety, elder abuse, community resources and end-of-life
concerns. By Alisha Berger.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ Personal Health column: New
research suggests that the consequences of chronic sleep
deprivation may be far worse than simply diminished mental
sharpness, shortened tempers and a tendency to doze off at every
quiet moment. Rather, sleep scientists at the University of Chicago
found that those who suffer from an accumulated sleep debt may
develop serious health problems, including obesity, diabetes and
high blood pressure. By Jane E. Brody. (1250 words)
</P>
<P>
   SELLING-PREVENTION (Undated) _ In Marseille, France, some
vending machines dispense neither soda nor candy but free sterile
needles for drug users. In Vancouver, British Columbia, a stack of
colorful coupons sits next to the register at a local drugstore,
offering 10 percent off on condoms. Both programs aim to block the
spread of infectious diseases, especially AIDS, by making
preventive tools available to people who might be reluctant to seek
them out in clinics or doctors' offices. And two studies in the
December issue of The American Journal of Public Health suggest
that they are working. By Alisha Berger.
</P>
<P>
   VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ News and notes on health and fitness:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Food and Drug Administration has approved a medication in
the form of a nail polish for hard-to-heal fungus infections of
fingernails and toenails. (222 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Sexual fantasies may be better than aspirin for reducing pain,
a Johns Hopkins University study inspired by The National Enquirer
has found. (333 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ A Veterans Affairs hospital in Lexington, Ky., says it has
found a way to keep its malpractice costs below those of most
similar hospitals: make full disclosure to injured patients, even
in cases when they would not otherwise have learned of the problem.
(275 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Smoking marijuana significantly increases the risk of head and
neck cancer, according to a new study, which also predicts an
increase in cases as baby boomers age. (225 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Experts have developed a new system for gauging head injuries.
(300 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-RACE-PAIN (Undated) _ Black patients with broken arms or
legs are less likely to be treated for pain in emergency rooms than
white patients with similar injuries and complaints of pain, a new
study has found. By Gabrielle Glaser.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Science question answered: What bird flies
the fastest? The winner, wings down, is the peregrine falcon, Falco
peregrinus, which may also be the fastest animal of any kind on
earth. (275 words)
</P>
