<P>
   BROADWAY-NEW-PLAYS (New York) _ The play ``Epic Proportions''
was greeted with mostly negative reviews two months ago and
attracted only modest audiences, but its closing on Dec. 19 brought
a historic moment to New York theater: for the first time, at least
in memory, no recently written comedy or drama is running on
Broadway. By Robin Pogrebin.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-MOVIE (Undated) _ How the Hurricane Carter film story
strays from the facts. By Selwyn Raab.
</P>
<P>
   Wity photo.
</P>
<P>
   PINTER-MOVIE (London) _ The playwright Harold Pinter talks about
his new movie role in ``Mansfield Park.'' By Mel Gussow.
</P>
<P>
   KATE-SPANGER (New York) _ Every once in a while that waitress
serving you coffee really does become a star. That's what is
happening to Amy Spanger. Ms. Spanger, 28, is now working at the
Martin Beck Theater, where she has received critical and audience
acclaim for her performance as Lois Lane, the freewheeling and easy
living cabaret singer turned thespian in the hit Broadway revival
of the 1948 Cole Porter-Sam and Bella Spewack musical, ``Kiss Me,
Kate.'' By Mervyn Rothstein.
</P>
<P>
   SMITHSONIAN-CANAL (Washington) _ Smithsonian exhibit interprets
the Panama Canal as an achievement, not a just possession. By
Renwick McLean.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-POTTERY (Istanbul) _ Arts Abroad: Istanbul pottery art.
By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   STRAVINSKY-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Stravinsky,'' by Stephen
Walsh (Knopf). Reviewed by Allan Kozinn.
</P>
<P>
   TV-KIDS-REVIEW (Undated) _ On ABC, a John Stossel Special:
``Kids' Rights.'' Reviewed by Walter Goodman.
</P>
