<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAMPAGNE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUBBLY MAY COST MORE, BUT IS STILL AVAILABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BILL CITARA  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If you haven't already picked up a bottle of
your favorite bubbly to celebrate the new year, don't be surprised
if you have to do some searching, pull a few more dollars out of
your wallet, settle for your second choice. Or drink beer.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is still plenty available for New Year's Eve
party-goers, many major Champagne and sparkling wine producers are
sold out of one or all of their lines. Many retailers are, too, or
down to their last few cases. To feed the demand for the fizzy
stuff, they are being forced to rely on the wines of lesser-known
houses or pay higher prices for ``name brands'' on the European
``gray market.''
</P>
<P>
   Supplies of some traditionally popular Champagnes, such as Veuve
Clicquot ``Yellow Label'' and Taittinger Brut non-vintage, already
are exhausted at the wineries, according to Harry Bird, the manager
of Beltramo's Wines &AMP; Spirits in Menlo Park, with the only bottles
left being those sitting on retailers' shelves. The same situation
exists with many upscale Champagnes from the well-regarded 1990
vintage, he notes, and what '90s can be found may cost
substantially more than consumers are used to paying.
</P>
<P>
   And it is not just French Champagnes that are out of stock at
the winery level. Such large-volume California producers as Korbel
and Gloria Ferrer haven't a drop of sparkling wine left to release
this year, though Korbel spokeswoman Margie Healy said that spot
checks by the company's sales force indicate plenty of product
remains for sale in stores.
</P>
<P>
   Korbel's 1999 sales are up 30 percent over last year, Healy
said, which translates to 1.6 million cases of 11 varieties of
sparkling wine sold. Sonoma's Gloria Ferrer, the American arm of
mammoth Spanish producer Freixenet, has sold out its annual
production of 80,000 cases, leaving only enough bubbly to pour in
the winery's spacious, airy tasting room.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been pretty crazy,'' said Eva Bertran, the executive vice
president of Gloria Ferrer. ``We've been getting calls every day
from retailers, salespeople and distributors'' trying to purchase
more sparkling wine. ``But it's all gone.''
</P>
<P>
   As crazy as it has been at Gloria Ferrer, '99 has been even
crazier at Freixenet, she noted. The company's enormous Spanish
winemaking facility has been operating 24 hours per day since
April, producing 9 million cases of its popular ``cava'' (sparkling
wine) for world markets. U.S. sales are up 40 percent over last
year, according to Bertran. In California, Freixenet's No. 1
American market, sales are up a stunning 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Sales also are up at Domaine Chandon and Domaine Carneros in the
Napa Valley. Domaine Chandon is bereft of its Cuvee 2000 reserve
wine, but is well-stocked with its best-selling Blanc de Noir and
Brut sparklers. At Domaine Carneros, winemaker and managing
director Eileen Crane said the Taittinger-owned California winery
shipped the last of its 28,000-case production of Brut and La Rave
sparkling wines in October and is down to a relative handful of
cases for the tasting room and large (magnum, three-liter and
six-liter) bottles of its special 1994 millennium cuvee.
</P>
<P>
   For anyone who didn't heed the warning about shortages of bubbly
this year, Beltramo's wine buyer, Howard Padgett, has a few
alternative bubblies up his sleeve. Anticipating sellouts of the
best-known Champagnes, earlier this year he brought in French
sparkling wines (not from the Champagne region) from small, obscure
houses.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, to those for whom price is no object, even some of
the most difficult to acquire Champagnes can be bought for a price.
Five months ago, Beltramo's plunged into the European ``gray
market'' of Champagnes, purchasing lots from buyers in countries
such as Britain and Belgium, who had stocked up on high-end French
bubbly in anticipation of just such last-minute foreign demand.
</P>
<P>
   The higher cost of these wines means that a 1990 Dom Perignon
with a suggested retail price of $125 will sell for about $150,
while the price of a bottle of 1990 Roederer Cristal will fetch
almost $100 more than its typical price of $160.
</P>
<P>
   Prices of other brands also have risen, according to Ed Guelld,
manager of PlumpJack Wines in San Francisco. Suppliers started
boosting prices incrementally months ago, he said, by as much as 10
percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
