<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING INK OFF A STONE HEARTH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for Ocala; moved 12/9/99)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My son has written in permanent black Magic Marker on my
raised stone hearth. The marks are on the hearth itself as well as
on the edge. I tried Soft Scrub and water, without success. What
will take it off?
</P>
<P>
   DAN SHAPIRO, Needham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. There are several things you can try. Lava soap is quite
harsh but might work; so might mechanic's gel hand soap. Solvents
to try are rubbing alcohol, acetone, dry-cleaning fluid, and
bleach. None of these will harm the stone or brick, but if you try
household bleach, try it in an obscure area to make sure it does
not bleach out the stone or brick. Wear skin and eye protection
when working with bleach.
</P>
<P>
   And, just for kicks, muriatic acid might work, if there is any
lime in the stone or brick. Muriatic acid attacks only lime, and if
the marker is on top of lime, then the acid will go through it and
attack the lime. Wear skin and eye protection when working with
acid. Mix the acid half and half with water, and always pour the
acid into the water.
</P>
<P>
   If hope turns to despair, and nothing works, try sanding off the
black with fine sandpaper.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What is the efficacy of central air conditioning in a hot-air
heating system, using the hot-air ducts for the cool air in summer?
And, the efficacy of gutter guards?
</P>
<P>
   CURIOUS, who wants to be cool next summer
</P>
<P>
   A. I don't know of any scientific studies, but I do know that
some a/c systems use the hot-air ducts for cooling, at a
respectable efficiency rate.
</P>
<P>
   Technicians may argue that a/c ducts should be near the ceiling
to be most effective, because cool air falls; ducts near the floor
would produce less cool air because of this factor, the argument
goes.
</P>
<P>
   That is true, but to a slight extent. It is not a matter of how
much air, which is forced under pressure, but how well it is
distributed in each room.
</P>
<P>
   And, anecdotally, the handyman had this done just this autumn:
central air using hot-air ducts for distribution. He will let you
know how well it works some day next summer.
</P>
<P>
   As for the gutter guards, there are so many kinds out there that
I am not convinced that they all work 100 percent in keeping
leaves, and especially evergreen needles, out of the gutter. The
guards that have slots instead of perforations may work better.
And, of course, if you do not have evergreens nearby, any guard
will work in keeping out deciduous leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Does polyurethane varnish have a shelf life, and if so, how
long is it? Or does it just get stale? I used some that was in the
can for four or five years and sealed the outside of a cedar chest
with it. It still smells quite strong and is a bit soft in spots.
</P>
<P>
   SHELDON HOCHMAN, Shrewsbury, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. As long as paint, stain, or varnish is in a liquid form, and
the scum coat over it is intact, the finish can be used. Sometimes
the formula is a little different because of that scum, but I don't
think that is very important.
</P>
<P>
   It may take a while for the varnish to dry and cure completely,
but it will, if you give it enough ventilation each day. Open
windows and put a fan on the floor to hasten the curing.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know if it is a perverse streak in New Englanders, but
we tend to throw away heavy dry goods that have years of life left
in them, but save a quarter-gallon of old, old, old varnish that is
probably worth $4.
</P>
<P>
   Q. My garage door opened by itself one day at 6 a.m. I changed
the code, but, again, it opened twice by itself. A garage door
company changed the manual switch in the garage, and it's been OK
for two weeks. But when we leave the house, we cannot depend on it.
What can we do?
</P>
<P>
   J.J., Arlington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. You can trust the company and what it did, or have the
company change all switches, maybe even the motor. It would not be
that expensive but is worth it for your peace of mind and safety.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I'd like to put insulation on my the attic floor. What about
covering light fixtures that stick up through the ceiling?
</P>
<P>
   JOHN ROUGEAU, North Attleborough, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. It is OK to cover a fixture if most of it is below the
ceiling. If the entire fixture is sticking through the ceiling, and
the bottom is flush with the ceiling, it cannot be covered with
insulation if it is not labeled ``no clearance,'' ``ventilated,''
or ``insulated.'' If the fixtures are not labeled as such, you must
leave 2 inches of space between insulation and fixture, and cannot
cover it, because if covered by insulation the fixture can generate
enough heat to cause a fire.
</P>
<P>
   To correct this (such fixtures do lose a lot of heat), replace
the old fixtures with insulated ones.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-99 1526EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
