<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 15:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0011 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-CUSTOMS-TONE-HNS &LR;      12-27 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUSTOMS-TONE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CUSTOMS SERVICE TRIES TO BOOST ITS PROFILE, REDUCE COMPLAINTS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ANASTASIA HENDRICKS  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The U.S. Customs Service is using more
traveler-friendly policies to soften its reputation for conducting
overzealous and intrusive searches or targeting a disproportionate
number of women and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were being assaulted in the courts and in the media and in
Congress,'' said Dennis Murphy, a Customs spokesman at the agency's
headquarters in Washington, D.C. ``In discussions with many members
of Congress it was clear that there was a growing mood that if we
didn't do something about ourselves, they would do it for us.''
</P>
<P>
   These changes, which took effect Oct. 1, are long overdue in the
eyes of Customs' critics. Ana Obando of Daly City, Calif., is one
of them.
</P>
<P>
   When Obando, a 51-year-old bank manager and a native of El
Salvador, returned to San Francisco last year after a weeklong stay
at her condominium in Cabo San Lucas, Mexico, she expected a quick
reunion with her daughter, who was waiting to take her home.
</P>
<P>
   What she got was a two-hour delay, a prolonged examination of
her suitcase, a search of her most private areas and no explanation
of why.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was humiliating and embarrassing,'' Obando said. ``You are
angry because you want them to stop, but at the same time you're
thinking that if you don't cooperate, you're going to be detained
even longer.''
</P>
<P>
   She said they also searched her boyfriend, a San Mateo County
bus driver, making him remove his shoes, spread his legs and put
his hands on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know drugs are a serious problem ... and I'm glad they are
doing something to try and stop it,'' she said. ``But they could at
least say `I'm sorry' after you are found innocent and explain that
they are just doing their job.''
</P>
<P>
   Other recent news accounts have detailed even more horrific
encounters:
</P>
<P>
   _ In 1998, a woman was forced to remove her tampon and sanitary
pad for an agent at O'Hare International Airport in Chicago to
prove she was not hiding drugs in her body. She is one of 100
African-American women involved in a class-action lawsuit against
the agency.
</P>
<P>
   _ In 1997 a woman, seven months pregnant, said she was taken to
a hospital near the Fort Lauderdale airport after returning from
Jamaica. An agent asked a few questions, she said, then handcuffed
her and took her to the hospital, where she was given a laxative so
agents could examine her bowel movements.
</P>
<P>
   She said she was kept there for three days, unable to contact
her family. Her baby was born prematurely 12 days later, and
weighed 3 pounds. She too, has filed a suit.
</P>
<P>
   _ In 1994, a 51-year-old widow returning to San Francisco from a
round-the-world trip was also X-rayed, given a powerful laxative
and detained more than 25 hours before Customs officials determined
she was not smuggling drugs. She won a $451,000 judgment against
the agency.
</P>
<P>
   _ A Boston nurse won a similar suit in 1991 when a judge found
that agents had insufficient evidence to suspect she was carrying
contraband before subjecting her to X-rays and a pelvic exam. She
received $215,000.
</P>
<P>
   None of the women mentioned above had illegal property. All are
women are either black or Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   The suits, many of which charge that the searches were race- or
gender-based, led to a congressional hearing during the summer
focused on passenger treatment at some U.S. airports.
</P>
<P>
   Congress requested a formal investigation by the General
Accounting Office, which is still under way, and Rep. John Lewis,
D-Ga., began drafting legislation to give travelers more
protections.
</P>
<P>
   Customs Commissioner Raymond W. Kelly, a former New York City
police commissioner, has insisted that racial minorities are not
singled out. He also created an independent five-member panel to
evaluate racial profiling charges and other allegations of
overzealous behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Customs agent Mike Freitas, based in San Francisco, admitted
that some officers ``thought that enforcement meant we had to be a
little overbearing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to break those habits,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The new rules limit the broad authorization agents held to
conduct personal searches, and represent what Kelly described as
``self-imposed restraint.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, a supervisor must approve all pat-down or strip
searches. If someone is delayed more than two hours, agents must
offer to notify by telephone a person the passenger chooses to
contact.
</P>
<P>
   Agents must have ``reasonable suspicion'' to delay passengers
more than four hours and a U.S. attorney must approve detentions of
more than eight hours.
</P>
<P>
   Every Customs agent has attended mandatory cultural diversity
training sessions and a revised 60-page personal search handbook.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers stopped for a ``random'' search are handed blue
sheets of paper explaining ``Why You Were Stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   Easy-to-read signs explaining the agency's purpose and practices
now sit on top of each luggage carousel. Soon monitors will be
installed with the same information in several languages.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A national survey of more than 800 travelers and Customs agents
at six major airports, commissioned by Customs in February, found
that more than one out of seven people whose bags had been examined
had little or no clue that they might be subjected to such a
search.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest surprise for many: Agents have absolute
authority to search anyone and anything they want.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers frequently argue that the Fourth Amendment protects
them from ``unreasonable searches and seizures'' without probable
cause.
</P>
<P>
   Though many are familiar with the phrasing, few are aware the
amendment does not apply when crossing the country's borders, said
Freitas, who is also a Customs passenger services representative in
charge of answering dozens of complaints filed formally _ or, more
often, verbally _ against the agency every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any country would fall apart if they can't stop things at the
border,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
