<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEATURE-BUDGET-ART-BOS </SLUG>
  
 ART ADV.: Photos with SCI-SALMON and HAITI-JUSTICE, and a graphic
with SCI-HEALTH are being transmitted to NYT Photo Service
subscribers.  
 For Immediate Release  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following FEATURE stories for
use by NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call  &UR; 888-346-9867  &LR; or  &UR; 888-603-1036 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HAITI-JUSTICE (Port au Prince, Haiti) _ In a room, 154 men are
locked up. In a courtyard, political prisoners wait for months
without trial. Critics of Haiti's nascent democracy say there's no
bigger problem than its justice system. By John Donnelly. 1400
words. PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   STEM-RESEARCH (Washington) _ Reopening some of the wrenching
moral questions of the abortion fight, Congress is preparing for a
debate on whether to fund research into new cures for disease that
may rely on destroying embryos and using other early forms of human
life. By Aaron Zitner. 1700 words. (w and a coding)
</P>
<P>
   (Eds.: Thomas Oliphant is not writing today.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS (p) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-SPOUSES (Amherst, N.H.) _ The wives of the GOP
presidential candidates are traditional, stay-at-home moms who are
rather reluctantly going on the campaign trail to speak up for
those values. By Mary Leonard. (2 takes)
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS-GORE (Undated) _ After two high-profile debates between
the Democratic presidential contenders, Al Gore's performance
suggests a politician more interested in scoring points than
engaging in an honest discussion of the issues. By Scot Lehigh.
1600 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LOST-PATIENTS (Salem, N.H.) _ Search and rescue specialists say
enormous resources already go toward locating wandering dementia
patients. Over the next 15 years, as the number of stricken elderly
increases from 4 million to 14 million, the burden could become
unmanageable. By Ellen Barry. 1500 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (k) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ESSAY-TIME (New York) _ Of course, we all know the new
millennium doesn't start until 2001. But that doesn't mean you
can't celebrate its arrival, anyway. By Fred Kaplan. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   ESSAY-CHEAP (Undated) _ The confession -- well, maybe more like
a proclamation -- of a cheap-skate. The joys of making do. By
Catherine Foster. 950 words.
</P>
<P>
   JACOBY-COLUMN (Undated) -- Poor parents love vouchers. Why don't
Al Gore and Bill Bradley? By Jeff Jacoby.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HEALTH/SCIENCE (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SALMON (East Orland, Maine) _ The Atlantic salmon is a few
drawers full of pearl-sized fish eggs away from being wiped out in
the United States. But Maine Gov. King says a US proposal to
declare the salmon ``endangered'' is the biggest threat to Maine's
economic prosperity. By Scott Allen. 1900 words. PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HEALTH (Undated) _ Since 1990 Americans overall have become
less likely to die from cancer, heart disease, and homicide, but
they're more overweight and more likely to develop diabetes. By
Dolores Kong. 1250 words. GRAPHIC: 20 picas x 8 inches, ``Healthy
People 2000 report card.''
</P>
<P>
   SCI-QUESTIONS (Undated) _ Did the star the Wise Men were
supposed to see really exist? By David Ropeik.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CENTURY-NOVEL (Undated) _ Poised at this artificial precipice of
Not Really the Millennium, we contemplate the near-infinite bounty
of our literary history by examining the novel's extended family
tree. By Gail Caldwell. 1800 words.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-HORSES (Undated) _ ``Some Horses'' is a brilliantly relaxed
collection of nine essays revolving around the author's dealings
with cow ponies. By Michael Blowen.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-MYSTERY (Undated) _ Reviews of the latest mystery novels.
By Robin W. Winks. 970 words.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-TIPS (Undated) _ What's hot on the just-published list.
</P>
<P>
   TV-YEAR (Undated) -- At the end of the century, amid all the
mediocrity and tin laughter, TV hiccuped and out came a few truly
superior pieces of entertainment. By Matthew Gilbert. 1550 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   TV-YEAR-CONSOLIDATION (Undated) -- TV in middle age has changed
so rapidly that it bears little resemblance to its infancy, except
in one key respect: the concentration of power in a handful of
large companies. By Don Aucoin. 760 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   YEAR-ESSAY (Undated) _ Poor 1999. Its biggest event may have
been its very demise, the turn of the you-know-what, the numerical
phenomenon that happens every 100 or 1,000 years or so. By Matthew
Gilbert. 1850 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   YEAR-MUSIC-WOODSTOCK (Undated) _ A storm missed the Woodstock
concert site by just a few miles, thus enabling some rowdies to set
fires. By Steve Morse. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   YEAR-MUSIC-EMPTY (Undated) _ Nineteen ninety-nine: The year of
living vacuously? A case could be made. There was a world of empty
cheer and blustery rage out there. By Jim Sullivan. 770 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   YEAR-MUSIC-TEENS (Undated) _ Creamy thighs and perfect navels
set the artistic mood, assembly-line dance tracks replaced
ingenuity and integrity. It was the Year of Teen Pop. By Joan
Anderman. 960 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   YEAR-CYBERSPACE (Undated) _ It's Howdy Doody time on the
Internet _ at least when it comes to online entertainment. By Patti
Hartigan. 990 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   YEAR-MOVIES (Undated) _ It must have been a good year for film,
a better year than usual. I can tell because I feel really grumpy
about leaving certain films off the annual list of 10 best. By Jay
Carr. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   YEAR-VIDEOS (Undated) _ This year signaled the beginning of the
end for VHS, and the celebration of the DVD as the home-video force
for years to come. By Michael Blowen. 995 words.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-GUIDE (Undated) _ Globe critics review current movies.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHANGING-NAMES (Undated) _ Not long ago, including ``2000'' in
your company name or product was seen as a good marketing move. Now
that the date change is actually here, companies are dropping
``2000'' like a hot potato. By Ross Kerber. 870 words.
</P>
<P>
   NENGLAND-Y2K (Boston) _ The electrical and phone networks are
crucial. This is where the most time and attention has gone for
engineers and technicians attempting to Y2K-proof New England. By
Ross Kerber. 1250 words.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCE-HOOKER (Undated) _ I hate to be a grouch, especially at
this time of year, but there is no such thing as a low-risk
investment that will deliver at least 10 percent to 15 percent
annual returns. By Kenneth Hooker.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
</P>
