<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0051 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-WRONG-PREDICTIONS-HNS     12-27 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRONG-PREDICTIONS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SEPARATING FACTS FROM THE FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDs: Susan Buck-Morss is CQ)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The future isn't what it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1950s and 1960s, the most upbeat visionaries imagined
2000 as a chrome-plated Tomorrowland with flying cars, lunar cities
and cancer cures.
</P>
<P>
   The most downbeat predicted nuclear wars, gasoline lines a mile
long, and widespread starvation.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, the flying cars never arrived. Instead, we have
Internet marketing, cell phones and hidden video cameras for
monitoring baby-sitters.
</P>
<P>
   The Soviet missiles never arrived, either. Nor did many other
expected disasters: On the brink of the millennium, democracy is
emerging around the world, nuclear arsenals are shrinking, world
nutrition levels are up, and petroleum prices are so low that Texas
oil kings are sinking their capital into fledgling Internet
companies instead of into the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the nation's generally upbeat mood, a new wave of
technological utopianism is sweeping the nation, a wave akin to the
``flying car''-style forecasts that titillated teen-age readers of
Popular Mechanics in the post-World War II era.
</P>
<P>
   Which makes some older, scholarly futurists grimace.
</P>
<P>
   Now in their 60s and 70s, they see many of today's visionaries
making the same mistakes that futurists made a generation ago, such
as assuming that today's technological trends will continue to grow
and fuel the economy without disappointments, detours or downturns.
</P>
<P>
   The futurist movement itself, never highly unified has further
fragmented in the post-Cold War era as different visionaries have
struck out in their own new, highly idiosyncratic directions.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance at futurist congresses has plunged compared with the
peaks in the 1980s. Futurist attempts to establish a foothold in
academia largely have failed.
</P>
<P>
   Three decades after the heyday of celebrated intellectual
futurists such as Daniel Bell, Herman Kahn and Buckminster Fuller,
``there isn't a widely visible person known as a futurist who is
respected by a substantial portion of the population,'' said Mike
Marien, a veteran futurist.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were on a roll back then, in the 1970s. (We) felt (we) were
part of something,'' said Marien, the editor of Future Survey,
which is published by the best-known futurist group, the World
Future Society of Bethesda, Md.
</P>
<P>
   But their sense of importance was shaken by repeated failures in
forecasting technological and social trends, ranging from the
emergence of the Internet to the end of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   Enthralled by the possibility of fabulous new technologies, few
futurists expected the trends that have really shaken society: the
rapid entry of women into the work force, the worldwide revival of
nationalism and religious fundamentalism, the return of mass
epidemics such as the acquired immune deficiency syndrome, and the
emergence of the environmentalist and gay and lesbian movements.
</P>
<P>
   Futurists have not always been wrong. But rare indeed is the
long-term forecast that accurate _ for example, the forecast by
United Nations demographers, around 1960, that the world population
would exceed 6 billion by 2000. That is almost exactly the present
world population.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of futurists who confuse their hopes with
reality,'' acknowledges a veteran futurist scholar, Don Michael of
San Francisco. The futurist movement has suffered from ``a failure
of leadership, a failure to get it together. (There's been) a far
too passive sense of sitting back and hoping something would
happen, instead of making it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Another big change in the futurist movement has been the shift
in what Michael calls the ``locus of utopia.'' A few decades ago
futurists tended to assume that whatever happened in the future,
governments would be substantially responsible for it.
</P>
<P>
   But now, when public confidence in government has fallen, Marien
sees a shift toward ``the privatization of utopia,'' toward
visionary thinking in corporations, for example. This is reflected
by business literature that emphasizes the corporate potential of
new technologies and managerial styles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dream of the 20th century was the construction of mass
utopia. As the century closes, this dream is being left behind,''
Susan Buck-Morss, a government professor at Cornell University,
writes in her book, ``Dreamworld and Catastrophe,'' to be published
in the spring by MIT Press. ``The larger social vision has given
way to private dreams of material happiness and to political
cynicism.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nineteenth-century visionaries such as Karl Marx looked forward
to the transformation of an entire society and the redistribution
of its wealth and power along egalitarian lines. Now, futurist
literature increasingly has a self-centered feel to it.
</P>
<P>
   Consider these projections from a new World Future Society
publication, ``The Opportunity Century _ 50 Paths to Success in the
21st Century'':
</P>
<P>
   _ ``In the future, biochip brain implants could increase
people's memory and information processing power, turning average
humans into geniuses.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Though medically and ethically questionable,
performance-enhancing synthetic hormones could give ordinary people
nearly superhuman powers.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Some researchers believe that the human brain works like a
computer, so we could eventually replace our brains and bodies with
computer chips and artificial parts that never wear out or could be
replaced indefinitely. Another alternative would be to simply
upload your entire brain into a computer and live forever as bits
of data in a custom-made, hardware body.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael said it is not surprising that the future proved so
difficult to foresee. ``There isn't even consensus on what the past
was,'' he said. ``We can't agree on the causes of the Great
Depression or on what happened in Vietnam.''
</P>
</TEXT>
