<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0052 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-Y2K-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      12-27 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME TO BYTE THE BULLET: TEXAS STAFFERS STANDING READY FOR ANY Y2K
GLITCHES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Prison cells will stay locked.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic lights will change on cue.
</P>
<P>
   Computers will continue to calculate child support payments.
</P>
<P>
   Air pollution detectors will keep right on sniffing.
</P>
<P>
   And, most importantly to some, lotto numbers will be drawn on
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the confident predictions of state government
officials who contend they have inoculated Texas public services
from the Y2K bug. Enough safeguards are in place and enough
doomsday tests have been conducted to assure a smooth arrival for
the New Year, when some outmoded computers might confuse 2000 with
1900 and malfunction, officials promise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state's experts are increasingly confident that Texans
face few or no concerns about computer related glitches,'' said
state Coordinator of Emergency Management Tom Millwee.
</P>
<P>
   But just in case things go haywire while Texans are celebrating,
Millwee and hundreds of other state employees will be on duty _ and
thousands more will be on call New Year's Eve and New Year's Day _
to carry out contingency plans patterned after hurricane response
procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of highway troopers, game wardens, liquor control agents
and other public safety officials will be on routine assignment
throughout the New Year's weekend. All have been assured that their
computers, communications gear, radar guns and other
high-technology gadgets will be working.
</P>
<P>
   It's the other guys _ utilities, mainly _ who are worried about
readiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have power, the signals will work,'' said Texas
Department of Transportation deputy director Carol Rawson.
</P>
<P>
   Her agency will be among dozens represented at the Texas
Department of Public Safety emergency command center in north
Austin, where state agencies ranging from the Public Utility
Commission to the Texas Department of Banking will be ready to
field reports of problems and coordinate their responses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like we're watching a hurricane out in the Gulf and we
don't know where it's going to make landfall in Texas. You bring in
all your key players to watch so that we can coordinate with the
local jurisdictions,'' said DPS emergency management spokesman Jo
Schweikhard Moss.
</P>
<P>
   If the services of the Texas National Guard are needed, either
to deal with a Y2K-generated calamity, excessive celebration or
even terrorism, Gov. George W. Bush will be available to deploy
them. Bush will be celebrating with his family at an undisclosed
location in Texas, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   State officials, who have spent up to four years planning for
``The Big Midnight'' and its potentially disruptive aftermath are
confident Bush, like most Texans, won't be inconvenienced come New
Year's Day. State government functions will continue without
interruption and offices will reopen on schedule Jan. 3, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from minor problems and glitches, ``I don't anticipate any
kind of inconvenience to the public,'' said Department of
Information Resources director Carolyn Purcell, who oversees the
state's computer operations.
</P>
<P>
   While the Y2K bug is not a major concern, the public's embrace
of this once-in-a-lifetime New Year's is. State law enforcement
officers and others will be out in force to make sure there is no
mayhem of any kind.
</P>
<P>
   Around the state, some workers on Y2K duty begin round-the-clock
shifts Tuesday. Others will report for duty on New Year's Eve or
New Year's Day. Rules against consumption of alcohol and drugs at
state offices will be enforced as usual, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   None of the state's 200 alcohol control agents will have New
Year's Eve off.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of our agents will be on assignment, as they normally are,
during these holiday hours,'' said Texas Alcoholic Beverage
Commission director Doyne Bailey, whose staff is spread thin trying
to regulate the state's 40,000 licensed drinking establishments.
That's why his agency has conducted numerous preparedness drills on
its computerized systems, he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Texas Department of Criminal Justice, which keeps about
140,000 criminals behind bars, the readiness checks have been
demanding and successful, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we're such a crucial agency, the Department of
Information Resources has just crawled all over us,'' said prison
spokesman Glen Castlebury. ``They're convinced we're going to work,
but prudence demands that you don't leave public safety to
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Technology that keeps prison cells locked and perimeters
monitored has passed the tests, Castlebury said, adding that the
concerns about Y2K have dovetailed for several years with a
long-term project to modernize older prison units. Even if there
were a security systems failure, the system is designed to lock
doors and gates, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of our embedded chips were on nonessential functions, like
microwaves and coffee machines in the employee break areas,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, ``all of our data services people are going to be on
duty or on standby,'' the prison spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   The same is true at the office of Attorney General John Cornyn,
where about 50 workers will be on duty throughout the weekend to
monitor mammoth computers that track 1.2 million child support
cases, 250,000 of which involve payment orders.
</P>
<P>
   Diana Williamson, deputy director for information technology in
the child support division, said ``we have tested and tested and
tested. ... Monday morning (Jan. 3) we expect to be right where we
would have been if it hadn't been Y2K weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, a back-up plan is in place if the mainframe locks up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would allow us to take payments, process those payments and
cut checks,'' she said. ``I'm not the least bit concerned about
losing people's cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if computers don't crash at the stroke of midnight,
Williamson said her crew won't be giving an ``all clear'' sign
until late Sunday, after field offices around the state log on and
test the agency's computer network.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to actually do some normal business on Sunday to
make sure it looks clean,'' Williamson said.
</P>
<P>
   At DPS, law enforcement officials are concerned about others'
computers more than their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we're ready,'' said DPS Col. Dudley Thomas. ``We're
not worried about it from an agency standpoint. We're worried about
those folks who might not be compliant,'' particularly utilities
and transportation providers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The potential is there that those things are not ready because
they've got some embedded systems in them,'' Thomas said. ``There's
no way, really, to test those. That's one of the scary things we
face.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
