<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0053 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-URBAN-SPRAWL-HNS &LR;      12-27 1252
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-URBAN-SPRAWL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
URBAN SPRAWL IN TEXAS FASTEST IN THE COUNTRY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ People on the fringes of Austin, Houston and
Dallas don't need a national study to tell them what's happening
over their back fences: Suburban homes, apartments and businesses
are sprouting on what used to be farms and ranches faster than
anywhere else in the country, the government reported.
</P>
<P>
   But state officials said the conversion of Texas cropland into
neighborhoods poses no threat to the food supply and does not
signal the demise of farming, even in an era of persistent drought
and record low grain prices.
</P>
<P>
   On the contrary, the demand for land on the fringes of cities
presents rural property owners with financial opportunities that
are sometimes more lucrative than food production, experts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's forced them off of their land is that someone has
offered them more money than they're willing to turn down,'' said
Charles E. Gilliland, research economist at the Real Estate Center
at Texas A&AMP;M University.
</P>
<P>
   Gilliland, an expert on rural land sales, said there's no doubt
lots of soil in Texas is being sold for nonagricultural use, but
the reported shift hasn't harmed farm production.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're losing a lot of prime agricultural land, it's sure
not having much effect on our agricultural output,'' Gilliland
said. ``A lot of what's disappearing into the developments is not
prime farmlands. It's marginal farmlands.''
</P>
<P>
   About 243,900 acres of Texas farmland, forests and other open
spaces are being built on each year, the U.S. Department of
Agriculture estimated. The agency's National Resource Inventory
said that between 1982 and 1992 the rate of conversion from rural
to urban uses was 139,000 acres a year, but between 1992 and 1997
the rate skyrocketed to 239,000 acres a year.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide about 16 million acres of farmland &UR; ,  &LR; woods and open
fields &UR;  &LR; were built on between 1992 and 1997 at a clip of 3.2
million acres per year _ twice the rate of building between 1982
and 1992, the USDA estimated. Its survey was based on data captured
from 800,000 statistically selected locations.
</P>
<P>
   State officials said they don't compile similar data and view
the USDA report as an extrapolated estimate rather than an
accounting of actual land transactions. And what data there is _
acreage qualifying for an agriculture or timber exemption _
suggests no major loss of farmland. The Texas Comptroller's Office
said that in 1997, there were 143 million acres of exempted land
and in 1998, the amount grew to 144 million acres.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the USDA report rekindled debate over ``urban sprawl.''
Vice President Al Gore said slowing urban encroachment on farmland
is a tenet of his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``These new figures confirm what our communities across America
already know. Too much of our precious open space is being gobbled
up by sprawl,'' Gore said. ``Every time a farmer is squeezed off
the land, a valuable way of life is eroded.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, the majority of Texas remains undeveloped. Texas spans
171 million acres. Of that, 9 million was developed by 1997, up
from 6.3 million in 1982, the USDA said.
</P>
<P>
   Prices for land around cities vary across the state. In the San
Antonio area, the median selling price for ``high quality, urban
fringe'' land was $13,000 per acre, according to a spring 1999
survey by A&AMP;M's real estate researchers. Near Dallas, the same
grade of land cost $3,250 per acre and around Houston, the median
price was $3,750 per acre.
</P>
<P>
   The highest selling prices for land were recorded in far South
Texas, from the Rio Grande Valley to Laredo, where the median price
for high-grade urban fringe land soared to $40,000 per acre, the
center reported.
</P>
<P>
   But some Texas land isn't so pricey. In West Texas' Big Bend
region and the Oil Patch, ``low-quality'' native rangeland sold for
a statewide low of $43 an acre in spring 1999, and at the top of
the Panhandle, nonirrigated cropland went for $150 an acre.
</P>
<P>
   Many rural land owners are able to cling to their land because
they are in strong financial shape, Gilliland said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last go-round in the '80s, a lot of farmers that had a
lot of debt were wiped out. They're gone already,'' Gilliland
explained. ``The ones that were left were probably in better
financial shape. They're not as vulnerable. Of course, a couple
more years of drought and bad prices could change a lot of that.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's not just dirt they might be selling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The water is going to be much more valuable to the urban users
than it is to agriculture in the future,'' Gilliland predicted.
``Farmers and ranchers are probably going to sell out _ sell their
water rights _ and not produce agricultural products because of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Some experts predict Texas will have a ``megalopolis'' in the
next century. A heavily populated area _ with the corners being
Beaumont, San Antonio, Denison and Marshall _ that could rival the
biggest urban areas of the East and West Coasts, Texas' chief
demographer Steve H. Murdock said in a report this year.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, other observers don't see Texas getting completely
paved over anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not worried, because of our incredible land mass,'' said
Texas Agriculture Commissioner Susan Combs. ``Houston and San
Antonio are not going to stretch to Midland. That's not going to
happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the year 2030, we're supposed to have about 33 million
people in the state,'' Combs said, up from the current 20 million.
``No matter how you look at it, they're not going to take up all
that land.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the loss of a quarter-million farming acres a year won't
destroy Texas' ability to feed itself and others, Combs said. Her
comments echoed statements of USDA officials who said the nation's
food supply is healthy and benefits from increased productivity on
its dwindling farmland.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not going to impact our ability to produce food and
fiber. That's not a concern. From an agriculture production
perspective, we're not going to find that we cannot produce food,''
Combs insisted. Before that ever happens, ``we'll get more
efficient,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over how to manage urban growth into rural areas is
already part of the 2000 presidential campaign, said Mark Dotzour,
director of research at the A&AMP;M center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be one of the most timely topics of the next
decade because of the overwhelming population growth facing us,''
Dotzour said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to be able to provide housing for those
people, and you just can't draw circles around cities and say
`we're not going to allow urban sprawl to happen,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dotzour, who studies urban real estate sales, said the state may
see more urban sprawl like that seen north of Houston, blending
housing and workplaces.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the big cities, the traffic situation's getting difficult.
In downtown areas, the pressure is on to move offices and even some
light industries out to the suburbs, so that you don't have such a
big commute time. The Woodlands is a case in point,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Woodlands is an affluent community of 37,500 people just
north of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a certain point of view, you can say The Woodlands is
urban sprawl because it's outside of the central business district
of Houston,'' Dotzour said. ``But on the other hand, I think that's
where it needs to go in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
