<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0055 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-GOP-HOPEFULS-PROFILE-     12-27 1405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-HOPEFULS-PROFILE-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP'S `SECOND-TIER' CANDIDATES LAG IN POLLS BUT LEAD IN TENACITY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KIM COBB 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They register as single-digit blips in the public opinion polls,
candidates frequently dismissed by the pundits as ``second-tier''
GOP presidential hopefuls.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bauer, the big-stick fundamentalist; Orrin Hatch, the
senior U.S. senator from Utah; and Alan Keyes, the former
ambassador and fiery orator are tenaciously pursuing Republican
presidential aspirations despite narrow odds.
</P>
<P>
   It could happen, the candidates argue. It's nearly a year away
from the election, and the perceived front-runners could stumble.
</P>
<P>
   But if candidates do not make an impact in the first caucuses
and primaries in coming weeks, their donor bases will shrivel and
they'll soon be out of the game. The modern political axiom is that
presidential candidates are like armies in battle _ they are not
destroyed, as much as their supplies give out.
</P>
<P>
   Yet holding down the bottom of the polls gives a candidate the
freedom to take chances. In the debates of recent weeks, televised
from New Hampshire and Arizona, many observers see the real passion
of the campaign coming from the so-called ``second tier.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
GARY BAUER &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's not easy to find a presidential contender conservative
enough to suit Gary Bauer. A leader in the Christian conservative
movement, Bauer started thinking maybe he was the best man for the
job more than three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew very frustrated watching the (1996) presidential
debates because Bob Dole was not making the case for conservative
values,'' Bauer said recently. ``I ran out of shoes to throw at the
television set during those debates, and I think a lot of other
Reagan-type conservatives did also.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer, 53, worked in the Reagan administration as a domestic
policy adviser before taking the helm of a nascent Christian
conservative think tank a decade ago. The Family Research Council
grew from a $1 million a year operation to a $14 million a year
lobbying force over the 10 years Bauer was in charge.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer made his name as a fundamentalist power broker so
immovable that he sometimes made Ralph Reed, former head of the
Christian Coalition, look like a moderate. The Family Research
Council shares many issues with the Christian Coalition, but
Bauer's group has been more openly critical of Republican leaders
in Congress in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of us were looking for who could fill that vacuum that
Reagan left,'' Bauer said. ``It was during that period (during and
after the 1996 election) that I started getting quite a bit of mail
... suggesting instead of looking for someone else, I should think
about running myself.''
</P>
<P>
   A Republican strategist who has known Bauer for years, but has
requested anonymity, says he's still puzzled by Bauer's decision to
run. Bauer has neither the media audience nor the following behind
ultraconservative candidates such as Pat Robertson in 1988 or, more
recently, Pat Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   And, he adds, the Christian conservative movement is in
disarray, especially when compared to the glory days of Robertson's
``moral majority.''
</P>
<P>
   When Bauer told longtime friend Bill Kristol, a former aide to
Dan Quayle and now editor of the conservative Weekly Standard, that
he wanted to run for president, Kristol said he did not try to
dissuade him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe there's a market for someone like Gary who takes on
these social and moral issues,'' Kristol said, adding, ``Look, his
candidacy was always a longshot.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is a real possibility that Bauer will outpoll Forbes
in the Iowa caucuses, Kristol said. Winning the nomination may be
farfetched, he said, but doing ``respectably'' is not.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you do, you're a major figure in the party,`` Kristol said.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer's agenda is one that many mainstream Republican candidates
shy away from after the last two dramatic Republican presidential
losses and the 1998 congressional elections. Bauer is unequivocally
opposed to abortion, wants a constitutional amendment to ban it and
pledges to nominate only anti-abortion justices to the Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   He opposes gay rights and is an ardent supporter of school
prayer and abstinence education. He would begin his term as
president with a major tax cut, he says, and supports a 16 percent
flat tax.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bauer's passion is to end abortion, he also is
identified with ending Most Favored Nation status for China _ a
topic that doesn't really energize the grass roots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it resonates or not, it's an important issue to the
country,'' Bauer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He almost seems to have been downplaying the moral and
Christian agenda by saying he's not a Christian candidate and he
shouldn't be viewed that way,'' the Republican strategist said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Bauer is not running as a Christian conservative, he
says George W. Bush can't get the party's nomination without them.
He plays to the uneasiness some have expressed with Bush's
middle-of-the-road conservatism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of them have decided he's good enough,'' Bauer said.
``It's my job to explain why he is not. But it would be a mistake
to (correlate) his climb in the polls with a decline in that group.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think those (social conservative) voters are the Republican
Party,'' Bauer said. ``I think that's why every candidate says
they're pro-life and pro-family, even if they won't do much about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a long history in this country of issue-oriented
presidential candidates who are almost, by definition, incapable of
being elected. They can, however, move the philosophical center of
their party,'' the Republican strategist said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The danger for those candidates is if you run as a cause or
ideological candidate and you don't do well, your issues suffer
commensurately. That's the danger that I think confronts Bauer.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer says he's not just trying to push his party to the right,
but is in it to win. He confesses that he is sometimes startled to
find himself still in the race after Elizabeth Dole, Lamar
Alexander and Dan Quayle have bowed out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm walking out on a (debate) stage with six podiums, running
for president, and I'm the son of a janitor,'' Bauer said. ``So
this is a great experience.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ORRIN HATCH &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The day Orrin Hatch announced he was running for president,
George W. Bush stole his thunder by announcing he'd already raised
a record $36 million in campaign funds.
</P>
<P>
   That would be enough to dampen any candidate's enthusiasm, but
Hatch greeted the news with puckish determination. If he could just
get 1 million donors to write checks for just $36 apiece, he said,
he'd be in as good a financial position as Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had the fat cats on board, he reasoned, so he'd mount a
``skinny-cat'' campaign. His small donors helped him raise enough
money to meet the threshold for federal matching funds last month,
which will provide enough money for advertising in the critical
Iowa caucuses and New Hampshire primary, but little more.
</P>
<P>
   Even in his home state of Utah, people initially greeted his
candidacy for president with puzzlement, said state Republican
Chairman Rob Bishop. ``But I don't see that any more.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people in Utah are proud of having one of their own as
a legitimate presidential prospect,'' Bishop said. His call for $36
donations netted Hatch about $500,000 from Utah alone, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're not convinced he can do it, they're at least
willing to put their money out there to see how far he can go,''
Bishop said. ``When the matching funds hit, that should put him up
around $3 million, and that's a credible start to a campaign.``
</P>
<P>
   Bishop sees some obvious parallels between Hatch's 11th-hour
decision to run for the U.S. Senate in 1976 (defeating a three-term
incumbent) and his relatively late announcement for the presidency
in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most political experts gave him no hope or chance of being
elected,'' Bishop said of the 1976 race. ``In fact, some of the
insiders in the know were really snotty to him _ and he pulled it
off.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch, 65, seems to relish the underdog role in a David and
Goliath political confrontation. Take his exchange with Bush in a
recent televised debate in Arizona, in which he suggested the
front-runner consider joining his ticket as a candidate for vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Just think, Ronald Reagan picked your father because he had
foreign policy experience,'' the senator said, referring to former
President Bush. ``Somebody suggested the other day that you should
pick me (as vice president) because I have foreign policy
experience. They got it all wrong. I should be president; you
should have eight years with me and boy, you'd make a heck of a
president after eight years.''
</P>
<P>
   The audience roared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, I'm the only one running in either party who has a
reputation for bringing both sides together in this divided city
called Washington,'' Hatch said. ``I could walk into the White
House and be effective from Day One.''
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the powerful Senate Judiciary Committee, Hatch
says the power to shape the nation's federal court system is ``a
huge motivating factor'' in his decision to run for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the end of eight years (in office) Clinton will have
appointed 50 percent of the judiciary,'' Hatch said. ``The next
president will appoint the other 50 percent, and up to five
justices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to say, I do not want 100 percent of the judiciary to
have been appointed by Clinton and Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch also wants to reduce the tax burden, simplifying the tax
code and saving Social Security and Medicaid. The next president
must strengthen the military, he says, and get the federal
government out of the schools.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch has come under fire recently for one of his own campaign
choices, having used a private jet owned by a pharmaceutical
company for some of his campaign travel. Shering-Plough Corp. of
New Jersey was, at the same time, seeking approval from the Senate
Judiciary Committee to keep its popular allergy drug Claritin from
being cloned by lower-priced generic drug makers.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch postponed the vote after the flap erupted over the use of
the company plane _ a practice the FEC allows as long as the
candidate reimburses the owner the cost of an equivalent
first-class ticket. He has firmly denied that using the drug
company's plane to meet tight campaign schedules represents any
kind of conflict of interest, frequently reminding critics that he
co-authored the 1984 legislation that allows the marketing of
cheaper, generic drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., knows Hatch well from their years
together on the Judiciary Committee and describes Hatch as
passionate about justice and opportunity for the underprivileged,
Specter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He speaks about growing up dirt poor in Pittsburgh, selling
eggs and tending chickens,'' Specter said. ``He's very much a
self-made man.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got into the race a little late, and he got into the race
underfunded,'' Specter said.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch concedes he's frustrated by his poor standings in the
polls. ``Sure, but I'm also realistic,'' he said. ``I didn't file
until July 1. Automatically, the media discounted me. They think
there's no way I can do this. They don't know me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ALAN KEYES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Alan Keyes grips the edge of a lectern and turns on That
Voice, people stop to listen.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes Keyes strikes a chord that resonates, frequently he
strikes a nerve. But he does not choose his message to please an
audience _ he is convinced he is right.
</P>
<P>
   His view of America is that of a people being sucked into a
``howling moral void,`` fed by the disintegration of the family. He
spelled out his apocalyptic vision vividly in a Fourth of July
speech in Iowa:
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's time we admit, the stock market may be going up
and for some, particularly those who aren't being destroyed by
depressed farm prices, the economy may be great,'' Keyes said.
``But I've got news for you. If the great moral heart of America is
being destroyed, if the conscience of America is being undone, then
it won't be long before all the rest tumbles from its pedestal.''
</P>
<P>
   For Keyes, restoring the ``great moral heart of America'' means
government that rejects abortion, euthanasia, and gun control.
Homosexuality is a behavioral choice, he argues, and he opposes
legislating rights for gays &UR; . &LR;  He frowns on sex education courses
that encourage promiscuity, saying they should be abolished from
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes has even endorsed public paddling of parents who abandon
their children.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes left Harvard graduate school as a young man with a fully
developed reputation for outspokenness. He entered the State
Department Foreign Service and began to rise quickly, his brashness
earning him a nickname _ ``the undiplomatic young diplomat.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet before he was 35, he was tapped by President Reagan to be
the highest-ranking black in the State Department _ the assistant
secretary for international organization affairs.
</P>
<P>
   But he resigned in September 1987, citing a racial snub by
Deputy Secretary of State John C. Whitehead, who in turn described
their conflict as a disagreement over a minor administrative issue.
A year later, he was running for the U.S. Senate in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes was selected to run by the state GOP in 1988 after the
winner in the primary stepped down. He lost, not unexpectedly, in
the heavily Democratic state.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes tried again in 1992, this time beating all the other GOP
hopefuls outright in the primary. But after a minor scandal over
his desire to draw an $8,000 monthly campaign salary from his war
chest, he lost.
</P>
<P>
   That was the same election cycle that saw Keyes battling the
Republican National Convention in Houston for podium time. The
convention hierarchy said they couldn't spare time for every
candidate running for the U.S. Senate, and former Maryland
Republican Chairwoman Joyce Lyons Tehres said Keyes immediately
questioned whether the refusal was racially motivated.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did ( finally) let Alan speak,'' Tehres said. ``I was
standing at the back of the hall and I heard that voice. And just
hearing the response of the attendees at that convention, someone
said, who is that? And it was Alan Keyes.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, having established himself as a radio talk show host
and a popular public speaker, Keyes made his first run for
president. His friend Marlo Lewis, staff director for a House
subcommittee, says Keyes decided to run because he truly wants to
be president, and because he thought the GOP needed a ``voice of
conscience'' to defend its commitment to ``the pro-life cause.''
</P>
<P>
   He fared poorly in the primaries, making perhaps his biggest
splash when he tried to force his way into two televised debates
restricted to the GOP front-runners. Four years later, Lewis said,
Keyes still wants to be president, but thinks it will take time to
be successful. ``He knows if you don't start, you never get
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Keyes accuses the news media of ignoring his current campaign
because he is black _ ``a blackout to keep the black out,'' in his
words. However, repeated attempts to schedule an interview with
Keyes for this story were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   A December editorial in the Manchester (N.H.) Union-Leader
agrees that the media are ignoring Keyes, ``but it's not because
he's black. It's because they have already foolishly decided he
will not be a factor, much as the Republican honchos in Washington
have already decided.''
</P>
<P>
   Though scientific public opinion surveys show Keyes has little
support, he brags about winning a number of online polls after
recent televised debates. His Web site has links to a plethora of
online presidential polls and his supporters are instructed to
``make sure Alan Keyes wins every online presidential poll over the
next two years. Please vote only once. ...''
</P>
<P>
   However, the Free Republic Presidential Straw Poll site noted
Dec. 8 that Keyes voters had ``stuffed'' their electronic ballot
box with in excess of 39,000 bogus votes over the previous weekend.
He still won the poll with 41 percent, even after the bogus votes
were eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, whose wife is Keyes' chief of staff, says there was no
organized effort to ``pack'' the Internet polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously those aren't scientific polls,'' Lewis said, ``But
the point is, as (pollster) Dick Morris put it so well, Alan really
does ignite something in people and he touches a chord.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he keeps creaming his counterparts in these debates and
speaking to the heart of what people care about, his candidacy
can't be written off.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
