</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991227.0217 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0057 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-ADOPTION-HNS &LR;      12-27 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADOPTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ADOPTION: AN ANTHOLOGY OF VOICES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BERNADETTE FAY  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO_ There have been memoirs, remembrances and how-tos
on the
</P>
<P>
   subject of adoption. But ``A Ghost at Heart's Edge, Stories
</P>
<P>
   and Poems About Adoption,'' published by North Atlantic Books,
</P>
<P>
   is the first book to look at adoption through the lens of
</P>
<P>
   fiction. The anthology of 52 poems and stories navigates a
</P>
<P>
   landscape that stretches from searing loss to ecstasy, from
</P>
<P>
   naked pain to reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   Co-editors Tina Cervin and Susan Ito have assembled a
</P>
<P>
   remarkable collection of voices from all sides of the adoption
</P>
<P>
   triad, from Charles Baxter, Alison Lurie and Louise Erdrich to
</P>
<P>
   lesser-known writers and poets. Nothing is taken for granted
</P>
<P>
   here. The collection bursts with a tumult of issues that shake
</P>
<P>
   us to our bones. Who are we? How do we find our way? What is
</P>
<P>
   family? Of course, searching for one's place in the world is
</P>
<P>
   nothing new to literature. And that's partly the point of the
</P>
<P>
   book.
</P>
<P>
   ``The themes of family, selfhood, loss, joy are universal
</P>
<P>
   themes,'' says Cervin.
</P>
<P>
   The aim was to present as many perspectives as possible
</P>
<P>
   about adoption, which touches 30 million Americans ? ``To open
</P>
<P>
   the door,'' Cervin says.
</P>
<P>
   It took them seven years to pull it off. Two weeks after
</P>
<P>
   placing requests for submissions in ``Poets &AMP; Writers'' and
</P>
<P>
   ``Associated Writing Programs,'' and two weeks before Cervin's
</P>
<P>
   first son was born, they were swamped with manuscripts. Ito
</P>
<P>
   was herself a new mother, and the two spent the next several
</P>
<P>
   years schlepping shopping bags full of stories and poetry.
</P>
<P>
   There was one fact keeping them focused: Ito, who teaches
</P>
<P>
   writing and is adopted, recently had found her birth mother.
</P>
<P>
   Cervin remembers she kept telling Ito, ``You should do a book
</P>
<P>
   about adoption.'' Ito finally followed her friend's advice, on
one condition: that Cervin, a psychotherapist and poet, do the book
with her.
</P>
<P>
   Ito's life story is itself the stuff of fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Half-Japanese, she was placed as an infant with a Japanese
</P>
<P>
   couple who had spent 10 years waiting for a child.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were constantly, as a family, barraged by (race
</P>
<P>
   questions),'' Ito says. ``At one point, it was in the early
</P>
<P>
   '60s .,.,. they were traveling with me in the South, and
</P>
<P>
   someone actually accused them of kidnapping me.'' Ito tells
</P>
<P>
   the story without bitterness or anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that a lot of people who are adopted can `pass'
</P>
<P>
   as not being adopted,'' Ito says. ``But especially with
</P>
<P>
   transracial adoptions, it's there all the time. I think we
</P>
<P>
   just all swallowed it down and pretended it wasn't there. And
</P>
<P>
   I think that's one reason why, for me, it's such a relief to
</P>
<P>
   have voices that talk about difficult things.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all under the lumpy carpet _ it's all under the
</P>
<P>
   surface of our lives as a family, but nobody talks about it.
</P>
<P>
   So I feel that, in a way, this book is like, not redemption,''
</P>
<P>
   Ito says, searching for the right word, ``but acknowledgement
</P>
<P>
   of all the complexities of (adoption).''
</P>
<P>
   The mission of the anthology, Cervin says, is getting to
</P>
<P>
   the truth of a difficult subject. Part of that truth is pain.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the stories and poems deal with the pain of adoption _
</P>
<P>
   on all sides. Many of the stories peek under the lumpy carpet
</P>
<P>
   to see, as in Isabel Allende's ``The Road North,'' trafficking
</P>
<P>
   in Latin American children; or, in poems by Jackie Kay and Mi
Song Bruining, the brittle realities of transracial adoption and
the burden of being ``chosen,'' which masks the burden of having
been given up.
</P>
<P>
   This prompts two questions: What does fiction offer that
</P>
<P>
   nonfiction doesn't? And, can someone who isn't adopted write
</P>
<P>
   truthfully about the experience?
</P>
<P>
   Ito believes fiction allows people to see more truthfully,
</P>
<P>
   to plumb ideas and emotions with a certain detachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a distance that allows people to go deeper,'' she
</P>
<P>
   says.
</P>
<P>
   Cervin nods, adding, ``It's a distance that brings you
</P>
<P>
   closer.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the validity of writing from personal experience,
</P>
<P>
   Cervin says, ``There's always that argument within the writing
</P>
<P>
   community: Do you have to have personal experience to write
</P>
<P>
   about something? A writer or poet has to have a certain
</P>
<P>
   ability to tap into something if you want to write about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was able to write a poem about being adopted, and I'm
</P>
<P>
   not adopted. But I've known Susan for almost 20 years, and my
</P>
<P>
   mother went on a search for her father, and I've known many
</P>
<P>
   people who were adopted. I feel I tapped into the experience
</P>
<P>
   both of the people I know, but also just the human experience
</P>
<P>
   of identity and search for meaning, and how does this piece of
</P>
<P>
   information fit into my life?''
</P>
<P>
   Good writing, of course, makes every story autobiography,
</P>
<P>
   every word telling, every emotion true. But Ito and Cervin
</P>
<P>
   have been criticized because the author blurbs at the back of
</P>
<P>
   their anthology don't necessarily reveal who has had real
</P>
<P>
   experience with adoption and who hasn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a strength,'' Cervin says. ``Because our goal was
</P>
<P>
   a literary collection. And I think first and foremost people
</P>
<P>
   represented themselves as writers, not as adopted people who
</P>
<P>
   are writers.''
</P>
<P>
   But it does show how familiar words _ family, mother,
</P>
<P>
   Identity _ can be weighted with new meaning.
</P>
<P>
   So what was the hardest part of collecting the 52 entries?
</P>
<P>
   After weeding out the sappy and the sentimental, after the
</P>
<P>
   hand-wringing over the voices that weren't heard from (the
</P>
<P>
   editors wished they had received more stories on transracial
</P>
<P>
   adoptions, and lesbian and gay adoptions), the two had to come
</P>
<P>
   up with a title.
</P>
<P>
   ``We both finally feel really good about the title,'' Ito
</P>
<P>
   says, laughing with something that sounds like relief. ``I
</P>
<P>
   feel it's so perfect because it really reflects every facet of
</P>
<P>
   the triad experience. There's that ghost if you're adopted _
</P>
<P>
   the family you don't know or the people you don't know who
</P>
<P>
   created you. And then if you're the birth parent, the kind of
</P>
<P>
   phantom child who isn't with you anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I also think for the adoptive parents there's the ghost of
the children they might have had or maybe wanted to have that
didn't materialize, because so many adoptive parents have
infertility as their way of getting into adoption.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, they found their title in a submission by Katharyn
Howd Machan:
</P>
<P>
   20 years now
</P>
<P>
   I have lived with others,
</P>
<P>
   your unknown name
</P>
<P>
   like a ghost at heart's edge
</P>
<P>
   And, finally, after seven years, they have their book _
</P>
<P>
   a remarkable chorus of pregnant teens and wary women; fathers
</P>
<P>
   relinquishing fatherhood or gaining relationships; mothers
</P>
<P>
   being sought and would-be mothers seeking; and, of course, the
</P>
<P>
   adopted _ babies, adolescents and adults negotiating the whole
</P>
<P>
   crazy DNA dance and searching for something that looks like
</P>
<P>
   home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
