<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WISCONSIN GEARS UP FOR THIRD ROSE BOWL IN SIX YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BRUCE ADAMS  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ About half an hour into Wisconsin's first
</P>
<P>
   football practice at the Coliseum a fight broke out, with two
</P>
<P>
   linemen going at each other with roundhouse punches.
</P>
<P>
   This is a team practicing with a nasty edge, with the air
</P>
<P>
   of the underdog. Don't try telling them that they're actually
</P>
<P>
   favored over Stanford in next Saturday's Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter,'' All-Big 10 defensive end Wendell
</P>
<P>
   Bryant said. ``You still have to play like the underdog. .,.,.
</P>
<P>
   It changes nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Badgers flew from Madison, Wis., late Christmas Day. They
got right to
</P>
<P>
   business Sunday under sunny Southern California skies.
</P>
<P>
   The team was in full pads, with many players dripping in
</P>
<P>
   sweat in a climate more than 50 degrees warmer than back home.
</P>
<P>
   The first team offense was going against the first team
</P>
<P>
   defense in scrimmage conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We banged around pretty good,'' coach Barry Alvarez said
</P>
<P>
   after the practice. ``We tried to get the speed of the
</P>
<P>
   game,'' he added, noting the Badgers were coming back from off
</P>
<P>
   days Friday and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought our guys got back in the swing of things,'' he
</P>
<P>
   said. ``They did better than I expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez said Wisconsin will practice in full pads, with
</P>
<P>
   contact scrimmages, through Wednesday's drills _ then back off
</P>
<P>
   on the hitting later in the week.
</P>
<P>
   This is Wisconsin's second consecutive trip to the Rose
</P>
<P>
   Bowl and the No. 4 Badgers are favored over No. 22 Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our players and coaches don't pay much attention to who's
</P>
<P>
   favored and who's the underdog,'' Alvarez said. ``It doesn't
</P>
<P>
   make any difference who's favored. We proved that the last two
</P>
<P>
   times out here.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to the Badgers' last two trips to
</P>
<P>
   Pasadena, beating favored teams from UCLA both times _ taking
</P>
<P>
   the Bruins 38-31 last year and 21-16 in the 1994 Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez said the Badgers were not putting much stock in the
</P>
<P>
   odds or taking Stanford lightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've already been beaten by Cincinnati,'' he said,
</P>
<P>
   referring to the 17-12 loss Sept. 18 to the lowly regarded
Bearcats.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've learned a tough lesson.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant is clearly more comfortable coming into a game as
</P>
<P>
   the longshot.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mind-set hasn't changed one bit from last year,'' he
</P>
<P>
   said, adding he was driven by the chance to win respect for
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin's football program. ``A lot of people overlook us.
</P>
<P>
   People don't consider us a big powerhouse like Penn State or O
</P>
<P>
   (Ohio) State. Of course, we're not carrying a fine tradition.
</P>
<P>
   We're trying to start one.''
</P>
<P>
   The Badgers are 9-2 and come into the Rose Bowl on a seven-
</P>
<P>
   game winning streak that took them to the Big 10 championship.
</P>
<P>
   Before the trip here in '94, the Badgers hadn't been to the
</P>
<P>
   Rose Bowl in 31 years.
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez remembered the lowly program he took over 10 years
</P>
<P>
   ago. ``It was flat on its back,'' he said, ``one of the worst
</P>
<P>
   in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   He built the program up by going out of state, particularly
</P>
<P>
   to the East Coast, where recruits included this year's Heisman
</P>
<P>
   Trophy winner, Ron Dayne, a native of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could always get big linemen,'' he said of the
</P>
<P>
   homegrown talent in Wisconsin. ``But to get skill players you
</P>
<P>
   have to go elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are 63 players from Wisconsin on the roster
</P>
<P>
   this year and 46 from other states, including five from
</P>
<P>
   California.
</P>
</TEXT>
