<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-RESEARCH-SPENDING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDUSTRY REDISCOVERS BASIC RESEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(mk) 
 By WILLIAM J. BROAD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   American industry is pouring extraordinary sums of money into
research and development in an effort to nurture strong growth,
private and federal officials are reporting.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had once feared that American industry in the 1990s,
faced with rising global competition, tightening budgets and
growing demands for quick profitability from investors, was quietly
abandoning the kind of high-risk research that historically has
produced the biggest payoffs and breakthroughs. Worrisome examples
cited by experts are W.R. Grace and Eastman Chemical, which
recently closed the doors on corporate laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   But a new study by the Industrial Research Institute, a
nonprofit group in Washington that represents large companies, says
overall trends turn out to be strongly the opposite _ and federal
officials in interviews echoed the upbeat numbers and analyses.
</P>
<P>
   The report, titled ``Basic Research in Industry,'' is based on
federal data and institute surveys, and concludes, ``Industry is
doing more long-range, high-risk, discovery-type research than ever
before.'' It was released on Dec. 15 by Charles F. Larson,
executive director of the institute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was amazed at the growth,'' Larson said in an interview.
``I've been sensing this for some time but was delighted to find
that it was true in terms of the hard numbers. It's a new era.''
</P>
<P>
   From 1994 to 1999, the study said, American industrial research
and development grew to a projected $166 billion from $97.1
billion, a rise of 71 percent, or slightly less if adjusted for
inflation, and in any case more than double the spending of the
federal government, which in 1999 is putting $75 billion into
research and development. Until the 1980s, the government was the
nation's unrivaled research leader as it probed new frontiers with
innovative technology from atom smashers to orbiting telescopes.
</P>
<P>
   By soaring during the past five years, industrial research and
development is rebounding from a flat period in the early 1990s,
when companies cut back on research in an effort to try to raise
efficiencies and cut redundancies. By 1992, Japan was seen as
having equaled or surpassed the United States as the world's top
patron of industrial research and development, giving it a powerful
weapon in the trade wars to produce a new wave of innovative goods
and services.
</P>
<P>
   But America is now indisputably back on top, with Japanese
industry spending some $95 billion last year, far less than the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the industrial money goes into the relatively prosaic
work of development, like engineering, making prototypes and
testing products. A lesser amount goes into applied research, which
focuses on making new products, processes and services for
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   A major surprise of the study, Larson said, is that directed
basic research _ the blue-sky pursuit of products and services that
might lie a decade in the future _ has grown even faster than
overall research and development in the past half decade. It is up
82 percent, to $10.9 billion in 1999 from $6 billion in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The Industrial Research Institute found that the rise came
mainly from companies doing business in the life and information
sciences, including enterprises like Cisco Systems, Compaq
Computer, Lilly &AMP; Co., Lucent Technologies, Merck &AMP; Co., Microsoft,
Monsanto and Sun Microsystems. Microsoft is reportedly investing 17
percent of its sales in research and development, and many
companies are putting in more.
</P>
<P>
   The feverish growth, Larson said, comes in reaction to strong
global competition and is made possible by healthy corporate
profits and cash flows. Other factors, he said, include the spread
of the idea that the economy is increasingly knowledge-driven, and
that raising intellectual capital is a good way to manage the
corporate enterprise for growth in sales, profits and shareholder
value.
</P>
<P>
   He added that many companies, including Intel, Hewlett-Packard,
Lucent, IBM, Texas Instruments and Xerox, have begun ``skunk
works,'' or independent start-ups, to help foster innovation.
</P>
<P>
   John E. Jankowski, a financial analyst at the National Science
Foundation, a federal agency that tracks science spending, said
that the Industrial Research Institute study was right on target.
``Our statistics show strong positive growth,'' he said. ``We've
had a very positive trend in terms of industrial research and
development.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
