   ISRAEL-POLITICS (Jerusalem) _ The Shas political party's threats
to bolt and break Prime Minister Ehud Barak's coalition government
have been a leitmotif of the Israeli leader's six months in office.
On Monday the threats were formalized when Shas, an ultra-Orthodox
party that represents Sephardic Jews of Middle Eastern and North
African descent, announced its decision to quit the government. By
withdrawing its 17 members of Parliament, Shas would leave Barak
with a minority government of 51 out of 120 members. Small parties
and Arab parties that are nominally in the opposition would keep
Barak's government from falling. But Shas' departure would throw
the political system into chaos just as it was facing important
budgetary and peacemaking deadlines. By Deborah Sontag.
