<HEADER>
A0075 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-RACE-PAIN-NYT &LR;      12-27 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-RACE-PAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACIAL BIAS SEEN IN TREATING PATIENTS FOR PAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., N.Y., Va.)  (The Science Times) 
(mk) 
 By GABRIELLE GLASER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Black patients with broken arms or legs were less likely to be
given painkillers in an Atlanta emergency room than white patients
with similar injuries and complaints of pain, a new study has
found.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at Emory University School of Medicine in Atlanta
examined the charts of 127 black patients and 90 white patients who
were treated by 37 doctors at the hospital, which was not
identified, from 1992 to 1995. They found that 43 percent of black
patients with fractures of the extremities received no pain
medication in the emergency room, while 26 percent of white
patients with similar injuries went untreated for pain. The study
appears in the January issue of The Annals of Emergency Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Because neither doctors nor patients were interviewed, Dr. Knox
H. Todd, an associate professor of emergency medicine at Emory, who
was an author of the study, said the report could offer no
definitive explanation for the disparity.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Lewis R. Goldfrank, the director of emergency services
at Bellevue Hospital Center in Manhattan, said the results spoke
for themselves. ``I think it's racism, flat out,'' he said. ``This
is a critical issue for emergency medicine and medicine in general.
How can we say that we have the best medical care in the world and
at the same time not be able to assure everyone _ with confidence _
that they'll get the same treatment as the next person, regardless
of their skin color? This is a wake-up call to our inability to
understand the needs of diverse groups of people in our society.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar study in Los Angeles, published in The Journal of the
American Medical Association in 1993, found that white patients
with broken bones were 64 percent more likely than Hispanic
patients with similar fractures to receive pain medication in the
emergency room.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more different your cultural background, the more the
disparity in pain treatment is likely to be,'' said Todd, who was
also an author of the JAMA study. Eighty-five percent of all
emergency room doctors in the United States are white, Todd said,
and some might unknowingly empathize with patients of their own
race, and tend to underemphasize the pain of another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although there are cultural differences in pain expression,
these are too often invoked as a cause of differential analgesic
treatment,'' Todd said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Marcus L. Martin, chairman of the emergency department of
the University of Virginia Health System in Charlottesville, Va.,
said that in tolerating and expressing pain, ethnic differences did
exist. But in an editorial accompanying the study, Martin raised
several questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do some patients express pain in a way that is more convincing
that they need medication?'' he asked. ``Do some patients present
in a way that they are viewed as overly dramatic, drug seeking or
for some societal reason not deserving of pain medication? Do
clinicians withhold or deliver inadequate medications on the basis
of personal bias, a subconscious fear of causing addiction, or
practice in a community where it is common for ethnic disparities
in health care to exist?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
