u a BC-SCI-DEMENTIA-NYT &LR;      12-27 0413
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-DEMENTIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW GUIDE BY AMA FOCUSES ON DEMENTIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(mk) 
 By ALISHA BERGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dementia strikes 4 million Americans every year, according to
the American Medical Association, sapping their memories and their
ability to live independently.
</P>
<P>
   Most commonly a result of Alzheimer's disease, it grows ever
more prevalent as the population grows older: The association says
35 percent to 45 percent of people over 85 have it to at least some
degree.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite its prevalence, dementia can be frustratingly hard
to diagnose. Its symptoms are often confused with those of
depression, delirium, vitamin deficiency or just old age.
</P>
<P>
   Now, to help family doctors and other nonspecialists identify
dementia and help their patients get appropriate treatment, the
medical association has published a booklet, ``Diagnosis,
Management and Treatment of Dementia: A Practical Guide for Primary
Care Physicians.'' Copies, at $5 each or $3 for AMA members, are
available from the association by calling (312) 464-5563.
</P>
<P>
   The 47-page guide includes reference cards to help doctors
perform preliminary diagnoses of suspected dementia. And it
includes information on treatment of cognitive and behavioral
problems, needs of family members, safety, potential for abuse of
people with dementia, community resources and end-of-life concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are different kinds of dementing disorders,'' said Dr.
Rosalie Guttman, a scientist specializing in aging who is an editor
of the guide. ``The symptoms are going to vary. In general, the
most observable signs are memory loss for recent events,
communication problems, word confusion _ the patient uses words
that sound similar but do not quite mean what they want to say. And
because they forget, they repeat questions and say the same things
over and over again.''
</P>
<P>
   Patients and their families need help coping with the insidious
progress of dementia and planning for the future _ making out
wills, for example, and working out power of attorney so patients'
wishes can be respected even after they can no longer voice them.
</P>
<P>
   Guttman noted that forethought could keep patients independent,
minimize the stresses felt by those who care for them, and keep
patients with their families for as long as possible. ``What's
important,'' she said, ``is that families who are confronted with
dementing disorders need all the help and support they can get.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-99 1651EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
