<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 16:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0081 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-SURGICAL-ZIPPER-N     12-27 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SURGICAL-ZIPPER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZIPPING UP:   A SUBSTITUTE   FOR STITCHES   AND STAPLES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Calif, Ga., Bermuda)  (The Science Times) 
(DW) 
 By KEITH MULVIHILL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Benjamin Brody awoke from abdominal surgery, he was groggy
and disoriented. As he slid back his surgical gown to take a look
at his new incision, he did not see the usual cross-hatching of
sutures or the minirailroad track of staples. Instead, he saw a
zipper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `Oh, my God, what is this?''' he recalled recently.
``I had never seen anything like it in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitcomb L. Judson, who invented the zipper back in 1893, would
doubtless be surprised to learn that his device had made the leap
to human bodies. Looking like an oversize white gauze bandage, the
surgical zipper is a polyester patch with a polyethylene zipper
running lengthwise down the middle. The underside is coated with a
nontoxic adhesive, like a Band-Aid.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes time to close an incision (the zipper works only
on straight ones), the surgeon peels off the paper strip, exposing
the adhesive, and places one edge on each side of the wound. While
gently pulling up on the tab, the surgeon pulls the zipper shut; as
the zipper comes together, so too do the edges of the skin. The
process takes less than two minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Brody, who lives in Brooklyn, says his 6-inch incision has
healed quite well. ``I had surgery on my chest a few years ago and
it was closed with staples, and boy was it painful,'' he said in an
interview. ``With the zipper, I had no pain at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Three hospitals in the United States are using the zipper,
though the manufacturer _ Atrax Medical Group Ltd., based in
Bermuda, which sells it under the brand name Medizip _ says it
plans wider distribution starting next year.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mitchell Roslin, a general surgeon at Maimonides Medical
Center in Brooklyn, who took part in a clinical investigation, says
he has now used it about 70 times, including Brody's operation in
October.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real benefit of these types of products is their
intellectual appeal to the patient,'' Roslin said. ``The patients
really, really love it. Instead of complaining that they are
nauseous or can't eat, they are showing people their zipper
incision. Patients also spend a lot less time agonizing over the
thought of having sutures or staples removed.''
</P>
<P>
   The zipper is generally quicker to apply than sutures or
staples, Roslin says. He adds that it leaves a less disfiguring
scar and can simply be peeled off in the shower after 10 days or
so.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Gregg, 53, a computer systems manager in San Francisco,
recently had quadruple bypass operation in which veins were
harvested from his legs, leaving incisions 12 and 20 inches long.
``I have been sewn, stapled, taped and zippered,'' he said, ``and I
like the zippering method best.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year I had abdominal surgery, and they used tape. It
didn't work very well. I don't think the incision closed properly;
I have a scar that is about three-quarters of an inch wide.''
</P>
<P>
   Rita Altman, a physician assistant who took part in a clinical
trial in San Francisco, says a possible drawback is that the zipper
takes a little practice. ``You might get a surgeon who uses the
zipper and doesn't get it quite right on the first try and
incorrectly assumes that it doesn't work,'' said Ms. Altman, who
now practices in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration says that it recognizes five
methods of closing wounds: suturing, stapling, taping, gluing and
now zippering _ and that others are in the works. ``Over the last
18 months or so, we have seen a variety of wound-closing devices
similar to the zipper, but they use Velcro or lace-close like a
shoe,'' said Jim Dillard of the agency's device-evaluation office.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest innovation in wound closing came last year with
the introduction of a tissue adhesive, Dermabond. This gluing
method is ``revolutionary in managing wounds,'' Dillard said.
</P>
<P>
   The tissue adhesive, 2-octyl cyanoacrylate, is used to repair
low-tension cuts and to close surgical incisions. It reacts with
moisture on the skin surface to form a strong flexible bond. This
method, which is gaining popularity in emergency rooms and plastic
surgery offices, is considered ideal for facial wounds. Children
who typically do not sit well for traditional methods seem to fare
well with gluing, Dillard said.
</P>
<P>
   Methods like gluing and zippering represent a trend toward the
use of sutureless wound closure, said Roslin, of Maimonides. ``I
think that you're going to see more widespread use of surgical
glues and adhesives,'' he said. ``People don't like the idea of
seeing something piercing through the skin; they find it upsetting,
as opposed to, say, a Band-Aid.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-99 1656EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
