<DOCNO> NYT19991227.0227 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 17:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0087 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-OXYGEN-NYT &LR;      12-27 1170
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-OXYGEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS BREATHING NEW LIFE INTO GASES LIKE OXYGEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Italy, Japan)  (The Science Times) 
(DW) 
 By MALCOLM W. BROWNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When you squeeze things hard enough, or change their
temperatures drastically enough, or both, wondrous changes occur _
seemingly magical transformations that have hooked more than a few
people on the joys of science.
</P>
<P>
   Take oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   We all know that oxygen is a colorless, odorless gas, as
invisible to the eye as it is essential to human respiration. But a
team of physicists at the European Laboratory for Nonlinear
Spectroscopy in Florence, Italy, has reported on a new form of
oxygen called epsilon-phase O4. Wonder of wonders, this stuff _
pure oxygen _ is a blood-red solid!
</P>
<P>
   Exotic substances like epsilon-phase O4 are never easy to make.
In this case, you need two large, gem-quality diamonds with apexes
pointed at each other and nearly touching, and with the space
between them encircled by a metal gasket. This arrangement creates
a tiny sealed chamber in which the pressure rises astronomically
when a vise squeezes the diamonds together.
</P>
<P>
   When a minute puff of oxygen is compressed in this diamond anvil
to a pressure of about 100,000 times that of the atmosphere, red
oxygen materializes. The Italian team believes the material is a
peculiar molecular configuration of oxygen, made of rectangular
units with an oxygen atom at each of the four corners. The ordinary
oxygen in air is a molecule containing two oxygen atoms; another
form, ozone, contains three oxygen atoms.
</P>
<P>
   The higher the pressure goes, the redder it gets _ up to a
point. As the pressure nears 1 million atmospheres, another
astonishing transformation occurs: oxygen becomes a metal; that is,
it becomes capable of conducting electricity.
</P>
<P>
   As if that were not amazing enough, oxygen compressed further
and chilled to near the absolute zero of temperature was shown last
year by a Japanese team to be a superconductor: a substance that
conducts electricity with no resistance.
</P>
<P>
   I remember the thrill as a high school student a half century
ago when I first beheld liquid air pouring into a dish from a kind
of thermos bottle called a Dewar. Ordinary air is invisible, and
this frigid liquid form, tinted a faint blue, seemed like a ghost
materialized from the ether _ a dangerous ghost that boiled
malignantly and swiftly coated its container with thick white
frost.
</P>
<P>
   A rose dipped into this sinister liquid instantly became as
fragile as a Christmas tree ornament, and a rubber ball briefly
immersed in it shattered when dropped.
</P>
<P>
   The founder of modern chemistry, Antoine Laurent Lavoisier, was
fascinated by the notion of liquefied gases, even though he never
saw one _ he died on the guillotine in 1794, before the feat had
been achieved. But according to a recent biography, ``Absolute Zero
and the Conquest of Cold,'' by Tom Schachtman, Lavoisier wrote at
one point, in a prescient surmise, that in very cold regions of the
solar system, ``the water of our rivers and oceans would be changed
into solid mountains. The air, or at least some of its
constituents, would cease to remain an invisible gas and would turn
into the liquid state. A transformation of this kind would thus
produce new liquids of which we as yet have no idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Changes in pressure are important for converting gases into
liquids or solids. One way to make a gas cold enough to liquefy is
to first compress it and then remove the heat created by
compression. After that, when the pressure is quickly released, the
gas instantly cools. Using this and other methods, including the
evaporation and dilution of liquids, physicists have reached
temperatures within one-billionth of a degree above the absolute
zero (which is approximately minus 459.67 degrees on the Fahrenheit
scale).
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all gases, including hydrogen, the lightest and simplest
of all substances, freeze solid well above this temperature. The
sole exception to this rule is helium, which can never freeze solid
at any temperature.
</P>
<P>
   A version of liquid helium that exists at temperatures below
2.17 degrees Celsius above absolute zero does something
astonishing: it becomes a ``superfluid'' that can flow without any
resistance through even the finest hole.
</P>
<P>
   It behaves in strange ways. Superfluid helium contained in a
beaker creeps up the inside of the glass, climbs over the rim,
descends on the outside and drips off the bottom of the container.
It looks like magic.
</P>
<P>
   Liquid helium, moreover, can act as a window into the
microscopic world ruled by the laws of quantum mechanics.
</P>
<P>
   When ordinary liquids are swirled they form a vortex, like that
of water entering a bathtub drain. The more vigorous the swirling,
the more pronounced is the vortex. But superfluid helium is
different.
</P>
<P>
   When it is swirled a little, one vortex forms, but when swirled
a little harder, two vortices abruptly appear, and then three, and
so on. It is a quantum fluid that changes states in sharp quantum
steps rather than in the smooth progression we see in the everyday
world.
</P>
<P>
   Liquid helium is expensive and hard to handle, but dry ice _ the
solid form of carbon dioxide _ is commonly used to ship ice cream,
and can offer some fun. The temperature of a block of dry ice is no
higher than minus 108 degrees Fahrenheit, and when dry ice is
lowered into a beaker of acetone, the acetone is quickly chilled. A
flower dipped into it becomes as brittle as glass, and liquid
mercury becomes a silvery solid hard enough to hammer nails. (But
bear in mind that acetone is a dangerous solvent and mercury is
poisonous.)
</P>
<P>
   People have learned to squeeze things so hard that their
molecular structure changes drastically. In the early 1950s
engineers learned to squeeze graphite hard enough to turn it into
diamond _ mostly in the form of industrial abrasives, but also into
costly gems.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists will probably never attain the kind of pressure that
creates neutron stars, in which atoms are literally crushed to a
matter so dense that just a spoon of it would weigh thousands of
tons, if it could be brought to Earth.
</P>
<P>
   But by firing metal plugs at targets using special gas guns,
scientists have generated brief pulses of enormous pressure _ the
kind of pressure that exists deep in the interior of giant planets
like Jupiter and Saturn. With the help of gas guns, astrophysicists
are deciphering the high-pressure structures of the solar system.
For example, about 90 percent of Jupiter's mass is hydrogen, most
of which is under such enormous pressure that it exists as a liquid
metal. The circulation of this metallic hydrogen is believed to be
the dynamo powering the planet's gigantic magnetic field.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists will never cease pushing the limits of pressure and
temperature they can achieve, because surprises await each advance.
Also, there's nothing so stimulating to the creative juices as
trying to imagine something that no one has ever seen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-99 1704EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991227.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0088 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-R-SCI-SURGICAL-ZIPPER     12-27 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-SCI-SURGICAL-ZIPPER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZIPPING UP:   A SUBSTITUTE   FOR STITCHES   AND STAPLES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Calif, Ga., Bermuda)   (REPEATING to add photo note; no other changes.)  
(The Science Times) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(DW) 
 By KEITH MULVIHILL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Benjamin Brody awoke from abdominal surgery, he was groggy
and disoriented. As he slid back his surgical gown to take a look
at his new incision, he did not see the usual cross-hatching of
sutures or the minirailroad track of staples. Instead, he saw a
zipper.
</P>
<P>
