   The zipper is generally quicker to apply than sutures or
staples, Roslin says. He adds that it leaves a less disfiguring
scar and can simply be peeled off in the shower after 10 days or
so.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Gregg, 53, a computer systems manager in San Francisco,
recently had quadruple bypass operation in which veins were
harvested from his legs, leaving incisions 12 and 20 inches long.
``I have been sewn, stapled, taped and zippered,'' he said, ``and I
like the zippering method best.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year I had abdominal surgery, and they used tape. It
didn't work very well. I don't think the incision closed properly;
I have a scar that is about three-quarters of an inch wide.''
</P>
<P>
   Rita Altman, a physician assistant who took part in a clinical
trial in San Francisco, says a possible drawback is that the zipper
takes a little practice. ``You might get a surgeon who uses the
zipper and doesn't get it quite right on the first try and
incorrectly assumes that it doesn't work,'' said Ms. Altman, who
now practices in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration says that it recognizes five
methods of closing wounds: suturing, stapling, taping, gluing and
now zippering _ and that others are in the works. ``Over the last
18 months or so, we have seen a variety of wound-closing devices
similar to the zipper, but they use Velcro or lace-close like a
shoe,'' said Jim Dillard of the agency's device-evaluation office.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest innovation in wound closing came last year with
the introduction of a tissue adhesive, Dermabond. This gluing
method is ``revolutionary in managing wounds,'' Dillard said.
</P>
<P>
   The tissue adhesive, 2-octyl cyanoacrylate, is used to repair
low-tension cuts and to close surgical incisions. It reacts with
moisture on the skin surface to form a strong flexible bond. This
method, which is gaining popularity in emergency rooms and plastic
surgery offices, is considered ideal for facial wounds. Children
who typically do not sit well for traditional methods seem to fare
well with gluing, Dillard said.
</P>
<P>
   Methods like gluing and zippering represent a trend toward the
use of sutureless wound closure, said Roslin, of Maimonides. ``I
think that you're going to see more widespread use of surgical
glues and adhesives,'' he said. ``People don't like the idea of
seeing something piercing through the skin; they find it upsetting,
as opposed to, say, a Band-Aid.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
