<HEADER>
A0093 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-FITNESS-MODELS-AR     12-27 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-FITNESS-MODELS-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROLE MODELS FOR FITNESS NOW COME IN BIGGER SIZES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: R.I., La.)  (The Science Times) 
(ART ADV: NYT photos 11 and 12 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By MARY DUFFY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They come at you from magazine covers and video advertisements
in particular profusion in this season of the New Year's
resolution: the perfect-looking people who promise ``sexy thighs in
six minutes a day'' or ``the body of your dreams.'' It's as easy,
they say, as buying this machine, following that diet or doing
another exercise.
</P>
<P>
   But for anyone alienated by these impossibly hard-bodied role
models, another approach is fast catching on: fitness programs led
by people who need to diet themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Experts in weight control and physical activity say it's about
time. ``The people who need to exercise most are the ones most
reluctant to do so,'' said Dr. Edward McAuley, a professor of
kinesiology at the University of Illinois. ``They are so conscious
of how others perceive them, and they anticipate they will be
judged negatively.''
</P>
<P>
   But by watching others like themselves progress, McAuley said,
people who are overweight or out of shape can gain the confidence
they need to proceed. And by working in groups of three or four, he
added, they share responsibility and support for the well-being of
the others.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best known of these programs is the Chub Club,
started in January by the talk show host Rosie O'Donnell and a
fitness coach, Judy Molnar, who stands 6-foot-1 and weighs 200
pounds. Because these two look no more like supermodels than the
average woman, they are moving many who sat out the fitness
revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``After we did a series of shows about breast cancer last fall,
I got a lot of letters from doctors telling me more people die of
cardiovascular disease than anything else,'' Ms. O'Donnell said in
an interview. ``If you really want to help people, they told me,
you'll try to get them to eat less and move more.''
</P>
<P>
   A veteran of many weight-loss plans, Ms. O'Donnell had no
intention of endorsing any particular diet. Instead, she would urge
her viewers to ``eat less, move more.''
</P>
<P>
   As for a fitness coach, she said, ``I didn't want some Barbie
doll-type saying, `You can do it, you can do it.''' So she hired
Ms. Molnar, who had been a guest on her show.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Judy first came on,'' Ms. O'Donnell said, ``I thought,
`Here's someone who looks like me, looks like our audience.''' Ms.
Molnar's message _ ``If I can get fit, anyone can'' _ resonated
with Ms. O'Donnell and her viewers.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, Ms. Molnar began walking for her health. At the
time, she weighed 300 pounds. ``For the first time in my life,''
she recalled, ``it wasn't about a diet. It wasn't about getting to
a certain body size. It was about my health.''
</P>
<P>
   Gradually her walking routine became a running routine. And
while she was not focused on losing weight, it began to happen,
``one doughnut at a time.'' After a year, she had lost 100 pounds,
and by last October she managed to finish the Hawaii Ironman _ a
2.4-mile swim, a 112-mile bicycle race and a 26-mile run.
</P>
<P>
   When the Chub Club was introduced on Ms. O'Donnell's show in
January, viewers were encouraged to band together with friends to
start their own branches. Clubs sprang up around the country, with
names like the Double Stuffed Oreos, Singing Fatties and Chubby
Charms. Members were urged to train for local five-kilometer
run-walk races, and received monthly newsletters with tips and
motivating messages. Ms. O'Donnell says membership was capped at
300,000 within weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ann Matteson, a 43-year-old nurse from Coventry, R.I.,
drafted three friends to form the TICU Tootsies. ``The four of us
work the 11 to 7 shift in the trauma intensive-care unit at Rhode
Island Hospital,'' she said. ``Being nurses, we're so focused on
taking really good care of our patients, but we don't take really
good care of ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Matteson, who says she has been overweight her whole life,
has lost more than 20 pounds and says her friends have all lost 15
to 30 pounds. ``It's not a drastic weight loss,'' she said. ``It's
just a little bit at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor does the club demand that members give up their favorite
foods. ``That's unrealistic,'' Ms. Matteson said. But she added
that since she organized her group, ``we do less chocolate and more
angel food cakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kelly Brownell, director of the Yale Center for Eating
Disorders and Weight Control, praises this approach. ``It sounds
like people in the Chub Club are taught to aspire to reasonable
goals, to eat a sensible but balanced diet and to be physically
active in a way they can enjoy and sustain and with some social
support,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he continued, the approach avoids a common
pitfall of diet and exercise programs: unrealistic goals. When you
begin with an unrealistic goal, Brownell explained, falling short
of that goal feels like failure. Instead of congratulating
themselves for the loss of say, 10 pounds, dieters may become
dejected because they have not come closer to an ideal. ``You
become frustrated, resigned and angry,'' he said. ``It sets up
expectations of failure for your next attempt.'' Research has shown
that this mind-set, perversely, leads to weight gain.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Chub Club is not the only program designed by and for the
overweight. A precursor, the New Face of Fitness, was founded eight
years ago by Dee Hakula, then a 350-pound Louisiana housewife who
wanted to spare others the humiliation she went through when she
began going to a gym.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some size 2 instructor was lifting her leg 50 feet in the air
telling me I could do it, when I could barely move,'' she said. It
was a beginners' class, yet she was way out of her league.
</P>
<P>
   Still, determined to be able to keep up with her small children,
Ms. Hakula kept going to the gym. And after dropping 100 pounds,
she became a certified fitness instructor and approached the owner
of her health club about teaching. ``At first he said, `You still
need to lose 100 pounds.' But then he said, `If you get 10 people
together, you can teach a class.'''
</P>
<P>
   She had enough clients for 10 classes, and has since won a
fitness innovation grant from Nike to spread her program.
</P>
<P>
   After the Chub Club was founded in January, its most famous
member said, she had to endure a six-month struggle with her own
philosophy of ``eat less, move more.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I started to feel imprisoned by my own comments,'' Ms.
O'Donnell said. ``I was really stressed and angry that all these
people were watching me and I had committed to doing this 5K.''
</P>
<P>
   The turning point in her own struggle came last June in Central
Park. It was a chilly, rainy Sunday morning, and tens of thousands
of people had come to watch the last in the series of Chub Club
five-kilometer events. Fans grabbed for the star as though her
touch would cure.
</P>
<P>
   One after another, Chub Clubbers approached Ms. O'Donnell to
thank her for changing their lives. ``It was really overwhelming,''
she said. ``Meanwhile, someone asked me if I had gained weight.
When the Chub Club started, I weighed 208. When I got on the scale
in June I weighed 216. I was shocked: It was the most I ever
weighed.'' It is all too easy, she said, to become disassociated
with your body when you are overweight.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people told me I inspired them,'' she said. ``Well, they
inspired me.'' Over the summer Ms. O'Donnell decided she owed it to
herself to get fit. As she put it, ``After a lot of soul searching,
I said, I'm going to take care of myself as if I'm one of my own
kids.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' she said, ``I eat more sensibly. I get on the treadmill
at home five days a week, and I get a lot of physical activity with
the kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Since June, as she recently told her audience, she has lost 28
pounds.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Brownell, of Yale, says Ms. O'Donnell's openness about her
weight and her struggle with it can help other overweight people.
``There is some research that shows having a role model who
struggles with a goal, can, in fact, be even more positive when you
are dealing with setbacks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Barker, a 25-year-old nanny from Nashville, Tenn., who
organized a Chub Club with three friends who are stay-at-home
mothers, agrees. ``Rosie was never secretive about her weight, and
watching her through her quote-unquote `failures' really helped
me,'' she said. ``I used to always lie about how much I weighed,
but now I'm not ashamed to say I weigh 200 pounds, and that makes a
huge difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. O'Donnell says she always hoped her viewers would feel that
way. ``I just wanted people with weight issues to be treated with
dignity,'' she said. As for Ms. O'Donnell, she is now at her
thinnest in three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have more energy, and I feel better,'' she said. ``It's not
that I feel good about my body, it's just that I don't feel as
badly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-99 1724EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
