<DOCNO> NYT19991227.0233 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0097 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-27 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BARBARA BUSH'S TRIAL BALLOON 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Bush family has put popular Barbara Bush, who
carefully cultivated an image of nonpartisan grandmotherhood while
in the White House, on one of her son George W.'s toughest
political cases.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month she launched an effort in a television
interview to banish or at least modify the odious Republican
platform plank that would criminalize all abortions, even those
that doctors believe are necessary to protect the life of the
mother. The 20-year-old official GOP stance that saving a fetus is
more important than protecting the health of a living, breathing
woman is an embarassment to the party and has been a drag on its
recent presidential nominees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in states' rights and I don't think it should be in
a national platform,'' the mother of the GOP presidential
frontrunner said. ``There's nothing a president can do about it
anyway, in all honesty.''
</P>
<P>
   The former first lady was indulging in devious Clinton-speak
there, technically sticking to the truth but in reality
oversimplifying things to distort the facts and create a false
impression.
</P>
<P>
   What sounded at first like a bold digression from Republican
orthodoxy was not really a change of heart but a shift to a kinder,
gentler rhetoric aimed at a similar outcome. She was doing her son
a favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``States rights,'' with its conservative anti-federalism ring,
is consistent with support for overthrowing the Supreme Court
decision granting abortion limited constitutional protection. If
the court reverses itself, the issue would automatically become
fodder for the state legislatures. Before the landmark 1973 Roe v.
Wade ruling, 45 states had laws forbidding or heavily restricting
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   And there are obvious, although indirect, things a president can
do about abortion rights. He gets to pick Supreme Court justices.
If he plops anti-abortion judges onto the present divided court, he
can tip the balance. George W. Bush has refused to specifically
promise to name anti-abortion judges, but he has also said he would
pick those who agree philosophically with him. Since he insists he
is anti-abortion, that in his case amounts to the same thing as a
litmus test on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   As president, he could also veto congressional laws that don't
suit him on abortion issues, as President Clinton has done. He
could use his bully pulpit to influence public opinion. As Bush
himself has said, ``An administration can change the tone in
Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Bush's pragmatic purpose in floating her trial balloon
is clear _ to wage war against a draconian platform plank sure to
give her son headaches in a general election in which he needs to
attract female votes. Despite her public image, she is politically
savvy.
</P>
<P>
   This move represents a political judgment about the temper of
the times, not a weakening of the family's anti-abortion views.
</P>
<P>
   As governor of Texas, George W. signed 18 provisions in bills
designed to reduce abortion and birth control. He supports a
constitutional amendment to bar the procedure except in cases of
rape or incest or to save the life of the mother. ``I'm going to
set a goal that says the unborn ought to be protected in law,'' he
promises.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some short-term legislation that a president can do. A
president can sign a partial-birth abortion ban. I would do so
quickly if one got to my desk,'' he says. Asked which Supreme Court
justice he most respects, Bush named Antonin Scalia, the most
rigidly anti-abortion jurist on the high bench.
</P>
<P>
   Every Republican presidential candidate opposes abortion. It is
considered necessary to win the GOP primaries, which are dominated
by religious fundamentalists and social conservatives. But there is
little public support in the country for returning to the
back-alley days of illegal abortions and sending women and their
doctors to jail. Most voters want abortion to be rare but not
outlawed.
</P>
<P>
   To appeal across party lines, a Republican presidential
candidate opposing abortion cannot thrust his view in the face of
voters who disagree by making it his primary objective (which rules
out Gary Bauer). And nothing would make a candidate appear to be an
extremist as much as advocating that outrageous platform plank.
</P>
<P>
   Getting rid of it would be a good move toward the moderate
middle. Bob Dole, the 1996 nominee, tried to modify the plank's
harsh language but was thwarted by anti-abortion activists. The
hapless Dole simply ignored the whole platform as meaningless. He
lost anyway.
</P>
<P>
   There are some early signs that anti-abortion radicals may be
losing some clout within the GOP. Arizona Sen. John McCain, Bush's
chief rival, has also been searching for ways to downplay his
anti-abortion stance by shifting emphasis elsewhere without
actually changing his tune. And some influential Christian
activists within the party seem more interested in winning the
White House than demanding continuing purity on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   It will still be a struggle for Bush to shake loose from the
vote-losing stranglehold of the pro-plank crowd. But he has sent
out his ``best man'' to make the start, his mother.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address
means &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
