<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-WORKING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR AULD LANG SHAME: FIRMS TRY TO EASE PAIN OF WORKING ON BIG
NIGHT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ It's bad enough to forfeit a New Year's Eve for your
job, but it's really tough to have to clock in on what has been
billed as the party night of the century.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, many companies are doing what they can to make the
situation more palatable for the employees who have to come in to
work.
</P>
<P>
   Most companies have a festive presentation of food planned. Some
are drawing names for trips and other luxurious prizes or paying
bonuses. And some confident companies that aren't expecting any
problems plan a weekend extravaganza of movies.
</P>
<P>
   A few companies, however, are playing Scrooge and trying to
avoid paying a New Year's Eve premium if employees are regularly
scheduled to work on Fridays. Other employers are suddenly getting
nervous as the minutes count down and quickly assigning more
employees to work the big one.
</P>
<P>
   For the pilots, flight attendants, technology specialists and
others who have to work on New Year's Eve and New Year's Day,
Houston-based Continental Airlines will draw 57 names each day. The
lucky 114 will win $2,000 each, said spokeswoman Catherine Stengel.
</P>
<P>
   Flight attendants and pilots also can bring two buddies with
them if they have to fly on New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   It's a way the airline can say, ``Thank you,'' Stengel said. It
also is something the airline can do because demand for seats is
lower than normal. Continental has cut its New Year's Eve flights
by 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   There is one catch: Buddies and employees have to fly to the
same place. The buddy can't take off to Hawaii while the friend is
on the Midland-Odessa (Texas) route.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to go together,'' Stengel said.
</P>
<P>
   To make the big night easier for its employees in Houston, BMC
Software will host a roast beef dinner followed by a screening of
the movie, aptly named, ``Entrapment,'' with Sean Connery.
</P>
<P>
   Children _ the whole family is invited _ can eat chicken nuggets
and watch kiddie flicks in another screening room.
</P>
<P>
   The software development firm isn't expecting any problems but
will have employees in 25 company locations around the globe, said
Betty Otter-Nickerson, vice president of product management and
development in Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The parties won't be as spectacular in some of the offices like
Singapore, which will have only two employees working, she said.
But they will get a party bag like everyone else, which includes a
top hat, calendar, candy, noisemakers and confetti.
</P>
<P>
   And everyone who is required to work _ Otter-Nickerson expects
several employees to show up to ring in the new year out of
curiosity _ is eligible to win a trip. A lucky U.S. employee will
get to go to Napa Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The company will also draw names for door prizes such as Palm
Pilots, handheld electronic organizers. All employees who work will
receive a bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another way to make it more fun and exciting,'' said
Otter-Nickerson.
</P>
<P>
   BMC is hoping those inducements will make it easier for its
employees in Australia to pass up lucrative offers to work as
bartenders the night of Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently a big party is planned in Melbourne, said
Otter-Nickerson, and restaurants are paying any warm body who can
pour liquor $5,000 for the night.
</P>
<P>
   St. Luke's Episcopal Hospital in Houston is requiring people who
would normally be on call to be at the hospital in case of a
breakdown in communications or transportation, but they won't have
jobs to do if everything goes smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   So the hospital will try to keep its employees happy with a disc
jockey from 9 p.m. to 1 a.m. in the hospital cafeteria. The
hospital plans a festive spread of hors d'oeuvres and maybe pizza
for the folks who have to burn the midnight oil on New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   Family members are welcome, family-oriented movies will be shown
and there will be board games set up. For the folks anchored to the
hospital floors, plates of cookies and pitchers of cider will be
taken around.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping to make it as festive as possible for people who
would rather be someplace else,'' said Caresse Young,
administrative director for human resources.
</P>
<P>
   Reliant Energy will have about 1,600 people working in Houston
on New Year's Eve. But there aren't any big parties planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have a little more of a festive atmosphere,'' said
spokeswoman Sandy Fruhman. Employees will get a little party bag
when they arrive that includes a lei and a bottle of water. Food
will be available, but no pig roasts or lobster boils.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're expecting them to be bored,'' she said, adding that the
company needed extra people on hand.
</P>
<P>
   Though some companies are inviting employees to bring their
children to work, others are not, presenting a bit of a child-care
problem for many. Many baby sitters were booked months ago, and
some are charging premium rates.
</P>
<P>
   Bright Horizons Family Solutions, a corporate child-care
provider based in Cambridge, Mass., is providing around-the-clock
child care for about a dozen clients nationwide, including Chase
Manhattan Bank, America Online and several hospitals and technology
companies. Bright Horizons has a contract to provide back-up child
care with Chase around the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the companies already have on-site child care. But at
those that don't, Bright Horizons will make do, turning conference
rooms and the like into child-care centers.
</P>
<P>
   There will be cribs for infants and cots for the older children
who will, hopefully, nod off after eating ice cream sundaes,
chomping popcorn and munching pizza.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a real slumber party,'' said Ilene Hoffer, director
of public relations for Bright Horizons.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
