<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSSTAND28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Magazines take last looks at 1999
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The final end-of-the-year issues hit the stands this week with
Time's ($3.95) Person of the Century (Albert Einstein), U.S. News &AMP;
World Report's ($3.95) pictorial reflections on the last 12 months
and US ($3) magazine's top stories of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Person of the Century package, Time offers an
interesting list of the most important people of the millennium,
starting with William the Conqueror in the 11th century. Others,
century by century, include Kurdish adventurer Saladin; Mongol
leader Genghis Khan; medieval artist Giotto; printing press
inventor Johann Gutenberg; Queen Elizabeth I; Isaac Newton; Thomas
Jefferson; and Thomas Edison.
</P>
<P>
   In the world of celebrities, US listed the top 99 stories, from
the deaths of John Kennedy Jr. and Carolyn Bessette Kennedy, to the
Latin music explosion. Most overplayed stories of the year,
according to a poll of US readers, were Monica Lewinsky, the JFK
Jr. plane crash, the Y2K bug and ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The
Phantom Menace.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  History in a nutshell: The January issue of National
Geographic ($3.95) is basically a time capsule of the millennium.
The cover of the magazine is a stylized tilting of National
Geographic's logo imposed on a deep-space image made by the Hubble
Space Telescope, symbolizing humankind racing into an exciting
future. Inside, foldout pages of photographs celebrate the Earth
from mist-wreathed Chinese mountains to the Saudi desert. Articles
touch on subjects from standards of beauty to undersea life.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most compelling essay is ``Rediscovering America,''
in which British-born author Tim Brookes hitchhiked across the
United States in search of his own American dream. Along the way,
Brookes encountered everyone from Elvis impersonators to Ramblin'
Jack Elliott, the singer who inspired Bob Dylan and other folk
musicians.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Spoiled sports: Those who think sports are just games haven't
been keeping up with the times. Utne Reader ($4.99) reports that
the loud noise you hear is not cheering, but the clang of cash
registers drowning out the thrill of victory. Writer Jay Weiner
proposes banning athletic scholarships in favor of financial aid
based on need, public ownership of professional teams and making
ticket prices affordable.
</P>
<P>
   In related articles, Susan Faludi, author of ``Stiffed,'' traces
the demise of the ``true'' sports fan; Maria Guhde Keri criticizes
domineering parents who ruin sports for their kids; and University
of Minnesota researcher Mary Jo Kane argues for more publicity _
and more funding _ for women's sports.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Trimming the fat: Once the worries about Y2K have been put to
rest, Americans' next big concern is how to shed the extra pounds
acquired during the holidays. Before you choose a diet, Women's
Sports &AMP; Fitness ($2.50) suggests you read a new study that reveals
that exercise, not dieting, is the most effective way to lose
weight. An added bonus: Recent studies also show that exercise can
slow and, in some cases, reverse the aging process.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Exercise spinoff: The publishers of Muscle &AMP; Fitness are
launching Muscle &AMP; Fitness Hers ($3) this month for women who want
to spend more time in the gym. ``The number of women in the weight
room has increased by nearly 200 percent over the last 10 years,''
says editorial director Thomas C. Deters, ``so we know women are
thirsty for the kind of information Hers delivers.'' The premiere
issue includes training tips from fitness competitors, nutrition
advice and articles on fashion, cross-training gear and low-fat
recipes.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
