<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Dec. 28, 1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Light snow will spread southeastward from the central Great
Lakes into the northern Ohio Valley and parts of western
Pennsylvania and New York. Most sections will receive 1 to 2 inches
of fluffy snow, but a few narrow bands east of the lakes may get
over 6 inches. The producer of the wintry weather is a strong
disturbance located near Lake Huron. It will force slightly milder,
moist air to be lifted over a gelid air mass covering the
Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Winds will slacken and some sunshine will be noticed east of the
Appalachians from Virginia to Massachusetts. Skies may stay sunny
much of the day in eastern New England. The fronts will pass across
the Northeast on Tuesday night, perhaps bringing flurries and maybe
a coating of snow to some spots between Washington and Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Cooler air will return to the Southeast. Clouds attendant to the
subtropical branch of the jet stream may bring scattered showers to
southern Florida. A large disturbance approaching Baja California
will send clouds into parts of the Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   Despite persistent winds from the northwest, much warmer air
will make steady progress across the Plains. Record warmth is
expected from Nebraska to the Texas panhandle. High pressure
stalled over Idaho will keep low clouds and polluted air trapped
over the valleys of the interior West.
</P>
<P>
   A strengthening offshore flow in northern California should keep
ocean fog out to sea. Except for valley fog, the coastal Northwest
will stay unusually mild and dry. The Southwest will remain warm
and sunny.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Not Good Air
</P>
<P>
   It has never been hotter at Christmas time than it was this year
in Buenos Aires, Argentina. On Saturday, the temperature rose to 90
degrees. By Sunday, readings soared to 104 degrees, establishing a
new record for the month and tying the highest temperature set in
the city. Usually, the mercury reaches the lower 80s in late
December. Sultry air arrived from Brazil at the start of the
weekend. On Sunday, a torrid wind from the west developed which
forced very warm air down the east slopes of the Andes across the
Pampas to the Atlantic Coast. A cold front triggered a cooling
thundershower Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
