<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLAGIARISM.ORG-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PLAGIARISM WEB SITE HELPS TEACHERS SAY `GOTCHA' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MATTHEW YI  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ The Internet, which is touted by some as an
invaluable learning tool, is also becoming a breeding ground for
cheaters who mine the computer network for term papers.
</P>
<P>
   Now, thanks to a former teaching assistant at the University of
California at Berkeley, there is a new weapon to catch students who
would rather surf the Web for a paper than write their own.
</P>
<P>
   John Barrie, a doctoral candidate in neurobiology UC-Berkeley,
launched an on-line service _ Plagiarism.org _ for professors and
instructors suspicious of their students' work.
</P>
<P>
   Barrie, 31, and his team of computer specialists, mathematicians
and statisticians, have created a new way to catch what he calls
thieves of intellectual property.
</P>
<P>
   This is how Plagiarism.org works:
</P>
<P>
   Teachers ask their students to turn in their work on an Internet
site set up for each of their classes. The papers are
cross-referenced in Barrie's database of more than 100,000 written
works he has gathered from universities across the nation. The
system also checks the Internet, making sure key phrases, sentences
or paragraphs are not simply lifted from another source.
</P>
<P>
   An electronic copy of the paper then is sent to the instructor
with questionable content underlined and highlighted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't make the determination on whether someone has
plagiarized. The instructor has to look at those reports and make
that determination. All we do is bring information to the table,''
Barrie said.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for such a service came up while Barrie was working as
a teaching assistant at Berkeley. He set up a Web page where his
students would post their work for peer review.
</P>
<P>
   The project was a success until he began hearing rumors about
those papers cropping up in other classes under different names.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students were turning each other in. Many of these students
are getting ready to go off to medical schools, and seeing students
cheat'' made some of the other students angry, Barrie said.
</P>
<P>
   While cheating on college campuses is not exactly news to
educators, one student-conduct official at UC-Berkeley sees a
correlation between the increased rate of cheaters and increased
use of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The number of cheaters grew by more than 100 percent since 1994,
about the same time the Internet started taking off, said Shawn
Decker, a UC-Berkeley student-conduct officer.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1994-95 school year, his office had 66 cases of academic
dishonesty, with about one-fourth of those being plagiarism.
</P>
<P>
   By 1997-98, the figure jumped to 140, with about the same
percentage of plagiarism.
</P>
<P>
   With the use of Barrie's Plagiarism.org, Decker believes the
number of students caught would go through the roof.
</P>
<P>
   UC-Berkeley is in final negotiations with Plagiarism.org, and
Decker expects the university to have full service by this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've given universities an answer to the problems of the
Internet,'' Decker said. ``I think any university that wants to
maintain their integrity, they would have to use services like
Plagiarism.org.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 300 schools ranging from high schools to universities
across the United States and abroad have contacted the
Berkeley-based group.
</P>
<P>
   As long as there are cheaters, Barrie figures his business will
take off without a hitch. The charge is $1 per paper for
participating schools.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
