A0106 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-Y2KMEDIA-1228-COX     12-27 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2KMEDIA-1228-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Y2K CZAR REPORTS NO PANIC AS NEW YEAR LOOMS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - A year ago, many feared this would be a week of
panic as Americans stockpiled groceries and greenbacks in
anticipation of Y2K-related computer crashes.
</P>
<P>
   But with the year 2000 just days away, government officials have
no reports of bank runs, stock market crashes or other kinds of
fearful behavior in the United States or elsewhere, said John
Koskinen, who chairs the President's Council on Year 2000
Conversion.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no indication so far'' that people are panicking, or
that serious computer problems are developing, he said Monday at
the federal Y2K Information Coordination Center, located just
blocks from the White House. While some computer errors have turned
up already in businesses and government agencies, they were ``all
quickly remedied,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The fear has been that vital computerized equipment would break
down because of the so-called ``Y2K bug,'' a software flaw that
could cause some older computers to misunderstand the date rollover
to 2000 at 12:01 a.m. Saturday. Between the 1960s and 1980s, many
computers were programmed to read only the last two digits of the
year. So it's possible ``00'' will be misread as 1900, triggering
computer malfunctions.
</P>
<P>
   For the past two years, business and government officials have
been attacking the most dangerous bugs. Today, the remaining ones
seem to involve printing mistakes, not system breakdowns, Koskinen
said. For example, this past fall in Maine, the state agency that
issues titles sent letters to owners of 2000 model cars and trucks
identifying their vehicles as ``horseless carriages,'' the
designation used for vintage vehicles produced before 1916. The
error was quickly caught and fixed, Koskinen said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the good news so far, Koskinen's office will begin
monitoring Y2K bugs 24 hours a day, starting Thursday and
continuing into early January. The Information Coordination Center,
which cost taxpayers about $50 million to build and operate, will
gather information from U.S. embassies and military bases
worldwide. It also will communicate with state and federal
agencies, emergency-relief organizations and industry trade groups
to pull together data concerning Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen said about 700 reporters and camera operators,
representing about 75 news organizations, have requested
credentials to report from the center. Beginning at noon Friday and
running through Monday evening, regular press briefings will be
held.
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen warned that reporters in Washington may become
frustrated because TV stations around the world will be ``reporting
incidents as they happen'' without evaluating whether they are true
or significant.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Information Coordination Center will be taking
its time to check facts from ``multiple sets of sources,'' he said.
``Our goal is accuracy,'' he said, not making deadlines.
</P>
<P>
   (Marilyn Geewax can be reached by e-mail at:
mgeewax(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
