<HEADER>
A0119 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-ART-N     12-27 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL'S 3RD-LARGEST PARTY SAYS IT WILL QUIT BARAK'S COALITION 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: This story will be updated as it develops.) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT 1 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The Shas political party, which represents Sephardic
Jews of Middle Eastern and North African descent, announced Monday
that it had decided to quit the coalition government of Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
   But Barak, who seemed unruffled, asked Shas to wait 24 hours and
see what could be resolved. The party, which is his biggest
coalition partner, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   By withdrawing its 17 members of Parliament, the ultra-orthodox
Shas would leave Barak with a minority government of 51 out of 120
members. Other small parties and Arab parties that are nominally in
the opposition would keep Barak's government from falling. But
Shas' departure threatened to throw the political system into chaos
just as it was facing important budgetary and peacemaking
deadlines.
</P>
<P>
   The Shas party has repeatedly threatened to bolt Barak's
coalition government during his six months in office, and it
remained to be seen whether this ultimatum was more ironclad than
previous posturing by the Shas.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to leave the government was made by phoning and
polling each rabbi in the ``council of sages,'' a body led by Rabbi
Ovadia Yosef that guides Shas politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Eli Yishai, the party's 38-year-old leader, said, ``The prime
minister asked us to wait 24 hours. We will respect this. We will
wait 24 hours.''
</P>
<P>
   But Yishai added, ``The rabbis' decision still stands. What will
be in 24 hours, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   As the third-largest political party in Israel, Shas has been an
unstable partner in Barak's broad-based coalition. With its
relatively dovish rabbis, it was enlisted as a potential ally for
the peace effort against vocal opposition from Barak's secular
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   But from the beginning, Shas has conditioned its support on
financing for its indebted religious school system and social
welfare programs.
</P>
<P>
   Shas' announcement came against the backdrop of frenzied
negotiations for next year's budget, which under Israeli law must
be approved by Friday. Yishai said that Shas could not remain in a
government that did not adequately support programs for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, Shas wants Barak to bail out its state-subsidized
school system, which is $36 million in debt because of financial
mismanagement and other alleged irregularities. The schools, which
provide hot meals and the longer days that working parents need,
are Shas' bread and butter, attracting adherents to its religious
and political agenda.
</P>
<P>
   As usual when speaking of Shas, Barak adopted a conciliatory
tone in discussing the party's demands. Looking relaxed and
confident, he said he was sure the crisis would fade.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech broadcast to his Labor/One Israel party at the
Parliament on Monday, the prime minister urged Israelis to
recognize the key role of the Shas party and how far it has come in
the last year since its previous leader, Aryeh Deri, was convicted
of corruption and stepped down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The movement of Shas is important to the government of Israel,
to its diplomatic route,'' Barak said. ``It is the third-largest
faction in the Parliament. It is a popular, broad-based movement
that maintains very sober, responsible and balanced positions in
terms of the peace process.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, empathy for Shas did not abound Monday. Yosef Lapid,
the leader of the Shinui Party, which won six votes on the basis of
an anti-religious platform, said he did not take Shas' threats
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is much ado about nothing,'' he said. ``This is another
extortionist trick by Shas that will be concluded in the coming 24
or 48 or 72 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shas does not want to leave the government,'' Lapid continued.
``It wants a fat budget, so it is increasing somewhat the dosage of
its extortion.''
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Radio reported Monday that Shas leaders met with Ariel
Sharon, the leader of the Likud Party, and received his assurance
that Likud would not rush in to take its place and bolster the
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have made it clear on many occasions, and I will reiterate
that we have no intention of joining this failing government,''
Sharon said later. ``We will not serve as a tool in the hands of
Barak to put pressure on any partner in the coalition.''
</P>
