<SLUG> BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGHTING FUNGUS WITH NEW NAIL POLISH; PLUS ITEMS ON THE POWER OF
FANTASY; MALPRACTICE; MARIJUANA USE; HEAD INJURIES  
(DW) 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Germany, Ky., Calif . ,, Mich.)   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration has approved a medication in
the form of a nail polish for hard-to-heal fungus infections of
fingernails and toenails.
</P>
<P>
   The prescription polish, Penlac Nail Lacquer, is made by Aventis
Pharma Deutschland and contains an antifungal medicine called
ciclopirox. It can be applied once a day for up to a year.
</P>
<P>
   Nail infections affect 3 percent to 5 percent of Americans,
causing nails to become dry, brittle and discolored, often turning
an opaque white, said Dr. Susan Walker of the FDA. In some cases
the infections can cause pain in walking or grasping objects.
</P>
<P>
   Penlac is the first topical medication approved for the
condition, which has proved difficult to treat locally because the
nails can block a cream or liquid's access to the infection. Most
cases have been treated with oral medications like terbinafine and
itraconazole, but Walker said the side effects of the oral
medicines could be serious, including liver enzyme abnormalities,
gastrointestinal problems and rashes.
</P>
<P>
   ``A topical medicine would not be expected to have the potential
side effects of an oral medication, but oral medications are
considerably more effective,'' Walker said. In various clinical
trials, oral medicines cleared up 90 percent of the infection or
more in 14 percent to 60 percent of patients. Penlac was that
effective for 5 percent to 12 percent of patients.
</P>
<P>
   INQUIRING MINDS FIND OUT THAT FANTASIES OUTPERFORM ASPIRIN
</P>
<P>
   Sexual fantasies may be better than aspirin for reducing pain, a
Johns Hopkins University study has found.
</P>
<P>
   In the study, 40 college students were asked to hold their hands
in ice water for as long as they could. Earlier, they had each been
asked to imagine sexual situations that they rated as maximally
pleasurable or less stirring. One group was asked to envision the
``preferred fantasy'' during the ice immersion; others,
``nonpreferred fantasy'' or an emotionally neutral act like walking
to class.
</P>
<P>
   The students who most liked what they were thinking about were
able to keep their hands submerged for an average of three minutes,
compared with slightly less than a minute for the others. Those in
the preferred fantasy group also scored lower on other pain
measures, said the study's author, Dr. Peter Staats, chief of the
university's pain medicine division. Results were presented at a
conference in October and formally released this month.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1996 study, Staats found that students who were told to
concentrate on words with positive connotations showed greater
endurance for cold than those thinking of negative words. Last
year, he came across an article in The National Enquirer
summarizing that research.
</P>
<P>
   ``Except that every time we used `positive word,' they said
`sex,''' Staats recalled. ``I got a kick out of that, and thought
that would be a very strong positive emotional state that we could
test.''
</P>
<P>
   The results, he added, should remind physicians of ``the power
of suggestion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The effect was certainly more powerful than aspirin and in
some cases more powerful than mild narcotics,'' said Staats, who
specializes in placebo effects.
</P>
<P>
   AN UP-FRONT APPROACH TO MALPRACTICE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Veterans Affairs hospital in Lexington, Ky., says it has found
a way to keep its malpractice costs below those of most similar
hospitals: make full disclosure to injured patients, even when they
would not otherwise have learned of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors generally agree that the angriest people, not the most
injured, sue for malpractice, and there is little that makes
patients or families angrier than learning that a hospital covered
up a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Revealing problems ``diminishes the anger and desire for revenge
that often motivate patients' litigation,'' the hospital's chief of
staff, Dr. Stephen Kraman, wrote in a study published last week in
The Annals of Internal Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The study compared malpractice costs at 36 similar centers
between 1990 and 1996. Payments over that span ranged from less
than $1 million to $12 million. Seven had costs lower than
Lexington's $1.3 million total.
</P>
<P>
   Under the policy, a hospital committee identifies and
investigates potential malpractice cases and notifies patients or
their relatives and offers money if the accident or negligence
resulted in loss of life, earning potential or other functions.
</P>
<P>
   In five of the 88 instances in which malpractice claims were
filed against the hospital during the study period, the patients
probably would not have learned of the problem if the hospital had
not told them, Kraman wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes there is anger and surprise,'' he said. ``In many
cases, they get very emotional that someone cared enough about
them, that they told the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   A DOWNER FOR AGING MARIJUANA USERS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Smoking marijuana significantly increases the risk of head and
neck cancers, according to a new study, which also predicts more
cases as baby boomers age.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, led by Dr. Zuo-Feng Zhang, a professor of
epidemiology at the Jonsson Cancer Center at the University of
California at Los Angeles, found that marijuana was almost as
damaging as tobacco in terms of respiratory tract cancer, despite
the fact that the drug was generally regarded as safer.
</P>
<P>
   The study, published in the journal Cancer Epidemiology,
Biomarkers and Prevention, compared the use of marijuana, tobacco
and alcohol by 173 patients suffering from head or neck cancers to
the habits of a control group of 176 cancer-free patients.
</P>
<P>
   Zhang said that marijuana users faced 2.5 times the risk of
cancer as nonusers. Tobacco increased the risk 3.5 times, he said,
and people who smoked both tobacco and marijuana raised their risk
36 times.
</P>
<P>
   A larger study now under way, is needed to confirm the results,
he said. Meanwhile, he said that people who smoked marijuana in
their youth should have regular examinations for the early warning
signs of throat, tongue or other cancers. ``If you consider the
latency time, about 30 years, we could well have an increase in the
next five or 10 years,'' he said. ``But many of these cancers are
easy to treat if they are caught early.''
</P>
<P>
   GAUGING HOW BADLY A HEAD IS HURT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Getting hit in the head, it turns out, is not a simple thing. As
a result, researchers from the Henry Ford Health Systems in Detroit
have been working with the National Football League, the National
Hockey League and the National Collegiate Athletic Association to
promote a new, more individualized system to determine when a
player who has suffered a concussion can safely return to
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Now, most sports physicians rely on one of a number of grading
systems, which rank symptoms and recommend varying lengths of
symptom-free observation, from 20 minutes to several weeks, before
allowing an athlete to return to play. Dr. Mark R. Lovell, the head
of the Ford division of neuropsychology and an author of an article
on concussions in The Journal of the American Medical Society last
week, said those guidelines had been useful but no longer reflected
the state of medical knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years, our understanding of concussion has been modeled
after boxing,'' he said. As a result, the guidelines place the
heaviest weight on loss of consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   But physicians have learned that what Lovell called the
``short-circuiting'' that occurs when brain tissue slams up against
the skull can often make itself known in a more gradual way. ``We
see players who weren't even close to being knocked out who later
develop symptoms that suggest more severe concussions,'' he said,
``and players who are knocked out who afterward have very little in
the way of symptoms.''
</P>
<P>
   The best way to tell if an athlete's mental processes have
returned to normal, he said, is to compare them with data from
preseason tests of memory skills and reaction times.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
