<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BUSINESS MAGAZINES: 'Magic' Johnson shows how it's done
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Atlanta Tribune (January), which calls itself
``black Atlanta's ultimate resource for business, careers,
technology and wealth-building,'' unveils its new format with a
profile of professional basketball star Earvin ``Magic'' Johnson's
business enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm motivated to show everybody, especially (corporations that
were) scared to come into our communities, that we are a success,
and that you can earn a return on your investment in the
African-American community,'' Johnson says.
</P>
<P>
   Magic Johnson Enterprises, based in Beverly Hills, Calif.,
invests in and operates a number of businesses, mostly within black
neighborhoods. His Atlanta operations include the 12-screen Magic
Johnson Theaters, a T.G.I. Friday's restaurant and a Starbucks
coffee shop. Other developments are planned, the magazine says.
</P>
<P>
   More buffeting for Buffett's portfolio
</P>
<P>
   Is Warren Buffett losing his magic touch after more than 30
years of unrivaled investment success? Probably not, says Barron's
(Dec. 27), but the billionaire investor's Berkshire Hathaway
portfolio ``may experience its first annual stock-price decline
since 1990.'' Analysts blame the anticipated drop of 22.5 percent
partly on Chief Executive Officer Buffett's distaste for technology
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The Berkshire Hathaway portfolio has been hurt in 1999 by losses
in Coca-Cola, Freddie Mac and Gillette. But American Express is a
big winner, offsetting some of the Coca-Cola losses since the two
stocks together account for more than half the portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Great investment ideas rest on fundamentals
</P>
<P>
   The theme of ``great investment ideas'' for 2000 continues to
dominate the personal finance segment of the business press.
</P>
<P>
   The new century promises ``unimaginable change,'' but Smart
Money (January), The Wall Street Journal's personal investment
magazine, says it's the well-managed companies that will still
attract most investors.
</P>
<P>
   Individual Investor (January) says an influential group of
naysayers challenges the idea that the Federal Reserve will raise
interest rates again in 2000. They argue that rates will fall, and
the 30-year Treasury yield will drop to 4.5 percent (it's almost
6.5 percent now).
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street guru Ed Yardeni tells Mutual Funds (January) that
real estate investment trusts are a bargain for investors looking
for income, especially REITs that specialize in apartment
properties.
</P>
<P>
   Worth mentioning ...
</P>
<P>
   Ten centuries have transformed mankind's wealth, numbers, work,
lifestyles, rights, literacy, communications and understanding of
the world, The Economist (Dec. 31) says in its special millennium
edition.
</P>
<P>
   Success (January), a magazine that targets entrepreneurs,
provides a Dick-and-Jane primer on how to start a business. It's
like hunting for buried treasure, the magazine says. ``You know
there's gold out there, but you need a map to get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
