<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UPS is the whole package, says Forbes
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ We may be living in a high-tech era but it still takes
a low-tech truck to deliver something you've ordered over the
Internet, which is why Forbes magazine picked Atlanta-based United
Parcel Service as its ``company of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With 157,000 ground vehicles, 610 aircraft and $11 billion
invested in technology, UPS moves both atoms and bits,'' says
Forbes in announcing its ``platinum list'' of ``America's best big
companies.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Forbes, UPS's role as a shipper of 6 percent of the
nation's gross domestic product makes it ``the missing link in the
burgeoning world of E-commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes notes UPS has invested heavily in technology in the last
decade, including mainframes, PCs, handheld computers, wireless
modems, cellular networks and 4,000 programmers and technicians.
</P>
<P>
   This makes possible the immediate knowledge of every movement of
goods, ``but is also the glue of trust for a new wave of worldwide
commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   ``UPS used to be a trucking company with technology,'' said
Forbes. ``Now it's a technology company with trucks.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately-owned for all but two months of its almost 100-year
existence, UPS went public in November with the biggest public
stock offering in history: $5.47 billion at an opening price of $50
per share.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes notes that UPS shows a 56 percent drop in net income in
the past 12 months, but says this is due mainly to $1.8 billion the
company had to pay to settle a tax assessment charge stemming from
the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
