NYT-12-27-99 1813EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991227.0265 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0142 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-CLEMSON-BOWDEN-CO     12-27 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CLEMSON-BOWDEN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clemson coach brings Bowden style to Peach
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ag &QR;  ile, adj. _ 1. quick and easy of movement; deft
and active. 2. keen and lively.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no better word sums up the coaching personality of the
Bowden family. In his first season at Clemson's head coach, Tommy
Bowden has had to wring virtually every usage out of that term to
fashion a 6-5 Peach Bowl team. The 1999 Tigers not only survived
but modestly prospered through one of the most difficult schedules
in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Three of Clemson's losses were to the only three undefeated
regular season teams in Division I-A football _ to Florida State
and Marshall by field goals and to Virginia Tech after pulling
within three points in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers were the only team in the country to play all three,
but their approach to each game did not vary by opponent. Along the
way, they set school records for passing offense with an
eye-popping offensive attack, employed an opportunistic defense and
unveiled some typical Bowden trickery to draw national notice.
</P>
<P>
   After inheriting a demoralized 3-8 squad from the fired Tommy
West, Bowden saw some possibilities for a quick turnaround. He was
welcomed by six returning upperclassmen starting on defense; an
experienced quarterback and receiving corps; and a squad that in
general was itching to break out of mediocrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know how to win. They just needed some tweaking, some
fine-tuning,'' Bowden said. ``Really, it hasn't taken a whole lot
(from coaches). They knew how to win games before we got here, and
they're going to continue to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   But something definitely was amiss. West, a linebackers coach
under Danny Ford, was well-liked personally, but the program wasn't
making any progress. West took Clemson to the Peach Bowl three
times and the Gator Bowl once in his five seasons, but the Tigers
never were able to join Virginia, North Carolina and Virginia Tech
in pursuing Florida State's dominance in the Atlantic Coast
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``After last year, we knew we should have been winning more,''
fifth-year senior quarterback Brandon Streeter said. ``We knew we
had to work harder and dedicate ourselves more. But the coaches
came in with a lot of confidence, and in turn, it gave us a lot of
confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Streeter thrived in the new offense and established a school
single-game record with 343 yards passing against Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   The silvery-haired, 45-year-old Bowden was brother Terry's
offensive coordinator at Auburn before getting the controls of a
program for the first time at Tulane in 1997. He was one of the
hottest coaching properties in the country after guiding the Green
Wave to an 11-0 season in 1998. Although reportedly offered more
than Clemson's $700,000 annual package to stay in New Orleans, the
competitive lure of coaching in a major conference was too strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were very good to me there; it was hard to leave,'' said
Bowden, a 22-year coaching vagabond whose longest stint was the six
years he spent at Auburn.
</P>
<P>
   He hired four members of his Tulane staff, including offensive
coordinator Rich Rodriguez, who installed a no-huddle offense that
used as many as four or five receivers. While Streeter was the
drop-back starter, Woodrow Dantzler was the option man; Dantzler
filled in admirably when Streeter was on the shelf twice with
injuries. At the same time, Clemson didn't abandon its cherished
ground game. Travis Zachery led the team with 826 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Clemson threw for a school record 2,417 passing yards and
trailed only Florida State and Georgia Tech in ACC total offensive
statistics. Doubling their 1998 win total also made the Tigers the
sixth-most-improved team in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know if we had the talent to do all that, but I
thought it was the system that would give us the best chance to
have some success,'' Bowden said.
</P>
<P>
   In order to accommodate such flexibility, Bowden ordered his
offensive linemen to slim down. No current starter weighs more than
270 pounds, the weight of their lightest Mississippi State
counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been most pleased with how the players have continued to
make progress since the spring,'' Bowden said. ``They understood
there was a sense of urgency. Their attitude has been very good all
along.''
</P>
<P>
   After dropping a 13-10 game to Marshall in the season-opener,
Clemson rebounded with a 33-14 win over Virginia. A Thursday night
trip to Virginia Tech had the Hokies on the ropes for longer than
they probably expected. Trailing 14-3 in the fourth quarter,
Clemson faked going for three points and instead had placekicker
Tony Lazzara toss a short pass for a touchdown. Although the Tigers
fell 31-11, it cemented the growing faith players had in their new
coach and those he brought with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realized they were winners everywhere they've been,'' said
All-American linebacker Keith Adams. ``They have helped put us in
position to win games.''
</P>
<P>
   When top-ranked Florida State arrived at Death Valley in October
with Bobby Bowden seeking career victory 300, his son wasn't about
to roll over easily. It took the strong, true leg of Sebastian
Janikowski and a last-minute field-goal miss by Clemson for the
Seminoles to escape with a 17-14 win.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, Tommy Bowden looks at Thursday's Peach Bowl date
as the first step toward the eventual goal of participating in the
Bowl Championship Series. Clemson fans haven't known such exalted
status since the Ford era, before there was such a thing as the
BCS. But Bowden is just a little bit too agile with his words to
offer a prediction for when that time may come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, no, you're not going to get me on that one,'' he said.
``The Peach Bowl is a great bowl game, but I can't afford to come
back three or four times. Then there'll be a new guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Parker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
