<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0148 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-GATECH-COX     12-27 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATECH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gregory key to Tech's success
 &HT;    By J.C. Clemons
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ Of course, Joe Hamilton is the reason the
Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets are ranked No. 17 and playing a New
Year's Day bowl game for the second year in a row.
</P>
<P>
   And yes, Hamilton, the consensus All-American quarterback and
Heisman Trophy runner-up is the main cog in the nation's leading
offense that cranked out 509 yards and 40.7 points a game.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, a strong case can be made that Tech (8-3) probably would
not be playing Miami in the Gator Bowl on Saturday were it not for
Sean Gregory, who began the season on the third team but spent the
campaign as the Jackets' featured back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just prepared at the time I needed to be prepared,''
said Gregory, who gained 837 yards despite starting six games. ``I
wasn't surprised by how well I did; I was just happy.''
</P>
<P>
   So was Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the highlight reels that focus mainly on Hamilton
connecting with speedy receivers Kelly Campbell, Dez White and
Kerry Watkins, the offense designed by Ralph Friedgen places a
premium on making foes concentrate on stopping the run.
</P>
<P>
   Once teams commit to eight or nine players close to the line of
scrimmage, the field opens for Hamilton &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   But first, the Jackets had to establish the run, and they did.
Tech finished the season ranked 17th nationally in passing (283.4
ypg) and 13th in rushing (225.6).
</P>
<P>
   With Hamilton's play-calling, that balanced attack was able to
keep opponents on their heels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hamilton has an uncanny knack of getting them into the right
play,'' Duke coach Carl Franks said. ``You don't know what to
expect from them.''
</P>
<P>
   After tailback Joe Burns fractured his leg against Florida State
in the second game, Gregory began sharing duties with Phillip
Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   In his first outing, Gregory rushed for 150 yards and two
touchdowns against Central Florida. Three games later, Rogers was
lost for the season after undergoing emergency surgery to relieve
internal bleeding surrounding a deep thigh bruise.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the job was all Gregory's, and the 6-0, 211-pound
sophomore from Homewood, Ill., would go on to crack the century
mark four more times.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing Sean does, he runs extremely hard,'' Tech
running backs coach Bill O'Brien said. ``He understands that, to be
a great running back, you have to break tackles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always knew he could do some great things.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yellow Jackets also had big things in mind for themselves.
But visions of another top 10 finish _ and a legitimate shot at a
Bowl Championship Series berth _ went up in smoke with late-season
losses to Virginia and Wake Forest.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory said ending the season with victories over rival Georgia
and the resurgent Hurricanes would make for a more pleasant winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We reached some of our goals _ especially beating Georgia for
the second year in a row,'' Gregory said. ``All things considered,
with a lot of injuries and a young defense, it has been a good
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Miami is on the rise, and they're hungry,'' he said.
``Winning a game like that would be great for us.''
</P>
<P>
   J.C. Clemons writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
