<HEADER>
A0150 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCIENCE-WATCH-NYT &LR;      12-27 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWN-CARE GENE  
 ENGINE'S MIXED RESULTS  
 QUICKER PICTURES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lawn-Care Gene
</P>
<P>
   It's a suburban homeowner's fantasy: a lawn that grows to a
certain height and no higher, and never needs mowing. That dream
may become a reality someday, with the recent discovery of a gene
that appears to control the production of an important growth
hormone in plants.
</P>
<P>
   The gene, known as BAS-1 and isolated from Arabidopsis, a weed
that is a member of the mustard family, works to break down the
hormone, a steroid called brassinolide. The discovery was made by
scientists at the Salk Institute for Biological Studies in
California and colleagues in Japan and was reported in a recent
issue of The Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   The hormone is found throughout the plant, but the researchers
discovered that the gene acts selectively to break it down in
different kinds of tissues, with the effect most noticeable in the
stems. Tinkering with the gene may make it possible to stop growth
completely in the stems, say, while allowing normal growth in
leaves and flowers. So a homeowner may someday be able to choose a
lawn like a carpet: from fine to plush to shag.
</P>
<P>
   Now if scientists could just figure out how to get it in
something other than basic green.
</P>
<P>
   Engine's Mixed Results
</P>
<P>
   A new kind of rocket engine for the next generation of reusable
space vehicles has been tested at full power for the first time.
The 18-second test of what is known as a linear aerospike engine
was carried out on Dec. 18 at a NASA center in Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the engine performed well, though some erosion,
in the form of pinholes, was noticed on an inside wall of a thrust
chamber, a structure that replaces the bell-shaped nozzles of
conventional rocket engines.
</P>
<P>
   The aerospike engine is being developed to power the X-33, a
half-scale unmanned prototype of a rocket that would take off and
land like the space shuttle but would be completely reusable (the
shuttle's huge external fuel tank, among other components, is
expended in each flight).
</P>
<P>
   NASA officials said that the erosion found after the test was
within the range expected for an engine under development and would
not slow the testing process. That's a good thing, as the X-33, a
cooperative project involving NASA, Lockheed Martin Corp.'s Skunk
Works division and other contractors, is at least a year behind
schedule and above its $1.2 billion budget.
</P>
<P>
   The engine, which is being developed by the Rocketdyne division
of Boeing Corp., has been plagued by development bugs, including a
major problem in bonding metallic parts of the thrust chambers. And
an effort to test-fire a small version of the engine was abandoned
after three years (and $27 million) because of persistent fuel
leaks.
</P>
<P>
   Quicker Pictures
</P>
<P>
   In the basic photographic process, film coated with an emulsion
of crystals containing silver ions is exposed to light. The photons
of light make electrons move within the crystal lattice, and
``holes'' are created where the electrons were.
</P>
<P>
   The free electrons then convert some of the ions to silver
atoms, eventually creating the plain silver metal that makes up the
dark spots on the negative. Pretty simple, but pretty inefficient.
Much of the time, the work of the photon is for naught: The
electron and its ``hole'' quickly recombine.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, it takes about 10 to 30 photons to convert enough
silver ions to atoms within a crystal so that it will become silver
metal during developing. Now French scientists have found a more
efficient method: doping the emulsion with formate ions. These ions
act as scavengers in the exposure process, quickly absorbing holes
before they can recombine with an electron.
</P>
<P>
   So just a couple of photons, instead of 10 to 30, are sufficient
to produce a silver particle. The development, reported in Nature,
may lead to films that create clearer low-light images and work at
much faster speeds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
