for ``Evening Magazine,'' walked along the water at Jack London
Square and waxed poetic, comparing his city to Hong Kong. ``We're
not nirvana yet,'' said the mayor, ``but we're getting there.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Maybe  &UR; Celine Dion &LR;  knows:  &UR; Bud Johns &LR;  is pondering why the
Australian lamb at Trader Joe's is labeled ``Product of Canada.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Having a nice holiday break? A German psychologist cited in
Discover magazine found that three weeks of mental inactivity can
cause IQ to drop by as much as 20 points.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reading in Personals last week about the Barbie doll- &UR; Joan of &LR; 
 &UR; Arc &LR;  incident behind the Echo Ridge school,  &UR; Liz Stevens &LR;  suggests
it was a holiday Barbie Q.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Catherine Zeta-Jones &LR;  flew to England unexpectedly to be with
her family for Christmas, and the British tabloids are atwitter
about her possible breakup with  &UR; Michael Douglas. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ German director  &UR; Wim Wenders &LR;  told the Sydney Morning Herald
that although his movies are popular in English-speaking countries,
even fans have a hard time saying his name. ``The first time I
heard my name pronounced correctly was at a Yankee game in New
York, when all of a sudden I felt someone was talking to me. ...
There was a message through the loudspeakers, `This is a message
for all the stadium vendors,' and I jumped up and said, `Hey,
that's me!' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NOEL, NOEL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Allen White  &LR; forwards the Bay Area Reporter tale of a fire
inspector who came to the paper's premises at 10 a.m. on the
morning of December 21, gave the office Christmas tree a careful
look _ including breaking off a branch, taking it outside and
setting it on fire _ and demanded that the tree be dismantled
``under his watchful eye.''
</P>
<P>
   After the deed was done, he left, saying he had a long list of
neighborhood businesses with trees that needed inspecting; but when
he got outside, he couldn't get his car started. Whereupon the
newspaper staff refused to let him use the phone to call for help.
</P>
<P>
   And so it came to pass that at 11:30 a.m., ``the fire department
vehicle was towed,'' says the Reporter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOW TO LOOK GREAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Fashion and beauty notes from the latest issue of W:
</P>
<P>
   ``Feng shui master and jewelry designer''  &UR; Carol Meltzer  &LR; is out
with sports chi-om bracelets, beaded wrist wear to improve one's
game. She told the magazine that her husband's golf game had
improved very much since wearing one.
</P>
<P>
   Also, F3, a new grocery store in Manhattan, sells nothing but
products ``for dieters without willpower.'' In addition to the
groceries, an on-site nutritionist ``will scold you if you dare to
mix your carbs and proteins.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, ``model-actress, Earth-worshipper and real-life witch''
 &UR; Jacqueline Collen &LR; , who (to provide a full resume) was once married
to a member of Def Leppard, is out with the Medieval Bath &AMP; Body
Collection, a bath line special because it was designed by a witch.
She says the products have ``no spells attached.''
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, this historic note: At a recent auction of
 &UR; Marilyn Monroe &LR; 's belongings at Christie's, designer  &UR; Tommy &LR; 
 &UR; Hilfiger &LR;  paid $37,000 for three pairs of jeans the star wore in
``River of No Return.'' The jeans were bought at J.C. Penney in
1953 for $2.29 a pair.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. InStyle editor  &UR; Hal Rubenstein  &LR; told Paper magazine of his
hopes for 2000: ``A way to moisturize your own back.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the pockets in back look weird and wrong _ I don't care.
Maybe they don't make your butt look so great, but somehow the way
they are placed is redefining what a pocket on a jean means.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &LR; Caroline Parent, creative director for Levi Strauss in
Brussels, about Levi's new Red jeans, which Metropolis magazine
says ``could be mistaken for, say, a street vendor in a former
Soviet-bloc village's sorry attempt to re-create the American
classic. ... The post-modern version of the master denim company.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;
</P>
