<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0162 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-HUGHES-INSTITUTE-     12-27 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-HUGHES-INSTITUTE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERA OF INNOVATION IS SEEN FOR MAJOR PATRON OF BIOMEDICAL RESEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., Colo., Mass.)  (See also SCI-HUGHES-CECH which has moved with NYT10, a photo of
Cech) 
(The Science Times) (DW) 
 By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Thomas R. Cech is about to acquire a whole clutch of new
friends. On Jan. 1, the 51-year-old chemist from the University of
Colorado in Boulder will become the president of the Howard Hughes
Medical Institute and chief dispenser of the fortune that Howard
Hughes protected for 23 years, using the institute as a shelter
from taxational erosion.
</P>
<P>
   The institute's affairs are keenly followed by university
biologists because it has become a famously generous patron of
academic biomedical research. The winners of a Hughes award can
count on $500,000 to $2 million a year in support of their
research. The Hughes largesse is distributed to 71 universities
around the country, freeing some 309 favored scientists from the
chore of writing voluminous grant requests to the National
Institutes of Health, the chief federal patron of biomedical
research.
</P>
<P>
   Cech (pronounced like check), chosen by a board of trustees that
includes two former chieftains of the Hughes empire, Frank W. Gay
and William R. Lummis, as well as former Secretary of State James
Baker III, is reserved about his plans, saying he supports the bulk
of present policies and that ``the board hasn't hired me to clean
house.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, conversations with Cech and the biologist he has chosen
as his deputy, Dr. Gerald Rubin of the University of California,
Berkeley, suggest they intend to propel both the institute and its
investigators into taking greater risks.
</P>
<P>
   The Howard Hughes Medical Institute in Bethesda, Md., has
emerged only recently from its shadowy role as a tax shelter to
become a major player in biological research. During Hughes'
lifetime, it served to shield the income of its main asset, the
Hughes Aircraft Co., giving only token amounts to medical research.
The institute's first head was Dr. Verne Mason, a physician who
tried to wean Hughes off the morphine to which he became addicted
after burns and injuries suffered in a 1946 plane crash.
</P>
<P>
   The eccentricities Hughes developed are well known: he harbored
a miscellany of hatreds, for the Internal Revenue Service,
Communists, nuclear tests, germs, doctors and relatives. He spent
most of the day naked, watching the same movies over and over.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes was addicted to codeine and gripped by so morbid a fear
of microbes that he instructed his aides, in one memorandum, to
handle his hearing device ``using a minimum of 15 Kleenexes. . . .
If necessary to use both hands, then 15 Kleenexes for each hand,''
James R. Phelan and Lewis Chester say in ``The Money,'' a 1997 book
about the disposition of Hughes' wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes died in 1976, leaving no will. It took nearly a decade of
litigation and the rejection of many concocted testaments before
the institute was declared his chief beneficiary. It is a
``monument to Hughes himself,'' Phelan and Chester write, ``a
bizarre one perhaps for a man who variously humiliated his own
medical advisers by ignoring them or turning them into drug
suppliers, who pursued his bizarre health rituals to a point that
devastated and laid waste his own body, and who viewed medical
research as a useful cover for fiddling his tax. But it is,
nonetheless, a monument built to last.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, the institute sold the Hughes Aircraft Co. to General
Motors for $5.2 billion, and for the first time gained control of
its own money and started to support medical research seriously. In
1987, its first president in its born-again mode was forced to
resign after his wife was found to have established a large
unauthorized account at a furniture store.
</P>
<P>
   The institute is now ending its first period of calmer
governance. Under the presidency of Dr. Purnell W. Choppin, its
endowment has grown to $12 billion, giving it $465 million to spend
this fiscal year on biomedical research. Although that is only 5
percent of the National Institutes of Health's grant-giving budget,
the Hughes institute's influence is greater than it may seem
because it supports many of the country's leading researchers.
</P>
<P>
   At first sight, the net effect of the Hughes institute's taking
over support for many top NIH researchers has merely been that the
institutes have been able to finance a bottom tier of researchers
who would not otherwise have made the cut. But the Hughes money
seems to have had a powerful effect on many recipients, freeing
them to take on chancier projects than they would have dared under
the NIH.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Hughes largesse has enabled academic biologists to use
more expensive research methods. ``NIH loses interest in funding
people when they get to $500,000 a year; that's a bit of a glass
ceiling,'' Cech said. Hughes-supported researchers can pay without
blanching at the high costs of maintaining germ-free mouse colonies
or buying Affymetrix chips for analyzing gene expression.
</P>
<P>
   The Hughes institute's new team, Cech and Rubin, are
Hughes-financed researchers. Cech discovered that RNA, a chemical
relative of DNA, can act as a biological catalyst, a finding
pertinent to the origin of life. Rubin, a leading expert on the
laboratory fruitfly, recently helped oversee the decoding of its
entire DNA, or genome. Following a new fashion among scientific
administrators, both intend to work part-time in their labs.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Cech nor Rubin has the medical qualifications that might
be expected for directors of a medical institute. Will it matter
that neither is an M.D.?
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have an impact without having those two little letters
after our names,'' Cech said. Other university biologists are
pleased with their appointment. ``The choice of Cech and Rubin was
brilliant and is applauded by the academic community,'' said Dr.
Arnold J. Levine, president of Rockefeller University.
</P>
<P>
   The two scientists are considering capping the number of the
researchers Hughes will support at perhaps 350, and using any extra
money that becomes available as the endowment grows to finance
special initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   One initiative undertaken by Choppin and his scientific
director, Dr. W. Maxwell Cowan, was to finance high resolution
X-ray crystallography, an especially expensive technique that has
proved invaluable for visualizing the fine structure of important
biological molecules.
</P>
<P>
   Although the NIH has various ways of encouraging new fields of
research, it is often slow to move, whereas the Hughes institute
can act quickly and go in any direction its leaders favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree we should be cognizant about how we can be more
risk-taking than we are,'' Cech said. ``If you have never fallen
down learning to ski, you aren't trying hard enough.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   He cited bioinformatics and functional genomics as two emerging
fields in which the institute might make special investments.
(Bioinformatics is the use of computer programs to analyze the
information in an organism's genome, such as which segments of DNA
specify genes; functional genomics means figuring out what the
genes in a genome do).
</P>
<P>
   Saying he was describing his personal views rather than
established Hughes institute policy, Rubin suggested that the
competition for Hughes research fellowships should be broadened
beyond the present system of university nominations, in which
``politics may not lead to the best candidates being put forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Cech said he had already arranged with Choppin to make Hughes
fellowships transferrable. Until now, Hughes-supported researchers
and universities trying to recruit them have been frustrated by the
so-called ``golden handcuffs'' _ the rule that scientists cannot
take Hughes awards with them.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if that might not lead in a few years to a high
concentration of Hughes researchers at Harvard and Stanford, Cech
said he hoped to preserve the geographic distribution of the
fellowships.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are great things happening in the middle part of the
country, I hope even including Boulder,'' he said. If an imbalance
develops, he added, ``We could have a competition where we say only
places without a Hughes investigatorship could nominate people.''
</P>
<P>
   Having enjoyed an overdue period of normality under Choppin and
Cowan, the Howard Hughes Medical Institute may be taking corners
faster under its new drivers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-99 1838EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
