<HEADER>
A0165 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-STRAVINSKY-BOOK-REVIE     12-27 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STRAVINSKY-BOOK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STRAVINSKY _ A CREATIVE SPRING': SO TOUCHY, AND ALWAYS RECASTING
HIMSELF 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
(lb) 
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shortly before his death in 1929 the impresario Sergei Diaghilev
made an astute observation about Igor Stravinsky, the composer with
whom he had crossed swords regularly about artistic and financial
matters over the previous two decades, yet whose early career was
inextricably bound to Diaghilev's Ballets Russes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is constantly on the move,'' Diaghilev told a friend,
``seeking out at every step how to deny the very thing that he has
been in his previous works.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the impression that Stravinsky himself fostered, but it
was not only his musical past that he sought to deny. A leitmotif
in Stephen Walsh's ``Stravinsky _ A Creative Spring: Russia and
France 1882-1934,'' the first installment of a two-volume
biography, is that as hard as Stravinsky worked on his music, he
worked equally hard to compose and recompose his public persona.
</P>
<P>
   This recomposition, moreover, tended not to be benign. Crucial
aspects of his training and early life, for example, were later
declared to have been meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, although he was a devoted student of Rimsky-Korsakov and
insinuated himself into that composer's family life, he eventually
declared his teacher's works worthless and his influence
negligible. Friends and close collaborators, similarly, were
routinely repositioned as talentless obstructors of his work.
</P>
<P>
   He even repudiated his own artistic ideas, though they were
copiously documented in interviews and correspondence whenever he
had a philosophical change of heart.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that he had spoken passionately about the evocation
of primitive ritual in ``The Rite of Spring'' when the work was
new; once he hit on the absolutist notion that music should be
``objective'' rather than descriptive, and that his music was meant
to express nothing but itself, he insisted that his vividly
pictorial early ballets were pure music, nothing more or less.
</P>
<P>
   As Walsh's book amply demonstrates, Stravinsky's persistent
self-redefinition was an odd and hopeless preoccupation for someone
who had lived his life in the public eye since before he turned 30.
</P>
<P>
   It was inevitable that the contradictions inherent in his
continual recasting would call attention to themselves; indeed,
Stravinsky's recasting of his past, whether through a faulty memory
or outright falsification, has long been evident to readers of his
1934 autobiography and the several volumes of conversations that
Robert Craft, Stravinsky's longtime assistant, published in the
1950s and '60s.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, only since the fall of the Soviet Union has it been
possible to paint a full picture of Stravinsky's early life, thanks
to a trove of documents, memoirs, correspondence and studies not
previously accessible to Western biographers. They throw a harsh
light on Stravinsky's efforts to recreate his past; in particular,
they blow away the dust that Stravinsky kicked over the traces of
his borrowings from Russian folk materials.
</P>
<P>
   The first author to make full use of these materials in an
examination of Stravinsky's musical and personal roots was Richard
Taruskin, whose comprehensive and well-argued ``Stravinsky and the
Russian Traditions'' was published three years ago. But although
there is ample biography in Taruskin's two-volume work, its primary
focus is the music, and at that, its 1,758 pages take the reader
only as far as ``Mavra,'' the opera Stravinsky completed in 1922.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh, a critic and musicologist who teaches at Cardiff
University in Wales, leans heavily on Taruskin's work, and
sometimes takes issue with it (though not as regularly as he
challenges Craft's writings on Stravinsky). But his book is written
for a less specialized audience. There are no musical examples, and
what musical discussion there is mostly avoids technical terms.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the book is by no means unscholarly. There are 132 pages of
footnotes, most of them source references. No quotations and few
assertions pass without one, although quite a few expand upon (or
even update) the findings in Walsh's text.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh is at his most engaging in the early chapters, in which he
provides enough detail about Stravinsky's surroundings _ social
customs as well as mundane details of life _ to give the reader the
flavor of late-19th-century St. Petersburg and the various country
estates where the Stravinsky family spent its summers.
</P>
<P>
   He fills out the family picture expansively as well, although a
genealogical chart would have been helpful to readers less
conversant with Russian names and diminutives.
</P>
<P>
   Often he seems out to take Stravinsky down a peg, although one
can't help feeling that Stravinsky brought this on himself. The
evidence, after all, shows that Stravinsky's sour reminiscences
were often both incorrect and unfair, and Walsh sometimes seems
intent on rescuing the composer's victims. Writing about the degree
to which Stravinsky's parents encouraged his musical activities, he
describes Stravinsky's claim that his parents did not recognize his
talent as ``a calumny against their memory.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh lightens up as Stravinsky's career takes off, although he
never allows the composer to redefine himself or his attitudes
without quoting his earlier (or later) positions.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the second part of the book becomes bogged down with
chronological details. Stravinsky is shown working on a new piece,
revising an old one (to extend its practical use and, therefore,
its earning potential), touring as a conductor or pianist,
squabbling with publishers, collaborators or Diaghilev, or pulling
strings on behalf of his sons, Theodore (a visual artist) and
Soulima (a pianist).
</P>
<P>
   A handful of tantalizing projects that Stravinsky considered but
did not undertake are mentioned _ ``David'' with Jean Cocteau;
incidental music for Shakespeare's ``Antony and Cleopatra,'' as
adapted by Andre Gide; ``Liturgie,'' a sacred work for Diaghilev;
and even a flamenco setting of ``The Barber of Seville.'' But the
nitty-gritty of the creative process is touched on only lightly.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The human side of the story is shown at a distance as well,
particularly after Stravinsky reaches 30. Early correspondence
conveys the tenderness of his relationship with Yekaterina Nosenko,
his first wife (and also his first cousin). But soon that side of
the story becomes merely a catalog of her illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Little of substance is said, for example, about how the frail
and increasingly religious Yekaterina dealt with her husband's open
romance with Vera Sudeykina during the last 20 years of their
marriage. Walsh only guesses that it must have been difficult for
both women.
</P>
<P>
   For that matter, he ascribes Stravinsky's own religious
fixations to feelings of guilt about the peculiarities of his
marital arrangements. That rings hollow: Here is a man who thinks
nothing of writing collaborators out of contracts, jettisoning
friends who are no longer useful and treating colleagues with an
unfeeling abrasiveness and lack of generosity.
</P>
<P>
   He is quoted making dozens of vehement anti-Semitic remarks,
some of them about musicians who had done much on his behalf, and
his response to the rise of Nazism was to write an obsequious
letter to his German agent averring that there were no Jews in his
family tree.
</P>
<P>
   He does not emerge from these pages as a man susceptible to
twinges of conscience. The Stravinsky that Walsh paints was too
self-absorbed and opportunistic for that, supremely creative though
he may have been.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `STRAVINSKY _ A CREATIVE SPRING'
</P>
<P>
   Russia and France 1882-1934
</P>
<P>
   By Stephen Walsh
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 700 pages. Alfred A. Knopf. $35.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
