<HEADLINE>
CURTIS MAYFIELD, 57; CONSCIENCE OF SOUL MUSIC DEAD AT 57 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Drops reference to Steppenwolf as a performer of ``Pusherman,'' in
3rd graf; a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Curtis Mayfield, a ghetto-born poet who became soul music's
social conscience and stayed a spiritual force even after he was
paralyzed in a stage accident in 1990, died Sunday in an Atlanta
hospital. He was 57.
</P>
<P>
   No reason was given for his death. He had been weak for months
and was unable to attend his induction into the Rock and Roll Hall
of Fame in New York in March. Rapper Puff Daddy inducted him at
that event, praising his ``sense of the holy and the sting of the
truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Mayfield, a mainstay of the Chicago vocal group the
Impressions before turning solo, wrote some of R &AMP; B's most famous
songs. Among them are ``People Get Ready'' (which also became the
``Amazing Grace'' of the pop world, sung by everyone from Rod
Stewart to Bob Marley), ``Gypsy Woman,'' and his '70s soundtrack
hits, ``Superfly'' and ``Freddie's Dead,'' which have been sampled
by countless hip-hop artists from Puff Daddy to Ice-T. Mr. Mayfield
also wrote ``Pusherman,'' about the dead-end world of drug
hustling.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Mayfield was a prime musical voice of the civil rights
movement, starting with 1964's ``Keep On Pushing,'' a Top Ten hit
on both R &AMP; B and pop radio stations. His other socially conscious
songs during that era included ``We're a Winner,'' ``This is My
Country,'' and ``Choice of Colors.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Mayfield was a silky-smooth singer whose falsetto was
immediately identifiable on the radio for many years. He reached
his commercial peak in 1972 with the ``Superfly'' soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1942, Mr. Mayfield grew up in Chicago's infamous
Cabrini-Green projects, where he shared one room with his mother
and five siblings. One younger brother was retarded and Mr.
Mayfield took special care of him until the boy died of an enlarged
heart at age 18.
</P>
<P>
   Trained in church singing, Mr. Mayfield took that gospel-infused
sound into the Impressions, where he shared vocal duties with Jerry
Butler. The Impressions had a falling-out which prompted Mr.
Mayfield to turn solo, but they reunited for a memorable 1983 tour
that came to the Berklee Performance Center. The show started an
hour late because Mr. Mayfield had a bad cold and lay sick in his
hotel, but he rallied and gave a mesmerizing performance.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Mayfield was also a poet of the heart, writing such tenderly
beautiful love songs as ``Woman's Got Soul'' and ``I'm So Proud.''
Everything he did showed consummate style and a poet's touch.
</P>
<P>
   The positive thinking that lay at his core was never more
evident than after the freak accident that left him paralyzed in
1990 _ when a lighting truss fell on him during a thunderstorm at a
free Brooklyn concert. He never indulged in self-pity _ and he even
made another album in 1996, ``New World Order,'' recorded while
lying on his back.
</P>
<P>
   The album featured the songs ``Back to Living Again'' and ``Oh
So Beautiful,'' with the verse, ``Never forget the life we live is
oh so beautiful.'' Nominated for two Grammys, it didn't win, but
Eric Clapton, who won three Grammys that year, interrupted his
acceptance speech to say that Mr. Mayfield's album was his personal
favorite of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all human beings, so we can get angry or bitter or mad,
but for me it doesn't last too long,'' Mr. Mayfield told the Globe
when the album came out. ``I'd rather be humble and cry tears of
joy than to take on the stress and burdens of being dogged out and
negative.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Mayfield leaves his wife, Altheida, along with ten children,
two sisters, a brother, and seven grandchildren. Funeral
arrangements have not been announced.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-99 1847EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
