<DOCNO> NYT19991227.0292 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0176 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BROADWAY-NEW-PLAYS-AR     12-27 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROADWAY-NEW-PLAYS-ART-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER BANNER YEAR, NEW STRAIGHT PLAYS NOW MISSING FROM BROADWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The play ``Epic Proportions'' was greeted with mostly
negative reviews three months ago and attracted only modest
audiences, but its closing on Dec. 19 brought a historic moment to
New York theater: for the first time, at least in memory, no
recently written comedy or drama is running on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   The moment won't officially end until mid-January. ``Wrong
Mountain,'' a new play by David Hirson, started previews Monday
night and is to open on Jan. 13, joining a robust Broadway field
dominated by megamusicals. And a couple of other new works are
planned for next year. But it is testimony nonetheless to a steady
erosion in the tradition of the straight play on Broadway. In the
1998-1999 season, 10 new plays opened on Broadway, compared with 22
in 1978-1979 and a high of 30 in 1979-1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anybody cared, they would call it a crisis,'' said
playwright Arthur Miller. ``I think people do care, but they feel
helpless.''
</P>
<P>
   One could see this as an embarrassing moment for Broadway, given
that it may be a stretch to fill the usual category of four
nominees for the Tony Awards in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, some say the decline of new plays _
particularly by Americans _ on Broadway is offset by the vitality
in recent years of Off-Broadway, where this season's hits include
``Dinner With Friends'' and ``Fuddy Meers.'' Every year for the
last five, Off-Broadway has produced the Pulitzer Prize winning
play: ``Wit'' (1999); ``How I Learned to Drive'' (1998); the
musical ``Rent'' (1996), which moved to Broadway; ``The Young Man
From Atlanta'' (1995); and ``Three Tall Women'' (1994). There was
no prize for drama given for 1997.
</P>
<P>
   According to this theory of shifting focus, the nexis of New
York theater has shifted permanently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Times Square is turning into something else _ a
mass-entertainment district _ and that includes the kind of theater
Broadway has now,'' said Ada Louise Huxtable, an architecture
critic and historian. ``I don't think that's all bad, as long as
you don't lose what matters.'' What matters, she said, is that new
work is still percolating elsewhere in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Among the staples in the Theater District now are solo shows
like ``Dame Edna''; splashy musicals like ``The Lion King''; dance
shows like ``Fosse''; revivals like ``The Price,'' ``Kiss Me,
Kate'' and ``Chicago''; and those long-running phenomena ``Cats,''
``Les Miserables,'' ``Miss Saigon'' and ``The Phantom of the
Opera.''
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically perhaps, this season's play vacuum comes when
business on Broadway is booming; ticket sales are brisk, and
theaters are booked. What's more, just last year there was a
healthy crop of straight plays on Broadway. But those were either
new plays written by foreigners (``Closer,'' ``The Weir'') imported
after successes in London and Dublin or revivals like ``Death of a
Salesman'' and ``The Iceman Cometh,'' featuring Hollywood stars.
</P>
<P>
   With plays now costing $1 million to $2 million to produce on
Broadway, and mass audiences normally less attracted to them than
to musicals, many Broadway producers are steering clear of new
plays. Musicals are more expensive to put on ($5 million to $12
million, especially now that corporations like Disney have upped
the ante), but they are more of a reliable draw.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little harder every year,'' said Todd Haimes, artistic
director of the nonprofit Roundabout Theater Co., which produced
``The Rainmaker,'' with Woody Harrelson, on Broadway this season.
``It's hard to see right now what's going to turn that around. It's
so expensive to produce these plays, and it's so difficult to
recoup.''
</P>
<P>
   As for why audiences might be staying away from straight plays
on Broadway, theater professionals offer several reasons: a ticket
price of $80 for the best seats; the decline in school programs
that introduce students to the dramatic arts; the more hip appeal
of unconventional theater downtown, and the allure of competition
like television, films and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Given this environment, one might ask why Dodger Theatricals has
chosen to raise $1.5 million to bring ``Wrong Mountain,'' a new
straight play with no stars and no out-of-town tryout, to Broadway.
``Beyond high-mindedness and good-deed doing and scoring spiritual
points, I suppose there is some kind of testicular bravado,'' said
Michael David, the president of the company, which has produced
shows like ``Footloose'' and ``Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   David said he was bucking the trend because he believed that the
play, a satire about the theater world, would find an audience.
Nevertheless, the venture is unusual for his company. Dodger has
done more shows on Broadway than anyone else in the last 10 years,
he said, but only one drama (``Hamlet,'' featuring Ralph Fiennes).
``I do think it becomes ever more daunting,'' David said.
``Broadway has become so dangerous, so unwelcome, that one has to
second-guess.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to ``Wrong Mountain,'' the other new plays to open
later this season are ``Taller Than a Dwarf,'' a comedy by Elaine
May featuring film stars Parker Posey and Matthew Broderick, and
``Copenhagen,'' by British playwright Michael Frayn. Producer
Emanuel Azenberg said he planned to present ``The Enigma
Variations,'' a new play by Eric-Emmanuel Schmitt, on Broadway this
spring starring Donald Sutherland, although he has yet to announce
it.
</P>
<P>
   The other plays expected are revivals of Tom Stoppard's ``The
Real Thing'' and Sam Shepard's ``True West.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   With a bit of stretching one could argue that other works could
qualify as new plays. These include Julie Taymor's new version of
her 1996 production of Carlo Gozzi's ``Green Bird'' and Arthur
Miller's ``Ride Down Mount Morgan,'' to open this season, and Noel
Coward's ``Waiting in the Wings,'' which opened this month. The
latter two have never been produced in New York, though both were
written years ago (Miller's in 1991 and Coward's in 1960).
</P>
<P>
   New musicals are better represented on Broadway. ``James Joyce's
`The Dead''' recently moved to the Belasco Theater from
Off-Broadway. ``Marie Christine'' is now at the Vivian Beaumont
Theater at Lincoln Center, which is large enough for its
productions to be eligible for Tony Awards and is therefore
considered a ``Broadway house.'' ``The Wild Party'' is to open this
spring. The dance shows ``Contact'' and ``Swing'' also qualify as
new musicals.
</P>
<P>
   The last season raised hopes that nonmusicals were poised for a
rebirth. It was often hard to get a ticket to plays like ``Death of
a Salesman,'' ``The Iceman Cometh'' and ``The Blue Room.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The audience came,'' said Azenberg, who produced ``Iceman.''
``They came in droves.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``Iceman'' featured Kevin Spacey (and the production made a
healthy profit with a steep top ticket price of $100). Similarly
``Salesman'' offered Brian Dennehy and ``Blue Room,'' Nicole
Kidman. And most stars agree to grace productions only for limited
engagements.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, whose plays have seen a steady stream of Broadway
revivals, suggested that leaning on Hollywood does not bode well
for Broadway. ``Being a theater that relies completely on star
draws is, generally speaking, not in a healthy condition,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Azenberg said he was nervous about bringing ``Enigma'' to
Broadway this spring. ``We're terrified, absolutely terrified,
because I have no guideposts anymore,'' he said. ``We don't know
that there is an audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years ago, Azenberg said, he had six plays on Broadway,
including Athol Fugard's ``Master Harold ... and the Boys'' and Tom
Stoppard's ``Real Thing.'' ``Now,'' he said, ``I'm struggling to
get one on.''
</P>
<P>
   Haimes suggested that there might not in fact be an audience,
that wordy, often cerebral plays can no longer compete with flashy
alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mass audience that's needed to make a commercial
production successful is used to not having to think as much
because of television and because of education problems
nationally,'' he said. ``Their idea of going to the theater is
having an experience, seeing musicals and plays like `Stomp' and
`Thwak.' Plays that require more work have trouble attracting a
mass audience.'' (``Stomp'' and ``Thwak,'' like the long-running
``Blue Man Group,'' are more performance pieces than narrative
works.)
</P>
<P>
   Some theater professionals suggest that tastes for such fare
have begun to dictate content. If people are flocking to see
``Beauty and the Beast'' and ``Jekyll and Hyde,'' the thinking
goes, why not try to replicate such remunerative offerings?
</P>
<P>
   ``Producers are producing plays they think have a better chance
of breaking even,'' Haimes said. ``That is affecting the product
that is ending up in their theaters.''
</P>
<P>
   One could argue that Broadway's current offerings are a
throwback to the days of vaudeville. And several Broadway producers
have talked about plans for summoning that era with a Broadway Hall
of Fame at the Lyceum Theater that would feature videotaped
segments of current Broadway shows as something of a tasting menu
for tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Some argue that ticket prices may be keeping people away,
especially young, unseasoned theatergoers. And several producers
have made an effort to set aside tickets at lower prices to attract
this population. Azenberg said 150 seats at $20 each were set aside
for performances of ``Iceman.''
</P>
<P>
   Others argue that money is not the main obstacle, since the
economy is so strong, and people are spending the same amount or
more on other diversions.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile at theaters downtown and west of Eighth Avenue, where
ticket prices are considerably lower, new theaters are being
created to accommodate the demand for stages.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plays have migrated to a different place,'' said George A.
Wachtel, president of Audience Research and Analysis, a marketing
group that specializes in the arts.
</P>
<P>
   And new audiences have followed them. Whereas Off-Broadway once
connoted experimental, offbeat work, it is attracting more people
from uptown and out of town. In 1997 non-New Yorkers amounted to 25
percent of the Off-Broadway audience, up from 7 percent in 1981,
Wachtel said. That figure is now close to what Broadway's
out-of-town audience amounted to in 1980: 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Off-Broadway is starting to approach where Broadway was 20
years ago,'' Wachtel said. ``And the line between the two is
diminishing.''
</P>
<P>
   Others say it is difficult to attract top talent to
lower-paying, lower-profile Off-Broadway productions: directors and
designers as well as actors.
</P>
<P>
   Some theater professionals expressed concern that even Broadway
had suffered from a long-term brain drain to movies and television.
``It completely depresses me because I think these forces are
driving artists out of the theater,'' Haimes said. ``There is no
doubt that some of these people would have been the next Arthur
Miller, would have been the next Tennessee Williams, and we'll
never know that.''
</P>
<P>
   Some producers seem to be looking for ways to develop new
audiences through school programs. And occasionally talk bubbles up
about possible new ways to finance the Broadway theater, though no
workable plan has emerged.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Broadway veterans remain disheartened. ``Time was when
New York theater was the one the British looked to for
inspiration,'' Miller said. ``Now Broadway theater is suddenly the
place where plays go to die. And it's too bad.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
