<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERU-FUJIMORI-490&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT OF PERU WILL RUN FOR A THIRD TERM 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina _ President Alberto Fujimori of Peru
announced his candidacy for an unprecedented third term Monday,
arguing that his country needed him to guarantee an end to
terrorism and to complete the country's economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori's announcement capped four years of legal and political
maneuvering to overcome a constitutional prohibition against three
consecutive presidential terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not want to return to the past,'' he said in an address
to the nation. ``That is the reason for my candidacy. Another
option may have been preferable but there are no alternatives.''
</P>
<P>
   The son of Japanese immigrants, Fujimori, 61, shocked the
political establishment by winning election in 1990 and was easily
re-elected five years later. During his decade of rule, he has
brought the country's traditional hyperinflation under control,
greatly reduced the cocaine trade and negotiated a settlement to a
border conflict with neighboring Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
   His enduring popularity, however, comes from the retreat of two
guerrilla groups that once controlled wide swaths of territory but
now can do little more than launch small, isolated attacks. During
his speech on Monday, Fujimori pledged to ``extinguish every
vestige of terrorism from the country'' during his next term.
</P>
<P>
   But Fujimori's often autocratic methods _ including replacing
the Congress and the Supreme Court by decree in 1992, and taking a
television station away from a critic of his government _ have
attracted widespread criticism among human rights groups. Most
recently, critics have accused him of manipulating and even
replacing judges and election officials who opposed his re-election
bid.
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution established in 1993 prohibits a third
presidential term. But three years later, supporters of Fujimori
who control the Congress pushed through a law that excluded him
from the prohibition since his first term began before the document
was written. Over the last two years, the Congress dismissed three
senior judges who opposed the law and then blocked a popular
referendum intended to block his re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Polls this year have shown that as many as two-thirds of the
voters do not favor a third presidential term. But Fujimori's
popularity has steadily increased through the year as the economy
recovered. He now appears to have a good chance of winning a
first-round victory in April.
</P>
<P>
   A poll published earlier this month showed Fujimori would win 46
percent of the vote. Running far behind in second place with 17
percent was Luis Castaneda Lossio, former director of the Peruvian
Social Security Institute and a former key aide to Fujimori. In
third place was Alberto Andrade, the mayor of Lima, with 13
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, which had a margin of error of plus or minus 4.5
percent, showed that Fujimori would easily defeat either opponent
if the splintered opposition were to unite.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   After suffering a recession in 1998, the Peruvian economy is
expected to grow by about 2.5 percent this year based on increased
manufacturing, improved fishing conditions and higher metal prices.
Fujimori's standing in the polls has also been helped by the arrest
of several important Shining Path terrorist leaders, which
underscored the president's record of having pacified the country.
</P>
<P>
   And in an effort to soften his image, Fujimori freed 12 people
from prison over the weekend who had been prosecuted in
anti-terrorism courts that did not allow their lawyers to
cross-examine witnesses, but who were later found innocent by a
government investigative panel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
