<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0185 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-OBITUARY-MAYFIELD-SUB     12-27 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-MAYFIELD-SUB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CURTIS MAYFIELD, 57; CONSCIENCE OF SOUL MUSIC DEAD AT 57 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Drops reference to Steppenwolf as a performer of ``Pusherman,'' in
3rd graf; a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Curtis Mayfield, a ghetto-born poet who became soul music's
social conscience and stayed a spiritual force even after he was
paralyzed in a stage accident in 1990, died Sunday in an Atlanta
hospital. He was 57.
</P>
<P>
   No reason was given for his death. He had been weak for months
and was unable to attend his induction into the Rock and Roll Hall
of Fame in New York in March. Rapper Puff Daddy inducted him at
that event, praising his ``sense of the holy and the sting of the
truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Mayfield, a mainstay of the Chicago vocal group the
Impressions before turning solo, wrote some of R &AMP; B's most famous
songs. Among them are ``People Get Ready'' (which also became the
``Amazing Grace'' of the pop world, sung by everyone from Rod
Stewart to Bob Marley), ``Gypsy Woman,'' and his '70s soundtrack
hits, ``Superfly'' and ``Freddie's Dead,'' which have been sampled
by countless hip-hop artists from Puff Daddy to Ice-T. Mr. Mayfield
also wrote ``Pusherman,'' about the dead-end world of drug
hustling.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Mayfield was a prime musical voice of the civil rights
movement, starting with 1964's ``Keep On Pushing,'' a Top Ten hit
on both R &AMP; B and pop radio stations. His other socially conscious
songs during that era included ``We're a Winner,'' ``This is My
Country,'' and ``Choice of Colors.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Mayfield was a silky-smooth singer whose falsetto was
immediately identifiable on the radio for many years. He reached
his commercial peak in 1972 with the ``Superfly'' soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1942, Mr. Mayfield grew up in Chicago's infamous
Cabrini-Green projects, where he shared one room with his mother
and five siblings. One younger brother was retarded and Mr.
Mayfield took special care of him until the boy died of an enlarged
heart at age 18.
</P>
<P>
   Trained in church singing, Mr. Mayfield took that gospel-infused
sound into the Impressions, where he shared vocal duties with Jerry
Butler. The Impressions had a falling-out which prompted Mr.
Mayfield to turn solo, but they reunited for a memorable 1983 tour
that came to the Berklee Performance Center. The show started an
hour late because Mr. Mayfield had a bad cold and lay sick in his
hotel, but he rallied and gave a mesmerizing performance.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Mayfield was also a poet of the heart, writing such tenderly
beautiful love songs as ``Woman's Got Soul'' and ``I'm So Proud.''
Everything he did showed consummate style and a poet's touch.
</P>
<P>
   The positive thinking that lay at his core was never more
evident than after the freak accident that left him paralyzed in
1990 _ when a lighting truss fell on him during a thunderstorm at a
free Brooklyn concert. He never indulged in self-pity _ and he even
made another album in 1996, ``New World Order,'' recorded while
lying on his back.
</P>
<P>
   The album featured the songs ``Back to Living Again'' and ``Oh
So Beautiful,'' with the verse, ``Never forget the life we live is
oh so beautiful.'' Nominated for two Grammys, it didn't win, but
Eric Clapton, who won three Grammys that year, interrupted his
acceptance speech to say that Mr. Mayfield's album was his personal
favorite of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all human beings, so we can get angry or bitter or mad,
but for me it doesn't last too long,'' Mr. Mayfield told the Globe
when the album came out. ``I'd rather be humble and cry tears of
joy than to take on the stress and burdens of being dogged out and
negative.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Mayfield leaves his wife, Altheida, along with ten children,
two sisters, a brother, and seven grandchildren. Funeral
arrangements have not been announced.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-99 1921EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991227.0302 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0186 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-HURRICANE-MOVIE-ART-2     12-27 1282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-MOVIE-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: police record.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The true nightmare for both men began after the early-morning
shotgun and pistol-fire slayings of two men and a woman in the
Lafayette Grill, a Paterson bar. The murders occurred only hours
after a black tavern owner had been fatally shot by a white man in
Paterson, and the police immediately theorized that racial
retaliation was the motive for the Lafayette Grill attack.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the murders Carter, then 29, and Artis, 21, were
picked up in Carter's white Dodge, which the police said resembled
the getaway car. The movie, however, disregards vital elements the
police used against Carter: the finding of a shotgun and a bullet
in the Dodge and the murder of the black tavern owner.
</P>
<P>
   Except for being black, neither Carter nor Artis resembled the
original descriptions of the killers, and they were released after
passing lie detector tests.
</P>
<P>
   Three months later, however, the two men were indicted based on
statements by two petty criminals, Alfred P. Bello and Arthur D.
Bradley, two white men who admitted that they had been committing a
burglary near the Lafayette Grill and said that they had seen
Carter and Artis emerge with guns in their hands.
</P>
<P>
   At a trial in 1967 the prosecution offered no motive for the
murders. Bello and Bradley were the only witnesses who identified
Carter and Artis, and their testimony was decisive in the
convictions and the imposition of life sentences.
</P>
<P>
   All appeals failed. By 1973 the penniless Carter's prospects for
a new trial seemed doomed. Nevertheless, Carter, a charismatic
figure inside prison as well as outside, enlisted help from Fred W.
Hogan, an investigator for the New Jersey public defender's office,
and Richard Solomon, a freelance writer. On his own time Hogan
searched for evidence while Solomon rekindled interest by
establishing a minuscule defense committee and by soliciting
journalists to write about Carter's plight. In 1973 and 1974 Hogan
and this reporter tracked down Bello and Bradley, and both men
separately recanted their identifications of Carter and Artis. They
asserted that Lt. Vincent DeSimone, the lead detective in the case,
and other investigators, some of whom made racist slurs, had
pressured them into incriminating Carter and Artis. The lies were
in exchange for lenient sentences in their own crimes and the lure
of a $10,000 reward.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times published front-page articles about the
recantations and about other questionable evidence used by the
prosecution. Overnight Carter became an international cause
celebre, with civil rights leaders, politicians, writers, and
entertainment figures joining his defense committee. Bob Dylan
supported Carter in his song ``Hurricane'' (which is used in the
new movie).
</P>
<P>
   Based on the recantations and the concealment of promises to the
prosecution's main witnesses, the New Jersey Supreme Court
overturned the guilty verdicts. But in 1976 at a second trial
prosecutors resuscitated an old theory, charging that Carter and
Artis had exacted racial revenge for the earlier murder of the
black tavern owner.
</P>
<P>
   Bello, in a surprise twist, resurfaced to recant his
recantation, testifying as the only prosecution witness who placed
Carter and Artis at the murder scene.
</P>
<P>
   After nine months of freedom Carter and Artis were found guilty,
cast back into prison and deserted by most of the celebrities and
civil rights figures. Still, the principal defense lawyers, Myron
Beldock, Lewis Steel and Leon Friedman of New York City, who worked
for a decade without payment, persisted in unearthing evidence that
the prosecution had concealed at the second trial.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous appeals over nine years in New Jersey courts failed.
But when the issues were heard for the first time in federal court,
a judge in 1985 overturned the convictions on constitutional
grounds, saying the prosecution had ``fatally infected the trial''
by resorting, without proof, to the racial revenge theory and had
withheld evidence that disproved the identifications made by Bello,
the star prosecution witness.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988 the U.S. Supreme Court upheld the appeal, and after 22
years all accusations against Carter and Artis were dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   In the film the two trials are confusingly compressed into a
brief courtroom sentencing scene with Carter protesting that he had
been convicted by an all-white jury. (In reality the first jury was
all white; the second included two elderly blacks.)
</P>
<P>
   Many pivotal scenes revolve around Carter's relationship with
members of a secretive Canadian commune, especially a young black
man, Lesra Martin, who befriended him in the later years of his
imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   In the film the young Martin and the commune revive a supposedly
despairing Carter's faith in himself and in his quest for freedom.
They are depicted as demon sleuths who uncover vital evidence
including a secret diary kept by an investigator, a forged police
document and incontestable proof that Carter's car was not the
get-away vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   These incidents are fairy tales. All essential evidence
concerning constitutional violations, manipulated witnesses and
prosecutorial misconduct was found by defense lawyers. The film
concocts suspenseful encounters _ unmentioned in the Canadians' own
book, ``Lazarus and the Hurricane,'' nor reported elsewhere _ in
which commune members are menaced by the reincarnated Javert and
narrowly escape death.
</P>
<P>
   Carter's lawyers do credit the Canadians with extensive
paralegal work that spared them hundreds of hours of research and
expenses. In an authorized biography, ``Hurricane,'' by James S.
Hirsch, to be published next in January by Houghton Mifflin, Carter
says he instantly bonded with Martin and was indebted to the
Canadians for spending $400,000 _ mainly on living expenses for
themselves and him _ before and after his release.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, in an interview, said he had little control over the
screenplay. He added that he had not objected to the description of
the Canadians' role because of his gratitude for their moral and
financial support.
</P>
<P>
   Missing from the film are the recantations by Bello and Bradley,
the critical disclosures that reopened a dead case and figured
prominently in Carter's ultimate exoneration. Nor is there an
indication of the support Carter received from relatives and
friends long before the affluent Canadians arrived. While Carter's
affection for Martin is the keystone of the movie, viewers have
little sense of the son and a daughter with whom he has had a
distant relationship even out of prison. There is only the merest
suggestion of the loyalty of his first wife.
</P>
<P>
   The film closes with a courtroom scene signifying the judicial
defeat of evil, attributed to the indomitable Canadians. It fades
out with a stirring (but invented) speech by Carter about injustice
and his embracing of Martin, and Lisa Peters, the leader of the
Canadians.
</P>
<P>
   A feel-good screen afterword notes that Carter lives in Canada
and runs an organization that seeks to correct judicial wrongs, and
that Martin has become a lawyer in Canada. Left unsaid is both
men's eventual disenchantment with the commune and its treatment of
them.
</P>
<P>
   After his release Carter married Ms. Peters. But he soon ended
all relations with her and other commune members, asserting in his
biography that they patronized him as a ``trophy horse'' whose main
purpose was to raise money for the group. He further complains that
the commune tried to control his life, with members escorting him
everywhere and censoring his words.
</P>
<P>
   As for Martin, he was expelled. His crime: dating a woman
without the commune's permission.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-99 1921EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
