<DOCNO> NYT19991227.0303 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0187 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-MILITIA-Y2K-HNS &LR;      12-27 1499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILITIA-Y2K-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MILITIA PLANNED NEW YEAR'S ATTACK ON PROPANE TANKS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LANCE WILLIAMS  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The militiamen called them the ``twin sisters,''
giant steel tanks in rural Sacramento County that hold enough
liquid propane to immolate every living thing for five miles if
they were to explode.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a year, a loose-knit band of survivalists, illegal
firearms traders and right-wing revolutionaries allegedly plotted
to detonate the tanks.
</P>
<P>
   But one of the conspirators turned out to be a shadowy informant
whom the FBI had recruited with money and the hope of leniency on a
weapons charge.
</P>
<P>
   And in the end, a series of FBI raids allegedly thwarted a San
Joaquin County militia's plan for a fiery holocaust near the
Sacramento suburb of Elk Grove.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 3, agents arrested Kevin Patterson, 42, of Camino, an
alleged bomb-maker and methamphetamine ``cook'' with ties to
paramilitary groups in other states, and Charles Dennis Kiles, 49,
of Placerville, a suspected militia commander who had been
convicted on an illegal firearms charge. They also seized a trove
of bomb-making chemicals and weapons parts from Patterson's house,
court records show.
</P>
<P>
   Both were part of a self-styled militia that hoped the new year
would bring the breakdown of vital public services throughout the
nation, according to a court affidavit filed by the FBI and the
U.S. Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms.
</P>
<P>
   They planned to lead an armed overthrow of the U.S. government
in the chaos and civil unrest they believed would follow potential
computer failures linked to the date change, said FBI agent Michael
LeMieux and ATF agent R. Graham Barlowe.
</P>
<P>
   The two men have been indicted on federal firearms charges. At
least three other people who discussed the abortive attack on the
propane tanks, including the informant, have not been charged with
any crime, records in U.S. District Court in Sacramento show.
</P>
<P>
   The agents' affidavit reports connections between Patterson and
such right-wing groups as the Montana Freemen, who faced down
hundreds of FBI agents in an armed siege near Billings in 1996; and
the Republic of Texas, which confronted the Texas Rangers in a 1997
standoff.
</P>
<P>
   The document indicates that in years since the bombing of the
Oklahoma City federal building in 1995, the militia movement's
stridently anti-government ideology has become infused with
apocalyptic predictions about the collapse of American society with
the arrival of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The affidavit also gives a glimpse into the workings of a
federal anti-terrorist task force that for more than five years has
been investigating militias for weapons and bomb-making violations.
</P>
<P>
   The informant told the authorities that one key player in the
militia unit was Kiles, described as the gun-toting former
commander of the Sacramento County militia, a paramilitary group
that after the Oklahoma City bombing.
</P>
<P>
   According to the affidavit, Kiles had been on probation since
pleading guilty to felony possession of an assault rifle in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The informant said Kiles was a longtime friend of Patterson's,
who had spent more than three years with rightist groups in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   According to the affidavit, a police officer who had infiltrated
Texas militia units identified Patterson as a methamphetamine
``cook'' and bomb-maker for the Texas Constitutional Militia and
then for the Republic of Texas, a separatist group known for its
standoff against the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, members of the group were arrested in connection
with an alleged plot to assassinate President Clinton and Attorney
General Janet Reno with cactus needles dipped in either the AIDS
virus or anthrax poison, according to news reports.
</P>
<P>
   By the informant's account, the militiamen had been mulling an
attack on Elk Grove's Suburban Propane storage facility since about
June 1998, court files show.
</P>
<P>
   He said the idea might have been hatched while Patterson and
Donald K. Rudolph, 42, reputed leader of the San Joaquin Militia,
were in Billings, Mont., to scout the Yellowstone County Jail as
part of an ultimately abandoned plan to help the Montana Freemen
escape, the affidavit says. Rudolph, a heavy equipment operator for
the California Department of Transportation, was later arrested and
imprisoned for possession of a machine gun, according to court
records.
</P>
<P>
   After his return from Montana, the informant said, Patterson
added other prospective targets: the California Aqueduct and what
he called the ``movie theater,'' giant television transmission
towers in Walnut Grove, east of Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, the affidavit says, the informant kept agents
apprised of Patterson's plans.
</P>
<P>
   According to the affidavit, members of another right-wing fringe
group called the Nevada Freedom Coalition helped Patterson get a
mail-order shipment of four pounds of red phosphorus, a chemical
that can be used to make both methamphetamine and explosives.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In September, in a wiretapped phone call with an alleged Nevada
survivalist named Curk Cave, Patterson was overhead in an extended
discussion of ``cooking the turkey at the wrong temperature.''
</P>
<P>
   The agents thought the men were talking in code and that
Patterson had been heating fertilizer in an oven to remake it into
explosives, a method also used by the terrorists who blew up the
World Trade Center in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, to the informant, and to two undercover FBI men who
befriended him at gun shows, and in wiretapped phone calls to
friends, Patterson increasingly shared his notions about the year
2000 computer glitch.
</P>
<P>
   According to the affidavit, Patterson had stockpiled a four-
month supply of food and water to tide him over during the
disruptions he was certain would follow the dawn of the new
century.
</P>
<P>
   He planned to ``go camping'' in late December and stay in the
woods until mid-January, he said. Some of his friends were building
bunkers on remote desert property, burying sea-going shipping
containers, electrifying them with a generator and stockpiling guns
and ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson assumed that the government would be forced to ration
food and gasoline because of breakdowns in the distribution net and
that mass arrests would result.
</P>
<P>
   In phone calls, he and Cave, his survivalist pal, swapped Y2K
gossip: the Air National Guard was supposedly being trained to
``corral, handle and transport detainees,'' as Cave put it, while
the Army would go door to door confiscating personal firearms.
</P>
<P>
   In other conversations they talked about ``Waco, Pat Buchanan
and a blood supply problem in Canada,'' the FBI noted; at one
point, Patterson said he avoided using supermarket discount cards
because he feared having his name entered in a ``satanic
database.''
</P>
<P>
   In June, FBI agents began surveillance of Patterson, tailing him
as he drove a rental car from Placerville to San Francisco and back
through the San Joaquin Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson seemed to know he was being followed. He made sudden
U-turns and route changes, and at one point stopped and confronted
a motorist he seemingly suspected of tailing him.
</P>
<P>
   After that, agents got a warrant to use a mobile tracking
device. In July, they tracked his rental car on a 500-mile, 24-hour
trip to Fallon, Nev., where Ronald Franklin Brown, 58, a member of
the Nevada Freedom Coalition, lived in a bunker-like compound
littered with military hardware. Brown has not been charged with
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   The agents were not always able to learn where he was going, but
often Patterson seemed bent on buying illegal firearms or
industrial equipment that might help him make a bomb, the affidavit
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In August, agents inspected Suburban Propane's sprawling Elk
Grove storage yard and made a sobering discovery: security was
``minimal at best'' around the two big tanks, which contained more
than 24 million gallons of pressurized liquefied propane.
</P>
<P>
   The agents saw that it would be easy for the militiamen to enter
the unfenced yard and overpower or slip by security guards.
</P>
<P>
   Concerns increased after the FBI commissioned a ``threat
assessment'' study by scientists at the Lawrence Livermore
Laboratory. They concluded that a ``small explosive device'' could
set off a vast fire at the propane yard.
</P>
<P>
   An explosion near either of the twin sisters likely would cause
a ``sympathetic reaction'' that would blow up the other tower,
along with all the propane-laden trucks and rail cars parked
nearby, the scientists concluded.
</P>
<P>
   The results would be catastrophic: a firestorm that would arc as
far as 8 miles across farmlands and suburban subdivisions, killing
50 percent of all living things 5 miles from ground zero.
</P>
<P>
   After the visit, the place was fenced, and security was beefed
up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
