u s BC-BKN-CELTICS-BOS &LR;      12-27 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELTICS ON A NO-PLAYOFF STREAK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ As bad as pro basketball has been in Boston
the last six seasons, no one ever guessed that you would be able to
say the following about the Celtics: They own the longest current
streak of non-playoff seasons (four and counting) in the Atlantic
Division.
</P>
<P>
   The Wizards/Bullets were swept away by the Bulls in 1997, but
they were there. John Calipari's Nets made a brief appearance at
the postseason party before also being swept away by the Michael
Jordan Company in 1998. The Magic, Heat, and 76ers made the
playoffs last season. But the Celtics haven't come close to the
playoffs since they last left them _ 1995 _ in the final year of
the Boston Garden's existence.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, only one team in the entire Eastern Conference, the
Raptors, has a playoff absence similar to Boston's. But if Vince
Carter, the Raptors' creative leaper, continues to find loopholes
in the laws of gravity, Toronto's playoff path will be opened this
season.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is annoying to the Celtics. It's like a kid who has
never been to Disney World listening to everyone else talk about
their visit. It may be overrated but _ so what? _ it still would be
nice to say you have been. The Celtics desperately want to make the
playoffs. You can sense that from talking with Rick Pitino, Antoine
Walker, or Paul Pierce. But The Streak will reach five seasons if
the team can't rid itself of a recurring problem.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, the Celtics play as though they are afraid to leave
the house. They have a video specialist and shot specialist on
staff. They might want to consider hiring a hypnotist who can find
out the root of their road phobia. At the FleetCenter, they are one
of the most competitive teams in basketball. On the road? You could
gather the bunch you play with at the local Y, put them against the
Celtics, and _ we're not saying you'd win _ you'd have to like your
chances in the last two minutes. The Celtics are so unstable away
from home that you almost root for them to go through road rage so
they can snap out of it.
</P>
<P>
   Celtics at home: 10-5.
</P>
<P>
   Celtics away from home: 1-10 (including 10 losses in a row).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame, because we're actually pretty good this year,''
Walker said. ``If I knew what the problem was, I'd tell you. It
seems like guys get hot against us. Unknown guys play against us on
the road and have career nights.''
</P>
<P>
   As Walker said, he would tell if he knew. So it's not surprising
that he revealed only part of the problem. When the Celtics lost to
the Clippers Sunday, the Unknown Theory was valid. Only hard-core
NBA fans outside of Greater Los Angeles know about the talents of
Tyrone Nesby. And not many people would look at 260-pound Maurice
Taylor and conclude that he is most comfortable away from the
basket, taking jump shots. Taylor impressed the Staples Center
crowd a few times by dribbling behind his back and between his
legs, as if Sacramento Kings point guard Jason Williams had jumped
into his body and was secretly controlling his movements.
</P>
<P>
   But anonymous players aren't the only problem for Boston. ``If
we make our free throws in Philadelphia, we win that game,'' Pitino
said. If they don't have a phantom call go against them in Chicago;
if they don't blow a 14-point lead in Atlanta; if they make a big
play or two in New York . . .
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics know they can afford to be mediocre on the road.
They can even get away with being far below average. What they
cannot be is what they have been, and that is embarrassing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to win the next two games,'' Walker said. ``We have
to. If we win these next two games, we'll be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   He was reminded that the next two games are against the Kings
Tuesday night at Arco Arena and against the Nuggets Thursday at
Pepsi Arena. Both teams are tough to beat when they are at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care,'' Walker said. ``We need these.''
</P>
<P>
   The games seem to be more urgent when you glance at the
standings. The Bulls are clearly the worst team in the East and in
all of basketball, so the Celtics won't descend to that level. But
the teams ahead of the Bulls, New Jersey and Washington, have 10
wins; the Celtics have 11. So if the Celtics can't win the next two
games, they might find themselves at the bottom of the Atlantic or
very close to it when they return to Boston on New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   But that's going too far ahead. First, the Celtics play the
Kings. As we all know, Sacramento is not close to North Station.
So, what to do about this away-from-home stage fright?
</P>
<P>
   ``Get enough rest at night?'' Danny Fortson said with a shrug.
</P>
<P>
   If that's what is bothering this team, the Celtics should win
this game by 20 points. Let's just say that the lights usually
don't stay on late in Sacramento. Anyway, Fortson has a point. It's
better to rest now when there are games to play. That's better than
the involuntary rest that comes in the spring when you are sent
home for not making the playoffs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
