<SLUG> BC-MASDAQ-MARKET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASDAQ SETS A RECORD, DESPITE SELL-OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Nasdaq stock exchange topped out at its highest level ever
Monday, despite a sharp post-Christmas sell-off in Internet
commerce stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index, loaded with Internet-related stocks,
closed at 3,975.38, up 5.94. The index has now set seven
consecutive closing records. Monday, though, it was down for most
of the day, as Internet retailers took a beating.
</P>
<P>
   The slump may have been kicked off by BancBoston Robertson
Stephens &AMP; Co. analyst Lauren Cooks Levitan's decision to cut her
rating on eToys, one of the best-known on-line retailers, from
``buy'' to ``long-term attractive,'' based on concerns customers
might be dissatisfied with eToys's service.
</P>
<P>
   Another possible factor was a report from PC Data Inc., a
Reston, Va., market research firm. It said that on-line sales the
week before Christmas reached just $884 million, compared to over
$1.2 billion the week before.
</P>
<P>
   Investors may have used both these reports as an excuse to cash
in some of their e-commerce shares. For example, eToys fell 5 to 25
15/16. Amazon.com, the biggest Web-based store, fell 8 7/8 to 81
1/8; the popular Web auction service eBay dropped 8 5/16 to 134.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, analysts still think Web retailers turned in a
strong performance. ``I think it was a phenomenal e-commerce
holiday season,'' said Jill Frankle of Gomez Advisors in Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   Her optimism is shared by Carrie Johnson, an e-commerce watcher
at Forrester Research in Cambridge, Mass. Forrester, she said, is
standing by its prediction of $8 billion in retail Internet sales
in the last quarter of 1999, with $4 billion in Christmas sales.
She also estimated that 7 million more people will have shopped on
line this holiday season than in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   While individual retailers have yet to release sales figures,
there are some positive signs. Yahoo Inc. said sales on its
shopping site were five times higher than during the 1998 holiday
season. As a result, Yahoo helped counter the decline of other
Nasdaq e-commerce issues. Yahoo shares soared 12 3/8 to 415.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average fell 14.68 to 11,391.08, after
rising as much as 69 points earlier in the day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
