<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REEVES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons win gives Reeves a reason to smile
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dan Reeves was several minutes early to his Monday
news conference, the first sign something was different. Reeves
usually is on time or, after a couple miserable losses when tape
review dragged on, a little late.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons had engaged in a number of unusual things a day
earlier, when they beat the Cardinals 37-14.
</P>
<P>
   The victory led to an obvious question for the coach of 4-11
team. If your team could play so well once, why not more often?
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to keep it in perspective,'' Reeves said. ``We were
playing a team that was really banged up and beat up.'' The
Cardinals (6-9) were so beat up that in the second half, linebacker
Patrick Sapp, a quarterback at Clemson, played defensive end.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Falcons deserve credit for playing well.
They ran the ball a season-high 163 rushing yards, held Arizona to
77 rushing yards, and won the turnover battle 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday was the first game all season the Falcons did not give up
at least one run of 14 or more yards. Arizona's best was an
8-yarder.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly, the victory stemmed from the timing of when the
Falcons were able to ``catch'' an opponent, Reeves said. The
Falcons also had three key offensive players return from injury:
Chris Chancler completed 14 of 23 passes for 230 yards and a
touchdown, Byron Hanspart ran 26 times for a career-high 102 yards
and Tim Dwight caught three passes for 52 yards. Last season, the
Falcons went 14-2 against a weak schedule. This season, their
opponents are a combined 114-96, and have included playoff teams
St. Louis (13-2) twice, Jacksonville (13-2), Tennessee (12-3),
Tampa Bay (10-5) and Minnesota (9-6).
</P>
<P>
   But for a minus-three turnover deficit, they might have beaten
the Vikings instead of losing 17-14. In two other games, the
Falcons didn't trail Tampa Bay until there were 58 seconds left in
what became a 19-10 loss, and they battled Tennessee to a 20-17
deficit after three quarters despite six turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   However, they also lost games they should have won, 19-13 in
overtime to 8-7 Baltimore and 13-9 at 6-9 Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   In the past five games, the offense has turned in four of its
five most productive performances, with totals of 343, 361, 338 and
Sunday's 393 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The exception was the loss at San Francisco, where they had a
season-low 105 yards against a poor 49ers team. The Falcons finish
the season against San Francisco on Monday night in the Dome with
third place in the NFC West at stake.
</P>
<P>
   The last game of the season, thankfully, will be in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without question, offensively it was the best game that we
have had this year,'' Reeves said. ``I think this is the first time
all year that we have met all of our goals offensively.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
