<HEADER>
A0200 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CENTURY-TOWN-COX     12-27 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENTURY-TOWN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Century at 100: Florida town celebrates its biggest birthday
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CENTURY, Fla. _ They'll ring in the new year here with miniature
pony rides, a pie eating contest, ugliest man competition,
fireworks and horseshoes.
</P>
<P>
   Why not welcome the coming millennium, organizers figure, in a
place named for the last turn of the century?
</P>
<P>
   No one's quite seen anything like it in this former lumber town
of 2,500 people, which has been in an economic coma since the mill
shut down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt it would be more well received this year given the
name of the town,'' said Century accountant Ann Brooks, who helped
organize the celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Billboards promote the event all along U.S. 29.
</P>
<P>
   When Michigan businessman Russell Alger needed to expand his
timber empire in 1900, he purchased 250,000 acres of forest here in
northwest Florida that included a black community then called
Teaspoon. A train station took the name of the community.
</P>
<P>
   In 1901, Alger _ a former Michigan governor and secretary of war
under President McKinley until he resigned after being criticized
for lack of military preparation prior to the Spanish-American War
_ rejected a push to rename the remote Florida station for himself.
But he agreed to a later suggestion, brought on by the calendar:
Century.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the town's Historical Society today brag they haven't
been able to find another town in the nation named Century.
</P>
<P>
   Remnants of the old Alger-Sullivan Lumber Co. are scattered
throughout Century's historic district, where Spanish moss cascades
down the branches of towering oak trees.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few generations ago, moonshiners and honky-tonks pervaded
the dense woods and flatlands along the Escambia River.
</P>
<P>
   In pockets of town, poverty lingers. Crack cocaine dealing has
replaced bootlegging. Despite an economic boom throughout the
South, Century's unemployment rate soars near 20 percent. Many
residents are on welfare.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the lumber company left town, they left behind a whole
lot of people who depended on them for everything,'' said Century
Mayor Benny Barnes. ``When they left, they took a whole lot of the
leaders with them.''
</P>
<P>
   There's been some resurgence. A state prison built about 10
years ago has provided jobs. A nearby industrial park has attracted
medical companies. In the 1970s, the Florida town of South Flomaton
annexed the community of Century, then changed the name of the
whole entity to Century.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Piggly Wiggly is the only grocery store in town.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just not lots here,'' said Daniel Moore, Piggly Wiggly
manager. ``So you have to go other places if you want to get a job
and you're going to be a professional.''
</P>
<P>
   Chicken crackled as the mayor dropped freshly floured pieces in
a black kettle of boiling oil fired by a propane burner set up
behind the police station. As he does every year, Barnes cooked for
the annual City Hall Christmas party.
</P>
<P>
   In one way, Century is more advanced than a lot of places.
Rather than fret over whether the town's 7-year-old computers would
survive Y2K problems on New Year's Day, Century spent $20,000 on
new ones. A generator is hooked up to City Hall to keep them
running.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people think the lights might go off,'' Barnes said.
``There might be some things happen we haven't thought about.''
</P>
<P>
   There will even be a generator hooked up to the lights at the
city park _ named for Century native and Arizona Diamondbacks
manager Buck Showalter _ when the town's millennium celebration
begins Dec. 31. A crowd of 7,000 is expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people that would not be happy here,'' said resident
Margaret Collier, 73. ``We are not a sophisticated town. But if you
want good, hearty people, then they're here.''
</P>
<P>
   Marlon Manuel writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
