<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0203 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CENSUS-PRIVACY-NYTR &LR;      12-27 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-PRIVACY-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENSUS BUREAU TRIES TO EASE PRIVACY FEARS AS 2000 COUNT
APPROACHES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By CARL HULSE   
 NYT Regional Newspapers   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Census Bureau was embarrassed. After all, it
hopes to induce all U.S. residents to take part in the upcoming
head count, even those here under sketchy circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Without a second thought, the federal office-leasing agency
located the new Tucson, Ariz., census headquarters in a building
recently vacated by the Immigration and Naturalization Service, the
bane of illegal aliens. Such a coincidence was hardly reassuring to
Hispanic immigrants already nervous that the census data could be
used against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a 24-hour flap,'' said a rueful Kenneth Prewitt, the
census director who, upon learning of the snafu, immediately
directed the General Services Administration to find an alternative
site.
</P>
<P>
   Such quick action cannot resolve all confidentiality concerns
that could hold down the response rate to the 2000 Census, a
massive undertaking set to launch April 1.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers, privacy experts and others fear that anxiety about
releasing personal data to a government agency _ heightened in this
information age _ could cause some people to refuse to return their
census forms.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is absolutely a concern, there is no question about it,''
said Rep. Dan Miller, R-Fla., who chairs the House Subcommittee on
the Census.
</P>
<P>
   Evan Hendricks, editor of a Washington newsletter on privacy
issues, agrees growing public nervousness over the security of
personal financial and medical records could harm the capability of
the Census Bureau to take a full tally.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is definitely a rising tide of dissatisfaction when
people are asked for personal information,'' he said. ``The Census
Bureau is really going to feel that this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt concedes that today's information-sensitive culture
presents a hurdle for his agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``This country is on a collision course between its desire for
information as we move into the next century and its deep
commitment to privacy and confidentiality,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Prewitt and others say the Census Bureau has serious
safeguards in place to protect its information as well as ample
evidence of their effectiveness. The main challenge facing the
bureau is to spread the word about what it views as its exceptional
standards of confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the history of census privacy has already passed into
lore, such as the agency's refusal to hand over local census data
to the Secret Service when President Truman was considering
Washington neighborhoods to live in during White House renovations.
Census data is protected by law, and anyone who releases it can be
imprisoned for up to five years. No other federal agency has the
authority to inspect personal census files.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a very, very strong record,'' said the census
director. ``No reporter, however enterprising, will be able to find
a single person in the United States who says, `I filled out the
census form and the following happened to me because the
information got shared.' It didn't happen. Not to a single
person.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of an extensive outreach program to encourage full
participation in the census, the bureau for the first time is
launching a paid advertising campaign, spending $167 million on
print, television and billboard advertising, even T-shirts and
bumper stickers.
</P>
<P>
   The message, which will be almost inescapable in the coming
months, is that failing to respond to the census can harm one's
community by reducing government aid distributed on the basis of
population and that any information provided is guaranteed to
remain confidential.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign will be nationwide but is heavily targeting
minority communities that can be difficult to reach in the
decennial operation. The Census Bureau estimates the typical
African-American media consumer will see a census message 122 times
between now and the end of the census period this spring and the
typical Hispanic 105 times.
</P>
<P>
   Census officials are also working with community groups such as
the Catholic Church to involve them in convincing their members of
the importance of the census.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the bureau still anticipates a response rate to its
initial mail campaign of just 61 percent, a projection the General
Accounting Office recently judged optimistic given the downward
trend in recent censuses. The rate has steadily dropped from 78
percent in 1970 _ the first year of the mail-out, mail-back survey
_ to 70 percent in 1980 and 65 percent in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``This declining trend is due, in part, to various demographic,
attitudinal and other factors, such as concerns over privacy and
mistrust of government,'' said the report from the GAO, the
watchdog for Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt said the agency's extensive research shows that 7-8
percent of the public is predisposed to not participate in the
census, citing privacy as among their reasons. The proportion runs
higher in some minority communities where residents fear real
repercussions _ such as deportation _ from cooperating.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get these pockets of the population who are concerned
because the stakes are much higher,'' Prewitt said.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who noted he was sworn to secrecy when he visited a
Census Bureau office outside Washington, said it is not only recent
immigrants who might resist the enumeration because of privacy
worries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wealthy people have the concern as much as the people on the
mountaintop in Montana or the illegal immigrants in Texas and
Florida,'' he said. ``The gated community on Longboat Key might be
just as difficult to count as the migrant camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt said he believes steps the agency is taking should limit
the role privacy fears will play in depressing participation. He
believes extensive follow-up to the mailing will result in a nearly
full count.
</P>
<P>
   And, despite GAO warnings that the bureau might not be ready for
the millennial count now only three months away, Prewitt is upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are feeling very good about where we are,'' he said.
``Everything we want to have in place for today, is in place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
