<HEADER>
A0207 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-KYRGYZ-POTTERY-ART-NY     12-27 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KYRGYZ-POTTERY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODERN CRAFTS IN KYRGYSTAN IMBUED WITH SPIRITUAL MEMORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT19 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(DW) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BISHKEK, Kyrgyzstan _ In a studio above the art school where she
teaches, Begaim Tenizbaeva turns out brightly colored and unusually
shaped ceramics. Her table sets are not only highly original in
their conception and execution, they also refer directly to her
Kyrgyz heritage.
</P>
<P>
   A sugar bowl is not, as it first seems, simply made in an odd
shape. Its shape is modeled on that of a yurt, the domed felt tent
in which Kyrgyz nomads have lived since time immemorial.
</P>
<P>
   The teapot that accompanies this bowl is made in the shape of
the traditional vats in which Kyrgyz villagers cook their food. It
also refers to the shape of the calpac, the tall felt hat worn by
many Kyrgyz men, which in turn reflects the profile of the towering
mountains that cover most of this country.
</P>
<P>
   Vases in Ms. Tenizbaeva's studios bear narrow strips of painted
figures. They are adapted from some of the thousands of ancient
petroglyphs that have been found on rocks in eastern Kyrgyzstan.
</P>
<P>
   The applied arts are vibrantly alive here, and not surprisingly
many of their leading practitioners are strongly influenced by
their native land. They are working to combine Western ideas of
abstraction with their Central Asian heritage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in my blood,'' Ms. Tenizbaeva said. ``No matter how much
I want to move toward art that is purely modern, the Kyrgyz
influence comes out in my work. It's not just shapes, but also
ideas and concepts that come out of the legends I heard from my
grandparents when I was a child.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tenizbaeva, 45, is one of several dozen artists here who are
taking a new approach not only to ceramics, but also to clothing,
jewelry and various forms of installation. Their work, while
modern, seeks to embody Kyrgyz tradition.
</P>
<P>
   This movement emerged in the late 1970s and thrived for about a
decade. It was set back by the social upheaval that followed the
collapse of the Soviet Union but has strongly re-established itself
in the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't call it an artistic current, because the art scene
in Kyrgyzstan is too small to have currents,'' said Valery Ruppel,
an artist known for his felt constructions. ``But we do feel our
roots very strongly. It's something that maintains our identity,
even while we follow a very contemporary sensibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruppel is one of the most successful of Kyrgyzstan's artists,
and the felt that he favors is the most traditional of Kyrgyz
materials. His works are largely abstract, but many seem to include
the shapes of the rivers and mountains that define this country's
rugged geography.
</P>
<P>
   The rectangular constructions that he has been making for the
last few years hang in the homes of several foreigners here in
Bishkek, and others are in European collections. But just as this
work is becoming recognized, he has moved away from them and begun
making free-standing installations.
</P>
<P>
   His ability to change directions like this reflects one
advantage that artists have in post-Soviet countries. Their local
market is limited, and much of the little that they earn comes from
foreigners, but life is relatively inexpensive, so artists can
survive by selling only modest numbers of works.
</P>
<P>
   When Kyrgyzstan became independent in 1991, Bishkek was
transformed from a remote provincial outpost in the Soviet
hinterland to a national capital. Foreign entrepreneurs, diplomats
and aid workers began moving here, and they provided a market for
Western-influenced work that still puzzles some Kyrgyz.
</P>
<P>
   To cater to this market, and also to the growing numbers of
Kyrgyz who are becoming interested in what applied artists are
creating here, a shop called Tamur opened a few months ago on one
of Bishkek's main streets.
</P>
<P>
   A steady flow of patrons, some from Kyrgyzstan and others from
abroad, passed through the shop on a recent morning. One bought a
striking pair of earrings made from silver and native gems. Another
settled on a chic felt vest with a traditional pattern discreetly
woven into the hem.
</P>
<P>
   Other items on display included ceramic and metal plates, all
with unusual designs; a lampshade decorated with motifs inspired by
the country's famous symbolic petroglyphs; evocative pendants in
the shape of yurts; and a 4-foot-tall clock made from sculptured
iron.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put on workshops here where masters show young people how
they work,'' said Aynura Ashirakhmanova, one of the shop's
managers. ``We also have fashion shows, and you can see that our
designers are making pieces that are really high fashion, although
they do have Kyrgyz themes. Every piece in here has a spiritual
memory.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Kyrgyz are nominally Muslim, but many feel closer to
pre-Islamic beliefs that stress spiritualism and the mystic power
of mountains, animals and natural forces. Shamanism is still
common. More than a few people in rural areas wear talismans around
their necks and keep ancient symbols, like one made from 40 sheep
femurs, in their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go into a yurt, you get a special feeling,'' said
Shamil Dayarbekov, a renowned jeweler who also makes constructions
and sculptures from metal, leather, or any other object that speaks
to his Kyrgyz soul. ``It's complex, but there's no excess.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that spirit is what animates the applied arts here,''
Dayarbekov said. ``Fine art only came to Kyrgyzstan at the
beginning of this century, but we always had a rich tradition of
folk arts and crafts. What we're doing today is using modern
approaches to art in a way that reflects our own artistic and
spiritual heritage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
