<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-STORM-705&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIOLENT STORM KILLS DOZENS IN EUROPE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Blocking off most of an intersection in one of this
city's most expensive neighborhoods, David Chezeaud stretched a
plastic tape from a light pole to the entrance of La Muete subway
stop.
</P>
<P>
   But no one objected. Scattered in the street were the remains of
two chimney stacks that had crumbled under the pressure of the 95
mph winds that accompanied Sunday's storm, including three boulders
that had fallen six stories to the pavement without shattering.
</P>
<P>
   Already workers had begun putting up scaffolding to prop what
was left of the chimneys belonging to a turn-of-the-century
apartment house. But Chezeaud, a contractor hired by the city to
help clean up, said it could be days before the sidewalk was
pronounced safe for passage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I was born, I've never seen anything like that storm,''
said Chezeaud. ``All over Paris there are problems like this.''
</P>
<P>
   The swath of Europe hit by Sunday's fierce storm tried to pick
itself up Monday. But the damage caused by the freak gales _ which
in some areas reached 110 mph _ was clearly formidable. In Paris
the roofers union estimated that there had been nearly $80 million
of damage to roofs and chimneys alone.
</P>
<P>
   France was hit hardest, with hundreds injured and at least 44
people dead, most from collapsing roofs and falling trees. But at
least another 40 people were killed in weather-related incidents in
southern Germany and Switzerland, Britain, Belgium, Spain and
Italy.
</P>
<P>
   In some parts of western Europe, main highways remained closed
because of fallen trees, which lay like pick-up sticks across
traffic lanes. Train service continued to be disrupted and airports
reported long delays. By evening some 900,000 homes in France were
still lacking electricity. And bracing for another storm, Air
France canceled its flights to most of the country's southwest
airports.
</P>
<P>
   But during the day, the clean-up began. Along the streets of
Paris, towing companies started collecting the cars that had been
so damaged by falling debris that they could not be moved on their
own. Work crews recaptured garbage cans swept into odd nooks, and
outside the stately National Assembly the shattered remains of a
small glass guard booth _ usually home to a half-frozen gendarme _
was carefully swept into a neat pile and carted away.
</P>
<P>
   The list of historic sites that had suffered some damage in the
storm grew.
</P>
<P>
   Officials reported that some stained-glass windows were broken
in the newly restored Notre Dame Cathedral and in the small gothic
Sainte-Chapelle, and that the roofs of both the National Library
and the Pantheon were damaged.
</P>
<P>
   Also the home of Balzac _ now a museum _ in the 16th
arrondissement was badly damaged when a falling tree smashed
through its roof. The National Fund for Historic Sites and
Monuments estimated that it would take upward of $75 million to
repair cultural monuments.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking off his vacation in Egypt, Prime Minister Lionel Jospin
returned to France, stopping at Versailles to assess the damage
there: 10,000 trees were uprooted in the royal park, windows were
shattered and officials were worried that water might leak through
parts of the roof. Even Jospin's official residence, Hotel
Matignon, was battered by the storm, suffering damage to the roof.
Huge sections of the fencing around the garden also fell down.
</P>
<P>
   As experts surveyed the damage, Versailles stayed closed to the
public, as did many other public sites, frustrating tourists.
Outside the Sainte Chapelle, Claudia Springfeld, 17, a German who
was visiting Paris with her boyfriend for three days, had to settle
for his description of the stained glass, which they could not get
in to see. ``It is not quite the same thing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials also reported that about 70,000 of the 300,000 trees
in the Boulogne and Vincennes forests had been toppled or badly
damaged. Another 3,000 trees elsewhere in Paris were uprooted.
</P>
<P>
   Francoise de Panafieu, Paris' deputy mayor in charge of parks
and gardens, called the storm an ``ecological disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It will take us years to get back to where we were,'' she
said. ``Just cleaning up the woods will take us three years. It
will take decades for real restoration.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Intercity trains gradually restarted Monday, some looking more
like rush-hour subway cars because passengers who had spent the
night waiting for service crammed aboard even if there were no
seats available. Still, complaining was rampant. Many passengers
said they had been given little information while they waited.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers in large cities such as Lille and Lyon spent the
night in emergency lodgings in sports halls or youth hostels, where
Red Cross volunteers gave them breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Despite improvements, service was still not available between
Paris and parts of Switzerland at the end of the day. Train
officials promised to do better Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In many villages, the sound of buzz saws clearing through fallen
branches dominated the day. But the job remained enormous and many
roadways still needed to be cleared. While meteorologists had
predicted Sunday's storm, they had not anticipated such strong
winds. In many areas the winds were the strongest ever recorded.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's never been anything like this,'' said Transport
Minister Jean-Claude Gayssot. ``Obviously, because it was unique
and exceptional, we were far less prepared than if it were
something that had happened before.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Britain, where eight people died, warned that
hundreds of homes were still at risk from severe flooding over the
next two days. Some 270 rivers across southern Britain remained on
flood alert, and more bad weather is expected.
</P>
<P>
   In Germany, where the storm killed at least 15 people, some
highways and many smaller roads _ especially in the Stuttgart area
_ were still blocked by trees. Train service was widely disrupted.
</P>
<P>
   The tornadolike winds also ravaged property throughout
Switzerland, where 11 people died, including two in a ski gondola
brought down in the Alps.
</P>
<P>
   ``We forget from time to time that nature has its own rules,''
said the president of Switzerland, Ruth Dreifuss.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
