<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0209 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLA-MILLENNIUM-COX     12-27 2388
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-MILLENNIUM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A (quick) history of Florida
 &HT;    (EDS: PHOTOS AVAILABLE. This story exists of cutlines for
accompanying photos. Call Cox News Service at 404-526-5456.)
 &HT;    By Michael Browning
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Florida, the ``Land of Flowers,'' seems
nakedly new, built yesterday or the day before. In fact we are in
our 10,000th year of human habitation, our 486th year of recorded
history, our 154th year of statehood.
</P>
<P>
   St. Augustine, America's oldest city, was founded in 1565, one
year after Michelangelo died, one year after William Shakespeare
was born. The oldest fossil, a tiny trilobite known as Colpocoryphe
exsul, was found in a test oil well shaft in Madison County and may
be 225 million years old.
</P>
<P>
   But so many of us are newcomers that we live in an amnesiac daze
when it comes to days gone by. In South and Central Florida
particularly, ``Before Disney,'' or ``Before I-95'' betokens vast,
almost Egyptian antiquity.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time we have no time for old time's sake.
</P>
<P>
   We like to bulldoze reality and put up fantasies. Disney is only
the largest. Silver Springs' glass-bottomed boats have been peering
into crystal depths for over a century. Opa-Locka was conceived as
a Moorish fantasy town in the 1920s by aviator Glenn Curtis. Sea
World is safely ashore, near Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   In fact much of Florida's history over the past 1,000 years must
be re-created, re-enacted, to be seen. Outside of St. Augustine,
outside of some old towns in North Florida where the light of elder
days still shines on old brick-faced downtowns and oak-shaded
graveyards, our yesterdays have been scanted for our big tomorrows.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a brief, backward glance, a small record of our comings
and goings. Much has come and gone, never to come again.
</P>
<P>
   Dreams of empire
</P>
<P>
   Discoverer of Florida on Easter Sunday, March 27, 1513 _ he
named the place Pascua de Florida, ``Easter of Flowers'' _ Juan
Ponce de Leon had accompanied Christopher Columbus on his second
voyage. A hard-bitten warrior who had earlier conquered Puerto
Rico, he led two expeditions to the state, both bloody failures,
and was forced to return to Cuba where he died of wounds suffered
in an Indian attack near Charlotte Harbor in 1521. Here, Robert
Hall of the Historic Florida Militia wears clothing and armor
similar to that carried by the Spaniards _ though chain mail
couldn't protect them from flint-tipped arrows. Ponce failed to
find the fabled Fountain of Youth, but his expedition was the first
to experience the powerful Gulf Stream, an ocean current running
north off the Florida coast.
</P>
<P>
   Bow and curtsy
</P>
<P>
   Public education in Florida was practically nonexistent before
1870 and schools were segregated until the 1960s. Children learned
to read from McGuffey's Readers and as late as the turn of the
century were taught to recite the alphabet forward and _ useless
skill! _ backward.
</P>
<P>
   At the Little Red Schoolhouse in Palm Beach, Janice Owens
re-creates an 1890s schoolhouse scene for the children of
Wellington's Panther Run Elementary School, teaching boys how to
bow, girls how to curtsy. Lunch might be a big wedge of cornbread,
washed down with cool water from the pump _ no Big Macs, no
Mountain Dew. At recess the girls might skip rope, while the boys
play ``Steal the Bacon.''
</P>
<P>
   Discipline was a ruler whapped across the palm of the hand.
Metal detectors and in-school sheriff's deputies lay 90 years in
the future.
</P>
<P>
   Conch solo
</P>
<P>
   Wynne Tatman of St. Augustine sounds a faraway trumpet note on a
conch shell, as Timucuan Indians did thousands of years ago, before
successive waves of Spanish, English and American settlers pushed
them into extinction. When Ponce de Leon sailed the Florida
coastline in 1513 there were an estimated 350,000 Native Americans
living here, and impressive mounds still exist at Crystal River and
Estero on the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Stubbornest, most resistant, are the Seminoles _ relative
latecomers to Florida, pushed south by white settlers from Georgia.
Today they sell cigarettes and gambling chips to us, we who once
despoiled them of their land and kidnapped their chief, Osceola,
under a flag of truce. They have never signed a peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Muscular Christianity
</P>
<P>
   Cross and sword seem one and the same as sandal-shod National
Park Ranger Chuck Dale strides through the streets of St. Augustine
in a swirl of black robes, during a recent re-enactment of English
privateer Sir Francis Drake's raid on the Spanish settlement. The
nearby Mission of Nombre de Dios is the oldest Catholic shrine in
the U.S., dating to 1577.
</P>
<P>
   Florida seemed well worth praying for, and fighting over. On
Sept. 20, 1565, the Spanish legate, Pedro Menendez de Aviles, fell
on Fort Caroline, overlooking the St. Johns River in modern
Jacksonville, and slaughtered a small colony of Protestant French
Huguenots.
</P>
<P>
   A monument to ``the first Protestant prayer'' offered in America
stands on the opposite bank of the St. Johns River.
</P>
<P>
   Islet of Liberty
</P>
<P>
   Winds of freedom blow across the marshlands 2 miles north of St.
Augustine, from the site of Fort Mose, (pronounced Mo-SAY), the
first free black settlement in America. It was established in 1738
as Gracia Real de Santa Teresa de Mose, by runaway slaves who
helped the Spanish and the Yamassee Indians fight the British.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Mose lasted until 1763, when Spain surrendered Florida to
the English, but buttons, gun-flints, clay pipe bowls, glass
bottles and a St. Christopher medal have been turned up here by
University of Florida archeologists.
</P>
<P>
   Here Gerald Eubanks of St. Augustine portrays Capt. Francisco
Menendez, commander of the Black Militia of St. Augustine, a city
where, in the early 1960s, blacks staged sit-ins at a local
Woolworth's lunch counter and ``swim-ins,'' at a white motel pool.
</P>
<P>
   Stars and Bars
</P>
<P>
   A Confederate flag in gray granite festoons this 1913 monument
at Olustee, in Baker County, near Jacksonville. On Feb. 20, 1864,
Union forces, including two black regiments, the famed 54th
Massachusetts and the Eighth New York, met and were defeated here
by Confederates in a sunny pinewoods. Black wounded were clubbed to
death with pine knots by enraged Southern soldiers and white
survivors were shipped north to the newly built prison at
Andersonville, where many perished miserably. In 1995 Olustee was
grievously looted by nocturnal treasure-seekers with metal
detectors.
</P>
<P>
   While Florida's coastline was largely held by the Union
throughout the war, the interior remained defiant, supplying
cattle, salt and soldiers to the Confederacy.
</P>
<P>
   Emerald city
</P>
<P>
   Across rolling hills north of Tallahassee grows a hidden forest
known as the Wade Tract, on 200 acres of private property _ a tiny
remnant of the estimated 60 million acres of ancient longleaf pines
that once flourished in the Southeastern U.S.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these trees are up to 500 years old, more than twice as
old as the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In winter the shade is faint, cast by millions of airy needles
far aloft, so that the sunlight searches out the whole landscape.
On early winter afternoons, everything can be brilliantly yet
gently illumined, from the topmost age-whorled boughs of pines
centuries old, to the tasseled ephemeral grasses and broom-sedges
of last month. In late summer and early autumn, blazing star asters
and goldenrod plumes twinkle in the wiregrass, lighting up a living
landscape from long, long ago.
</P>
<P>
   Stone sentinel
</P>
<P>
   Guarding the northernmost point in Spain's New World empire, the
venerable 1672 Castillo de San Marcos' gaunt, gray coquina walls,
33 feet thick at the base, glower defiantly over the passage
between St. Augustine and Anastasia Island.
</P>
<P>
   The fort withstood two sieges, holding out for 50 days in 1702
and for 27 days in 1740. It has never fallen to an enemy in battle.
Its masonry, made of billions of ancient mollusk-shells, absorbed
cannonballs like big sponges. Fragile periwinkles proved stronger
than gunpowder and iron. Seminole chief Osceola was briefly held
prisoner here.
</P>
<P>
   Considered the best example of 17th-century Spanish military
architecture in the New World, the Castillo underwent a $4.3
million restoration in 1998. Its beautiful, mirrory moat, a
picturesque addition from the Roosevelt era, was, alas, drained
forever. The water was sapping and splitting the fort's
foundations.
</P>
<P>
   Spaghetti eastern
</P>
<P>
   Rush hour traffic oozes like molasses along Interstate 95 at
Lake Worth, in a state where in 1907, the first year automobiles
had to be registered, there were only 296 vehicles. Today there are
more than 12 million, not counting seasonal tourist-mobiles,
puttering down 113,777 miles of highway, and 11,057 bridges, more
bridges than any other state.
</P>
<P>
   Cars have been named after places in Florida: The Chevrolet
Biscayne and Delray, the Studebaker Daytona. Cars have been used to
create artificial offshore reefs in the Gulf of Mexico. Florida
novelist Harry Crews wrote a book in 1972 about a man who ate a car
for a stunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``He felt the metal on his lips. He felt his tongue take it,
hold it. The taste of metal flooded his throat, his stomach. He
felt the taste run, touch his blood, and he almost swooned in the
pleasure of it ... `` Crews wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Now the car is eating us.
</P>
<P>
   Stairway to heaven
</P>
<P>
   Cape Canaveral is where Florida interfaces with infinity, where
man leaped off earth and landed at last on the moon in 1969. Alan
Shepherd, John Glenn, Neil Armstrong and the tragic Gus Grissom
left earth, or life, behind here in epics of exploration and
daring.
</P>
<P>
   Today at the Kennedy Space Center Visitor complex, the Firing
Room Theater re-creates the countdown sequence for the Dec. 21,
1968 Apollo 8 moon mission, during which astronaut Frank Borman and
his crewmates first orbited the moon on Christmas night.
</P>
<P>
   Florida's official state gem is the moonstone, a semi-precious
gem that is found nowhere in the peninsula, but which we have mined
in symbolic dreams. Armstrong tracked his last footprints in
Florida, before making his first on the moon. If there is the least
particle of earth-dust on the moon, it is almost certainly
Floridian.
</P>
<P>
   Head 'em up! Move 'em out!
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish introduced cattle, horses, dogs and pigs to Florida
in the 1500s, where they have flourished ever since (especially the
pigs: Feral hogs number half a million in the state and the runway
at Cape Canaveral has to be cleared of them before the space
shuttle can land there). Here at the 15,000-acre Adams Ranch in St.
Lucie County, cowboys Billy Adams (left) and Frank Lewis round up
Braford cattle (a cross between Brahmans and Herefords), as ranch
hands have done here since 1937.
</P>
<P>
   In 1948 there were 1.5 million cattle in Florida, and only 2.1
million people. Fuller Warren won the governorship promising to
keep cattle off the state highways. Today there are 1.9 million
cattle but nearly 15 million people. Disney World stands in large
part on a former ranch owned by Kissimmee cattleman Irlo Bronson.
</P>
<P>
   Under wraps
</P>
<P>
   A Calusa Indian courtier pays homage to his king in this
life-sized tableau depicting royal protocol ca. 1000 AD, which is
being prepared at the Museum of Florida History in Gainesville. The
Calusa, a tribe of approximately 20,000 hunter-gatherers and
mound-builders, were the third-most numerous tribe in Florida,
after the Timucuans and Apalachees, by the early 16th century when
the first Spanish arrived. Aerial photographs have revealed
arrow-straight walls from a probable Calusa settlement near Fort
Center, north of Lake Okeechobee in Glades County. Wooden carvings
were found preserved in the mud of a nearby pond.
</P>
<P>
   Today the Calusa are all gone, but the name survives in the
Miami telephone directory under listings including Calusa Cleaners,
Calusa Adult Care, Calusa Hairstylists, Calusa Realty and Calusa
Crossings.
</P>
<P>
   The Calusa came up with Miami's name: They called the great Lake
Okeechobee ``Mayaimi,'' or ``Big Water.''
</P>
<P>
   Forever blowing bubbles
</P>
<P>
   Nicole Marino plays The Little Mermaid at Weeki Wachee, one of
Florida's 320 springs. The ``Spring of Live Mermaids'' tourist
attraction was the brainchild of ex-Navy frogman Newton Perry, who
trained young women to stay underwater for extended periods, taking
sips of air from rubber hoses while they swam and performed
graceful ballets before spectators in a submerged, glassed-in
theater. The first mermaid show was in 1947.
</P>
<P>
   Springs were Florida's first tourist attraction _ witness the
mythical Fountain of Youth, sought by the Spanish conquistadors. In
our own day the Creature from the Black Lagoon was filmed at
Wakulla Springs (along with several Tarzan movies) and The
Incredible Mister Limpet was made here at Weeki Wachee. The first
big theme park, Cypress Gardens, opened in Winter Haven in 1936.
Disney World bubbled up in the middle of Florida in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   Rolled gold
</P>
<P>
   Grapefruit tumble along a conveyor belt at Sunbrite Citrus Inc.
in Fort Pierce, bright symbols of Florida's citrus industry, which
produced 202 million boxes of oranges, 52 million boxes of
grapefruit and 10 million boxes of tangerines, tangelos and other
specialty fruit in 1996. Citrus originated in Asia, was brought to
the Mediterranean and introduced in Florida by the Spanish near St.
Augustine in 1570.
</P>
<P>
   Three hundred years later, retired Confederate Gen. Robert E.
Lee toured North Florida and was shown an exotic fruit near
Palatka. It was called grapefruit, because it grew in grape-like
clusters. Lee sampled it gingerly and praised it politely.
</P>
<P>
   Today Florida is the leading producer of grapefruit in the
world, and our orange crop is second only to Brazil's. Citrus
groves occupy nearly a million acres in Florida, and 30 of the
state's 67 counties.
</P>
<P>
   A small spray of unfrozen orange blossoms, sent by Miami matron
Julia Tuttle to railroad baron Henry Flagler after a disastrous
cold spell in 1895, persuaded Flagler to extend his line to South
Florida, opening up the southern peninsula. Florida is still the
Orange Blossom Special.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Browning writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
