A0210 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-KIDS-REVIEW-ART-NY     12-27 0543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-KIDS-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WHY DON'T THE KIDS HAVE A VOICE?' :  SEEING CHILDREN SUFFER IN A
WELFARE MAZE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (Eds.: Production notes appear at end of review. Time and channel
are for New York area. Check local listings.) 
(DW) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tuesday night John Stossel, ABC's scourge of liberalism and all
its works, comes forward as a champion of children caught up in the
tangles of the social welfare establishment. In pursuit of the
question ``Why Don't the Kids Have a Voice?'' Stossel provides case
histories of children who are being deprived of wholesome homes by
benighted bureaucratic regulations, particularly one that favors
their biological parents, however unworthy.
</P>
<P>
   He begins with 11-year-old Timmy who was living happily with his
stepfather after the death of his mother when his biological father
appeared suddenly with a demand for the child. ``This is family,''
says Timmy as he is removed from his accustomed home. ``It's where
my mom wanted me to live, and this is where I want to live.'' But a
judge ordered him to go to his father.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Gill, a juvenile court judge, who calls himself a child
advocate is fighting to change the rules. He says: ``There is a
biological bias out there. The person who donates an egg and the
sperm owns the soul of the child. That's the way it works out. It's
ownership.''
</P>
<P>
   Stossel finds that foster parents are not the answer either.
It's hard to weigh the evidence here because of secrecy regulations
that are ostensibly aimed at protecting children but that critics
say really serve to protect social workers from scrutiny. As one of
Tuesday night's child advocates puts it, ``What goes on is
negligence, and the bureaucracies operate to protect their own
butts.'' He charges that 20 percent of foster parents do a
``downright rotten'' job of it.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to adoptive parents, the program is more
charitable. Here, as Stossel sees it, the problem is with
regulations that make adoption difficult for parents who are eager
to take on even children with handicaps.
</P>
<P>
   Stossel's interview with Harvey Kawasaki, who is in charge of
adoptions for Los Angeles County, where children routinely spend
years in foster care, will do nothing to improve the image of the
bureaucracy. ``Your critics say you're incompetent,'' Stossel
notifies him. The adoption chief, who seems to have very few
successful adoptions to his credit, says he enjoyed the interview.
</P>
<P>
   At the very end of this hour Stossel gets into the touchy
subject of race, which might have made for a rewarding report if he
had applied himself. Despite a law that prohibits consideration of
race in adoptions, he finds that social workers are still averse to
giving black children to white couples.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, as in much of the program, Stossel doesn't do
much digging into the whys and wherefores, and settles mainly for
the moving anecdote.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `WHY DON'T THE KIDS HAVE A VOICE?'  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   10 p.m. ET, Tuesday on ABC &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Victor Neufeld, executive producer; Martin Phillips, senior
producer; Vicki Samuels, Deborah Colloton and Audrey Baker,
producers. A production of ABC News. John Stossel, correspondent.
</P>
</TEXT>
