<SLUG> BC-SEAT-BUFFETTI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAT TO BUY BUFFETTI FOR $718 MILLION IN MOVE FOR ELECTRONIC SALES
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Seat Pagine Gialle SpA, the Italian publisher of yellow
pages that has expanded into online businesses, reached an
agreement Monday to buy Buffetti SpA, which operates a chain of
office supply stores, for 708.4 million euros ($718 million) in
cash and stock.
</P>
<P>
   Seat's move, if successful, would create a big European company
in the growing market for electronic sales, focusing not only on
individual retail purchasers but also on professionals, like
doctors and lawyers, and small and midsize companies, which abound
in Italy. It would be the latest step in the accelerating spread of
electronic commerce, as companies pick partners to gain products,
expertise and capital.
</P>
<P>
   Tiscali SpA, an Italian company that, like Seat, helped to
pioneer free Internet access in Continental Europe, said last week
it was spending $101 million to acquire control of two French
telecommunications companies: Nets SA, which operates a glass fiber
cable linking London and Paris, and A Telecom SA, a provider of
local phone service with potential Internet applications.
</P>
<P>
   Lorenzo Pellicioli, the chief executive of Seat, said Buffetti,
which has also been expanding online, ``complements Seat in
developing the Internet for professionals and small and midsize
companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Seat, based in Turin, in northern Italy, acquired Virgilio, one
of Italy's leading Internet search engines, earlier this year. Its
acquisition of Buffetti would be the next step in a strategy that
it expects would lead to online operations accounting for at least
10 percent of revenue by 2002. Through Virgilio, Seat now offers
links to companies selling products online and search tools for
phone numbers. Seat expects its online businesses to account for 40
billion lire ($20.9 million) this year, compared with 27 billion
lire ($14 million) in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Buffetti, based in Rome, has been pushing out of its traditional
over-the-counter sales and into online selling and has diversified
the products it offers. Buffetti sells books and software online,
and announced plans earlier this month to join an undisclosed
partner in the financial services industry to sell insurance and
banking products through its network of about 1,200 stores in
Italy. The alliance with Seat will enable Buffetti to sell products
online and give Seat access to Buffetti's ability to deliver
products without using the unreliable Italian postal system.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Seat rose 0.517 euro Monday, or 18 percent, to 3.43
euros. Buffetti rose 3.64 euros, or 26 percent, to 17.51 euros.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, shares in Internet companies have surged on the
Milan stock exchange as investors in Europe and abroad poured money
into companies operating in telecommunications and related
technology. Swept by this fever, shares of Seat rose more than 75
percent over the last month.
</P>
<P>
   In trading before Christmas, Seat was worth about 22 trillion
lire, or $11.5 billion, roughly 80 times its profits. Yet analysts
said its price could continue to rise. In a report earlier this
month, Lehman Brothers Securities raised its price target for Seat
to 3.05 euros, or $3.08, from 1.82 euros, and maintained an
outperform rating for the stock.
</P>
<P>
   Based on share prices on Thursday, the last trading day before
the bid was officially made, each package of 500 Buffetti shares,
the minimum amount the Milan stock exchange buys and sells, would
bring about 44 euros, or $44.57, in cash, and 2,735 shares in Seat.
That represents a premium of almost 16 percent to Buffetti's
closing share price.
</P>
<P>
   Though Internet use in Italy lags behind that in many other
European countries because of the low number of households with
computers and sparse familiarity with English, the Web's dominant
language, experts expect it to surge in coming months as the sale
and leasing of computers grows and Internet content in Italian
increases.
</P>
<P>
   Seat was advised by Salomon Smith Barney, while Buffetti was
advised by ING Barings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
