<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0219 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-WASHINGTON-MONUMENT-A     12-27 0511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WASHINGTON-MONUMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON MONUMENT LIGHT SHOW DRAWS CONCERNS, AND ASSURANCES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo, NYT14, is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(ms) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the final seconds of the century, the Washington
Monument will turn into a giant sparkler, with most of the 555-foot
obelisk ablaze with pyrotechnic diamonds at the stroke of midnight.
``And please don't call them fireworks!'' one of the show's
organizers said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   More about definitions in a moment. Not everyone has been
enthusiastic about lighting up the monument. Rep. Ralph Regula,
R-Ohio, wrote President Clinton last week of his ``grave concerns''
that it might be damaged physically and desecrated spiritually.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Washington Monument is one of the most important symbols
of the nation's capital, a monument to the father of our country,
and a symbol of our patriotism and democracy,'' Regula wrote,
urging the president to change the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   As chairman of the House Appropriations Committee's subcommittee
on the Interior, Regula has some influence. He also has history on
his side. While many rallies and protests have been held at the
monument in its 114-history, nothing has been hung from the
monument itself. Federal law prohibits it.
</P>
<P>
   But this Dec. 31 is not just any New Year's Eve, and the Clinton
administration wanted a celebration worthy of a new millennium. So
the word went forth from the White House to the Interior Department
and the National Park Service: Let there be light.
</P>
<P>
   By a wonderful coincidence, the monument has been surrounded by
scaffolding for many months for the landmark's first major
renovation and cleaning since the 1930s. So the pyrotechnics will
not have to be draped on the obelisk itself but can hang from the
scaffolding's outer edges, more than nine feet from the stone.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Park Service was worried not only about precedent but
about powder burns. ``There was concern about putting fireworks up
there,'' Dave Barna, the Park Service's chief spokesman, said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not fireworks,'' M. Philip Butler of Fireworks by
Grucci said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The light show at the monument will come from special
pyrotechnic effects, said Butler, the company's chief
pyrotechnician. ``When it's lit, it doesn't fire; it drips,'' he
said. He said the distinction is crucial: With true ``fireworks''
explosive projectiles are fired out of tubes, but with the special
effects to be used at the monument there is minimal burnt-powder
residue.
</P>
<P>
   The Interior Department has written Regula in an attempt to ease
his concerns, a department spokesman said Monday. A spokeswoman for
the congressman said she had not talked to him over the holidays
and so did not know his reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Butler said the technique to be used at the Washington Monument
has been employed at Lincoln Center in New York and on the roof of
the Smithsonian Institution in Washington without harm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
