<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COSTLY-RESCUES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.H. PLANNING TO MAKE SOME HIKERS FOOT THE BILL FOR RESCUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After 30 years venturing into vicious cold, over icy rock, to
save the lives of hikers, it occurred to Joe Lentini for the first
time last year that they might not be worth the effort.
</P>
<P>
   During the years he spent in New Hampshire's White Mountains,
Lentini had noticed a gradual increase in the number of hikers who
set out unprepared. But, like other rescue workers, he says cell
phones have given hikers an ugly arrogance.
</P>
<P>
   Once, in white-out conditions, he urged a hiker to turn around
and head back and the man almost hit him. Lentini, director of
Eastern Mountain Sports' climbing school, took two months off to
think about quitting.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``I had a good friend of mine killed in a rescue and I'm
risking my life,'' he said. ``Now part of the time I was risking my
life for people who just were ignorant.''
</P>
<P>
   Later this week New Hampshire's Fish and Game Department will
announce new regulations that will establish what White Mountain
volunteers have felt in their gut for years: that a significant
minority of hikers are so careless they don't deserve to be rescued
for free.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the Manchester (N.H.) Union-Leader, Fish
and Game Col. Ron Alie said hikers deemed reckless will be billed
for rescue missions, whose costs can mount quickly. A rescue last
year of a Canadian man who ran out of food near Mount Eisenhower
cost Fish and Game $3,000, not counting the $1,400-an-hour bill for
the National Guard helicopter used to find him, Alie said.
</P>
<P>
   Alie would not comment further on the plan Monday. The
department will release more details at a news conference on
reducing the overall number of rescue missions.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement could stake out radical territory for New
Hampshire in a debate that has been heating up nationwide for 10
years. On one side are purists like Tim Kovacs of the
Colorado-based Mountain Rescue Association, who says it's the job
of rescue workers to save lives, not judge people in distress. On
the other side is a growing sense that Americans have stopped
taking the wilderness seriously. And anger is mounting among the
volunteer searchers who work in treacherous conditions for nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them are really bloody foolish people that are
ill-prepared and inappropriately dressed and not emotionally ready
or experienced, carrying a damn cell phone, and I think they
wouldn't have been there without a cell phone,'' said Bill Aughton,
a 40-year veteran of White Mountain search operations and the
director of the N.H. Outdoor Council. ``When someone calls and
says, `Hey, I'm stuck on the side of Mount Washington,' and they're
not prepared to do anything except call for help, I personally
would rather leave them to die.''
</P>
<P>
   Rescuers have grown more angry since cell phones have given
hikers the ability to call for help from anywhere. Already this
fall at least three groups of hikers have called for help and been
rescued in the White Mountains. But rescue workers also tell of a
proliferating number of unjustified rescue missions. Kovacs, of the
Mountain Rescue Association, recalled a distress call two years ago
from a man who had run out of cigarettes. And New Hampshire rescue
workers were angered two weeks ago when two New Jersey men got
caught at night on Mount Washington in blizzard conditions, Aughton
said.
</P>
<P>
   When rescue workers told them they would not send searchers up
the mountain until morning, the men called their wives in New
Jersey and ``said the police won't get us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, New Hampshire has had a law allowing the state to levy
fines for reckless endangerment, but veteran rescuers can only
recall one hiker who was fined _ a hiker who was found on Mount
Moriah, ``lying in the snow with an empty liter and a half of
vodka,'' Lentini said. The hiker was fined $500.
</P>
<P>
   Debates over rescue costs erupt regularly after major search
operations, which rely on massive contributions of time and
equipment by volunteers. In many western states, where rescue
operations can bankrupt whole counties, sheriffs and the forest
service have the right to charge for the cost, said John Moss, a
Colorado attorney who specializes in outdoor recreation law. But
even where laws allow local officials to charge the subject of a
search, they are rarely enforced, Moss said.
</P>
<P>
   And although Moss himself left search and rescue because he was
so tired of ``seeing stupid people do stupid things,'' he said he
opposes the threat of charges, which could prevent a hiker from
calling rescue workers in a crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic tenet of search and rescue is that you save the
life. The theory is, if the person has to make a decision to call,
he won't call,'' he said. ``You'd much rather do 10 stupid rescues
than miss one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-99 2013EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
