<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: MILITARY BASES MAKE ANOTHER MODEL FOR SCHOOLS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ANTHONY LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Schools on military bases, run by the Department of
Defense, have a better record than most public schools in this
country. Student test scores are high. Black and Hispanic children
far outperform those elsewhere. Children from poorer families do
almost as well as the better-off.
</P>
<P>
   I learned about the base schools in an article by Daniel Golden
in The Wall Street Journal last week. It was an eye-opening piece,
reporting remarkable facts about a little-known institution and
leaving us with important questions about what makes those schools
work and how our society can learn from their success.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon has 71 schools for children of service members at
bases in this country, and 153 overseas. In the last six years,
pupils have taken 13 National Assessment of Educational Progress
tests; in 12 their results were above the national mean. More than
80 percent of the graduates go on to college, compared with the
national figure of 67 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 34,000 students in the domestic base schools, more than
half qualify for free or reduced-price lunches because of low
family income. They did almost as well as other students in
demonstrating writing proficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Forty percent of the domestic students are black or Hispanic. On
writing proficiency, 26 percent of the black children scored at or
above passing level compared with 7 percent nationally; 32 percent
of the Hispanics did, compared with 10 percent nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Golden's story quoted Roy Truby, executive director of the board
that administers the National Assessment tests, on those results:
``This debunks the notion that demography is destiny.''
</P>
<P>
   How is it done? The article mentioned a number of distinctive
factors.
</P>
<P>
   One is money. The domestic schools spend $7,279 per pupil, 23
percent more than public schools do on average. Among other things,
the money goes for art and music classes _ which have been trimmed
in many public schools as marginal extras but which I think are a
vital part of the learning atmosphere. Some goes for technology:
more computers for the students.
</P>
<P>
   Parent involvement is a second factor. The military gives
parents of children in base schools an hour off a week or a
half-day a month to volunteer in the schools, and many do.
</P>
<P>
   A third is discipline. If a student misbehaves and moderate
measures do not work, a parent will be called in for a conference.
If he or she does not show up, the school may get in touch with his
or her commanding officer. Enough said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the practices that help account for the good showing of
the base schools could readily be duplicated in ordinary public
schools. If a community is able to spend more on its schools _ and,
crucially, has the political will to do so _ students may benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Other elements are peculiar to the military. We would not want a
school principal to telephone a private employer of a parent who
has not come in for a conference about a misbehaving child.
</P>
<P>
   Underneath the particular reasons for the performance of the
base schools there are, surely, larger social factors. For one,
military families may have modest housing, but they are not likely
to live in the desperate ghettos that exist in our inner cities. To
put it mildly, it is harder for a child to learn when she lives
amid decay and danger.
</P>
<P>
   The gap between high and low incomes is less stark among
military personnel, and less distorting, than in our civilian
society today. The difference between rich and poor school
districts is a major problem for public schools in many states.
There are one-parent families in the military, but probably not so
many as in civilian America.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, I think there is a deeper sense of community among
military families. The free market and the race to get ahead have
given us, along with their economic benefits, an atomized society.
We do not care for each other as we believe, perhaps romantically,
Americans once did.
</P>
<P>
   We do not want to be militarized as a nation. But we have to
recognize that the military is one of our most successful
institutions: profoundly effective in achieving racial integration
in the services and now, we find, in educating its children. We
should be able to learn from its successes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-99 2014EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991227.0336 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0228 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-2TAKES-     12-27 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE CONSIDERED UNSTOPPABLE, GORE SEEKS TO STAVE OFF BRADLEY
CHALLENGE
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It was all so simple for Al Gore back in the days
when he expected an effortless coast to the Democratic presidential
nomination. He had the money, the endorsements and a careerist
staff comfortable in the corridors of power.
</P>
<P>
   Potential rivals concluded it would be foolish to challenge him.
And his airy campaign slogan of ``practical idealism'' encapsulated
just what Gore wanted the world to know about him: he was pragmatic
yet optimistic, visionary even.
</P>
<P>
   But his glide to the nomination hit a brick wall _ in the person
of Bill Bradley _ and the common assumptions about Gore's
once-inevitable candidacy have shattered. It is hard now to think
of a candidate who has undergone more transformations in a shorter
period than Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Now Gore faces perhaps the most critical weeks of his political
career, a hectic two-and-a-half-month campaign sprint through Iowa,
New Hampshire, New York, California and the Deep South that will
most likely determine whether his frantic self-makeover and the
doubts he has tried to raise about Bradley have worked, or whether
he will be denied what he once viewed as his rightful
``promotion.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore strategists believe that the vice president, who already
has a lock on hundreds of the so-called superdelegates to the
Democratic National Convention and is ahead in the national polls,
can win the nomination under several scenarios. But they say
Bradley can win under only one _ by winning the Iowa caucuses on
Jan. 24 and the New Hampshire primary a week later. Without those
states, especially New Hampshire, whose voters tend to favor
insurgents, Bradley would be hard pressed to convince the rest of
the country that he is a winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they do not stop us there, we will not be stopped,'' said a
top Gore strategist. ``They understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore is leading Bradley in Iowa polls by 20 percentage points
and claims a strong organization there. But with Bradley pouring
everything into Iowa next month, including more than $800,000 for
television and radio commercials and a full schedule of daily
appearances, the Gore campaign says it will need to match him
dollar for dollar to make sure the lead does not slip away.
</P>
<P>
   Gore advisers do not yet know how much time Gore will spend in
Iowa because he also needs to campaign in New Hampshire, where the
most recent poll showed him behind Bradley by 12 points. Their hope
is that if Bradley fails in Iowa the loss may prompt some
supporters to cross party lines and vote for Sen. John McCain, a
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Darrell West, a political scientist at Brown University, said
the stakes were higher for Bradley than for Gore in New Hampshire.
``Bradley really does have to win it because New England should be
a very good place for him,'' West said. ``It has a tradition of
independence, and the Northeast is the most liberal region in
national politics.''
</P>
<P>
   But this is unusual, and in most states, Gore is leading Bradley
by healthy margins.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the early months of the 2000 presidential campaign have
been rife with frustration for Gore and his aides. Even though he
moved his campaign out of Washington and into Nashville, pared the
staff and the salaries of those who remained and shed the
cumbersome entourage that once followed him on campaign trips, Gore
still seems to be trying to shake the image of a stiff Washington
insider.
</P>
<P>
   Even more galling to the Gore staff is that the man he is
campaigning against spent 18 years in the Senate, is bankrolled by
Wall Street and has still managed to cast himself as the
nonestablishment, noncalculating nonpolitician.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Hart, a pollster not affiliated with any campaign, said
his most recent surveys showed that 38 percent of voters nationally
have a positive view of Gore while 35 percent have a negative view.
By contrast, he said, Bradley had a positive rating of 42 percent
and a negative rating of 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore has a lot of work to do to warm up the electorate,''
Hart said. ``He is perceived as a politician, who comes across more
with a rotelike performance than a human performance, and while
that may have changed over the last month and a half, I'm not sure
the electorate has seen that.''
</P>
<P>
   These numbers, combined with the simultaneous Bradley surge and
Gore's disappointing poll results in a hypothetical race against
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, sent Gore into a tumult of
reinvention at the end of September and spawned a painfully public
makeover. The competition jolted him out of his blue suit, out of
his predictable stump speech and out of the arms of Bill Clinton.
The remodeling was so extensive that it raised questions of his
essential self and whether he was a ``beta'' male who could morph
into an ``alpha'' male.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the continual recalibrating and focus on the
performance aspects of politics began to overshadow what his
supporters saw as his strongest assets: his experience and command
of the issues.
</P>
<P>
   That point seemed to be at the heart of the heated exchange
between Gore and Bradley in their Dec. 19 debate on the NBC news
program, ``Meet the Press.'' Hoping to unmask Bradley as a
conventional politician who could not survive without high-priced
television ads and a hefty bankroll to pay for them, Gore proposed
that both he and Bradley drop all 30-second commercials and instead
hold twice-a-week debates.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley spurned the offer, as some in the Gore camp expected he
would, and ridiculed it as a gimmick. ``The point is, Al,'' he said
derisively, ``and I don't know if you get this, but a political
campaign is not just a performance for people, which is what this
is, but it is, rather, a dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   For Gore, the offer was about more than performance, or even
saving money on commercials. He wanted to show himself as the true
``reformer'' and paint Bradley as beholden to the status quo.
Despite the negative press reviews of the calculated theatrics,
Gore advisers said they were pleased with the gesture because the
public did not like 30-second commercials, even if it got most of
its information from them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are sick of these old advertisements and the
old approach to campaigning,'' Gore said a few days after the
debate. He dismissed campaign commercials as ``filled with fuzzy
images and little, short slogans'' and cast Bradley as cautious and
timid, precisely the words often used to describe Gore.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Gans, director of the nonpartisan Committee for the Study
of the American Electorate, said that the Gore campaign was
determined to portray Bradley as just another politician. ``What
Gore was trying to establish in that debate was that Bradley
couldn't run above it all,'' Gans said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not Gore succeeded, many analysts say that his
aggressive approach has thrown Bradley off his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore has stemmed the bloodletting,'' West said. ``He's been a
better candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has also sought to draw Bradley into an argument over
policy details _ and away from the former basketball star's big
themes and compelling personal story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bradley was saying to people, `Here's who I am,''' Hart said.
``People aren't going to pick a president on the basis of that. At
this point, I don't know that Bradley has the message that
overrides the constituency groups that Gore has put together. Gore
has the backbone of the Democratic Party _ women, labor,
minorities.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore helped solidify that base, at least in the primary
campaign, with his sharp attacks on Bradley's proposals. In
particular, he has warned relentlessly that Bradley's health care
proposal would ``shred the social safety net,'' because it would
eliminate Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gore's relentless attacks on Bradley have so far failed
to turn the tide in New Hampshire, Gore still has plenty of cause
for optimism. After New Hampshire, attention turns to the March 7
primaries in New York, Ohio, California and a dozen other states.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley could receive a tremendous lift by winning in New York,
perhaps his best state after New Hampshire, but polls in California
show the vice president strongly ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, if Gore, who is from Tennessee, does well on March 7,
the calendar will turn in his favor as the voting heads South.
Tennessee, Texas, Florida and other Southern states vote on March
14, followed by several states in the industrial Midwest, which
leans toward Gore.
</P>
<P>
   And beyond that, Gore has the underlying advantage of official
party support and the endorsement of organized labor and the
teachers' unions. He has already locked up endorsements from more
than 520 of the 799 superdelegates to the convention. These are the
governors, senators, members of Congress and other party worthies
who are automatically delegates. Bradley has endorsements from
about 20 superdelegates.
</P>
<P>
   The first to claim 2,169 delegates wins the nomination; without
a single vote yet cast, Gore is nearly a quarter of the way there.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Carrick, a Democratic strategist based in California and
not affiliated with either campaign, put it this way: ``Bradley
almost has to get a nuclear blast out of Iowa and New Hampshire to
carry him out of March 7 and March 14.''
</P>
<P>
   After Iowa and New Hampshire, he said, ``you begin to play to
the vice president's strength, which is broad support across many
demographic groups. Even in New York the numbers are moving for
Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   But other challenges remain. In voter surveys, Gore ranks poorly
in the category of leadership. On money, he has two problems. He is
vulnerable to charges he was overzealousness in fund-raising at a
Buddhist temple in 1996, and vulnerable to concerns that he might
not have enough to campaign effectively against Bush through the
spring and summer.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, if Gore wins the nomination, he may be in the
position of convincing moderate swing voters that he is not as
liberal as he may have seemed in his primary fight with Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bradley has forced Gore to the left on a wide range of issues,
from education to health care to gay rights,'' West said. On
education, he has promised to increase federal spending to $115
billion over 10 years. He is now framing his health-care plan as
one that would lead to universal coverage, as Bradley proposes, and
he has followed Bradley in his public support for allowing gays in
the military.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps no challenge is stickier than the question of what
to do about Clinton. Gore seems caught in a revolving door of
walking out on his mentor and then walking back in. Clinton is a
strong force in mobilizing black voters for Gore. But he is also a
drag on Gore with other voters, especially the independents and
Republicans whom Gore would need in a general election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore's biggest problem is that he represents the equivalent
of a Clinton third term,'' said Ari Fleischer, a spokesman for the
Bush campaign. ``And no one is of a mind to give Bill Clinton a
third term.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
