<HEADER>
A0232 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-UKRAINE-AMOCO-BP-475&AMP;     12-27 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UKRAINE-AMOCO-BP-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BP AMOCO WITHDRAWING FROM NATURAL GAS FIELDS IN UKRAINE
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By TOM WARNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIEV, Ukraine _ BP Amoco has decided not to develop a series of
natural gas fields in Ukraine, dealing a blow to the country's
hopes of decreasing its dependence on Russian gas.
</P>
<P>
   But the decision opens the way for other companies to explore a
vast region in central and eastern Ukraine with potentially huge
deposits. An official of BP Amoco, the British-American oil and gas
giant, confirmed earlier this month that the company had informed
the Ukrainian government of its decision.
</P>
<P>
   But even if a number of investors were to express interest, they
would be unlikely to match the speed of development or the highly
advanced drilling technology that BP Amoco could have brought to
bear.
</P>
<P>
   BP's decision startled some people in the industry. ``I'm
surprised to hear they're pulling out,'' said Konstantin Skorik, a
gas industry specialist at the World Bank's office in Kiev. ``The
last time I talked to them, they said there was plenty of gas and
they were just waiting on legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Bown, the head of BP Amoco's representative office in Kiev,
said his company's research did not confirm that there was enough
gas in central and eastern Ukraine to be profitably exploited. A
company statement said the region's potential did not equal
opportunities in Trinidad and Tobago, Egypt, Indonesia and in the
Caspian Sea.
</P>
<P>
   Bown said that in many respects, prospects for businesses in
Ukraine had been improving. A few months ago, the former Soviet
republic adopted a law on production-sharing that BP Amoco had been
promoting for years, and Ukraine is now forming what is expected to
be a more investor-friendly government. ``All these positive
changes going on only add to our sense of disappointment,'' Bown
said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that when British Petroleum began the study in 1996, it
had huge reserves of oil but its gas reserves were thin. Since
then, BP has merged with Amoco and has been trying to acquire ARCO,
increasing its gas supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bown declined to put any figures on the scale of the
untapped reserves in central and eastern Ukraine, a government
official said he and others had been told that BP Amoco could reach
production of 50 billion cubic meters a year by 2007.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe that any other company or companies will get
more than 30 or 35 billion cubic meters a year out of those
fields,'' said Mykola Yevdoshchuk, deputy chief of Ukraine's State
Geology Committee. ``BP really has the best technology for deep
drilling and for drilling in difficult terrain.''
</P>
<P>
   Ukraine now imports between 56 billion and 60 billion cubic
meters a year from Russia, and the republic's habit of getting
behind in its payments is a constant source of friction between
them. The Ukrainian president, Leonid Kuchma, warned last week that
disputes over gas payments were building toward a broader
``economic war.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   BP Amoco's withdrawal from Ukraine could nonetheless be a
windfall for many smaller gas-production companies, which stand to
benefit from the company's extensive research. Even while walking
away from the project, BP said it believed that deposits in the
area could prove lucrative for companies interested in
smaller-scale investments. When purchasing geological data from the
State Geology Committee, BP obligated itself either to invest in
the region or to produce a report outlining potential finds,
according to Western standards. The report is expected to be issued
by February.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Cormick, president of Epic Energy, a Canadian company
involved in a handful of small oil-production projects in Crimea,
said, ``We see this as basically a generous gift from BP to the
smaller companies like ourselves that are already here and
working.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies like Epic also hope the report will help clarify just
how much gas remains underground in central and eastern Ukraine.
The basin around the Dnieper and Donets rivers was the Soviet
Union's primary source of gas until the 1970s. It has produced
almost 1,700 billion cubic meters of natural gas since the first
drilling in 1936 and around 60 billion cubic meters a year at its
peak in the mid-1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, however, the Ukrainian gas became harder to exploit,
and new Siberian fields proved so rich that the Soviets practically
halted investment in Ukraine. Gas production in the Dnieper-Donets
basin has since fallen to 14 billion cubic meters a year.
</P>
<P>
   BP Amoco has concluded that the amount of recoverable gas in the
area at this point has fallen below its minimum standard for
investment, which others close to the project said was about 300
billion cubic meters, Bown said.
</P>
<P>
   But Yevdoshchuk's State Geology Committee believes there are
some 3,200 billion cubic meters left in the basin, about a third of
which is recoverable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think BP will be back after the Dnieper-Donets basin proves
itself,'' Yevdoshchuk said. ``I'm just afraid they will be too
late.''
</P>
<P>
   Significant economic change in Ukraine would have been required
for BP to make a profit on the project. BP would have demanded cash
payment for its share of the gas produced, but Ukraine's government
has so far been unable to collect enough taxes to pay public
institutions' gas bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you merely got everybody to pay for the gas they receive,
suddenly you would have conservation, and exploration would pick up
dramatically,'' Cormick said. ``Ukraine's economy would be on the
road to recovery in a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Bown, however, said BP Amoco's decision not to invest was based
purely on its gas explorations and had nothing to do with the
investment climate in Ukraine, which he sees as improving. The
decision also had nothing to do with BP Amoco's recent difficulties
with its investment in Russia's Sidanko oil company, he added. BP
announced last week that it had reached agreement with Tyumen Oil,
a Russian company, in connection with the dispute. The agreement
restores BP's control over a Siberian oil field.
</P>
<P>
   Bown stressed that BP Amoco was not reducing its presence in
Ukraine and would continue to expand as a retailer of gasoline and
distributor of specialty fuels, chemicals and lubricants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
