<SLUG> BC-SKI-SLUMP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKI BUSINESS IN NEW ENGLAND RELYING ON SNOW MAKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MEG VAILLANCOURT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most New Englanders will be only dreaming of a white new year
this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the dearth of natural snow, sustained cold
temperatures are still allowing many New England ski resorts to
generate greenbacks by making artificial snow.
</P>
<P>
   Monday marked the the longest stretch without measurable snow at
Logan International Airport since the National Weather Service
began keeping records 108 years ago. There have been 287 days
without any white stuff in Boston, surpassing last year's record of
274 days.
</P>
<P>
   For ski areas, like retailers, the Christmas season can make or
break a year. So while Mother Nature hasn't brought snow, many ski
operators have taken advantage of the bitter cold by running their
snow guns around the clock.
</P>
<P>
   At Wachusett Mountain, located outside of Worcester, Mass.,
manmade snow now covers more than 75 percent of the mountain. The
Princeton resort's operators recently signed an agreement allowing
them to purchase excess water from the City of Fitchburg, which
quadrupuled Wachusett's snow-making capacity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in great shape,'' general manager David Crowley said
Monday. ``We've got the weather and the water to make snow, and
we're doing it 24 hours a day. And from an operator's standpoint,
the manmade stuff is actually better because it's more durable and
will last through thaws.''
</P>
<P>
   In a bid to encourage skiers, some operators even ``guaranteed''
a white Christmas by offering vouchers and future price reductions
if most of their trails weren't open for skiing over the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   As workers continued blanketing the slopes with manmade snow
ealier this week, skiers at the six New England resorts operated by
the American Skiing Co., for example, were being offered a $500
voucher toward lodging packages at the company's two western ski
resorts.
</P>
<P>
   The guarantee, limited to skiers who had reserved lodging
packages, kicked in if at least 70 percent of the terrain wasn't
open for skiing. Company officials, however, stressed they expected
to reach the mark at all six resorts, which include Sunday River
and Sugarloaf in Maine; Killington, Sugarbush and Mount Snow in
Vermont; and Attitash Bear Peak in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``The technology has really improved so much that you can't
really notice the difference between manmade and natural snow,''
said Chip Seamans, managing director of Sunday River in Newry
Maine. ``The toughest part is convincing people there's still great
skiing up here.''
</P>
<P>
   But while officials at Killington boast their Vermont resort has
``the best snow-making equipment on the planet,'' smaller ski
operators without large capital budgets are clearly struggling.
</P>
<P>
   At the Blue Hills ski area, justoutside of Boston in Canton,
limited snow-making operations began Sunday night. Monday only
about 35 skiers were on the slopes, though snowmaking will continue
this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lose 25 percent or more of business if we aren't fully
operational this vacation week,'' said Blue Hills operator Stanley
Beers. ``And if you lose it, you never make it up. It's been this
way for the past three years. It's very, very tough.'' Traditional
New England resorts like the Woodstock Inn in Woodstock, Vt. and
The Balsams in Dixville Notch, N.H. saw no decline in business
because both resorts offer numerous other amenties for guests, many
repeat customers. Located deep in the North Woods and high in the
White Mountains, the Balsams even had enough natural snow to offer
cross-country skiing, as well as manmade snow on alpine trails.
</P>
<P>
   However, farther north in Pittsburg, N.H. businesses were hit
hard by the lack of snow. Here in the sparsely populated area along
the Canadian border, it's snowmobilers who are the winter cash
crop. And no matter how cold it gets, no one can afford to
manufacture the miles and miles of snow snowmobilers need.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we really need is a good storm,'' said Jim Kenny,
president of the North County Chamber of Commerce and owner of the
Northern Comfort Motel in nearby Colebrook. ``Usually that's not
hard to find. We got a couple of feet in November, but we lost it
all with the warm weather.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know any snow dances,'' Kenny added. ``But if I did, I
think I'd be doing them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
