<SLUG> BC-U.N.-TERROR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. SEEKS TO ENACT MEASURE TO CUT OFF FUNDS FOR TERRORISTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ In the waning days of this fall's General
Assembly session, a majority of nations, united by concerns about
terrorism, voted to establish an international agreement to stop
the flow of money to terrorist organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, the International Convention for the Suppression
of the Financing of Terrorism, is intended to encourage nations to
monitor closely the collection or deposit of funds by foreign
organizations that may be using the money to buy arms or to support
in other ways terrorists in another country.
</P>
<P>
   The convention asks governments to freeze such funds and to deny
groups or individuals the right to gain access to the money by
contending that any criminal acts committed are justifiable on
political, racial, ethnic or religious grounds. It asks governments
to extradite people found guilty of carrying out financial services
for terrorist groups.
</P>
<P>
   Under its provisions, the agreement will not go into effect
until at least 22 nations have signed and ratified it. That process
will begin in January.
</P>
<P>
   While many nations, large and small, welcomed the growing
international determination to cut off sources of income for
terrorist groups, the convention may be of most immediate help to
Sri Lanka, where a violent Tamil separatist movement against an
ethnic Sinhalese government has been sustained almost entirely by
money raised in ethnic Tamil communities in Canada, the United
States, India and Southeast Asia, diplomats and Sri Lankan
officials say.
</P>
<P>
   The separatist group, the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, has
over two decades eliminated all its more moderate Tamil rivals,
usually by killing them. It is suspected in the assassinations or
attempted assassinations of several prominent Sri Lankan
politicians, including government ministers. Most recently, the Sri
Lankan government blamed the Tigers for two bomb attacks on Dec.
18, one of which injured President Chandrika Kumaratunga just
before the vote in which she was re-elected to a second term.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has placed the Tamil Tigers on its list of
terrorist organizations, helping Sri Lanka in its efforts to draw
attention to the group's activities abroad. Sri Lanka, supported by
American and Canadian officials and ethnic Tamil community leaders
in other countries, says, for example, that the Tigers collect
money through intimidation from Tamils in Southeast Asia, and,
posing as victims of ethnic repression, use charitable front
organizations to raise money.
</P>
<P>
   With millions of dollars at their disposal, the Tigers buy arms
and pay to transport them to the north and east coasts of Sri
Lanka, where fierce fighting has gone on since the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The Tamil Tigers once had bases in the Indian state of Tamil
Nadu, across a narrow strait from Sri Lanka, where they received
training and help from Indian intelligence agencies and sympathetic
state officials. Those links have been cut by the Indian
government.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Rajiv Gandhi, a former Indian prime minister who sent
troops to Sri Lanka in 1987 to disarm the Tigers and other groups,
was assassinated in an attack that investigators said was planned
by the Tigers. He was killed at an election rally in Tamil Nadu by
a suicide bomber, who was identified as a member of the Tigers, in
an attack similar to the Dec. 18 assassination attempt on the Sri
Lankan president.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
