<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; INVEST _ &LR;  The rapidly growing importance of individual investors
has been one of the most remarkable developments in the U.S.
financial markets during the 20th century. By Arthur M. Louis
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; BANKS _ &LR;  At the dawn of the 20th century, the young city of San
Francisco was firmly established as the financial capital of the
West, its wealth amassed from Sierra gold, Nevada silver and the
growing agricultural outpouring of California's sun-washed valleys.
</P>
<P>
   One hundred years later, the city by the Bay is more than ever a
center of finance. But the sources of riches and the magnets for
capital include things undreamed of in 1900: computers, the
Internet, biotechnology. By Sam Zuckerman
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-99 2038EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991227.0345 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0250 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-BANKS-BANKS_SFCHRON &LR;      12-27 2205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKS-BANKS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 S.F. Banks Set National Trends  &HT;     By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
At the dawn of the 20th century, the young city of San Francisco
was firmly established as the financial capital of the West, its
wealth amassed from Sierra gold, Nevada silver and the growing
agricultural outpouring of California's sun-washed valleys.
<P>
   One hundred years later, the city by the Bay is more than ever a
center of finance. But the sources of riches and the magnets for
capital include things undreamed of in 1900: computers, the
Internet, biotechnology.
</P>
<P>
   In the past century, banks and brokerages have come and gone,
and proud names have risen and been erased. But San Francisco has
remained a wellspring of financial energy _ a place where new and
sometimes revolutionary ideas have taken root.
</P>
<P>
   Take branch banking, credit cards, discount stock brokerage and
online investing, which are now routine parts of the financial
lives of hundreds of millions of people around the world. San
Francisco entrepreneurs played major roles in spreading these
innovations. If not invented here, they first became marketplace
successes in the hands of banks and securities firms based in this
region.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Bay Area is the world headquarters for venture
capital, with the most important venture firms based here. More
public stock offerings are hatched here than any place in the
United States outside of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Schwab Corp., San Francisco born and bred, now stands as
one of the world's premiere financial firms, having conquered the
discount brokerage industry. Schwab and E-Trade Group, based in
Menlo Park, are No.1 and No.2 in the fast-growing online investing
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The region's financial influence has grown even as it has lost
many of its most powerful financial firms. San Francisco's biggest
banks _ most notably Bank of America _ have been taken over by
outsiders. Almost all of its homegrown investment banks have been
snapped up by far-off banks and brokerages.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Bay Area remains the world's most important nexus of
money and technology. The world's fastest-growing industries are
centered here. San Francisco and Silicon Valley are where the &LR; 
places &LR;  financial firms flock to manage stock offerings for  &LR; or
dole out merger advice to companies that are building the digital
infrastructure of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bay Area is the epicenter. It's where the information
economy gets financed,'' said Sandy Robertson, founder and former
chairman of Robertson Stephens, one of the San Francisco investment
banks that tied its fortunes to the technology industry, now owned
by Fleet Boston Financial Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Every top-tier U.S. investment bank today does a large portion
of its business from offices in San Francisco or Silicon Valley.
Wall Street powerhouse Credit Suisse First Boston may be based in
New York, but Frank Quattrone, the firm's superstar technology
dealmaker, plots strategy for IPOs from his office in Palo Alto.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Money for the Masses
</P>
<P>
   Like high finance, personal finance has changed dramatically for
Bay Area residents since 1900.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the century, banks catered mostly to the
propertied and privileged, those who owned businesses or farmland.
Ordinary people borrowed from family, friends, pawnshops or the
neighborhood moneylender.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virtually all banks that existed 100 years ago were
institutions founded by merchants and farmers for the purpose of
extending credit,'' said Andy Anderson, a historian employed by
Wells Fargo Bank.
</P>
<P>
   In 1900, Bank of California, which had risen to prominence
financing Nevada silver miners, was San Francisco's largest bank.
Wells Fargo was principally an express company that also did
banking through some 3,500 shipping offices throughout the West.
</P>
<P>
   Four years into the new century, Amadeo Peter Giannini, a
34-year-old son of Italian immigrant parents, opened a new bank in
San Francisco on the site of a former saloon. He dedicated his
enterprise to the then-unheard-of business of making loans to
ordinary shopkeepers and working people, often in amounts of $100
or less.
</P>
<P>
   Giannini's vision for his Bank of Italy was dismissed as
``pushcart marketing'' by other bankers. But the bank earned the
loyalty of customers and small shareholders, especially when it was
the first to extend credit _ from an improvised wooden counter on
the waterfront _ after the city's disastrous earthquake and fire in
1906.
</P>
<P>
   A few years later, when California liberalized banking laws,
Giannini bought a bank in his hometown of San Jose, establishing
Bank of Italy's first branch office. At the time, most banks
operated out of single offices.
</P>
<P>
   Giannini was the first to envision a far-flung chain of
branches. Despite obstacles thrown in his path by state and federal
regulators, Bank of Italy began buying banks throughout the state.
By 1927, Giannini had 276 branches in 199 California cities. Three
years later, he adopted the name Bank of America for his
institution.
</P>
<P>
   Giannini set his sights on expanding nationwide and moving into
insurance and securities. Federal regulators thwarted his plans,
but riding California's phenomenal growth after World War II, BofA
emerged as the world's largest bank.
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo, meanwhile, went in the opposite direction. When it
merged with Nevada National Bank in 1905, it split off its express
operations and began doing business out of a single San Francisco
office. It didn't venture into branch banking again until the
1950s.
</P>
<P>
   In 1958, BofA launched BankAmericard, the first successful bank
credit card. It wasn't the first bank charge card that extended
credit to holders. A New York bank had pioneered the idea seven
years before. But BofA promoted its card more aggressively and was
the first bank to build a critical mass of users and merchants.
</P>
<P>
   Soon it began franchising the card to other banks. In 1970, an
association of banks issuing the card was formed, an organization
whose name was later changed to Visa. Today Visa, headquartered
about 20 miles south of San Francisco in Foster City, is the
dominant credit card and one of the most powerful brand names in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Financial Prominence
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco started the century as a remote outpost of the
securities industry. By the end of the century, it had become one
of the industry's capitals, setting trends for corporate finance
and retail brokerage.
</P>
<P>
   The city's stock and bond exchange opened its doors in 1882,
trading the securities of local mining companies, municipal transit
concerns and utilities. In the 1920s, it established a ticker tape
link to the New York Stock Exchange, allowing local trading of the
Big Board's listed shares. Still, San Francisco's bourse was a
second-tier regional exchange, doing less business in a year than
the New York exchange did in a day.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's old-line brokerages _ such as Schwabacher and
Sutro _ managed the money of the local well-to-do. One exception,
Dean Witter, built a national business, ranking as one of the
nation's largest brokerages when it was bought by Chicago retail
giant Sears, Roebuck in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   By the late 1960s, the winds of change were blowing over the San
Francisco securities industry. Down the Peninsula, in a region that
had not yet earned the moniker Silicon Valley, corporations such as
Hewlett-Packard and National Semiconductor were building businesses
based on information technology. The new industry needed capital to
expand.
</P>
<P>
   Regional brokerages ``were making no attempt to understand the
technology world,'' recalled William Hambrecht, who opened his
investment bank, Hambrecht &AMP; Quist, in 1968 to fill the vacuum.
``The New York firms couldn't respond, so we did.``
</P>
<P>
   Within months, another firm opened with the same idea, an
investment bank later known as Robertson Stephens. An offshoot of
the firm became Montgomery Securities.
</P>
<P>
   The three firms and several others helped finance the Bay Area's
technology industry. Their clout grew as the computer,
semiconductor and software industries mushroomed.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990s, New York investment banks invaded the region in
force, and the Bay Area became the nation's second-most-important
center for raising capital.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the decade, H&AMP;Q, Robertson Stephens and Montgomery
had all been taken over by commercial banks based on the East
Coast. New firms emerged _ in some cases founded by the same
entrepreneurs who built the investment banks of the 1960s and
1970s, such as W.R. Hambrecht &AMP; Co., _ to raise capital by selling
IPO and private placement shares over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   During the last quarter of the century, Bay Area firms also
revolutionized the retail investment industry.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1975, the New York Stock Exchange ended fixed commissions
on stock sales. At the time, it often cost hundreds of dollars to
buy shares. Across the country, a handful of brokers recognized an
opportunity to slash commissions for clients who made their own
investment decisions. But it was an unknown San Francisco firm
started the year before, Charles Schwab &AMP; Co., which vaulted to the
top of the discount brokerage industry.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Schwab, a 38-year-old Sacramento native who had attended
Stanford University on a golf scholarship before entering the
securities business, turned discount brokerage into a crusade. He
traveled the country preaching his new gospel to anyone who would
listen.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional brokers didn't act in the interest of clients, he
argued. They encouraged customers to trade as often as possible in
order to earn commissions. It's better for investors to make their
own decisions and pay lower rates, Schwab insisted.
</P>
<P>
   The company started building branches around the country and
using Schwab's sincere, bespectacled image in its advertisements.
By 1983, when BofA bought the firm, it was the nation's largest
discount broker. Four years later, Schwab bought the company back
and took it public.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Schwab has ridden an investment boom to become the
securities firm with the highest stock market value in the nation.
Just two years ago, the firm remade itself by cutting commissions
for trading on the Internet. Today, more than 2 out of every 3
Schwab customer trades are carried out online, and the firm
dominates the electronic brokerage industry.
</P>
<P>
   The Bay Area is also home to the No.2 online brokerage, Menlo
Park's E-Trade, whose goal is nothing less than to become a global
provider of the entire gamut of financial services, from mortgages
and credit cards to IPOs.
</P>
<P>
   Once home to the world's largest bank, San Francisco's status as
a center of traditional banking has slipped in an era of
megamergers.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese banks bought Bank of California and Los Angeles' Union
Bank in the 1980s. In 1996, the two banks combined to form Union
Bank of California, based in San Francisco. Bank of
Tokyo-Mitsubishi owns about two-thirds of the bank's stock.
</P>
<P>
   After years of reckless lending around the world, BofA came
perilously close to failing in the early 1980s. When First
Interstate of Los Angeles made an unsuccessful hostile bid for the
bank in 1986, some predicted the Southern California metropolis
would eclipse San Francisco as a banking power.
</P>
<P>
   BofA recovered and ended up buying First Interstate's crosstown
rival, Security Pacific, in 1992. And four years later, First
Interstate was acquired by Wells Fargo, which had emerged as one of
the industry's best-regarded and toughest competitors.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase catapulted Wells Fargo from California to a
presence throughout the West. But its overly aggressive plan for
combining the two banks caused service breakdowns and customer
defections.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, a weakened Wells Fargo was bought by Minneapolis's
Norwest Corp., which moved its headquarters to San Francisco and
kept the acquired bank's name. The new Wells Fargo is the nation's
seventh-largest bank and the largest bank based in the West.
</P>
<P>
   BofA itself was swept away in banking's merger wave, gobbled up
by North Carolina's NationsBank in 1998. NationsBank chief
executive Hugh McColl cast aside his pledge to make the combination
a merger of equals, fired BofA's former chief executive, David
Coulter, and reduced San Francisco to a regional headquarters of
his bank, which kept the BofA name.
</P>
<P>
   The Bay Area had once been the headquarters for dozens of
savings and loans, institutions created to finance home ownership.
Ill-planned expansion created a financial crisis in the industry
during the late 1980s and early 1990s. Some local thrifts failed,
while many others were swallowed up by stronger rivals.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the century, only a handful of local S&AMP;Ls remain.
Two rank among the industry's giants: San Francisco's CalFed Bank
is No.2 and Oakland's World Savings is No.3 among the nation's
thrifts.
</P>
<P>
   In the space of a century, Bay Area finance has gone from an era
of green eyeshades and rolltop desks to ATMs and online stock
trading. But, despite wrenching changes, when the subject is money,
San Francisco and its environs still rank as the most powerful
place in the West.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
