<SLUG> BC-CHAMPAGNE-OPENING-IT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LESS SPRAY, MORE PLAY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: With CHAMPAGNE and CHAMPAGNE-TOASTS) 
By NATALIE HAUGHTON 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that you have a terrific bottle of champagne to ring in the
millennium, what's the most expedient way to open it without
exploding it and spraying it everywhere or blinding someone with
the cork?
</P>
<P>
   Make sure the wine is well chilled (at least four to six hours
in the refrigerator) before attempting to open it. It should be 40
to 45 degrees F.
</P>
<P>
   Point the cork end of the bottle away from you. Remove the foil
wrapper.
</P>
<P>
   Cover the top of the bottle with a heavy towel or cloth.
</P>
<P>
   Untwist the wire cage but do not remove it (some experts remove
the wire cage). Keep a thumb on top of the bottle to prevent an
unexpected pop of the cork.
</P>
<P>
   Holding the bottle at a 45 degree angle, gently twist the cork
(with its wire cage) in one direction (holding the cork down with
steady pressure) and the bottle in the opposite direction. GENTLY
ease the cork from the bottle with a delicate pop or hissing sound,
not a loud bang. The more momentum you have when the cork pops, the
more effervescence and champagne you lose.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-99 2042EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991227.0348 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0253 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-INVEST-INVEST_SFCHRON     12-27 1356
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-INVEST </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Discount Brokerages, Online Trading Helped Change Investing  &HT;     By Arthur M. Louis 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
The rapidly growing importance of individual investors has been one
of the most remarkable developments in the U.S. financial markets
during the 20th century.
<P>
   For most of the century, individuals were kept ``at the end of a
long food chain that started with institutional investors,'' such
as insurance companies, banks and pension funds, observes Dan
Leemon, executive vice president for business strategy with Charles
Schwab Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Institutions controlled the bulk of the money, they traded
heavily, and they got loving attention from brokers and other
financial-service providers.
</P>
<P>
   But today, after nearly two decades of relentless buying, more
than half of all U.S. households own stocks either directly or
through mutual funds. Those holdings are worth roughly $10
trillion.
</P>
<P>
   The individual investor, Leemon says, ``has assumed his or her
role alongside the institutional investor.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that individual investors are throwing so much weight around
in the market, they, too, are being ardently courted by purveyors
of financial services.
</P>
<P>
   The staggering growth of the mutual-fund industry _ which caters
almost exclusively to individuals _ is a sign of that.
</P>
<P>
   Other signs include the proliferation of discount brokers, the
rapid development of online trading and investment research, the
extension of after-hours trading to individuals as well as
institutions and the greater availability of initial public
offerings to individuals.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the century, individual stock ownership was
confined primarily to a small coterie of wealthy people _ business
proprietors, their families, associates and friends. The rest of
the population needed whatever money it could muster just to make
ends meet.
</P>
<P>
   Individuals entered the stock market in great numbers for the
first time during the widespread economic prosperity that began in
the mid-1920s. The value of stocks owned by individuals swelled to
$5 billion in 1929 from less than $2 billion at the start of the
decade.
</P>
<P>
   It was a wild time in the market _ not unlike the present.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were buying tips, investing on momentum _ if something
goes up, buy it _ and often on margin,'' says W. Roger Servison,
executive vice president and managing director of Fidelity
Investments. ``It was highly speculative.''
</P>
<P>
   The October 1929 stock-market crash and the Depression that
followed blew most individual investors out of the market.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't return in a big way until three decades later,
during the waning years of the Eisenhower administration, when the
nation began another period of sustained prosperity and stock
prices again shot up.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, individuals fled yet again during the deep, grinding bear
market of 1973-74.
</P>
<P>
   The flow of individuals into stocks and mutual funds has
accelerated greatly since the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   That's partly because the market became wildly attractive during
that period, with the Dow Jones industrial average rocketing
fourteenfold from its 1982 bear-market low of less than 800 to more
than 11,000 in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   The other big reason _ as many readers of this article  &LR; know too
well _ is that the great corporate cost-cutting movement of recent
decades has revolutionized pensions, forcing workers to fend more
for themselves if they hope to properly fund their retirements.
</P>
<P>
   The old-style, standard, defined-benefit pension plans _ which
guaranteed workers a comfortable annual income once they retired,
no matter what _ are on their way out. Corporations consider it too
risky and expensive to continue providing such guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   In their place have sprung up an assortment of
defined-contribution plans _ most notably, 401(k)s and individual
retirement accounts _ whose benefits can vary widely, depending on
how successfully the contributions are invested.
</P>
<P>
   Most workers still are entitled to a modest, defined-benefit
pension in the form of Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   But economists and policymakers have expressed doubt that the
Social Security system will be solvent by the time today's younger
generation retires. That uncertainty has given individuals still
more incentive to invest in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the money flowing into 401(k) plans gets channeled into
stock mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   Just 30 years ago, the mutual-fund industry was a genteel
backwater of the investment world. There were only about 300 funds,
with total assets of around $50 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the biggest mutual fund alone _ Fidelity Magellan _
boasts assets of more than twice that amount, and the industry as a
whole is swarming with 7,000 funds holding some $3 trillion in
investor assets.
</P>
<P>
   Mutual funds now own about 20 percent of all publicly traded
U.S. stocks. That's up from less than 15 percent five years ago,
according to Chris Wioszczyna, a spokesman for the Investment
Company Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Individual investors also can claim considerable credit for the
huge reductions in brokerage commissions.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the century, commissions were noncompetitive. The
industry's self-regulatory bodies decreed that any given trade must
cost exactly the same regardless of who you were or which broker
you used.
</P>
<P>
   After commissions were deregulated in the mid-1970s,
institutional investors _ thanks to their heavy trading volume _
got big discounts from their brokers. They typically paid
commissions of 6 or 7 cents per share, while many individuals had
to pay upward of $1 per share.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the discount brokers, led by such pioneers as Schwab,
which got its start in San Francisco a quarter-century ago. They
had the foresight to coddle individual investors when there weren't
all that many of them.
</P>
<P>
   The early wave of discounts cut commission costs by 50 to 80
percent. The latest wave _ made possible by online trading, which
is far less labor-intensive than other forms of brokerage _ has cut
commissions to the point where they are negligible.
</P>
<P>
   Now you can buy or sell as many as 5,000 shares of stock for a
flat commission as low as $5 to $10 per trade _ as little as 0.1
cent per share.
</P>
<P>
   That has encouraged individuals to trade more heavily than they
did in the past _ behavior that undoubtedly endears them to their
brokers, though not necessarily to their heirs.
</P>
<P>
   Some market historians wonder how long the new Era of the
Individual Investor can last. They keep harking back to those other
periods when individuals had a fling with stocks, only to flee in
panic when the market faltered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typically, at some point, these cycles end,'' Fidelity's
Servison warns. ``We seem to be getting near the peak of enthusiasm
for stocks. When companies with no revenues go up eight- or tenfold
in a single day, you've got to say that there's an awful lot of
optimism that may not be fully warranted.''
</P>
<P>
   Other experts feel that individual investors will show more
staying power than they have in the past.
</P>
<P>
   James Spellman, a spokesman for the Securities Industry
Association, says individual participation in the stock market
clearly is becoming deeply entrenched.
</P>
<P>
   He notes that the national fixation on stocks has been filtering
down to kids who aren't old enough to buy securities on their own.
The SIA sponsors a stock-market education program in schools, and
700,000 kids are participating this year _ up from 415,000 in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Bernstein, chief quantitative strategist with Merrill
Lynch, thinks individual investors will hang in there if the market
turns sour, if only for one compelling reason: ``Individual
participation is going to continue unless someone does away with
defined-contribution plans.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Steinberg, chief executive of Individual Investor
Group, which publishes several financial magazines, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we talk again in another 100 years, there will have been a
lot of bumps in the meantime,'' he observes. ``But the basic trends
of greater individual participation will continue.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
