</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-MENTAL-HEALTH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERIMENT OF PRIVATIZING A FLORIDA MENTAL HOSPITAL SHOWS
BENEFITS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(DW) 
 By BARRY MEIER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEMBROKE PINES, Fla. _ Mental health care advocates long viewed
South Florida State Psychiatric Hospital here as a dumping ground,
a place where patients were treated poorly, languished for years
and died mysteriously.
</P>
<P>
   South Florida State, only a few years ago threatened with
closing as the way to solve its problems, is now at the heart of an
experiment. Experts say it is the first state mental hospital in
the nation to be turned over completely to a private company that
hopes to operate it at a profit.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 legislators in Florida, which was involved in a long
court battle to improve conditions at the hospital, voted to
contract out its operation. The winning bidder was a subsidiary of
Wackenhut Corrections Corp., one of the companies that started the
boom in private-enterprise prisons a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Many local advocates for the mentally ill were initially
horrified that a prison company was taking over a mental hospital,
but they now say that conditions here have improved. For example,
patients, rather than staying indefinitely, are put into treatment
programs intended to get them out.
</P>
<P>
   Wackenhut Corrections officials say they are making money but
refuse to say how much. The company is paid $32 million a year to
operate the hospital, its budget when it was run by the Florida
Department of Children and Families. The company's profit will come
from cost savings.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking over the hospital in November 1998, the Wackenhut
subsidiary, Atlantic Shores Healthcare, has reduced full-time
positions to 500 from 720, and it plans to cut 80 more jobs, to pay
for a new building.
</P>
<P>
   George Zoley, the chief executive of Wackenhut Corrections, said
further staff reductions would not affect care because the new
building would centralize the hospital's operation, making it
easier to manage.
</P>
<P>
   Some mental health experts say they fear that Wackenhut is
spending more at South Florida State now than it will in the future
because its track record there will help it market itself to other
states.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are going to use this as a poster facility to win
contracts in other states, they ought to be operating it in the
black,'' said Patty Cooper, a program director in Florida with the
Advocacy Center, a federally funded group that works on behalf on
the mentally disabled.
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of states have contracted with private
companies to operate mental health services, including community
clinics, substance abuse programs and homes for troubled youth.
With billions of dollars involved, companies large and small have
jumped into the arena, promising to operate programs more
efficiently and effectively than public agencies.
</P>
<P>
   While some mental health experts say privatization has led to
improved services in some states, programs elsewhere have collapsed
amid accusations that companies shortchanged patients or even
abused them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a vast social experiment at this point whether private
companies can serve as effective intermediaries to coordinate
health care,'' said Steven Findlay, research director at the
National Institute for Health Care Management, a nonprofit group in
Washington. ``And mental health care is a lot more pragmatic than
health care in general''
</P>
<P>
   Amid this transition, the 260 state psychiatric hospitals
nationwide have largely resisted such change.
</P>
<P>
   The number of such hospitals has been sharply cut. Because of
moves over the past decade to deinstitutionalize the mentally ill,
the number of patients has dropped just as sharply, to 59,000 in
1996 from about 560,000 in 1955, according to the Center for Mental
Health Services, a federal agency.
</P>
<P>
   The hospitals now serve the most seriously ill patients, and
federal statistics suggest that states spend about half their
mental health care budgets to operate them.
</P>
<P>
   Some states have moved to close psychiatric hospitals and send
patients to facilities owned by private companies that get patients
with private insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining public mental hospitals like South Florida State,
which is west of Fort Lauderdale, are often remnants of a different
era. South Florida State, which was opened in the late 1950s, is on
a campus dotted with low-slung cottages, ficuses and palms. Once
home to 1,500 patients, it now houses up to 350.
</P>
<P>
   At South Florida State, the vast majority of patients are
involuntarily committed by judges who determine that they are a
danger to themselves or others. Others are committed after being
found not guilty of a crime by reason of insanity.
</P>
<P>
   While states sought out private companies to build prisons
because they wanted more jail space, there are ample psychiatric
hospital beds. Wackenhut's chief executive, Zoley, said there might
be another powerful incentive to privatize the hospitals: Many
states face court orders or Justice Department actions to improve
care at them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are approaching other states, and other states are
interested,'' Zoley said.
</P>
<P>
   As with prisons, Zoley said, he believes that a company can
improve conditions and run a mental hospital more efficiently than
a state agency because it can, among other things, contract for
services quickly and cheaply.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly a decade, South Florida State was at the center of a
legal battle. In 1989, mental health care advocates sued the state
after finding conditions at the hospital like a lack of toilets and
patients wandering around naked, said Alice K. Nelson, a lawyer
with Southern Legal Counsel, a public interest law firm in
Gainesville.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, the state and advocates entered into a consent decree
under which Florida pledged to improve living conditions. But the
advocates, displeased with the pace of change, continued to fight
in court over patient issues.
</P>
<P>
   As the battle played out, Florida officials considered closing
the hospital. Then in 1997, the Florida Legislature voted to
privatize it, and the legislation was passed and signed by the
governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an opportunity to do something different,'' said State
Rep. Debby Sanderson, a Fort Lauderdale Republican who was one of
the privatization bill's sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Several companies including Magellan Health Services, which
administers mental health programs for several states nationwide,
expressed interest. In the end Atlantic Shores Healthcare, which
was formed around the time of the Florida bill, was the only
bidder.
</P>
<P>
   The company's experience was limited. Wackenhut Corrections
provides psychiatric services to inmates in prisons it runs, and
Atlantic Shores Healthcare bought a small private psychiatric
hospital in 1997 in Fort Lauderdale as it prepared to bid on the
Florida contract.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials quickly found, however, that running a large
state mental hospital involved far bigger challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Under the state's operation, for example, patients at South
Florida State could smoke when they wanted, buy snacks when they
pleased or roam the hospital grounds if they desired. Atlantic
Shores Healthcare officials proposed banning smoking and restricted
access to vending machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right away, they came in and brought in changes that affected
everyone, and the patients didn't have a say in it,'' said Robert
Bowyer, who was treated at the hospital for manic depression.
</P>
<P>
   Those changes stirred fears among some advocates for the
mentally ill that the company was transferring its prison industry
roots to a mental health setting. Officials soon backed off some
changes, like the proposed ban on smoking. Vending machines were
kept in place, but color-coded to alert patients with diabetes, for
example, to snacks that are laden with sugar.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
