u a BC-FLA-MENTAL-HEALTH-ART     12-27 0306
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-MENTAL-HEALTH-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
PEMBROKE PINES, Fla.: with sugar.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sal Barbera, the hospital's administrator, said that some of the
new restrictions, like those involving food, were important because
they affected a patient's health or interfered with medication. But
Barbera acknowledged that the company had moved too quickly and
without consulting patients or advocates.
</P>
<P>
   Still, most area advocates say the company has moved to improve
conditions at the hospital. Anita Godfrey, president of the Mental
Health Association of Broward County, said patients were receiving
better treatment. And this year the hospital was accredited by the
Joint Commission on Accreditation of Healthcare Organization, a
national group that surveys hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Under the five-year contract, the state approves all admissions
and discharges and monitors the company's compliance with its
contract.
</P>
<P>
   Another subsidiary of Wackenhut Corrections is building a
psychiatric hospital here that is being financed by public bonds.
In order to pay the annual $3 million debt on those bonds, 80 more
staff positions at South Florida State will soon be cut.
</P>
<P>
   Even supporters of the company's efforts say it is too early to
tell whether the company will succeed. Though Atlantic Shores
Healthcare has set a goal of minimizing patient stays,
community-based mental health programs here, like elsewhere in the
country, often lack the resources to take those set for discharge.
</P>
<P>
   Findlay, the health care expert, said that he believed it would
take at least three years to amass the data to determine success
here. His concern, he said, is that Florida officials, now that
they have shed a problem, may simply forget to keep track of how
the hospital evolves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can only hope that the state watches it carefully,''
Findlay said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
