<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-BRAZIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRINT BARRED FROM MANAGING ITS BRAZILIAN SUBSIDIARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ In a decision that may shake up Brazil's
long-distance industry, Sprint Corp. was barred from managing its
Brazilian subsidiary after its partner in the company, National
Grid PLC of Britain, persuaded a court that delicate corporate
information might be disclosed to MCI Worldcom.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling, which effectively removes Sprint from participation
in day-to-day decisions at Intelig, a start-up concern formed
together with National Grid and France Telecom SA, came after MCI
Worldcom announced plans earlier this year to acquire Sprint. MCI
Worldcom already operates Brazil's dominant long-distance carrier,
called Embratel.
</P>
<P>
   ``If National Grid were to hope to compete in any way, it was
crucial for them to get Sprint out of the venture,'' said Carlos
Eduardo Siqueira, a telecommunications analyst with Banco BBA
Creditanstalt. ``Now that this is under way, the next step is to
find a new partner that will help in selling Intelig to the
Brazilian consumer.''
</P>
<P>
   The jostling among partners in Intelig comes at a crucial time
for the company, which plans to begin operations next month.
National Grid, which owns 50 percent of Intelig, with Sprint and
France Telecom holding 25 percent stakes, is one of several
companies hoping to grab market share amid the gradual deregulation
of telecommunications in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Yet while National Grid's plans seemed fine last year, when it
acquired a license to provide long-distance service, they were
thrown into doubt with the MCI Worldcom deal for Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   Government regulators in Brazil had expressed concern about the
merger because the subsidiaries operated by the two companies are
the only competitors in providing a breadth of long-distance
services to individuals and companies. But regulators have not
moved to force Sprint to divest itself of its holdings, apparently
awaiting for U.S. regulators to complete their review of the
merger.
</P>
<P>
   National Grid and France Telecom, however, could not wait. ``The
situation would be chaotic otherwise, with trust among the partners
at stake,'' said Marcio Simoes, an editor of RNT, a Brazilian
telecommunications magazine.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Sprint declined to comment on the ruling, which
was handed down by a Rio de Janeiro court on Monday, citing a
company policy against speaking on pending litigation.
</P>
<P>
   In the Brazilian legal system, a ruling affecting business
matters can often be upheld or overturned several times during a
lengthy appeals process before high courts in Brasilia make a final
decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
