r e BC-FILM-MR-DEATH-REVIEW-     12-27 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MR-DEATH-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY `MR. DEATH'?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: EMBARGOED until Wednesday, Dec. 29. Fact box below) 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Errol Morris has a deserved reputation for reinventing the
documentary form into something more self-consciously artistic. But
his basic schtick _ disorienting stock changes, repetitive staged
shots set to mesmerizing music, a predilection for oddball subjects
_ is getting rather tedious.
</P>
<P>
   Combine that with an individual who, to put it mildly, did not
need to have a movie made about him, and you've got the strange
case of ``Mr. Death: The Rise and Fall of Fred A. Leuchter, Jr.'' A
character worthy, perhaps, of a TV newsmagazine segment (Leuchter
was, in fact, profiled on ``PrimeTime Live'' and was originally
considered by Morris for his last compilation of eccentric
obsessives, ``Fast, Cheap and Out of Control''), Leuchter is an
execution wonk who made a big mistake. And when your purpose in
life is building better killing machines, the mistake threshold is
a pretty severe one.
</P>
<P>
   A rodentlike little man who wears big glasses and ugly ties,
Leuchter spends the first part of the movie speaking
matter-of-factly about developing ``non-torturing'' execution
devices in a serious Boston accent. The son of a prison worker, he
had been fascinated by the penal killing field since childhood, and
although he never studied engineering, his singular devotion to
building better deathtraps won him contracts with a number of state
prison systems.
</P>
<P>
   But while his desire to facilitate humane executions appears
sincere enough, his under-educated but overweening ego proved
Leuchter's downfall. Sought out by a Canadian neo-Nazi on trial for
disseminating hate literature, ``expert'' Leuchter flew to
Auschwitz (on his honeymoon, no less) to illegally collect samples
from the gas chamber ruins. A bad chemical analysis resulted in
false evidence that made up the infamous ``Leuchter Report,'' which
Holocaust deniers have tried to exploit ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Morris gives us endless, artsy footage of Leuchter (or someone
like him) chiseling away at the Auschwitz walls (or something like
them). The intended effect, I guess, is to show us the misguided
effort that went into the despicable report, but it rather
inadvertently also gives the impression that Leuchter was a
conscientious, hard-working researcher. Ditto the more interesting
but highly questionable footage of Leuchter defending his work; his
efforts genuinely seem to spring from stubbornness rather than
prejudice, but his clueless self-justifications make him look like
a victim as often as a fool.
</P>
<P>
   Morris apparently feels that Leuchter represents the archetypal,
banality-of-evil potential that supposedly resides within us all.
But the fact is that this fellow was deeply peculiar from the
start, the product of one warped system of state-sanctioned murder
who, however subconsciously, wound up trying to excuse an
infinitely more heinous one. It's a cautionary story, all right,
but who exactly might want to follow in Mr. Death's uniquely
crooked footsteps? &QL; 
____ &QL; 
The film: ``Mr. Death: The Rise and Fall of Fred A. Leuchter, Jr.''
(PG-13; language, racism). &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Errol Morris. Produced by Michael
Williams, David Collins and Dorothy Aufiero. Released by Lions Gate
Films. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 31 minutes. &QL; 
Playing: Nuart, West L.A. &QL; 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
