</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HABITAT-FORECLOSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HABITAT IN DETROIT SEEKS TO FORECLOSE ON DELINQUENT HOME
RECIPIENTS 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Mich., Ga.)  (jw) 
 By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Habitat for Humanity, the organization that gathers
volunteers to hammer together houses for poor families, is
preparing to foreclose on as many as 14 of the 70 families it has
housed here.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of these folks are seriously delinquent _ any bank would
have had these people on the street months and months ago,'' said
Robert Arcand, executive director of Habitat for Humanity Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Habitat is known less as a lender than as a home builder. The
nonprofit organization buys wood, bricks and other supplies, then
organizes volunteers who join a family in constructing a modest
house. Habitat then gives the family a loan without interest for up
to 30 years to pay for the building materials and uses the monthly
payments to build more houses in the area.
</P>
<P>
   The Detroit Habitat office has sent legal notices to the 14
families, beginning foreclosure proceedings against them, Arcand
said. The foreclosures were first reported Monday in The Detroit
News.
</P>
<P>
   In Detroit, a fifth of the 70 Habitat homeowners are behind in
their payments, and one never paid at all, said Kenneth Bensen,
president of the board of Michigan Habitat for Humanity.
</P>
<P>
   Habitat builds about 300 houses a year statewide, but last year
built just nine in Detroit, the nation's poorest big city. ``We're
building more in Grand Rapids and Kalamazoo,'' Bensen said.
</P>
<P>
   But Arcand, who wants the money so the organization can build
more houses in Detroit, said the 14 families were not the only ones
to blame.
</P>
<P>
   For two years after the last executive director quit, Habitat's
Detroit office was run by a secretary and a bookkeeper with some
help from volunteers. When people fell behind on their loans, or
simply failed to make monthly payments, not much happened. Word
spread, and more Habitat families took advantage of free housing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We erred too frequently on the side of compassion and
sensitivity in the past, and we've got to take steps to rectify
it,'' said Arcand, who joined in January and has been trying to
rebuild the Detroit office. ``We had to put the brakes on.''
</P>
<P>
   Going easy on the recipients hurts them in the long run, said
Bensen, a former member of Habitat's Detroit board.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some responsibility that rests on both sides,'' he
said. ``Part of it is that our board did not go and ask for the
money and allowed them to get too far in the hole.''
</P>
<P>
   The large number of foreclosure cases here is unusual for
Habitat for Humanity, said Dennis Bender, a spokesman for Habitat
for Humanity International, based in Americus, Ga. Nationwide,
Habitat forecloses on just 1 percent of the loans it makes, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very unusual to have something like this,'' Bender said.
``It is our desire to provide homes, not to remove people from ones
they have been living in.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, the Detroit action is justified. ``It is unfair
to people who are waiting for future homes to not have the
repayment cycle,'' Bender said.
</P>
<P>
   Habitat typically builds 1,100-square-foot, three-bedroom
houses, with an average market value in Michigan of $65,000, Bensen
said. The families, after helping build their homes, pay mortgages
that cover construction costs _ about $42,500. Monthly payments are
roughly $400, and cover both the mortgage and taxes, Bensen said.
</P>
<P>
   To qualify for a Habitat house in Detroit, the family's income
must be less than 80 percent of the city's median household income.
In Detroit, families could earn up to $14,994 a year to qualify for
a home.
</P>
<P>
   Having built just 70 houses in the past 13 years, the Detroit
branch of Habitat is planning to build 50 next year, and, with
enough donations, work its way up to 150 homes a year three years
from now, Arcand said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-99 2106EST &QL; 
