<DOCNO> NYT19991227.0360 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0273 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-Y2K-PEACE-CORPS-NYT &LR;      12-27 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-PEACE-CORPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEACE CORPS TAKES STEPS ON YEAR 2000 
</HEADLINE>
  (Also moving in `i' category; with Y2K-PUBLIC, moved `f.') 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Peace Corps has urged some volunteers to return
home for the holidays and is moving others to safer locations,
among a series of precautionary measures for the New Year,
officials of the organization said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The exact impact of the New Year holiday on more than 7,000
volunteers in 78 countries around the world is uncertain, but Peace
Corps directors in each country are working with volunteers, local
governments and host-country staff members to minimize potential
disruptions and ensure personal safety.
</P>
<P>
   In some countries, officials have warned, serious computer
problems associated with the rollover to the year 2000 could cut
off food supplies, electricity, transportation and telephone
services. The Peace Corps has encouraged volunteers in these areas
to spend vacation time in the United States, said Dana Topousis, an
organization spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers in Belize, Madagascar, Moldova, Mozambique, Slovakia,
Zambia and Zimbabwe are expected to leave their sites; others in
Jamaica, Nepal and Papua New Guinea may also relocate.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Topousis said the Peace Corps had also been monitoring those
countries for which the State Department had issued travel alerts.
The department released what it called a ``worldwide terrorism
warning'' advising Americans to stay away from ``large gatherings
and celebrations'' throughout the world, and also warned against
travel to specific regions, like the Khyber Pass between Pakistan
and Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   Peace Corps directors in each country drew up plans for
volunteers in the field, Ms. Topousis said. In some cases,
volunteers will remain at their sites. Volunteers in large
countries, like Russia, will congregate in small groups at larger
regional centers. In smaller countries, volunteers and Peace Corps
staff members will gather in capital cities.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers have received a checklist for the country where they
are serving, with an emergency action plan. And in a few countries
with severe weather concerns, volunteers will receive emergency
kits, with sleeping bags, flashlights, batteries, extra clothing,
additional medical supplies and food items.
</P>
<P>
   Most Peace Corps headquarters are equipped with generators in
case of the loss of electricity, but in some countries in Eastern
Europe, West Africa and South America, satellite telephones have
also been provided.
</P>
<P>
   Roslyn Docktor, the year 2000 director for the Peace Corps, said
the organization had begun preparations in the spring of 1997,
sending surveys to country directors to learn about their concerns.
Peace Corps officials at headquarters in each country, for example,
considered whether rural or urban locations were at greater risk.
The most important issue, Ms. Docktor said, is that organization
officials are able to contact volunteers at all times.
</P>
<P>
   ``The directors must be as informed as they can be about risks
in their countries,'' Ms. Docktor said.
</P>
<P>
   She said extensive work that the organization had done through
the years in countries with developmental problems afforded the
organization a unique advantage for handling challenges that the
new year might pose. The Peace Corps, she added, has set up an
operations center to answer questions from families and friends of
volunteers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-99 2109EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991227.0361 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0274 &Cx1f; tth-z
u l BC-WORLDSEND-RELIGION-SP     12-27 1603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLDSEND-RELIGION-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW THE WORLD ENDS IS A MATTER OF FAITH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By D. PARVAZ  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You probably want to know when and how the world's going to end,
right?
</P>
<P>
   As you must suspect, there is no definitive answer.
</P>
<P>
   For some, the details of The End depend on religious faith and
the calendar, but there are plenty of faiths and calendars to
choose from.
</P>
<P>
   What follows are general interpretations of the end of the world
_ at least as we know it _ in the classical texts of the world's
major faiths. To further complicate things, not all people
belonging to these faiths interpret the texts in the same way.
</P>
<P>
   The Second Coming,
</P>
<P>
   disasters and
</P>
<P>
   general chaos
</P>
<P>
   Most monotheistic or single-God religions _ the major ones being
Christianity, Islam and Judaism _ have a linear theory of time.
</P>
<P>
   There's a beginning and an end, and the end usually ain't
pretty.
</P>
<P>
   More often than not, it involves a battle between divine and
demonic principles, says Martin Jaffee, chair of the Comparative
Religion Program at the University of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   These religions have other similarities, including redemption
for the pious. Jaffee says there are usually long stretches of time
during which the devout work for their redemption. That, he says,
is the reward of the righteous.
</P>
<P>
   Also, these religions tend to have a sense of Judgment Day _ a
nasty, doomsday end followed by God's judgment of all people and
then a heaven/hell scenario.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all,'' Jaffee says, ``part of the thrill of redemption
is seeing your persecutors punished.''
</P>
<P>
   Christianity _ Millions of Christians worldwide look to the
start of the new millennium as a spiritually significant day. Some
interpretations of the Bible hold it as the day when the prophecies
in the Book of Revelation begin to come true.
</P>
<P>
   For other Christians, the day may signify the start of the
events leading to the Second Coming.
</P>
<P>
   Interpretations of Biblical predictions vary greatly among
scholars and churches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many scholars believe that many of the events have already
taken place _ like the 1879 destruction of Jerusalem, which was
predicted in the scriptures,'' says Pastor Fred Kropp of the City
Church, a non-denominational Christian church in Kirkland.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the signs of the Last Day in the Book of Revelation
include:
</P>
<P>
   _Harsh weather changes.
</P>
<P>
   _False messiahs appearing around the world.
</P>
<P>
   _Global persecution of Christians.
</P>
<P>
   _The mark of the beast (Satan) appears in world commerce. Some
believers have held that bar codes, ATM cards and credit cards are
all part of Satan's scheme to force his mark on people.
</P>
<P>
   _Drought and famine.
</P>
<P>
   _The Antichrist returns as the false messiah. Adolf Hitler,
Mikhail Gorbachev and Sadam Hussein all have been labeled as
Antichrist figures.
</P>
<P>
   _A great war _ possibly World War III _ breaks out.
</P>
<P>
   Kropp explains that the Four Horsemen of the Apocalypse bring
with them a seven-year period of chaos and destruction otherwise
known as the tribulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, every major catastrophe will take place,'' says
Kropp, who rattles off a list of disasters that includes war,
disease, famine, drought, earthquakes and the implosion of the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the question of when the Rapture will happen. The
Rapture _ not referred to in the Bible by that term _ is when
Christ takes Christian souls to heaven without them dying. These
people will just disappear.
</P>
<P>
   Some hold that the rapture will happen before the tribulation,
some think during, others think after.
</P>
<P>
   As as for when these things will happen, Kropp says the Bible is
pretty clear _ only God knows when the end of the world will come.
</P>
<P>
   Judaism _ Judaism has the least harsh version of how things will
end. In fact, you can't really qualify it as an end, because
according to the scriptures, things continue on. One way of living
ends, another begins.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi David Fine of the Jewish Education Council locally says
Jews believe that at a certain point in time, the Messianic Age
will come. This may or may not correlate with the end of the Jewish
calendar, due in about 2,240 years.
</P>
<P>
   Some Jews see the age as an actual period during which a messiah
_ a political figure rather than a savior of souls _ will restore
the Davidian Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   How do we know when the Messianic Age has arrived? ``When the
hearts of parents will be turned towards their children and when
the hearts of children will turn towards the parents,'' says Fine,
quoting Judaic scriptures.
</P>
<P>
   The signs of the impending Messianic age are fairly general _ no
demons, no fire, no brimstone. ``The Jewish idea of the Messianic
Age is the age of peace. It's not an apocalypse,'' Fine says.
</P>
<P>
   The Jewish notion of the end of this world also includes an
afterlife, but it's unique in that it entails bringing the dead
back to this world.
</P>
<P>
   There is no final Judgment Day in the Jewish faith, Fine says.
Instead, Jews believe that they are being judged every day.
</P>
<P>
   As for heaven and hell, well, that's not so clear either.
``That's one of the mysteries. What happens after we die? We don't
know,'' Fine says.
</P>
<P>
   Islam: Unlike some other religions, Muslims believe that what is
in their holy book, the Koran, is not up for interpretation. ``We
don't have that luxury,'' says Abdul-Latif of the Islamic
Information Center of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   As for when the world will end, Abdul-Latif quotes the Koran,
``The knowledge of the hour is with Allah alone.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Mohammed reveals the signs of ``the hour'' _ or the end
of the world _ to the angel Gabriel as follows (in no particular
order):
</P>
<P>
   _The False Christ will appear in the form of a Jew named
Abdulah. He will have one bulging blind eye, will be heavy-set and
will perform acts that non-Muslims will view as miracles _
resurrect the dead, grow crops from barren lands, etc.
</P>
<P>
   _The beast (Satan) will appear.
</P>
<P>
   _Shi'ite Muslims believe that the 12th imam (prophet), Mahdi,
will return just before Issah (Jesus) and lead Muslims in prayer.
</P>
<P>
   _Jesus will appear in Syria wearing a saffron yellow robe. He
will follow the Koran and the words of the Mohammed. ``He will
marry, have children and die like a real human being,'' Abdul-Latif
says.
</P>
<P>
   _Gog and Magog _ a massive, ruthless tribe _ will finally scale
the wall built to fence them in. They will swarm the earth,
pillaging and looting
</P>
<P>
   _The sun will set, then rise from the west; a fire will start in
the Middle East that will force people to move and gather in one
place. There will be a great deal of killing and general moral
decline.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there will be The Big War between the Jews and Muslims,
who will be joined by the Christian army. Then Allah will send a
wind and sweep up all the souls of true Muslims and take them to
heaven.
</P>
<P>
   ``We firmly believe that whoever among the people heard about
Allah and Mohammed and didn't believe in them will die as a
disbeliever, will burn in hell,'' Abdul-Latif says. But before
that, the souls remaining on Earth will be consumed by powerful
earthquakes, mayhem and what the Koran refers to as ``the snorting
of war steeds.''
</P>
<P>
   Cycles of rebirth
</P>
<P>
   The two major world religions with cyclical concept of time _
Hinduism and Buddhism _ stand as total opposites in every way to
the single-God religions in their views on the apocalypse.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, the end is never really the end _ it is the end of
a cycle and the start of another. Therefore, there is no afterlife,
heaven or hell.
</P>
<P>
   Hinduism: Hindu apocalyptic theory involves the trinity of
Brahma, the creator; Vishnu, the preserver; and Shiva, the
destroyer.
</P>
<P>
   Most Hindus believe in reincarnation, so time is cyclical, with
each cycle slightly shorter and darker that the last. The final
major cycle, known as the Kali Yuga will be 432,000 years long, all
the cycles put together will last 4,320,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   The Kali Yuga already has begun _ it started in 3012 B.C., so it
doesn't look like Hindus are expecting the end of the world anytime
soon.
</P>
<P>
   The events leading up to the end may start in 2003, when
Krishna's incarnation comes to enforce the reign of righteousness.
</P>
<P>
   When the end comes, you can expect Vishnu's final incarnation
descending from the open sky. All evil is destroyed, purity
restored and things begin anew when a lotus grows out of Vishnu's
navel and from it, Brahma appears to start the cycle of creation
once again.
</P>
<P>
   Buddhism: The Buddhist theory of time is also cyclical. The path
of events follows the Kalachakra, or wheel of time.
</P>
<P>
   Sister Jendy Shih, a Buddhist nun for 20 years and a teacher at
the American Evergreen Buddhist Association in Kirkland, says the
end of this cycle will come approximately 5,760,000,000 years after
the Buddha completed his teachings, which was about 2,500 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talk about how the world comes to exist, how it
deteriorates and dissolves. Then the end will come and then the
beginning,'' Shih says. The deterioration has little to do with
disasters and more with spiritual deterioration.
</P>
<P>
   However, contrary to the single-God religions mentioned earlier,
Buddhist theory holds that as time goes on, the deterioration
eventually bottoms out and things get better, with Earth eventually
resembling paradise. There will be no shortage of food and people
will be leading angst-free lives.
</P>
<P>
   It may seem odd that the Buddha should appear to start the cycle
over just as things are going so well, but Shih says Buddhists have
faith in the Buddha's wisdom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-99 2110EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991227.0362 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
