<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIET-TVAD-COL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEET MONICA LEWINSKY, DIET PLAN SPOKESWOMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Advertising Column) 
(sw) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ First it was a White House internship. Then a job
with Revlon that never materialized. Earlier this year, she started
a pocketbook-making business. Now, Monica Lewinsky, the woman known
for her relationship with President Clinton, is marching down yet
another professional path: as a television pitchwoman for a diet
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Sunday, Ms. Lewinsky's very familiar face and form will
appear in commercials for Jenny Craig Inc., the diet company, as
part of a $7.2 million advertising campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The commercials, which are also her first national television
forays since a March interview with Barbara Walters, will air that
day during the Brian Boitano Holiday Skating Spectacular on NBC,
and will be shown subsequently during daytime talk shows like
``Oprah'' and ``The Rosie O'Donnell Show.'' The campaign, which
includes cable television and Internet ads, will run at least
through March.
</P>
<P>
   In taking this step, Ms. Lewinsky appears to be following the
example of Sarah Ferguson, the Duchess of York, who sought a kind
of public redemption and financial redress through a similar
arrangement with Weight Watchers, another diet program.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after her divorce from Prince Andrew, the duchess signed
a lucrative deal with Weight Watchers International, then a unit of
the H.J. Heinz Co., to appear on television and in print ads for
the program. Heinz has since sold the Weight Watchers instruction
business to a unit of Artal Luxembourg S.A., although it continues
to make and sell Weight Watchers food products.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether Ms. Lewinsky will give the program a
hoped-for lift or drag it down because of the negative publicity
that her presidential dalliance generated. For many Americans, the
episode marked a low point in professional and personal conduct for
everyone involved.
</P>
<P>
   In a rough cut of the Jenny Craig commercials, Ms. Lewinsky _
whose weight worries, among other things, were chronicled in
Kenneth W. Starr's report to Congress _ appears relatively
contained and confident, although there is still that breathy
teen-ager quality to her voice and manner.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a bright pink blouse as she perches on a chair in a
flower-bedecked setting that looks like it might be a bedroom, she
declares, ``I've tried every diet in the world,'' ending with a
giggle. ``I mean, if it was stand on your head, I've tried it. If
it was eat only grapefruit, I've tried it. Magic diet pills, I've
tried it.''
</P>
<P>
   She says, however, the Jenny Craig program has helped her. She
claims she has lost 31 pounds so far, and the Monica speaking does
look far more svelte than she does in the ``before'' pictures
included in the spots. Those show her watering plants in a garden,
dressed in what appears to be a truncated muumuu over slacks, and
standing at an ironing board, snipping an article of clothing with
scissors _ perhaps to let out a seam.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky was chosen as the spokeswoman for Jenny Craig
because she tried the program and it worked for her, said Linell
Killus, vice president for marketing at the publicly traded diet
company. ``She's an example of a client success story, and
obviously she's highly recognizable,'' Ms. Killus said.
</P>
<P>
   She refused to say either how much Ms. Lewinsky weighs or how
much weight she is trying to lose, citing client confidentiality
policies. ``She's someone who truly wants to change her life in a
positive way, and that's what Jenny Craig is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what was Ms. Lewinsky's appeal to Jenny Craig's target
audience, mostly women aged 25 to 54, Ms. Killus said: ``She
represents a busy active woman of today with a hectic lifestyle.
And she has had weight issues and weight struggles for a long time.
That represents a lot of women in America.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jenny Craig program emphasizes personal ``consulting,'' in
which dieters receive advice about not only what they eat, but also
how they conduct themselves in other aspects of their lives. ``It's
about creating a healthy relationship with food, creating an active
lifestyle and creating a balanced life,'' Ms. Killus said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a journey. It's not a beginning and an end. You have to
change your life and the way you lead your life in order to become
an independent weight manager.''
</P>
<P>
   The ads featuring Ms. Lewinsky promote a ``Low Carb Option,''
which the voiceover describes as ``balanced and hassle-free,''
pretty much the opposite of Ms. Lewinsky, as her own testimony
underscores, in the final days of her relationship with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Reports that Ms. Lewinsky would be paid $1 million if she lost
60 pounds could not be confirmed on Monday. Ms. Killus said she was
not aware of any such arrangement and declined to say how much Ms.
Lewinsky was being paid for her appearances
</P>
<P>
   In the commercials, Ms. Lewinsky is shown laughing as flashbulbs
go off in the background, suggesting paparazzi. ``One of the
amazing things about Jenny Craig for me is that I haven't felt
deprived on this program at all,'' she says. ``I think Jenny Craig
is a great program for someone who not only wants to lose weight
but who's looking to change their life.'' Later, she adds, ``I feel
fantastic.''
</P>
<P>
   Working with her was a good experience, said David Suissa, the
chairman and executive creative director at Suissa Miller, the Los
Angeles agency that created the ads and others over the last six
years for Jenny Craig, including a spot starring Jerry Mathers, the
star of ``Leave it to Beaver.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She's friendly,'' Suissa said. ``I think she has experience in
front of the camera.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no question about that. Ms. Lewinsky gave hours of
videotaped testimony to Kenneth W. Starr, the special prosecutor
whose investigation of her relationship with Clinton consumed the
country and the Congress for large chunks of this year and last
year.
</P>
<P>
   The release of Starr's report detailed the relationship, which
began with Ms. Lewinsky flashing a glimpse of her thong underwear
to the commander in chief during the government shutdown in 1995.
It continued for 18 months with clandestine encounters in the
vicinity of the Oval Office before the president broke it off.
</P>
<P>
   Suissa said he was under no constraints as to what he could and
could not use about Ms. Lewinsky's past in the commercials. ``We
wouldn't have done it, anyway,'' he said. ``It's too expected, to
trade on her notoriety. She's a fun, interesting person in real
life. We didn't want to get too gloomy, you know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-99 2122EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991227.0368 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0292 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-COLOMBIA-UNIVERSITY-N     12-27 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-UNIVERSITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TERRORIZED UNIVERSITY IN COLOMBIA FIGHTS TO BE TRUE TO ITSELF 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo, NYT24, has been sent. Non-subscribers can
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEDELLIN, Colombia _ Some days it is hard to tell just how
profoundly this country's brutal, deepening civil conflict has
affected the University of Antioquia here. Outside the library, at
the school's main plaza, students relax in the sun, study for final
exams, play soccer or flirt with each other, just like their
counterparts anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a campus increasingly under siege by armed groups of
both the right and left. The main administration building has been
dynamited by leftist guerrillas; a respected professor, a student
leader and a popular cafeteria worker have been shot to death on
university grounds for political reasons; and a right-wing
paramilitary group has begun to operate openly and circulate a
``death list'' of future targets.
</P>
<P>
   A result is ``a state of panic and consternation'' at Antioquia,
Colombia's oldest public university, said Luis Fernando Jaramillo
Salazar, the institution's senior vice president. Things have
gotten so bad that administrators met recently with both left-wing
guerrilla leaders and the chief of the country's main right-wing
death squad to plead with them to curb their attacks and respect
the university's neutrality as a place of learning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went not to negotiate, but to express to them the notion
that a university is not a battlefield, but rather a place where
ideas compete,'' Jaramillo, a physicist, said in an interview in
his office, rebuilt after the bombing last February. ``That is
something that should be so obvious as not to have to be said, but
they insist on bringing the war here.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the university's more than 20,000 students, most of whom
come from families of limited means and shy away from politics, the
situation has bred a kind of fatalism. ``We have learned to accept
the abnormal as normal,'' said Patricia Molina, 24, a foreign
languages major, as she and three classmates took a study break at
the plaza.
</P>
<P>
   Monica Garcia, 24, a pharmacy student, said with a resigned
shrug, ``It is painful that the circumstances are what they are,
but this university is like a small city, a version of the nation
in miniature, and so you see here what you see everywhere else in
Colombia.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sorry people have been killed,'' she said, ``but how can
we not be affected, how can we expect the war not to penetrate our
university?''
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the political violence has also underlined the
university's general vulnerability and its inability to fend off
other kinds of attacks. Taking their cue from the warring forces of
the right and left, criminal gangs have also invaded the campus in
the last year, robbing the university financial office and the
professors' cooperative.
</P>
<P>
   Although the death squads have claimed responsibility for the
killing last August of Gustavo Marulanda, a philosophy major and
member of the Student Council they say was a guerrilla sympathizer,
it is still not clear who shot Hernan Henao to death in his office
in May. Henao, an anthropologist, was director of the Institute of
Regional Studies and had been supervising research into the
displacement of peasants by both sets of armed groups.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Antioquia (pronounced auntie-OH-key-yah) has
lived through periods of violence in the past, most notably in the
mid-1980s, when nearly a dozen professors were killed by armed
groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the worrying difference now is that these killings have
occurred on campus, and the sanctity of the university as a center
of inquiry is no longer respected,'' Jaramillo said.
</P>
<P>
   After Marulanda was killed, the university was closed for
several days, and statements by administrators led students to fear
it would remain shut indefinitely. Instead, a plebiscite was held
in which students, teachers and other employees, as well as the
community at large, were asked whether they favored ``a University
of Antioquia that is open, functioning, pluralist and without
violence.''
</P>
<P>
   About half of those affiliated with the university and some
70,000 people from outside the university voted. The outcome,
overwhelmingly endorsing the concept of the university as ``a space
for freedom,'' seemed to invigorate the university and underline
its importance to this city of 2 million, notorious outside
Colombia for its drug cartels.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is easy to say it was just something symbolic, that it was
nothing but a publicity stunt,'' Sergio Urquijo, 19, a
communications major, said of the vote. ``But when we saw the
results, we no longer felt so isolated, and it gave us the
confidence to continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the killings, combined with the threat of new
assassinations, continue to dampen campus life. Several professors
have left the country or gone into hiding, and the Student Council
has simply vanished from sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The atmosphere of fear and insecurity has driven them away,''
said the Rev. Alvaro Velez Vazquez, the college chaplain. ``Some
student leaders have left because they are frightened, and others
have left because they were threatened, but whatever the reason,
they haven't met in a long time, or if they are still meeting at
all, it is done very discreetly and clandestinely.''
</P>
<P>
   Professors who are still teaching say the chilling effect of the
violence has also entered their classrooms. It is no longer
possible, several said, to view their students with anything but
wariness and mistrust, and office hours have become an ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try not to be too visible and to tread carefully in what
you say in class,'' said the chairman of one department, speaking
on condition of anonymity out of concern for his safety. ``You
never know how your words, even some casual comment, are going to
be interpreted and turned against you, so there are certain themes
that you no longer broach in class.''
</P>
<P>
   In an unsigned essay in the university's literary magazine, a
writer compared the current situation to finding ``strange
presences that little by little take over one's own house.''
</P>
<P>
   First the guerrillas and now the ``hateful arrival of the
ultra-right groups,'' the article lamented, have transformed the
university into a ``soulless'' and ``devastated'' place.
</P>
<P>
   ``We begin to look at each other with suspicion, to calibrate
our words so as not to draw fire, because the blacklists began to
circulate right away,'' the writer added. To see one's name on one
of those lists ``means to become mute, to suspend research so as
not to step on mines, to distrust even the dogs that wander the
hallways with a certain fanaticism in their glance.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet even with all of that, Juan Jose Hoyos, a communications
professor who edits the magazine, sees grounds for optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still open, conducting research and teaching and
attending our classes,'' he said. ``After everything that this
university has been through in the past year, that in itself is a
tremendous victory.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
