<HEADER>
A0296 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-CLINTON-PHARMACY-NYT     12-27 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PHARMACY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO SEEK CRACKDOWN ON INTERNET PHARMACIES
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Clinton administration officials said Monday that
they would ask Congress to regulate the growing sale of
prescription drugs over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said President Clinton would ask for
legislation requiring online pharmacies to get approval from the
Food and Drug Administration. In addition, they said, he will ask
Congress to beef up the agency's investigative powers and increase
the penalties for online sales of prescription drugs to people
without prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals are also intended to make it easier for the
government to stop online sales of unapproved drugs, counterfeit
drugs and products promoted with fraudulent claims.
</P>
<P>
   There is no federal certification program for online pharmacies
and, operating in cyberspace, many of them do not get the state
licenses that are required of traditional drug stores. Policing
these stores and their sales of prescription drugs has been
difficult, federal officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jane Henney, the commissioner of food and drugs, said
Clinton's proposal would create civil penalties of up to $500,000
for selling a prescription drug to a person who did not have a
valid prescription or for operating without federal certification.
Federal officials say they now have difficulty prosecuting online
pharmacies and fines are usually limited to $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   As part of his budget request next month, White House officials
said, Clinton will seek $10 million to hire 100 people and upgrade
computer technology to investigate Web sites suspected of illegally
dispensing prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Monday night, Dr. Henney said the proposal
called for screening out disreputable online pharmacies and made
getting inappropriate drugs more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``The object of the whole proposal is to to make sure there's a
strong safety net for patients,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jeffrey Shuren, a medical officer at the FDA, said the
agency was already investigating more than 200 Web sites suspected
of selling unapproved drugs or selling approved medications without
valid prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   Under Clinton's proposal, the FDA would be given power to issue
administrative subpoenas compelling online pharmacies to provide
records for federal investigators. The administration said it would
protect patients' privacy, but did not give details.
</P>
<P>
   William Hubbard, a senior associate commissioner at the agency,
said: ``Online pharmacies come and go daily. Some are fly-by-night
operations. Some are located overseas.''
</P>
<P>
   In a document describing its plan to regulate online pharmacies,
the White House says sites will have to demonstrate that are
licensed by a state before they can be certified. The new federal
rules would, in effect, piggyback on state regulations on the
practice of medicine and pharmacy and would not replace them, the
document added. The White House document says that Internet
pharmacies now often ``bypass traditional safeguards against the
use of unsafe or inappropriate drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   If, for example, an online pharmacy based in Florida sold
prescription drugs to consumers in New York, the pharmacy would
have to comply with licensing requirements in both states, federal
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton plans to announce his proposals this week. A
White House official said: ``Internet pharmacies are not all bad.
Sometimes you can get access to quality prescription drugs at lower
prices in a more convenient way over the Internet. The president's
proposals are intended to target the bad apples who purvey fraud on
the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   To order drugs from an online pharmacy, a customer uses a
computer to visit the company's Web site. Many sites offer
information about drugs and diseases. Reputable companies insist on
getting a prescription from the patient or the doctor.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study by doctors at the University of Pennsylvania said
that it was alarmingly easy for consumers to get prescription drugs
without seeing a physician or a pharmacist.
</P>
<P>
   States have traditionally regulated the prescribing and
dispensing of drugs, the study said. But several states have found
it difficult to locate and prosecute online violators because the
prescriber, seller and buyer may be in different states.
</P>
<P>
   Several state attorneys general have filed lawsuits against Web
site owners, alleging violations of state laws _ for example,
providing drugs without a local pharmacy license or mailing drugs
to minors. In some cases, drugs are sent from online pharmacies
overseas, so it is difficult for federal and state authorities to
take action against them.
</P>
<P>
   The Pennsylvania study found 86 Web sites that sold Viagra
without requiring a doctor's visit or a prescription. Twenty-two of
the sites appeared to be based outside the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Matthew E. Naythons, vice president of one of the best-known
online pharmacies, PlanetRx.com, based in South San Francisco,
questioned the need for more regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are licensed to dispense drugs in all 50 states,'' he said.
``There are sufficient rules and regulations at the state level to
govern the practice of online pharmacy. Legitimate pharmacies
conform to those state regulations. To layer on another level of
regulation, at the federal level, would seem to be unnecessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Contrasting his company with some of its competitors, Naythons
said: ``At PlanetRx, we dispense medication. We don't prescribe it.
We are like your neighborhood pharmacy, but we have 35 million to
40 million branch offices through desktop computers. We want to
speak to your physician in every case, to verify your prescription,
unless we get it through the mail.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, other companies are not always so scrupulous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some online pharmacies _ rogue sites _ prescribe and
dispense,'' Naythons said. ``You can log on, complete a brief
questionnaire online and get Viagra or other drugs without seeing a
doctor in person.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
