<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARVARD-LAW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD LAW MULLS CUTTING NUMBER OF STUDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ABEL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Harvard Law School has many pluses to offer prospective
students _ a lofty reputation among lawyers and judges, a good bet
students will be lucratively employed by graduation, and an
education that prepares most students to pass the bar exam.
</P>
<P>
   But the three-year paper chase at Harvard has one critical con:
Students have to compete more for a professor's attention than they
do at nearly all of the nation's other top law schools.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after years of student and faculty criticism, Harvard is
poised to address the issue as early as next month.
</P>
<P>
   A recent memo written by a professor and circulated among her
colleagues has raised the idea of cutting the size of incoming
classes from an average of about 600 new students to as few as 450
students. Other professors have promoted the idea of boosting the
number of tenure-track professors beyond the current 79.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Law School is tied for the second-worst
student-professor ratio among the 50 law schools ranked this year
by US News &AMP; World Report. According to the magazine's survey,
Harvard had 20 students for every professor in 1998, compared with
9 to 1 at Yale, 13 to 1 at Stanford, and 15 to 1 at Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know that the Harvard student-faculty ratio is higher
than our peer institutions,'' said Elizabeth Warren, a law school
professor who heads a faculty committee looking into increasing
student contact with professors, as well as addressing other
student gripes such as a need for more financial aid, new housing,
and better athletic facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a big institution. But size alone is no excuse to have a
student-faculty ratio out of balance,'' Warren said. ``If we have
fewer students, there are fewer demands on the faculty.''
</P>
<P>
   Warren, however, has avoided staking out a position before
professors debate the issue in January. But she and others said
Dean Robert Clark considers lowering the ratio a top priority.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard's review comes in the wake of a comprehensive study of
student satisfaction at the law school. In September the McKinsey &AMP;
Co. consulting firm of New York polled students and found they
resent everything from big, impersonal classes to aloof,
hard-to-find professors.
</P>
<P>
   The typical size of a first-year class is 138 students, compared
with 60 at Stanford University Law School. While the
student-faculty ratio has improved in the past decade _ the ratio
is down from 26 to 1 in 1986 to about 18 to 1 in 1999, according to
a letter Clark sent students in September _ many still view it as a
major problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Harvard could change just one thing, I recommend that
(class size) be it,'' one student was quoted as saying in the
McKinsey report.
</P>
<P>
   But some professors at Harvard think too much is being made of
the student-faculty disparity. For one thing, such statistics often
exclude visiting professors from other universities and the many
guest lecturers who teach at the law school but are not considered
faculty.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get too mechanical about this student-faculty ratio
business,'' said Todd Rakoff, a law professor and a former
associate dean at the law school.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the classes our students like best, they're
often big classes taught by good teachers. . . . It is not my view
that the school with the smaller student-faculty ratio is
necessarily giving the better education.''
</P>
<P>
   Rakoff said he and others favor increasing the faculty instead
of lopping off the number of students, and he predicted that's what
will likely happen.
</P>
<P>
   But some professors believe the faculty has already grown too
big, and they fear the larger it gets, the less the professors will
get to know one another and collaborate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes the place more like a factory,'' said one professor,
who asked not to be named. ``We're already a very big faculty. You
don't want to see professors more removed from other faculty
members.''
</P>
<P>
   In the dean's letter, he promised action.
</P>
<P>
   While he told students they will soon benefit from a lower
student-faculty ratio, he said they already enjoy Harvard Law
School's largest faculty ever. In addition to the full-time
professors, he said, there are 113 other teachers who lecture at
Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be meaningful and consistent, of course, one has to make
many adjustments, such as converting part-time faculty to full-time
equivalents and adjusting for faculty on leave,'' Clark wrote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
