<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-HOTSPOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY: SILICON VALLEY NO LONGER HOT SPOT FOR TECH JOBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE BUTTERFIELD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Move over, Silicon Valley. California's high-tech world is about
to be eclipsed by the likes of Louisiana and Arkansas as national
hot spots for new technology hiring.
</P>
<P>
   And Southern states like Florida and Georgia _ not Massachusetts
and New England _ are expected to run a close second in the demand
for newly created technology jobs through the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   So says a new study by Computerworld, a Framingham, Mass.
information services company that has surveyed more than 1,900
major companies.
</P>
<P>
   The study found the hottest market for technology jobs is
expected to be in Southern states and in the central Southwest. New
England is pegged to be third. California _ despite its spot as the
nation's technology center _ is a distant sixth.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the change: Companies across the nation are
rushing into the Internet age, and many of them have a lot of
catching up to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corporate America's reliance on technology continues to spark
tremendous demand for highly skilled'' workers, Maryfran Johnson,
editor in chief of Computerworld, said in releasing the study
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that much of this demand for 2000 and beyond is in
areas outside the traditional technology regions shows just how
(technology) dependent our nation has become.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said nearly all companies _ not just high-tech firms _
have suddenly found themselves in need of developing and
integrating new technology to keep up with the Internet economy.
</P>
<P>
   She said the survey reflected the fact that many companies not
in high-technology areas have realized they have the greatest need
for highly skilled information technology employees.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, she said, the companies expect to do the most hiring
in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   With a shortage of qualified workers, particularly in Internet
technology, Johnson said many employers expect the bidding for
skilled workers to be fierce between regions, with many companies
gearing up for massive training programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, it's an indication that you don't have to live in the
(traditional) technology areas anymore to work in the technology
industry,'' Johnson added.
</P>
<P>
   She said the survey's findings may also be an indication that _
given the portability of technology _ both workers and companies
feel freer to move where they prefer.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Computerworld survey, the hottest technology
jobs in the year 2000 will be in computer applications, networking,
Internet development, and e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   The top employers looking for technically savvy workers include
government, financial institutions, real estate firms, software
developers, and communication and transportation companies.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Computerworld said the study was conducted in
October and November among major companies representing a broad
cross section of industries and employing more than 475,000
computer professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel very comfortable these trends are accurate,'' said
David Weldon, a senior editor directly involved in the study.
``Technology is just dominating whatever a company does today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-99 2145EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
