<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OFFICER-SHOT-ARREST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPECT ARRESTED IN SLAYING OF OFFICER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARCELLA BOMBARDIERI  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The man accused of killing a Holyoke, Mass. police officer was
arrested in Scranton, Pa., Monday, ending a five-day manhunt in
more than a dozen states and bringing comfort to mourners as they
prepared for John A. DiNapoli's funeral Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest was announced at DiNapoli's wake Monday afternoon,
and hundreds of the officer's friends, family, and colleagues
applauded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means there is a closure to John DiNapoli's death,''
Holyoke Police Chief Marc Cournoyer said at a news conference. ``It
doesn't lessen our pain, but at least we're relieved he's in
custody and no one else got hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Scranton police arrested Eddie Morales, 27, of Holyoke, as he
left his car in a strip mall parking lot about 4:45 p.m., Scranton
Detective Robert Brenzel said. Morales surrendered without
incident.
</P>
<P>
   Morales allegedly shot DiNapoli, 52, five times while the
off-duty patrol officer was chasing him in an unmarked car last
Wednesday. DiNapoli was responding to a call to break up a fight
and died from wounds in the abdomen, shoulder, arm, and heart.
Police say Morales has an extensive record of drug arrests and was
connected to a local gang.
</P>
<P>
   Morales was quickly identified by witnesses as DiNapoli's
assailant, police said. The dragnet expanded across the Northeast
and included federal and state investigators. Police said Morales
also broke into a Holyoke woman's home.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts State Police contacted Scranton authorities about
2 p.m. Monday with ``a pretty good idea'' where Morales was,
Brenzel said. Cournoyer refused to specify what leads brought the
search to Scranton.
</P>
<P>
   Local police staked out the residence where Morales was staying
and followed him when he left. They seized him when he stopped his
car in a parking lot, Brenzel said. About 20 officers participated
in the arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no fight at all,'' Brenzel said. ``I think he was
just overwhelmed by the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Relations between police and Hispanics in Holyoke are strained.
Latinos make up half of the city's population of 45,000. Some in
the community have accused law enforcement officials of
insensitivity. Some activists had feared that Morales might not
live if he resisted arrest.
</P>
<P>
   When in court Tuesday, authorities will request Morales be
returned to Massachusetts to face murder charges, Hampden District
Attorney William Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   Morales's capture ends an exhaustive search that strained
grieving members of the Holyoke police force, as well as DiNapoli's
friends and family.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been going 24 hours a day since this started, and I
thank God we were able to put everybody's mind at ease,'' Cournoyer
said. ``This man's capture has certainly relieved the community of
Holyoke and made . . . the entire Western Massachusetts community
sleep a little better this evening.''
</P>
<P>
   The news of the arrest brought a moment of excitement for the
relatives and colleagues attending the officer's wake. ``A lot of
tears, a lot of hugging,'' police chaplain Bill Hamilton said.
</P>
<P>
   Holyoke officials and police unions had offered a $50,000 reward
for information leading to an arrest and conviction. Cournoyer said
he thought the reward helped secure Morales's capture, but refused
to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   DiNapoli was a 21-year veteran whose duties included classroom
visits dressed as McGruff the Crime Dog. He had patrolled the
streets until he was asked to perform administrative duties about
six months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Holyoke mayor-elect Michael Sullivan said last week that he
would order that police cruisers and stationery be emblazoned with
the letters ``wwjdd,'' a take-off on the popular ``What would Jesus
do?'' slogan _ ``What would John DiNapoli have done?''
</P>
<P>
   Divorced, DiNapoli had a grown son and daughter who live in the
Holyoke area. His 30-year-old son, Andy, had been interested in
becoming a police officer.
</P>
<P>
   At the funeral mass at Immaculate Conception Church in Holyoke,
several thousand are expected to attend, including about 4,000
police officers from 60 departments around New England and beyond,
according to State Police Captain Robert Bird.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Correspondent Hermione Malone contributed to this report.
Wire service material was used in its preparation.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
