<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0317 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-CARLESIMO-FIRED-N     12-27 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CARLESIMO-FIRED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARLESIMO FIRED AS COACH OF THE 6-21 WARRIORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo, NYT 00, is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(ms) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After surviving rumors of his firing for more than a month, P.J.
Carlesimo was dismissed as head coach of the Golden State Warriors
Monday, a little over two years after being involved in one of the
ugliest incidents in National Basketball Association history.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came an hour and a half before the team's game
with the San Antonio Spurs in Oakland, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Garry St. Jean, the club's general manager, led the Warriors
onto the court shortly after agreeing to a multiyear contract to
coach the team as well.
</P>
<P>
   Carlesimo, who was in his third season as Warriors coach, had
two and a half years left on a five-year, $15 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   During a Warriors practice on Dec. 1, 1997, one of Carlesimo's
players, Latrell Sprewell, choked the coach in a fit of rage. He
said Carlesimo's abrasive coaching style had led to the attack.
After serving a 68-game suspension, Sprewell was traded to the New
York Knicks before last season.
</P>
<P>
   While Carlesimo's verbally aggressive tactics often put him at
odds with his players _ and was a major factor in his being
dismissed by the Portland Trail Blazers in 1977 after three winning
seasons _ it was his record that cost him in Golden State as much
as anything. In their first season in the newly refurbished Arena
in Oakland, the Warriors were 6-21 under Carlesimo.
</P>
<P>
   Carlesimo, who took over the Warriors in June 1997, shortly
after leaving Portland, had a 46-123 record with Golden State. A
successful collegiate coach at Seton Hall before joining the NBA,
Carlesimo, who is 50 years old, has an NBA record of 183-222.
</P>
<P>
   Carlesimo's firing will further the perception that he came out
the loser in his violent confrontation with Sprewell. While
Carlesimo is out of a job, Sprewell recently signed a five-year,
$61.8 million contract extension with the defending Eastern
Conference champions and is a crowd favorite at Madison Square
Garden.
</P>
<P>
   The two appeared on the same court for the first time since the
choking incident when the Knicks visited the Warriors on Nov. 20.
Though Carlesimo hinted that he would have liked to shake
Sprewell's hand and put the ugly occurrence behind them, Sprewell
showed no such inclination and in fact reacted so viciously to
Golden State's fans that he was fined $10,000 for his actions.
</P>
<P>
   In another meeting, at the Garden on Dec. 7, Sprewell again kept
his distance from Carlesimo.
</P>
<P>
   It was around the time of the clubs' first meeting that rumors
of Carlesimo's removal began circulating around the league. The
Warriors were 2-7 at the time and went on to lose their next nine
games.
</P>
<P>
   However, a surprising string of four victories in six games
midway through December, including a victory over the Sacramento
Kings, extended Carlesimo's tenure. But three straight losses, one
of them to the lowly Los Angeles Clippers, finally did him in.
</P>
<P>
   The 57-year-old St. Jean, who was an assistant coach with the
Warriors under Don Nelson from 1988-92, became the team's general
manager before the 1997-98 season. He served as Sacramento's head
coach from 1992 to 1997 and accumulated a 159-236 record before
being replaced by Eddie Jordan, now an assistant with the Nets, 67
games into the 1996-97 season. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
