<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0318 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-CENTURY-FASHION-ART-N     12-27 1225
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENTURY-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PICTURE THAT DIVIDED THE OLD FROM THE NEW 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By CATHY HORYN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   No one photograph or, for that matter, style could sum up the
century of fashion that rose on the pinched bosoms of Edwardian
ladies and ended, for all practical purposes, one night in December
with rap stars exiting the Metropolitan Museum of Art in a flourish
of diamonds and couture silk. It would be impossible, if not
outrageous, to ignore the influence of Chanel and Saint Laurent,
the glamour of Hollywood, the contagion of youth or the spirit of
absolute freedom that drove designers as different as Paul Poiret
and Ralph Lauren to invent their own worlds.
</P>
<P>
   But let's. Let's for a moment skip past the crowded faces, the
reflective blather, and look at the century as if through a
photographer's lens. It may be surprising what a single image
reveals not only of its time and place, but also about the force
that has shaped fashion since some unsung Edwardian hellion let her
corset fly _ the roaring, squealing, yahooing train of modernism.
</P>
<P>
   The photographer is George Hoyningen-Huene (pronounced
hoy-nee-HAN hoo-NAY), and the picture is ``Swimwear by Izod,''
taken in 1930 for Vogue. It shows a couple sitting, apparently, on
a diving platform overlooking a hazy sea. They could be in Greece,
and indeed Huene (as he is always known), like his contemporaries
in Paris in the 1920s and '30s _ the poet Jean Cocteau, the
dressmaker Alix Gres _ enjoyed posing his subjects against cold
Greek marble. In this instance, the giveaway is the man's radiant
musculature, a foretaste of Bruce Weber's beefcake. The tank-topped
fellow, by the way, was Huene's friend Horst Bohrmann, who later
became the photographer Horst P. Horst.
</P>
<P>
   A Russian aristocrat by birth as well as temperament, Huene had
convictions about almost everything, which left little room for
argument. ``It was not conceit but the certainty of my creative
ability,'' he said, that led him to adopt the attitude that ``Vogue
was to be honored by my presence.'' Fortunately for the magazine's
indulgent editor in chief, Edna Woolman Chase, such highhandedness
was mitigated by Huene's technical wizardry and his fondness for
simplicity and surprise.
</P>
<P>
   He was a master of light and illusion _ ``the master of us
all,'' said Richard Avedon _ and his ingenuity went beyond artful
displays of society models in Vionnet evening pajamas. In the late
'40s, while working in Hollywood for the director George Cukor (and
hanging out with Garbo), Huene devised an elevated reflecting pool
around the hillside home of his friend Oreste Pucciani, the French
literary scholar who became the companion of the designer Rudi
Gernreich. Apparently, Huene thought the terror of the vertiginous
view could be alleviated a bit by endlessly reflected sky.
</P>
<P>
   What's interesting about ``Swimwear by Izod'' is what you don't
see: the cheap thrills of Surrealism. Despite Huene's friendship
with Salvador Dali and other Surrealists, his work remained largely
free of such contrivances as teacups made of fur or mutton-chop
hats, a favorite of Elsa Schiaparelli.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 25 years earlier, in 1906, Poiret had shown the first
straight-line silhouette, without underpinnings, and although
Poiret became better known for designing Oriental pantaloons and
for fancy-dress balls, where he sat on a throne at least once,
Huene must have recognized the future in that earlier, unencumbered
style. He always tried to imbue his photographs with the same
relaxed air of freedom, even putting his models in such real props
as cars, so that they would represent, as he said, ``the modern
woman in the true light of the period.''
</P>
<P>
   If Huene identified with any dressmaker, it was Coco Chanel, who
wasn't exaggerating when she said, ``I was the first to live the
life of this century.'' Her deceptively simple innovations _ the
little black dress, the cardigan jacket, the jersey pullover, the
quilted bag and costume jewelry _ subscribed to the notion that if
a woman felt good, she would be free to concentrate on things other
than what she was wearing.
</P>
<P>
   So Chanel anticipated the demands on working women and designed
a modern uniform. Though it has gone through endless mutations, as
the slouchy Armani jacket, the utilitarian Gap T-shirt, the no-fuss
Prada nylon bag, it adheres to Chanel's original ideals of comfort
and function.
</P>
<P>
   Another overt influence in Huene's work was the impoverished
style of the esoteric painter and set designer Pavel Tchelitchev,
who was, the curator William A. Ewing wrote, ``the first to see in
commonplace clothes such as workman's outfits and army surplus gear
the stuff of genuine novelty.'' In other words, said Cecil Beaton,
another whose work was affected, ``Tchelitchev's idiom was
antifashion.''
</P>
<P>
   Although there's nothing obviously ragtag in ``Swimwear by
Izod,'' the fact that Huene sought to evoke an everyday moment, an
athletic-looking couple dressed for the beach, suggests that at
least he knew which way the fashion wind was blowing. A decade
later, Louise Dahl-Wolfe was photographing Claire McCardell's spare
bathing suits and tunics, which were unlined, made of simple
fabrics like gingham and looked best on athletic bodies.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1960s, realism would be the norm, as Twiggy and Penelope
Tree leaped in their miniskirts and Yves Saint Laurent mixed the
harder edge of the street (pea jackets and motorcycle leather) with
the knowing cool of a mannish pantsuit, a style that remains a
symbol of self-assured chic precisely because it hasn't changed.
It's no wonder, to look at Ralph Lauren's 1980s advertising image
of a clean-cut family leaning against its ski poles, why his
essentially anti-fashion ``Boola Boola'' gear provoked scorn while
making him rich. It's the apotheosis of Heune's modern glamour.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, in the postmodern era, fashion has hiccuped from one
big look to the next as designers have revived punks and mods, even
the corseted jewel-box figurines of Dior's New Look. But invariably
it comes back to resembling something that combines Chanel's idea
of function with new forms of louch excitement (in a nutshell,
Gucci's hippie chic).
</P>
<P>
   Beaton once said that fashion, like certain popular songs, has
an uncanny ability to call up emotions. As he put it: ``Perhaps it
is precisely because of their fleeting qualities that they seem to
incorporate, in their expression, a peculiar poignancy and almost
tragic awareness of the unique moment in time that will never come
again.'' That is the unique power and beauty of Huene's image. It
conjures up not just a feeling, but also a sense of the
photographer's far-sighted judgment.
</P>
<P>
   But fashion, as Huene knew, is an infinitely tricky business.
For all its realism, there is nothing particularly real about
``Swimwear by Izod.'' The diving board the couple is sitting on is,
in fact, a stack of boxes. The hazy sea? That too is pure illusion.
Huene simply took his subjects up to the roof of the Vogue studio
in Paris and aimed his lights. The horizon line is actually the top
of the building's parapet, and on the other side, down below, is
the Champs-Elysees. Life marches on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
