<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0319 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-ALAMO-HNS &LR;      12-27 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ALAMO-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NEIL HOHLFELD  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
SAN ANTONIO _ In September, the idea of playing a bowl game in a
domed stadium in a tourist city _ the only bowl taking place that
night, mind you _ would have suited Penn State and Texas A&AMP;M just
fine.
<TEXT>
<P>
   That scenario would have brought to mind playing for the
national championship at the Sugar Bowl in New Orleans. Instead,
the Aggies and Nittany Lions face the harsh reality of playing for
far less tonight in the Alamo Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   In Penn State's case, the wounded Nittany Lions (9-3) are
playing only for pride. They were undefeated and ranked No. 2 in
the country in early November before losing to Minnesota, Michigan
and Michigan State to end the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   The collapse is all Penn State has heard about for nearly two
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a good team, but it's easy to forget what happened
before those three (losses),'' said Penn State linebacker LaVar
Arrington. ``We need to make a statement with our last game.
Everybody remembers what you do at the end of the season, so we
want to go out as winners.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You match our roster against any other team in the country,
and I think we have more talent than anybody,'' said Penn State
wide receiver Chafie Fields. ``But we lost. We didn't make plays
when we had to, and the other teams did. Talent doesn't always win
games. It's as simple as that. It's time to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies (8-3) had their national title hopes punctured one
month earlier than Penn State. On the first weekend in October, the
Aggies, ranked No. 5 in the nation at the time, were stunned by
Texas Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Lopsided losses to Oklahoma and Nebraska and the dismissal of
tailback Dante Hall for disciplinary reasons followed, but the
Aggies finished the season with wins over Missouri and Texas. The
Alamo Bowl provides a chance to end the season on an upswing and
improve on a 2-6 record in bowls since R.C. Slocum took over as
head coach in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played a lot of the top, traditional programs in our bowls,
and we've come close nearly every time,'' said Slocum. ``A win in
this game against a team like Penn State would close our season in
the right way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were the No. 5 team, and we had just as high aspirations as
they did,'' said Aggies running back Ja'Mar Toombs. ``When you lose
like we did to Texas Tech, the mood of your whole season goes down.
Once you lose, you have to step back and realize what you have to
do to get back in there and win games.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nittany Lions were unable to regroup after a last-minute
24-23 home loss to Minnesota the first week in November. With three
straight losses, Penn State is on the brink of a four-game losing
streak for the first time in the Joe Paterno era, which began in
1966.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's scary,'' said Arrington, who won the Butkus Award as
the nation's top linebacker this season. ``Everybody talks about
tradition at Penn State, and we don't want to go down as the team
that was the first to lose four straight games. We can't go out
there and lose four straight. We've got to fight to avoid that.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can't get excited about playing in this game, you'd see
us get one of the worst tail-kickings in Penn State history. Texas
A&AMP;M is playing what's going to be a home game, and they're going to
try to embarrass us.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Aggies will have what amounts to a home game
tonight. The Alamodome has been sold out for weeks, and a record
crowd of more than 65,000 is expected. Most will wear maroon, as
Penn State returned about 2,400 tickets and traveled only about
6,500 fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of our fans are obviously disappointed,'' said Paterno,
who has a 19-9-1 bowl record. ``I think they're shellshocked. There
were such high expectations; they were all making plans to go to
New Orleans. That was one of the reasons (for the lack of
interest).''
</P>
<P>
   Paterno also has said those national championship expectations
might have been unrealistic, considering the quality and depth of
opponents in the Big Ten. It sounds like a spin, but Paterno might
be right about teams in tough conferences like the Big Ten and Big
12 having a built-in impediment to winning a national title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was talking to some of the coaches in the conference, and
this league's gotten so tough that maybe the BCS (Bowl Championship
Series) is not a viable option for us because of the difficulty of
the schedule,'' said Paterno. `` It would be unfair to expect every
year to be a national championship (year) in a conference as tough
as this one. You've got to be realistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Realism will take center stage tonight in the Alamodome, where
Penn State and the Aggies will finish a season that will be
remembered mainly for what might have been.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
