<SLUG> BC-NY-NIGHTCLUB-PUFFY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARREST IS NOT FIRST FOR PUFFY COMBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (With NY-NIGHTCLUB-SHOOTING)  
(lh) 
 By MONTE WILLIAMS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sean ``Puffy'' Combs' arrest for criminal possession
of a weapon following a shooting incident at Club NY early Monday
morning was not his first brush with the law.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Combs, the rap producer and performer, was arrested on
charges of beating a record executive, Steven Stoute, who suffered
a broken arm, a broken jaw and cuts to his head.
</P>
<P>
   Stoute, an executive at Interscope Records, said at the time
that Combs and two bodyguards had pummeled him with their fists, a
telephone, a Champagne bottle and a chair.
</P>
<P>
   Combs, a 30-year-old multimillionaire with his own record label,
Bad Boy Entertainment, faced up to seven years in prison if
convicted of felony assault.
</P>
<P>
   But after Combs publicly apologized, Stoute asked the Manhattan
district attorney to drop the charges.
</P>
<P>
   Combs was sentenced to a mandatory day of ``anger management''
classes.
</P>
<P>
   The rift between Stoute and Combs apparently occurred after
Combs appeared in a scene for a video by the rapper Nas, according
to an article in Billboard magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Combs had second thoughts and asked Stoute to cut the scene,
which featured him on a crucifix, but the video was shown on MTV
unedited, the article said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Combs was found guilty of criminal mischief for
threatening a New York Post photographer with a gun. He paid a
$1,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   Last January, Combs and the rapper Dwight ``Heavy D'' Myers were
found to bear half of the responsibility for the deaths of nine
students crushed in a stampede during a party that they sponsored
at City College in December 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Louis C. Benza of the state court of claims in Albany said
the other half of the blame should be shouldered by the college.
</P>
<P>
   The families of the dead concertgoers have sought to negotiate
settlements with the rappers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-99 2205EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991227.0390 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
