   (NYT34) ALBANY, N.Y. -- Dec. 27, 1999 -- NY-BUNKER-1 -- The
state's command post for emergencies sits in a 40-year-old
two-level bomb shelter built during the prime Cold War years as the
post-nuclear seat of state government. The entrance to the tunnel
is near the state police building. In the last four years, the
bunker has been given a technological makeover. (David Jennings/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) NEW YORK -- Dec. 27, 1999 -- FRONTROW-FASHION -- Hostess
skirts and sweater sets from Heidi Weisel are doing well at Barneys
New York. There is something decidedly future-averse about the
popularity of the hostess skirt, an artifact belonging more to the
world of a Rick Moody story than to the world of the Palm V.
(Barbara Alper/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) UNDATED -- Dec. 27, 1999 -- CENTURY-FASHION-B&AMP;W --
George Hoyningen-Huene took ``Swimwear by Izod'' for Vogue in 1930,
drawing a line in the fashion sand. It may be surprising what a
single image reveals not only of its time and place, but also about
the force that has shaped fashion since some unsung Edwardian
hellion let her corset fly - the roaring, squealing, yahooing train
of modernism. (Staley-Wise Gallery/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) PEMBROKE PINES, Fla. -- Dec. 27, 1999 --
FLA-MENTAL-HEALTH -- Patients cleaning the grounds recently as part
of a work program at South Florida State Psychiatric Hospital.
Experts say it is the first state mental hospital in the nation to
be turned over completely to a private company that hopes to
operate it at a profit. (Cindy Karp/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti -- Dec. 27, 1999 --
HAITI-SOCIAL-LAB-2 -- Haitian children play on a field that was
cleared just for them. On this 15-acre lot where the only things
that glistened were thousands of shards of broken glass, Robert
Duval founded Athletics of Haiti, a sports organization that takes
youngsters from the slums of Cite Soleil and gives them training,
food and tutoring. (Alex Quesada/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti -- Dec. 27, 1999 --
HAITI-SOCIAL-LAB-1 -- Robert Duval talking to parents in
Port-Au-Prince. After decades of political activism during which he
encountered dictators, military governments and coups, Duval
founded Athletics of Haiti, a sports organization that takes
youngsters from the slums of Cite Soleil and gives them training,
food and tutoring. (Alex Quesada/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) NEW YORK -- Dec. 27, 1999 -- NY-IMMIG-III-3 -- ``I never
saw bias until I ran in 1991,'' says City Councilwoman Una Clarke,
left (with Mark Goodman and former Mayor David Dinkins). ``When I
entered office, the street talk was, 'Why do these West Indians
feel they have to be in politics?' `` (Chester Higgins Jr./The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- Dec. 27, 1999 -- NY-IMMIG-III-2 -- ``People
say to me, 'I'm Italian. You are going to know what I need?' ``
says John Lie, president of the North Flushing Civic Association in
Queens. ``I say, 'You need regular garbage pickup. You need the
schools to be good.'' (Nancy Siesel/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- Dec. 27, 1999 -- NY-IMMIG-III-1 --
``Politics is the same everywhere in the world,'' says Morshed
Alam, founder and president of the New American Democratic Club in
Jamaica, Queens. ``Nobody wants to give up their power. But times
are changing.'' (Ozier Muhammad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) UNDATED -- Dec. 27, 1999 -- OBIT-FISHER-B&AMP;W -- Harold L.
Fisher, a lawyer who played a prominent role in Democratic politics
in New York for several decades and also served as a chairman of
the Metropolitan Transportation Authority, died Sunday at his home
in Fort Lauderdale, Fla. He was 89. (Barton Silverman/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) MEDELLIN, Colombia -- Dec. 27, 1999 --
COLOMBIA-UNIVERSITY -- At the University of Antioquia, students
prepare for finals under graffiti calling for paramilitary killers
to get out. This is a campus increasingly under siege by armed
groups of both the right and left - unwitting victims of the
country's deepening civil conflict. ``We have learned to accept the
abnormal as normal,'' says Patricia Molina, 24, a foreign languages
major. (Larry Rohter/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- Dec. 27, 1999 -- NY-BALL-HOPKINS -- Dr. Mary
Ann Hopkins, a surgeon, volunteers her skills in various war zones
for Doctors Without Borders, the international relief group that
won the Nobel Peace Prize this year. Dr. Hopkins, 36, will push the
button that drops the New Year's ball on Times Square. A main
reason she was picked from amongst her co-volunteers is that the
organization wants to draw attention to the conflicts in India and
in Somalia, where she has worked. (Chester Higgins Jr./The New York
Times
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- Dec. 27, 1999 -- KATE-SPANGER-2 -- Amy
Spanger as Lois Lane, the cabaret singer turned actress in the
musical ``Kiss Me, Kate.'' Ms. Spanger doubles as Bianca in the
show's version of ``The Taming of the Shrew.'' ``My initial idea,
from seeing all the classic ditzes, was that Lois should be
platinum blond, maybe short and kinky hair,'' she says. ``But the
second I put on the wig and costumes I felt, there she is. It made
total sense.'' (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- Dec. 27, 1999 -- KATE-SPANGER-1 -- Amy
Spanger, 28, handles dual roles in ``Kiss Me, Kate.'' Ben Brantley
in The New York Times hailed Ms. Spanger as a ``fresh young star in
the making'' who gets three of the evening's best songs (''Why
Can't You Behave?,'' ``Tom, Dick or Harry'' and ``Always True to
You'') and ``lands each of them with a sharp-edged sensuality that
turns her gold-digging archetype into something newly minted.''
(Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) UNDATED -- Dec. 27, 1999 -- TV-KIDS-REVIEW -- John
Stossel of ABC's ``Why Don't the Kids Have a Voice?'' In pursuit of
the question posed by his show's title, Stossel provides case
histories of children who are being deprived of wholesome homes by
benighted bureaucratic regulations, particularly one that favors
their biological parents, however unworthy. (ABC/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) BISHKEK, Kyrgyzstan -- Dec. 27, 1999 -- KYRGYZ-POTTERY
-- Begaim Tenizbaeva, who makes ceramics in Kyrgyzstan, is
influenced by her heritage. ``No matter how much I want to move
toward art that is purely modern, the Kyrgyz influence comes out in
my work,'' she says. (Staton R. Winter/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) BEIJING -- Dec. 27, 1999 -- CHINA-QIGONG -- In this park
in western Beijing, hundreds of cancer patients practice rituals as
they try to harness the invisible forces of qigong to fight their
disease. This thriving anti-cancer movement is one of hundreds of
variants of qigong (pronounced chee-goong) that continue operating
in China, even as the authorities pursue their harsh crackdown on
one prominent offshoot, Falun Gong, and step up their scrutiny of
the others. (Erik Eckholm/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- Dec. 27, 1999 -- BROADWAY-NEW-PLAYS -- The
closing of ``Epic Proportions'' at the Helen Hayes Theater on Dec.
19 left no recently written drama or comedy running on Broadway.
The current situation is testimony to a steady erosion in the
tradition of the straight play on Broadway. (Jeffery A. Salter/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Dec. 27, 1999 -- HURRICANE-MOVIE-2 -- Rubin
``Hurricane'' Carter outside his lawyers' office in New York in
1998. ``The Hurricane,'' directed by Norman Jewison, depicts the
boxer's compelling real-life story, which touches on thorny issues
of race, civil rights and celebrity involvement in criminal trials.
(Nancy Siesel/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) PHILADELPHIA -- Dec. 27, 1999 -- HURRICANE-MOVIE-1-B&AMP;W
-- Rubin ``Hurricane'' Carter warming up for a middleweight
championship bout against Joey Giardello in Philadelphia's
Convention Hall on Dec. 11, 1964. Carter was convicted of a
multiple murder in 1966 and imprisoned for 19 years in a case that
was eventually overturned in a landmark ruling. (Robert Lipsyte/The
New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 27, 1999 -- WASHINGTON-MONUMENT --
Scaffolding used by workers for a $10 million restoration project
surrounds the 114-year-old Washington Monument. At midnight, Dec.
31, the 550-foot monument will turn into a giant sparkler. ``We
just cleaned the monument and there was concern about putting
fireworks up there that could cause black powder burns or
whatever,'' says Dave Barna, chief spokesman for the Park Service.
(Shana Raab/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) BOSTON -- Dec. 27, 1999 -- SCI-EGYPTOLOGY -- A statue of
Amenhotep IV, in Boston, offers a glimpse of royal life in Egypt in
the 1300s BC. Egyptian art and culture has fascinated the general
public longer and deeper than any other branch of archaeology.
(Museum of Fine Arts, Boston/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Dec. 27, 1999 -- SCI-FITNESS-MODELS-2 --
Rosie O'Donnell, center, with a Chub Club from Reno, Nev., has
become a role model for those dieters who must struggle. ``After we
did a series of shows about breast cancer last fall, I got a lot of
letters from doctors telling me more people die of cardiovascular
disease than anything else,'' says Ms. O'Donnell. ``If you really
want to help people, they told me, you'll try to get them to eat
less and move more.'' (Warner Brothers/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Dec. 27, 1999 -- SCI-FITNESS-MODELS-1 --
Chub Club Squads from Greenwich, Conn., and Hermitage, Tenn., vying
in the Mommy Marathon for the ``Rosie O'Games.'' For anyone
alienated by impossibly hard-bodied role models, another approach
is fast catching on: fitness programs led by people who need to
diet themselves. (Warner Brothers/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) BOULDER, Colo. -- Dec. 27, 1999 -- SCI-HUGHES-CECH --
Dr. Thomas R. Cech, the new Hughes Institute president, on the
University of Colorado campus in Boulder. Cech noticed a reaction
in a Tetrahymena that occurred when no proteins were around, only
RNA. He later proved that RNA itself could be an enzyme. At first
his work was ignored. ``No one felt very threatened by it, because
it was happening in Boulder, with this weird organism,'' says Cech,
who has won a slew of prizes, including in the Nobel Prize in
Chemistry in 1989. (Brian Payne/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- Dec. 27, 1999 -- SCI-SURGICAL-ZIPPER -- The
surgical zipper can be peeled off in the shower. When it comes time
to close an incision (the zipper works only on straight ones), the
surgeon peels off the paper strip, exposing the adhesive, and
places one edge on each side of the wound. While gently pulling up
on the tab, the surgeon pulls the zipper shut; as the zipper comes
together, so too do the edges of the skin. The process takes less
than two minutes. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) LOS BATAVIA, Ill. -- Dec. 27, 1999 -- SCI-FERMILAB-3 --
One of two huge detectors powering the mighty Tevatron, a power
accelerator at the Fermi National Accelerator Laboratory in Los
Batavia. The most conspicuous achievement of the Tevatron in its 14
years of operation was the discovery in 1995 of the ``top quark,''
which filled in the last blank space for six quarks allotted by a
table of fundamental particles known as the Standard Model.
(Malcolm W. Browne/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) LOS BATAVIA, Ill. -- Dec. 27, 1999 -- SCI-FERMILAB-2 --
Fermilab's new director, Dr. Michael Witherell, had to act fast to
block a major highway that would have run right through the site of
the Fermi National Accelerator Laboratory in Los Batavia.
``Fermilab's useful life is far from over,'' Witherell says. ``We
just need some cooperation by nature and a little luck.'' (Malcolm
W. Browne/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) LOS BATAVIA, Ill. -- Dec. 27, 1999 -- SCI-FERMILAB-1 --
The Fermi National Accelerator Laboratory in Los Batavia at sunset;
at left is Robert Wilson's sculpture ``Acqua alle funi.'' The High
Rise, as the building at right is known, was designed for a 20-year
lifetime but it is now more than 30 years old, and fixing the
structure and its plumbing will take two years and cost $20
million. (Fermilab/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) EAST ORLAND, Maine -- Dec. 27, 1999 -- SCI-SALMON-BOS --
At the Craig Brook National Fish Hatchery, 3-week old Atlantic
salmon eggs are examined by biologists Dave Bean, left, and Tracy
Copeland. This hatchery incubates up to 95 percent of the salmon in
Maine's salmon streams. Hatchery workers round up eggs after they
have already been laid by the females in rivers, using the hatchery
as an incubator and nursery to improve their survival chances.
(Mark Wilson/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti -- Dec. 27, 1999 --
HAITI-JUSTICE-2-BOS -- A bible group meeting in the refurbished
courtyard of Haiti's National Penitentiary. Some 80 percent of all
prisoners in Haiti's prison system have yet to be sentenced. Some
are awaiting trials as much as four years after arrest. (Janet
Knott/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti -- Dec. 27, 1999 --
HAITI-JUSTICE-2-BOS -- Prisoners returning to their cells at
Haiti's National Penitentiary. Across the country there are 19
prisons with a population of 4000 prisoners, an increase of 1
prison and 2500 prisoners since 1993. (Janet Knott/The Boston
Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti -- Dec. 27, 1999 --
HAITI-JUSTICE-1-BOS -- At Haiti's National Penitentiary, a prisoner
tries to sleep in a 1,200-square-foot cell where 154 men are locked
up for 23 hours a day. The room has only 11 beds. Though miserable,
conditions are better than they were a few years ago, when the
prison held 400 men in a single room. (Janet Knott/The Boston
Globe) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) JERUSALEM -- Dec. 27, 1999 -- ISRAEL-POLITICS -- Sitting
between Finance Minister Baiga Shohat, right, and Ofer Pinnes, the
head of ``One Israel,'' Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak did not
seem concerned with the crisis in his coalition government as he
met his party members Monday. A portrait of Yizhak Rabin hangs
behind them. Shas, an ultra-Orthodox party that represents
Sephardic Jews of Middle Eastern and North African descent,
announced its decision to quit the government. It is the third
largest political party in Israel. (Rina Castelnuovo/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
