<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CREW-EDUC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL BOARD TO DISCUSS CREW'S EXIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The best candidate to replace Schools Chancellor Rudy
Crew would be a good administrator and manager, not necessarily
someone with experience as an educator, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's words are likely to reverberate through Board of
Education headquarters in Brooklyn, where the seven-member board
will meet Tuesday to consider whether to try to buy out Crew's
contract, which expires in June, and to consider options in finding
an interim and permanent replacement.
</P>
<P>
   The names of several potential successors, including those of
school officials in Chicago, Dallas and San Diego, have surfaced
since the board voted on Thursday not to renew Crew's contract.
</P>
<P>
   If Giuliani were to get his wish, a successful candidate would
be ``a very, very skilled administrator, very skilled manager, the
kind of person that could run a very, very complex business or
multinational corporation,'' as he said at a press conference
Monday. ``That could be an educator, but I would not limit myself
to that. I would consider people outside the field of education who
have the skill to run very, very complex organizations.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time Giuliani has expressed such
sentiments. Four years ago, too, during the search that led to the
hiring of Crew, the mayor said he was interested in a business
leader as schools chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   But such a person, lacking formal credentials as a school
administrator, would have to get a waiver from Richard P. Mills,
the commissioner of the state Education Department, to be appointed
_ a potential problem if the choice is viewed as a highly political
one.
</P>
<P>
   Among those mentioned in as a potential candidate is Herman
Badillo, a mayoral adviser and chairman of the City University of
New York. But a person who has been involved in high-level
discussions about possible chancellor candidates said there was no
chance of Badillo being offered the job, in part because of his
previously voiced interest in running for mayor. Badillo was on
vacation Monday and was unavailable for comment, a spokesman for
CUNY said.
</P>
<P>
   Ninfa Segarra, one of Giuliani's appointees to the school board,
said last week that while there had always been candidates with
good credentials who were willing to come to New York, it was
perhaps more important now that Crew's replacement ``should be from
the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Crew was on vacation in Washington state on Monday and could not
be reached for comment. He is scheduled to return to New York early
next month. Meanwhile, two education officials close to Crew said
that school districts in several cities, including Oakland and San
Francisco, had expressed interest in hiring him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
