<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0334 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-NIGHTCLUB-SHOOTING     12-27 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NIGHTCLUB-SHOOTING-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 HURT IN CLUB SHOOTINGS; PUFFY COMBS FACES GUN POSSESSION
CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
 (jw) 
 By WILLIAM K. RASHBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sean (Puffy) Combs, the multimillionaire rap
entrepreneur, whose career and lavish East Hampton parties have
been fodder for the gossip columns, was arrested on gun possession
charges with the actress and singer Jennifer Lopez after shots were
fired at a midtown dance club early Monday, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Three people were wounded by gunfire at 2:55 a.m. at Club NY,
which sent panic-stricken clubgoers into the frigid air outside the
nightspot half a block west of Times Square, police and witnesses
said. Police described the victims as bystanders and said that none
of them suffered life-threatening injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Ms. Lopez nor Combs was charged in connection with the
shootings, and Ms. Lopez was later released.
</P>
<P>
   A rap performer, Jamal Barrows, 19, who was in Combs' group, was
charged with three counts of attempted murder and criminal
possession of a weapon, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators later said they were looking into witness accounts
that Barrows fired because he believed that someone had said
something disrespectful to Combs. Prosecutors also said that Combs
drew a gun in the fracas, but, through a spokesman, Combs denied
that he was involved.
</P>
<P>
   Police Commissioner Howard Safir said Combs and Ms. Lopez, who
both fled after the shooting in a 1999 Lincoln Navigator, had been
arrested along with Combs' bodyguard and his driver on gun
possession charges, because a stolen pistol was found in the
vehicle. The Manhattan District Attorney's office later decided to
release Ms. Lopez, saying they had evaluated the evidence and had
declined to prosecute. The gun found in the vehicle was not the
same one used in the shootings in the club, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials said Ms. Lopez, who has appeared in
nearly a dozen films and has been romantically linked to Combs, was
released because she was unaware that the gun was in the car and
because she cooperated with the police.
</P>
<P>
   Combs, 30, who grew up in Harlem, rose from an intern at a small
rap record label to become one of the hip-hop world's leading
impresarios. His successful recording career led to his greater
success as a producer and promoter; he founded his own label, Bad
Boy Records, which he later sold to Arista Records for $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   His entrepreneurial skills have catapulted him from the
street-styled world of rap music to parties with the likes of
Donald Trump and Martha Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   But even as he became renowned as a rap mogul, Combs has also
had brushes with the law, most notably a case this year in which he
was accused of severely beating a record executive.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Klores, a spokesman for Combs, said he was not involved in
the shooting at Club NY and that his client was just trying to get
Ms. Lopez out of harm's way. ``Sean Combs and Jennifer Lopez had
nothing to do with the shooting,'' Klores said. ``We're confident
that the investigation will prove these to be the actual facts.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lopez, 29, was released about 4 p.m. from the Midtown South
precinct station house as fans gathered outside to try to catch a
glimpse of her. She did not speak with reporters, but her lawyer,
Larry Ruggiero, said, ``They established she did nothing wrong.
Jennifer had nothing to do with the gun or the shooting. She's
relieved and glad the truth came out.''
</P>
<P>
   Also arrested were Combs' bodyguard, Anthony Jones, 34, and
Combs' driver, Wardel Fenderson, 41. Police charged Combs, Jones
and Fenderson with criminal possession of a weapon and criminal
possession of stolen property, because the 9 mm Smith &AMP; Wesson
Model 915 pistol found in the Navigator was reported stolen in
August in the small Georgia town of Powder Springs, authorities
said. Jones was also charged with marijuana possession, police
said.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the club, investigators recovered four shell casings, two
from a 9 mm pistol and two from a .40-caliber gun, police said. The
9 mm casings were believed to have come from the weapon that police
said Barrows was carrying when he was arrested. It was not clear
who fired the .40-caliber bullets, and no .40-caliber pistol has
been recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Funk, the club's general manager, said Combs and Ms. Lopez
arrived with an entourage of about 30 people sometime after
midnight and spent most of the time in a VIP section that is set
off from the rest of the club by velvet ropes. ``Well wishers came
by, they partied together,'' Funk said.
</P>
<P>
   Funk said club patrons were searched and screened with a metal
detector, but neither he nor the club's owner, Michael Bergos,
could say how the guns got inside the nightspot. Neither man would
discuss the details of the shooting, citing the police
investigation, but both praised Combs and said his behavior had
been exemplary. ``Puff Daddy has been here many times before, he's
always a gentleman, he's never had any problems,'' Funk said.
``He's always a welcome guest here.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Combs and the other three men were scheduled to be arraigned
Monday night in Manhattan Criminal Court. The criminal complaint
filed against Combs by the Manhattan District Attorney's office
said that an unidentified woman who witnessed the shooting
``observed Combs in an argument with another group of individuals
inside the club, whereupon one of the other individuals threw a
stack of money at Combs.''
</P>
<P>
   The complaint charges that Combs and Barrow then ``each pulled
out semiautomatic pistols.''
</P>
<P>
   Police identified the victims of the shooting as Natanya Ruben,
29 and Julius Jones, 27, both of Brooklyn, and Robert Thompson, of
Danbury, Conn. Ms. Ruben, who was shot in the face, and Jones, who
was shot in the shoulder, were both in stable condition Monday
night at St. Vincent's Hospital, said Mark Ackerman, a hospital
spokesman. Thompson refused medical attention, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Police said that after the shooting inside the club, Combs and
Ms. Lopez ran out and jumped into the car driven by Fenderson. The
Navigator sped down West 43rd Street toward Eighth Avenue and
swerved around a marked police car, its dome lights flashing, that
officers had parked in the middle of the street to close off the
block.
</P>
<P>
   The Navigator sped north on Eighth Avenue, the authorities said,
running 11 red lights before it was pulled over on the northeast
corner of West 54th Street and Eighth Avenue. Combs, Jones,
Fenderson and Ms. Lopez all climbed out of the car and the police
found the gun under the front passenger seat, where Jones had been
riding, authorities said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
