<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0344 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-1STLD     12-27 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIGIOUS FACTION SAYS IT WILL QUIT BARAK'S CABINET 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to update. Rewriting throughout. Reorganizes, adds background
information and analysis.)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT 1 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lh) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Israel's third-largest political party Monday
formalized six months of threats to bolt Prime Minister Ehud
Barak's coalition by announcing its decision to quit the
government.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement shook the country, because the party's
departure would throw the governing coalition into chaos just as it
moved into a critical period, facing key budgetary and peacemaking
deadlines.
</P>
<P>
   Threats by the party, Shas, an ultra-Orthodox group that
represents Sephardic Jews of Middle Eastern and North African
descent, have been a leitmotif of Barak's first six months in
office. As such, many Israelis, including Barak, were skeptical
that the decision was any more ironclad than previous posturing by
the party.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, who seemed unruffled, asked Shas Monday to wait 24 hours
and see what could be resolved, and the party agreed.
</P>
<P>
   The party said it could not remain in a government that did not
adequately support programs for the poor. More specifically, Shas
wants Barak to bail out its government-subsidized school system,
which is $36 million in debt.
</P>
<P>
   The schools, which provide hot meals and the long hours that
working parents need, are Shas' bread and butter, attracting
adherents to its religious and political agenda.
</P>
<P>
   By withdrawing its 17 members of Parliament, Shas would leave
Barak with a minority government of 51 out of 120 members. Small
parties and Arab parties that are nominally in the opposition can
be expected to keep Barak's government from falling.
</P>
<P>
   But it would be a destabilizing event at a sensitive moment, as
Barak heads into intensified peace negotiations with the
Palestinians and Syria. If those negotiations lead to a peace
treaty, Shas' support would be critical in an ensuing national
referendum.
</P>
<P>
   Shas' decision was made on the basis of a telephone poll of each
rabbi in the ``council of sages'' that guides its politicians, led
by the chief sage, Rabbi Ovadia Yosef.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have made a clear and unequivocal announcement,'' said Eli
Yishai, 38, the party's current leader. ``We don't play with
announcements. The prime minister asked us to wait 24 hours. We
will respect this. We will wait 24 hours. The rabbis' decisions
still stands. What will be in 24 hours, I don't know. At any rate,
we have to go back to the rabbis.''
</P>
<P>
   Shas has been an unstable partner in Barak's broad-based
coalition. With its relatively dovish rabbis, it was enlisted as a
potential ally for the peace effort, against vocal opposition from
Barak's secular supporters.
</P>
<P>
   But from the beginning, in true Israeli marketplace style, Shas
has conditioned its support on financing for its indebted religious
school system and social welfare programs.
</P>
<P>
   Shas' announcement came against the backdrop of frenzied
negotiations for next year's budget, which Israeli law requires to
be approved by Friday, although an extension is permissible. As
usual, when speaking of Shas, Barak adopted a conciliatory tone and
said he was sure that the crisis would fade.
</P>
<P>
   In a broadcast speech to his Labor/One Israel Party at
parliament Monday, he urged Israelis to recognize the key role of
Shas and how far it had come in the last year, since its leader,
Aryeh Deri, was convicted of corruption and stepped down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The movement of Shas is important to the government of
Israeli, to its diplomatic route,'' Barak said. ``It is the
third-largest faction in the Parliament. It is a popular,
broad-based movement that maintains very sober, responsible and
balanced positions in terms of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I say this because we often hear voices that lose their
patience _ look honestly at the road traveled by Shas in the last
year, and at the road we have traveled together contrary to all
predictions.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, empathy for Shas did not abound Monday. Yosef
Lapid, leader of the Shinui Party, which won six votes on the basis
of an anti-religious platform, said he did not consider Shas'
threats to be serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is much ado about nothing,'' he said. ``This is another
extortionist trick by Shas that will be concluded in the coming 24
or 48 or 72 hours.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Barak surprised many of the secular dovish Israelis who voted
for him when he reached out to Shas to form a coalition. He decided
that he could count on the party for support in the peace effort,
while accepting that frictions between religious and secular
Israelis would persist.
</P>
<P>
   On the peace front, Shas has been flexing its muscles since
Israeli-Syrian negotiations resumed in Washington this month.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's intention to seek peace with Syria was no secret to
Shas; it was in the government's guidelines when Shas made the
decision to join.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Rabbi Yitzhak Kadouri, an elderly cabbalist rabbi with a
big following, proclaimed himself opposed to a withdrawal from the
Golan Heights, and on Sunday flew to a Golan kibbutz. There, he was
carried aloft in a chair, a knitted prayer shawl draped over his
tarboosh hat, as he blessed the kibbutzniks in Hebrew mumbles that
required Hebrew subtitles on the Israeli evening news.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   If Shas is treated like a ``stepson,'' said Yishai, the party
leader, it cannot ``take responsibility for the diplomatic
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Yosef has not yet ruled on the future of the Golan. He is
considered unlikely to urge his followers to vote down a peace
agreement if the alternative is the likelihood of violence. But
since his voice carries so much power, President Ezer Weizman
visited him in his home on Sunday night to lobby him to support the
peace initiative with Syria.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, Shas was believed to have been pushed to the
edge by a maneuver by Finance Minister Avraham Shohat. To get the
budget bill through the Finance Committee without Shas' votes,
Shohat struck deals with two other religious parties _ the National
Religious Party, a coalition partner, and United Torah Judaism, an
opposition party _ agreeing to meet their budgetary demands of some
$40 million.
</P>
<P>
   While showing Shas that it is not indispensable, the end run
also bruised its feelings. Experts on Shas say Yosef thinks the
party has suffered a series of humiliations under Barak _ from
accepting Deri's resignation under protest to giving up the
Interior Ministry and dismissing its school superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Radio said early Monday that Shas leaders met with Ariel
Sharon, leader of the opposition Likud Party, and received his
assurance that Likud would not rush in to take its place and
bolster the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have made it clear on many occasions, and I will reiterate
that we have no intention of joining this failing government,''
Sharon said later. ``We will not serve as a tool in the hands of
Mr. Barak to put pressure on any partner in the coalition.''
</P>
</TEXT>
