<HEADLINE>
BRUINS READY TO MAX OUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With one week to prepare for Pac-10 play, UCLA has
two issues to address. The Bruins must improve their half-court
offense _ an ongoing and well-documented deficiency _ and they must
learn to generate maximum effort against less-talented opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're so talented, but the only thing is that we take teams
for granted,'' freshman forward Jason Kapono said. ``It's the
so-called weaker teams from the so-called weaker conferences, like
Colorado State. If we're playing Stanford and Arizona, we know we
have to bring it.''
</P>
<P>
   In that respect, tonight's opponent, Pepperdine, has created its
own predicament.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves have played well under first-year coach Jan van Breda
Kolff. But in beating Colorado State (by 10) and Detroit Mercy (by
22), the Waves inadvertently grabbed UCLA's attention. After all,
the Bruins lost to Colorado State last week, and they lost to
Detroit Mercy in the NCAA Tournament nine months ago. Given the
comparative scores, there seems little chance of them snoozing
through Pepperdine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Detroit _ we've definitely talked about that,'' Bruins coach
Steve Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves also played well against Auburn (11-point loss) and
Kansas (15-point loss).
</P>
<P>
   ``Pepperdine has played well, but it's more about ourselves,''
Lavin said. ``When we play for 40 minutes, we're pretty good. But
when we play for 20 minutes, anybody can beat us.''
</P>
<P>
   Making progress? Point guard Earl Watson's totals from the Pearl
Harbor Classic _ 19 assists, 10 turnovers, 53.5 percent shooting,
several clutch baskets _ drew high praise from Lavin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he had a breakthrough three days, across the board,''
Lavin said. ``He showed poise and composure. When teams made runs
at us, he didn't panic.''
</P>
<P>
   Will Watson show the same poise when Arizona and Stanford turn
up the pressure?
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a Rook: Freshman Brandon Brooks, the water polo
goalie who joined the basketball team recently to bolster a
depleted frontline, looked good in his first practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's impressed me as much as any walk-on, who's a freshman, in
my nine years,'' Lavin said. ``He has a good feel for the game. He
works hard. He sets screens. He's very competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks, a Honolulu native, has been placed on a basketball
scholarship, per NCAA rules. He grabbed one rebound against Maine
in the Pearl Harbor Classic _ his only appearance thus far _ and
he's fifth in the frontcourt rotation, behind Jerome Moiso, Dan
Gadzuric, Matt Barnes and Sean Farnham.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes made 8 of 15 shots in Hawaii in his first games back from
fall-quarter academic suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Rush update: Suspended forward JaRon Rush did not return to
campus with his teammates on Dec. 26. Instead, he's at home in
Kansas City working with his legal counsel. Rush is due back when
school starts next week, perhaps earlier.
</P>
<P>
   In a related development, Rush's brother, Kareem, a Missouri
freshman, was suspended for 13 games by the NCAA for taking a few
hundred dollars from former AAU coach Myron Piggie. That's not good
news for Rush, whose financial relationship with Piggie was deeper
than Kareem's, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri will appeal. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-99 2232EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
