u s BC-FBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     12-27 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: GIANTS LACK PLAYOFF-TYPE PERFORMERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Giants fans are a peculiar mix of
contradictions. They have confidence born of deep tradition and the
equally deep insecurity of never being able to recapture that
glorious past. Unlike Jets fans who look for misery in every silver
lining, Giant fans look at two-game winning streaks as a return to
the empire the Giants once knew.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants destroyed the Jets and upset the Bills. In the Jets
game, Coach Jim Fassel turned the play-calling over to Sean Payton,
and before we knew it the airways were proclaiming Payton as the
new offensive guru. After the victory over Buffalo, fans became so
enamored of Kerry Collins, saying he had finally found a home, and
they predicted a victory over the Rams. Last week some experts who
should have known better predicted a Giant victory over Minnesota.
The Giants were routed in each game.
</P>
<P>
   So, at 11 a.m. Monday, Fassel walked briskly to a podium to face
a polite but withering series of questions about the 34-17 loss to
Minnesota and the lost opportunity of securing a place in the
playoffs. Why hadn't the Giants taken advantage of Robert Tate, the
Vikings' wide receiver turned defensive back? Why did they settle
for a field goal when they needed 6 points at the end of the third
quarter?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very disappointed with the way we played,'' Fassel said.
``I'll be honest with you, I thought we were ready to come play
this game. I thought our players focused in on all the right things
that we did during the week. Obviously we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   You'd think from the nature of the questions that the Giants
were the team of the century that had lost to the lowly Cincinnati
Bengals. What Fassel should have said was: ``Look, Minnesota is
better than we are, 17 points better. They are an explosive,
veteran team with money players. We're just the Giants and we'll be
just the Giants until we get some explosive players.''
</P>
<P>
   No one fears the Giants; no one spends extra time preparing for
a Giant weapon. Against Buffalo, the Giants had to stop Doug Flutie
and Bruce Smith. Against St. Louis, they had to contain Kurt Warner
at quarterback, Marshall Faulk in the backfield and the Rams'
speedy wide receivers. While preparing for Minnesota, they had to
devise ways to stop Randy Moss, watch Cris Carter, key on Robert
Smith and hope that Jeff George would have an off day.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday against Dallas, the Giants have to prepare for Troy
Aikman, Emmitt Smith and Deion Sanders. Opponents talk about what
the Giants like to do, not which Giants they have to stop. The
Giants always bear the burden of having to stop somebody.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' locker room door opened at 11:30 Monday morning. A
group of players huddled and talked about playoff possibilities.
One said that if Green Bay won, the Giants would have to beat
Dallas by 70 points to win the tie breaker. Everyone laughed.
Someone from the Giants' public-relations staff came around and
gave the players a two-page playoff scenario. If Green Bay wins,
the Giants are out. If Green Bay loses and the Giants beat Dallas,
the Giants are in.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel threw down the gauntlet to his players to play at a
championship level. Problem is, none of the current Giants knows
what that means; no one has played on a Giants championship team.
Phillippi Sparks, in his eighth season, came to the Giants in 1992,
a year after the Giants' last Super Bowl appearance. Jessie
Armstead and Michael Strahan came in 1993. Jason Sehorn came in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' front office has to find a way to get dynamic
players who can provide answers to the challenges that a team like
Minnesota posed on Sunday: Moss throws a perfect option pass to
Carter; Moe Williams returns a kickoff 85 yards; Smith breaks a
70-yard touchdown run. The Giants' offense could only manage a
field goal and a plodding time-consuming touchdown drive in the
second half.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways the option pass from Moss to Carter underlines not
just the game but the disparity in big-play talent between the
Giants and elite teams like the Vikings. ``It took a great throw;
Moss made a great throw,'' Fassel said. ``That's what I'm talking
about. They made a great throw. It wasn't like we blew it or just
didn't know it was coming; we knew it was coming.''
</P>
<P>
   The shortsighted Giants fan will wonder if the team will make
the playoffs. The farsighted fan sits and wonders whether the
Giants will get championship players on the field. Will they ever
rebuild the Big Blue Empire?
</P>
<P>
   On afternoons like last Sunday, the empire seems several
marshlands away. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
