<SLUG> BC-OBIT-FISHER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAROLD FISHER, 89, LAWYER WHO WAS ACTIVE IN POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Calif., N.C.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By NICK RAVO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Harold L. Fisher, a lawyer who played a prominent
role in Democratic politics in New York for several decades and
also served as a chairman of New York state's Metropolitan
Transportation Authority, died Sunday at his home in Fort
Lauderdale, Fla. He was 89.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher, sometimes called ``Mr. Brooklyn,'' was appointed to the
board of the authority, when it was created by Gov. Nelson
Rockefeller in 1968. He became vice chairman in 1975, acting
chairman in January 1977 and chairman in April 1977, serving in
that post through 1979.
</P>
<P>
   As head of the authority, Fisher may be best known for
negotiating two labor agreements without a strike or a fare
increase during the fiscal crisis of the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher was also a crucial behind-the-scenes adviser in New York
City's fiscal crisis, thanks to friendships he formed years earlier
with Gov. Hugh Carey, Mayor Abraham Beame and Democratic Party
leaders like Carmine DeSapio and Meade Esposito, as well as
Republicans like Assemblyman Perry Duryea.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was indispensable,'' said Edward Koch, who was mayor during
the late '70s. ``Without him we wouldn't have actually been able to
do all these things we did, namely prevent strikes. People
respected him.''
</P>
<P>
   Although his political career overshadowed his law practice,
Fisher was known for his legal skills, too, particularly his
knowledge of the state's election laws. He once ordered a car
driven into the freight elevator at the Board of Elections
building, taken to the Board of Election's floor and clocked in _
all because the filing petitions for party candidates were locked
in the trunk, the lock would not open and the filing deadline was
minutes away.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher also made a name for himself in commercial law. Once,
acting as the lawyer for creditors of sugar companies and an
airline expropriated by the Cuban government after the communist
revolution, he seized the airplane that brought Fidel Castro to New
York for his first U.N. session. Only after the U.S. State
Department intervened was the plane released.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what his secret for success was, Fisher said in an
interview with The New York Times in 1978: ``I don't have a great
ego, but I'm smart. I know the personalities around town. I don't
lie. I keep my word and I keep my mouth shut.''
</P>
<P>
   Harold Leonard Fisher was born on the Lower East Side of
Manhattan on Dec. 10, 1910. He attended New York University for a
year before entering St. John's University College of Law, where he
graduated in 1932. After a law firm clerkship, he opened a law
practice in 1935 in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, he served on a local draft board. After the
war, he traveled to Europe on behalf of Jewish refugee
organizations to resettle Jewish orphans. He was also active in
raising funds and supplies for the Irgun, the militant underground
organization fighting for Israeli independence.
</P>
<P>
   In 1948, Fisher returned to the United States and moved his
office to Brooklyn, where he was to practice law for more than 40
years. In 1992, he returned his practice, now known as Fisher,
Fisher &AMP; Berger, to Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   In 1959, he became assistant counsel to the minority leader of
the New York state Assembly, Anthony Travia. Fisher then helped
Travia become Assembly speaker after the 1964 elections. For the
next five years, Fisher served as counsel to the speaker, helping
to shape the revision of New York's divorce law and other
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher also served from 1971 to 1976 on the board of Centro, the
mass transit authority for the Syracuse area, and as chairman of
the American Public Transit Association. He was chairman of
Convention Center Development Corp., which built the Jacob K.
Javits Convention Center in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, President Carter asked him to join the U.S. delegation,
invited by President Anwar Sadat of Egypt, to witness the transfer
of control of Mount Sinai under the Camp David Accords.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher's wife, Betty Kahn, to whom he was married for almost 63
years, died in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by five children, Leonard of Danville, Calif.;
Alice Fisher Rubin of New York, Stephanie Cooper Harrison of
Asheville, N.C., Andrew and Kenneth, both of New York; 11
grandchildren and five great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
