<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-SABRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS END A LOSING PATTERN WITH VICTORY OVER SABRES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ For 10 days at least, the New Jersey
Devils will not have to deal with the question of why they can't
seem to win on the second night of back-to-back games.
</P>
<P>
   They put an end to that streak of futility Monday night with a
4-1 triumph over the Buffalo Sabres before a crowd of 16,248 at
Continental Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils had dropped the second of two games on consecutive
nights eight straight times this season. On Sunday, they played the
Rangers to a 3-3 tie, so Monday night they faced the situation
again. The Devils don't have another such scenario until they meet
the Sabres again on Jan. 6 in Buffalo, a night after they play in
Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Petr Sykora, John Madden and Patrik Elias scored the goals for
the Devils, against Martin Biron, with Sykora getting two goals.
Biron was replaced at the start of the third period by Dwayne
Roloson, who was removed for an extra skater before Sykora got an
empty-net goal with 5.8 seconds to play.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres (15-16-5) fired 20 shots at Martin Brodeur of the
Devils (20-12-4), whose only lapse was a goal he allowed to Geoff
Sanderson early in the third period, after the Devils had built a
3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils were leading by three goals after two periods. Two of
the goals came after Sabres turnovers at their blue line.
</P>
<P>
   Sykora scored the game's first goal, with 6:54 left in the
opening period. He stole the puck from Cory Sarich and went in
alone on Biron, beating him over the glove with a backhander. It
was Sykora's ninth goal, but only his first in the last 12 games.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest play in the first two periods came 12:17 into the
second. With the Sabres on a power play, Madden swiped the puck at
the Buffalo blue line and skated in alone on Biron, beating him
with a rising shot.
</P>
<P>
   It Madden's seventh of the season and his league-leading third
short-handed goal. He was left out of the lineup a day earlier in
the tie against the Rangers, and he worked hard to impress Coach
Robbie Ftorek, who used him to kill penalties Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres' intensity fell noticeably after Madden's goal and
the Devils scored their third goal just over five minutes later
when Elias' shot from the slot got past Biron. It was his seventh
goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres failed on all five man advantages they had in the
first two periods, underscoring why their power play is last in the
league.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-27-99 2241EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
