<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 22:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0357 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-FASHION-FRONTROW-ART-     12-27 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-FRONTROW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT TO WEAR TO STAY HOME NEW YEAR'S EVE; PLUS THE APPOINTMENT OF A
FASHION CRITIC 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By GINIA BELLAFANTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a recent Time/CNN poll indicated, 72 percent of Americans
have no plans to do anything special on this New Year's Eve of all
New Years' Eves, despite the hoopla that has surrounded this coming
Friday night for the latter part of the decade. But for many, doing
something unextraordinary doesn't translate into wearing something
ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people who think one should get dressed up,'' said
Elle's fashion director, Marin Hopper. ``On the other hand, you
think to yourself, `Who makes the best pajamas?'''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hopper, who, like most other people, plans to hole up with
family and close friends for the holiday, said she was thinking
about vintage '60s Jean Muir, or maybe sleepwear from Kate Spade.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ms. Hopper remains a part of that rare faction of the
shopping public for whom the name Jean Muir means something, her
problem _ what to wear to do not much _ is apparently gripping
many. Salespeople in and out of New York say they have received
many requests from customers in the last few weeks for advice on
outfitting themselves for sitting in their living rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Nanette DiFalco, the director of personal shopping at Saks Fifth
Avenue, said that people have come to her proclaiming: ``I've
decided to stay at home. I want to look special.''
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, women are choosing to achieve that specialness
with more or less the same look. ``In the last month and a half,
people have gone hostessy,'' said Kathleen Kruer in San Diego, who
bears the imposing title high-fashion wardrobe coordinator for
Nordstrom.
</P>
<P>
   That is to say that Ms. Kruer's clients (they number more than a
few, given that she is Nordstrom's highest grossing sales
representative nationwide) are opting for full-length, A-line
skirts _ ``hostess skirts'' as they are known _ to hold
get-togethers at home or to attend them at someone else's.
</P>
<P>
   The skirts are generally made from some variation of silk. Ms.
Kruer, who said she had not had a single request for a beaded gown
for this New Year's Eve, has sold hostess skirts by Donna Karan,
Vera Wang and Valentino, among others. Workshop, a fashionable
boutique in San Francisco, has done well with hostess skirts in
tulle from the Italian label Oneday. Banana Republic is offering
them in crinkled, pastel silk versions. Because so many people are
spending New Year's Eve with their families, it is common for women
choosing hostess skirts to buy tiny replicas for their young
daughters, said Ms. Kruer.
</P>
<P>
   David Ingram, a personal shopper at Barneys New York, has also
been dressing women who plan to do nothing particularly spectacular
this Dec. 31. The hostess skirt, paired with the requisite sweater
set, ``is unequivocally what people are wearing,'' he said.
High-profile clients _ ``the ones who aren't interfacing with the
food,'' Ingram explained _ are electing to wear traditional
mobility-inhibiting taffeta versions. Others _ presumably those
forced to lean over and spoon out the caviar themselves _ are
favoring satin crepe.
</P>
<P>
   There is something decidedly future-averse about the popularity
of the hostess skirt, an artifact belonging more to the world of a
Rick Moody story than to the world of the Palm V. The skirt is an
outgrowth of the postwar suburban boom, when regular Americans
increasingly entertained at home, said the fashion historian
Valerie Steele. The idea behind the skirt, she explained, is that
the hostess could be dressed up but still comfortable. In the
1960s, even Barbie had hostess clothes. (Pairing full-length skirts
with twin sets was first popular in World War II, said another
historian, Caroline Rennolds Milbank: Mainbocher incorporated
sweaters into evening looks, as oil rations left people heat
deprived.)
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the popularity of the hostess skirt shouldn't be all
that surprising at a century's end that is also seeing a TV game
show renaissance. ``There's been an enormous flee backward,'' the
trend forecaster Faith Popcorn said of the unsettling millennial
moment. ``Maybe we think that if we dress naively, nothing bad will
happen to us.''
</P>
<P>
   A FASHION CRITIC IS APPOINTED
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Horyn, a fashion reporter for The New York Times, has been
appointed fashion critic. Ms. Horyn, 42, joined The Times in
January from Vanity Fair, where she was a contributing editor. From
1990 to 1994 she was the fashion reporter for The Washington Post.
She began her career covering fashion for The Detroit News in 1986.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
