<DOCNO> NYT19991227.0422 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0363 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-BALL-HOPKINS-ART-N     12-27 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BALL-HOPKINS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A STEADY-HANDED SURGEON IS DROPPING THE BALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo, NYT23, is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(ms) 
 By NEIL MacFARQUHAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Word that the task of ushering in the next millennium
has been bestowed on Dr. Mary Ann Hopkins is filtering slowly
through the wards where she works at Bellevue Hospital Center and
NYU Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   One patient, Celesti C. Fechter, for example, heard it from her
anesthesiologist. Ms. Fechter was being wheeled into surgery when
he explained that the hands wielding the scalpel would be the very
hands entrusted with pushing the button to drop the New Year's ball
on Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins was picked, he explained, because she volunteers her
skills in various war zones to Doctors Without Borders, the
international relief group that won the Nobel Peace Prize this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I thought the anesthesiologist was joking,'' Ms.
Fechter said. ``But then I was kind of pleased. I figured if she
can perform surgery in the conditions of most Third World
countries, she can do it in New York in a hospital with no bullets
flying.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, conjecture about whether bullets or explosives will be
flying crops up frequently when patients or other medical workers
hear about her assignment. ``Are they keeping you in a secure
place?'' a technician asked.
</P>
<P>
   Given where she's been, Hopkins, 36, takes a rather calm
approach to the remote possibility of any violence. She quoted
advice from her boss: ``If anybody needs first aid, you'll be
there.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, being in the thick of things, more or less, got Hopkins
to Times Square. (Doctors Without Borders was selected for the
button-pushing role by the Times Square Business Improvement
District, the celebration's main organizer.)
</P>
<P>
   As a classics major at Harvard, Hopkins spent the three summers
before her graduation in 1985 volunteering in India and Somalia for
a relief group, Families for Children. In India, she and her sister
helped to manage an orphanage housing 500 children.
</P>
<P>
   One day, the job of taking a 13-year-old girl with typhoid to
the hospital fell to her. The child died and she had to take the
body back to the orphanage on her lap in a bicycle rickshaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know now that she must have been in septic shock, that her
veins had collapsed,'' Hopkins said. ``But at the time I knew
nothing except that there was no blood in her when they cut into a
vein, and she looked very white.''
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins is descended from three generations of surgeons _ her
grandfather spent his residency at Bellevue _ but it was that death
in India that pushed her to enter Harvard Medical School.
</P>
<P>
   ``Medicine had always been in my background, but when you have a
child die like that ...'' she said, her voice trailing off. ``That
was traumatic. I haven't thought about that for a while. I tend to
block traumatic things from my head, or I would probably never go
back.''
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from medical school in 1992, she was a resident
in general surgery at New York Hospital-Cornell Medical Center, and
she worked at Staten Island University Hospital before switching to
Bellevue and NYU this fall.
</P>
<P>
   For surgeons, Doctors Without Borders bends its usual
requirement that medical volunteers commit to a minimum of six
months for their initial relief trip. But still, getting the time
is always a process of negotiation. Hopkins said one reason she
moved to Bellevue was its commitment to public health worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   She believes the main difference between her work in American
hospitals and her stints overseas, aside from day-to-day issues
like not ordering a lot of X-rays and lab tests, is that her
expertise has a far larger impact. ``If I was not here, someone
could replace me tomorrow,'' she said of her work in New York. In
contrast, during her time in Sri Lanka in 1996, she was the only
surgeon in a region of 500,000 people, while two months ago in
Burundi she taught a doctor how to perform basic surgery like an
emergency Caesarean section.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the great rewards of this work is to leave someone who
can take care of patients if there isn't a surgeon there,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   A main reason she was picked from the 30 or so Doctors Without
Borders volunteers in New York City is that the organization wants
to draw attention to the conflicts in India and Somalia, where she
worked. The Times Square appearance involves showing up at 6:30
a.m. Friday so she can be available for things like television
interviews. (She bought some new lipstick _ ``Thank God I'm a
surgeon, I can wear pajamas all day long'' _ and she hopes that by
then someone will have briefed her on a few pertinent details _
like what precisely she will do.)
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins said she started laughing when she was first asked to
perform the task, and her biggest problem so far has been
convincing people that it is true.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can think of the least likely thing that you would ever
be asked to do, this would rank up there,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After her sudden anointment, she and her husband, Dr. Pietro
Mazzoni, a neurologist, postponed a surprise visit to his family on
the West Coast. He will be with her on the square, along with her
parents. He has been kidding her that she is likely to change the
course of the next millennium, not to mention confusing the
millions of people watching, by hitting the button too early or too
late.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is convinced that I will be late and the next 1,000
years will be a few seconds behind,'' she said, laughing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
