<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0364 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GEN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     12-27 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS LOSING ITS COMIC RELIEF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's the final minute of the third period for the
Wayne Gretzky of cartoons. The Michael Jordan of comic strips has
his right wrist cocked, ready to apply one last penstroke to a
singular career.
</P>
<P>
   Another man who made an indelible mark on athletics is leaving
us.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday Charles Schulz signs off on ``Peanuts.'' If you can't
see what a loss to the sports world that will be, then you didn't
grow up as I did, digesting Schulz's comic strip as part of a
healthy, hearty breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   I tell people I've been devouring the sports pages first thing
in the morning since being weaned from Dr. Seuss and Dick and Jane.
Like the roundness of Charlie Brown's head, this is a slight
exaggeration, for effect. The truth is, I long have turned to
sports only after reading ``Peanuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, many days it's hard to see where ``Peanuts'' ends and
the sports section begins. That has been by design. For Schulz, who
recently was diagnosed with colon cancer, sports has been equal
parts perspiration and inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   Before he became the father of Charlie Brown and Snoopy, Schulz,
77, was an enthusiastic athlete. Like Gretzky in his youth, Schulz
used to practice his slapshot by swatting tennis balls at his
grandmother while she tended the goal with a broom.
</P>
<P>
   He earned money for comic books, his one great indulgence as a
youth, by caddying at Highland Park Golf Course in his hometown of
St. Paul, Minn.
</P>
<P>
   And, contrary to popular belief, Schulz's first true love wasn't
a certain red-haired girl, it was the sport of every red-blooded
American boy. We're talking baseball, Willie, Mickey and `The
Duke'.
</P>
<P>
   In the sandlots of St. Paul, Schulz once pitched a no-hitter in
a summer-league baseball game. In more typical Charlie Brown
fashion, Schulz also was on the losing end of a 40-0 score.
</P>
<P>
   Once a pitcher, always a pitcher: As he settled into the middle
innings of the biggest game of all, sports became the mound from
which Schulz delivered precise lessons about life's fastballs and
curves.
</P>
<P>
   There was the time Charlie Brown told Lucy Van Pelt he had
dreamed of playing in baseball's big leagues all his life ``but I
know I'll never make it.'' To which she replied he ought to set
more immediate goals and offered this gem of an example: ``See if
you can walk out to the mound without falling down.''
</P>
<P>
   A fine (and funny) lesson in perspective, that.
</P>
<P>
   For every winner there must be a loser. It's one of life's
harshest axioms. Schulz tackled the point tactfully time and again,
using Charlie Brown as his carrier.
</P>
<P>
   Lucy's younger brother Linus once described to Charlie Brown how
a football team came back from a 6-0 deficit in the final seconds
to win, prompting the team's fans to spill onto the field and start
dancing and hugging and laughing. Charlie Brown was silent until
Linus finished his story. Then he wondered aloud, ``How did the
other team feel?''
</P>
<P>
   Another time Lucy told Charlie Brown, ``You think you'd be happy
if you won a ball game, don't you? Well, you wouldn't. If you won
one game, you'd want to win another and then another. Soon you'd
want to win every ball game you played.''
</P>
<P>
   It's true; winning can be addictive. Just ask the Clippers, who,
unlike good ol' Charlie Brown, are finally getting a taste of
success.
</P>
<P>
   The reason Charlie Brown has been a luckless loser since well
before Donald Sterling gave L.A. bad basketball is simple.
``Winning is great,'' Schulz is fond of saying, ``but it's not
funny.''
</P>
<P>
   But of course. You can't laugh if you don't recognize the
punchline.
</P>
<P>
   The simple fact is, most of us are on far more intimate terms
with failure than success. That's why we can feel Charlie Brown's
embarrassment when he is bounced from a spelling bee after spelling
maze M-a-y-s.
</P>
<P>
   We know exactly what Charlie Brown means when he observes,
``Distances on a baseball diamond are deceiving. When you walk from
the bench to the plate it's about 30 feet. When you walk from the
plate to the bench (after striking out) it's four miles.''
</P>
<P>
   We easily catch Lucy's drift when she tells Charlie Brown, ``you
are three putts on the 18th green, you are a seven-ten split in the
10th frame... a love set... you are a missed free throw, a shanked
nine-iron and a called third strike.''
</P>
<P>
   Wholly human, that's what Schulz's characters are.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenges to be faced in sports work marvelously as a
caricature of the challenges we face in the more serious aspects of
our lives,'' Schulz has said. ``When Charlie Brown has tried to
analyze his own difficulties in life, he has always been able to
express them best in sports terms.''
</P>
<P>
   With a few strokes of his pen, Schulz turned basic human
vulnerabilities into a rare art form. He paved the way for Ziggy
and Cathy and, yes, Eric Cartman (for which he is forgiven).
</P>
<P>
   Schulz was ahead of his time in other ways. A trustee of the
Women's Sports Foundation, he was a champion of female athletes
long before Mia Hamm and Company made it fashionable.
</P>
<P>
   One of the characters in ``Peanuts'' is Peppermint Patty, who is
nearly as old as Michelle Akers and every bit as feisty.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA had yet to embrace women's collegiate athletics when
Peppermint Patty, an aspiring Olympic figure skater (as were two of
Schulz's daughters), waged her war against the boys at the local
rink. They tried to kick her off the ice so they could play hockey,
but Peppermint Patty stubbornly held her ground. At length the
conflict was resolved when the boys asked her to be a center on
their team.
</P>
<P>
   Another day found her railing at a sports broadcast that ended
without any mention of female athletes. ``What about women in
sports?'' she screamed at the television. ``Did you tell us what
Conni Place has been doing? And how about... Evelyn Ashford and Ann
Meyers and Judy Sladky and Sarah Doctor?''
</P>
<P>
   It takes a true sports fan to know of Sladky, a five-time U.S.
champion in ice dancing. It was an unabashed sports nut who, when
asked to list his three heroes named Dwight Eisenhower, Billie Jean
King and Sam Snead.
</P>
<P>
   When I was 13, I sent Schulz a booklet of my Peanuts drawings.
He sent me back a handwritten note, ``You draw very well for your
age.'' On that day he joined Abraham Lincoln, Donna deVarona and my
parents on my heroes list.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd dearly love to have won the U.S. Amateur or the World
Series,'' Schulz once said, ``but what I've done, I think, is much
better.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll get no arguments here. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
