<HEADLINE>
KINGS TO ADD CORKUM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In an attempt to regroup from five consecutive
losses, the Kings will sign unrestricted free-agent center Bob
Corkum today before leaving for Wednesday's game in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Corkum, the former Mighty Duck who played the past three seasons
with the Phoenix Coyotes, needs to pass a physical this morning to
complete the one-year deal that includes a club option for the
2000-01 season.
</P>
<P>
   Corkum, who scored 23 goals for Anaheim in 1993-94, had just
nine last season. But he is considered a valuable two-way player
who is excellent on faceoffs. He was seeking $1.5 million this
season on the free-agent market but had no takers. He is believed
to be getting about a third of that figure in his deal with the
Kings.
</P>
<P>
   Despite injuries to top players all season, the Kings are
surprisingly solid at center. Jozef Stumpel has returned after
missing five weeks after abdominal surgery. Bryan Smolinski is
among the league's leading scorers and Ian Laperriere has added a
few goals to his enforcer role on the Kings third line.
</P>
<P>
   Corkum, who turned 32 on Dec. 18, will not play Wednesday
against Colorado or Thursday at home against Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings have a roster spot open after sending left winger Bill
Huard to minor-league Lowell, Mass., on Tuesday. Huard, brought in
to add grit to the Kings front line, played just one game and did
not score. But Corkum still needs to show the Kings how close he is
to being ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't played all season and we need to get him in here to
evaluate his level of conditioning,'' coach Andy Murray said. ``We
like his all-around ability and his ability to play against the top
skating centers in the league. He doesn't fill a specific need, but
he adds great depth to our club.''
</P>
<P>
   Better effort: Defenseman Jere Karalahti, who scored his first
NHL point in Sunday's 3-2 overtime loss to Phoenix, is expected to
remain with the club now that Aki Berg will miss the next two games
with a rib injury.
</P>
<P>
   Karalahti, shaky in his first NHL game Dec. 11 at Montreal, was
more composed Sunday and played 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very nervous for my first game,'' he said. ``This was my
first home game, but it didn't seem so bad. I got into the flow of
the game right away and felt a lot more relaxed.''
</P>
<P>
   Karalahti was teased by his teammates for his first point. He
was credited with the second assist on the first-period goal by
Laperriere even though replays showed he never touched the puck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those things happen,'' said Karalahti, who was sent down after
the Montreal game and later caught the flu. ``After everything I'll
take it. There will be more.''
</P>
<P>
   Injury update: Goaltender Jamie Storr, sidelined 10 days ago
with a concussion, is still at least a week away from returning.
Marcel Cousineau is backing up starter Stephane Fiset.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
