<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0432 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-FOOD-ZAPPER-2TAKES-KA     12-27 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-ZAPPER-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCHERS USING TECHNOLOGY TO ZAP DANGEROUS BACTERIA OFF FOODS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN BAVLEY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, Mo. _ There's new hope for meat lovers who'd like to
bite into a juicy, rare hamburger without worrying that they're
swallowing a deadly dose of E. coli bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have found a way to take technology _ developed by
the military to knock enemy missiles out of the sky _ and use it to
zap dangerous bacteria on meat and other foods.
</P>
<P>
   These germ-killing devices, called electron beam accelerators,
have become the focus of intensive research by engineers and food
scientists at the University of Missouri-Columbia, Iowa State
University and other places.
</P>
<P>
   One manufacturer of e-beam accelerators already is building
plants in Iowa and Hawaii to irradiate hamburger, chicken and
tropical fruit. Big producers of beef and poultry, including IBP
Inc. and Tyson Foods Inc., are planning to give e-beams a tryout.
</P>
<P>
   And as word of the capabilities of electron beams spreads, food
processors are lining up to have test batches of their products
irradiated, as well.
</P>
<P>
   University of Missouri researchers have been approached by
suppliers of soft drinks, produce, fruit juices, baked goods and
even pet foods. All are interested in using the university's
electron beam accelerator.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hot market, everybody's anxious to get into it,'' said
Thomas Clevenger, a civil engineer involved in e-beam research at
MU. ``For every food industry, there're applications for this.''
</P>
<P>
   Fueling that interest is the growing public concern about food
poisoning. The U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention
estimates that Americans suffer about 76 million cases of
food-borne illness each year. About 325,000 people are hospitalized
and 5,000 die.
</P>
<P>
   Although some advocates for safer foods question the
wholesomeness of irradiated food, e-beam researchers insist the
food is safe.
</P>
<P>
   Electron beam accelerators already are used extensively to
disinfect medical instruments and supplies, such as catheters.
Applied to food, researchers say, e-beams promise to virtually
eliminate salmonella, E. coli, campylobacter, listeria and other
germs that cause disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``It guarantees that meat is safe when it leaves the factory,''
Clevenger said.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers, however, still would have to handle and prepare
irradiated foods as they would other products. Some bacteria may
not be destroyed by irradiation, and bacteria from other foods
could still contaminate irradiated foods.
</P>
<P>
   Technology to irradiate foods has been around for decades. Until
e-beams became available, radioactive isotopes were used to supply
the radiation. But the cost and logistical problems involved in
building safe nuclear facilities and the public's distrust of
anything involving radioactivity have slowed the technology's
development.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Agriculture published regulations this
month to govern irradiation of hamburger, steaks, pork chops and
other raw meat. Irradiation has been approved for disinfecting a
number of other foods, including poultry, spices, fruit and
vegetables, but its use has been limited.
</P>
<P>
   E-beam proponents acknowledge that consumers may be skeptical
about eating irradiated food, but they hope public opinion would
favor the technology because it relies on electricity rather than
radioactivity.
</P>
<P>
   They prefer to call e-beam treatments ``cold pasteurization''
rather than irradiation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process we're talking about is non-nuclear....You can turn
it off with the flip of a switch,'' said Randy Curry, a University
of Missouri electrical engineer.
</P>
<P>
   Curry used to work on electron beam technology as part of the
Strategic Defense Initiative, the Reagan administration's plan to
protect the United States from missile attacks.
</P>
<P>
   After budget cuts shut down Curry's research, he and other
engineers began looking for new applications for their expertise.
</P>
<P>
   An electron beam accelerator uses a cathode to produce a stream
of electrons. High voltage is applied to accelerate the electrons,
creating a pencil-thin, high-energy e-beam.
</P>
<P>
   When the beam strikes food, it damages or destroys the DNA of
bacteria so they die or become unable to reproduce.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kill... MORE
</P>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, Mo. _ ...become unable to reproduce.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kill is instantaneous,'' Clevenger said.
</P>
<P>
   The electron beam accelerator at the University of Missouri is
formidable _ about 6 feet of coiled wire, metal pipes and rubber
hose mounted to a metal frame on a laboratory floor.
</P>
<P>
   Accelerators, such as this one, can cost as much as $5 million
and require an additional $5 million in shielding. Researchers are
working with manufacturers to develop smaller, less-expensive
accelerators.
</P>
<P>
   Clevenger believes that eventually, the price could be reduced
to $1 million for an accelerator and shielding. And the
accelerators would be small enough to add to the conveyor belts of
food-processing plants.
</P>
<P>
   The MU researchers also are looking at modifying accelerators to
produce X-rays that could penetrate foods more deeply than e-beams.
</P>
<P>
   E-beams have many potential applications, said MU food scientist
Nan Unklesbay.
</P>
<P>
   They could prevent mold from growing on baked goods, she said.
They could pasteurize fruit juices without changing their taste, as
conventional pasteurization does. They could even be used to make
raw seafood less risky.
</P>
<P>
   All these uses would require government approval, but Unklesbay
didn't see anything blocking the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as the technology is proven with one food, I think it
could happen very quickly,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some consumer advocates, however, don't share Unklesbay's
enthusiasm for e-beams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a false solution to a very real problem,'' said Ronnie
Cummins, national director of the Organic Consumers Association,
based in Little Marais, Minn.
</P>
<P>
   Cummins said researchers have found that irradiation of any kind
robs foods of substantial amounts of vitamins. It also causes
chemical reactions in foods that create cancer-causing substances,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (the food industry) will have a grave problem
convincing the public that it is safe,'' Cummins said.
</P>
<P>
   Meat processors are turning to irradiation rather than employing
better sanitation to keep contaminants off meat, Cummins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's coming up now because they've reached a crisis. They know
they have to do something, but they're doing the wrong thing. It's
not going to fly.''
</P>
<P>
   Those concerns, however, aren't generally shared by medical
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Scientific evidence is strong that irradiated foods are safe and
nutritious, said Carol Tucker Foreman, a distinguished fellow with
the Consumer Federation of America, a coalition of consumer groups.
</P>
<P>
   But Foreman, too, said irradiation should not become a
substitute for good sanitation.
</P>
<P>
   She anticipated that irradiated food would be marketed first to
hospitals and nursing homes, and to people with weakened immune
systems, such as AIDS patients. Next might be fast-food
restaurants, she said.
</P>
<P>
   E-beam irradiation would raise the price of hamburger or chicken
by about 5 cents per pound, said Ralph Williams, spokesman for
Titan Corp., a San Diego-based manufacturer of electron beam
accelerators.
</P>
<P>
   Titan has built an e-beam plant in Sioux City, Iowa. Beginning
in February, several large producers of chicken and ground beef
will use the facility's SureBeam to irradiate frozen meat for test
marketing.
</P>
<P>
   The USDA is requiring that irradiated products be labeled with
the international symbol for irradiation, called a radura, and
carry a statement that they have been treated.
</P>
<P>
   Unklesbay and other e-beam proponents had hoped the USDA would
have had a campaign to educate consumers about the benefits of
irradiation. But that's not in the agency's plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to appear to be endorsing it,'' said Carol
Blake, USDA spokeswoman. ``All we're saying is, it's permitted. It
certainly doesn't replace the sanitation standards companies have
in place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
