<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0486 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-DRUNKDRIVING-LAWS-KAN     12-27 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUNKDRIVING-LAWS-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Lawmakers promise to work for tougher laws against drunken
driving  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATT CAMPBELL and JOE LAMBE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Democratic leaders of the Missouri Senate on
Monday said that in the coming legislative session they would work
with the House and governor to pass tougher laws against drunken
driving.
</P>
<P>
   Bills to tighten the state's laws on drunken driving have
faltered in recent years, but a push by the Democratic leadership
may make the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're making it one of our priorities,'' said Sen. Ronnie
DePasco of Kansas City, who as majority floor leader moves bills
once they come out of committee.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Jackson County Prosecutor Bob Beaird said Monday that
he plans to start a special court in the coming year to force
repeat drunken drivers into extended treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Several members of the Kansas City legislative delegation called
for tougher laws following The Kansas City Star's examination of
drunken driving in the city and state.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper found that Kansas City leads Missouri in
alcohol-related accidents, leads the state in the number of repeat
drunken drivers and leads the state in the most repeat offenders
with 10 or more convictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was certainly appalled that we're the drunk driving capital
of Missouri,'' said Democratic Rep. Bill Skaggs of Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper also reported that Missouri ranks above the
national average in the percentage of traffic fatalities involving
alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   DePasco said House and Senate Democratic leaders met recently
with Gov. Mel Carnahan to draft a strategy for the next legislative
session, which starts Jan. 5. Tougher drunken-driving legislation
was on the Democrats' agenda, he said.
</P>
<P>
   DePasco predicted 2000 will be the year Missouri approves
lowering the definition of intoxication from 0.1 percent
blood-alcohol content to .08 percent. Seventeen states, including
Kansas, receive millions of dollars in federal highway incentives
because they already have the lower level.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bound to pass,'' DePasco said. ``It's about time. It
comes up every year.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have majorities in the House and the Senate, which
gives the party control of committees and the power to move bills
quickly, to limit amendments and schedule votes on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Sen. Morris Westfall of Halfway, Mo., has fought for
.08 and already has introduced another bill. The measure passed the
House in the 1999 session but failed in the Senate. Westfall has
been critical of the leadership for not backing .08.
</P>
<P>
   The beverage industry has opposed lowering the definition for
intoxication, arguing it would unfairly focus on social drinkers.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the .08 issue, Missouri stands to lose about $25
million in federal highway construction money if it does not adopt
a stricter law against open alcohol containers in vehicles and
tougher laws against repeat drunken drivers.
</P>
<P>
   If the measures fail, Missouri would still get the money, but it
could not be used for much-needed highway construction. Congress
has mandated that the money be used on safety programs.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Sen. Ed Quick of Liberty, president pro tem of the
Senate, said Monday he thinks a measure to forbid open alcohol
containers in the passenger area of vehicles has a good chance of
passing next year.
</P>
<P>
   But Quick was more cautious about measures against repeat
offenders, which include impoundment of vehicles and mandatory
minimum penalties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure tougher penalties are the answer,'' he said. ``We
need to enforce the laws we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Rep. Henry Rizzo of Kansas City, however, said the
state cannot afford to risk losing federal dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to do whatever it takes to keep the
highway money because our highway department is in total disarray
right now,'' Rizzo said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Carnahan has said the governor will support the
.08 issue, tougher rules against repeat drunken drivers and open
container restrictions. House Speaker Steve Gaw has said he
supports Carnahan on those issues.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri Department of Public Safety and Mothers Against
Drunk Driving also support .08 legislation, the open-container law
and tougher penalties for repeat offenders. MADD plans an
aggressive strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We intend to be on the offensive this year,'' said Paula
Kanyo, president of the Missouri chapter of MADD. ``This is the
year we say, `Why haven't you done something?' ''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the other measures, DePasco said he would like to
see tougher penalties linked to higher blood-alcohol levels because
evidence suggests drivers with a blood alcohol content of .13 or
higher cause more accidents and deaths. That position is supported
by spirits distillers and by MADD.
</P>
<P>
   DePasco also would like to see more cooperation between state
and local officials to keep better track of convicted alcohol
offenders to discourage them from relapsing.
</P>
<P>
   The special court that Beaird has in mind would be modeled after
existing drug courts, in which a judge supervises drug offenders
regularly for a year and directs them into treatment, counseling or
short jail terms.
</P>
<P>
   Beaird said the Jackson County program would send drunken
drivers with three or more convictions to 120 days in prison and
then to the special court. Drivers who fail to complete the year of
treatment could go back to prison for four more years.
</P>
<P>
   The program would be similar to one now operating in Buchanan
County, Mo., and at about a dozen courts nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Beaird said Jackson County would also put some repeat offenders
on a drug called naltrexone to kill the desire for alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Beaird said he may seek some funding assistance for his new
court from the state. Such a request could come before the House
appropriations committee for education and public safety, which is
led by Democratic Rep. Scott Lakin of Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Lakin, who last year sponsored a bill to register beer-keg
rentals as a deterrent to underage drinking, said Monday he
supports a comprehensive package against alcohol offenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to make sure we do something that is not just cosmetic
but something that is really good public policy,'' Lakin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
