<SLUG> BC-BKN-WALLACE-ARREST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELD 12 HOURS ON LICENSE VIOLATION, KNICKS' WALLACE SAYS POLICE
DEMEANED HIM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After being arrested in Manhattan early Monday for
driving with a suspended license and spending 12 hours in jail, New
York Knicks forward John Wallace described the police treatment of
him as demeaning and believed he was picked on because of his race
and celebrity as an athlete.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace said he was handcuffed and placed in a van after the
police stopped him at a routine checkpoint on West 43rd Street
around 2 a.m. Wallace said the police told him his license had been
suspended since Dec. 9, and that when he tried to explain how their
information was in error, he was ignored.
</P>
<P>
   On the way to a midtown precinct house, Wallace, who is black,
said one of the officers used a racial slur in describing people
standing outside of a club. Wallace said that when he was being
processed at the police station, one of the officers was bragging
about the number of celebrities he had arrested.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see it in their faces, they were happy they got one,''
said Wallace, who was released after paying a $175 fine for driving
without a license.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a half hour after Wallace was stopped at the
checkpoint near Times Square, three people were wounded at a nearby
dance spot, Club New York. When asked where he was going when
stopped by the police, Wallace said, ``That's personal.''
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke with reporters on a conference call Monday
afternoon, Wallace remained upset at the situation and resented
being held in jail for 12 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is I spent a night in jail, they put me in cuffs and
it was demeaning to myself,'' Wallace said. ``They said I'd be let
go at 8 a.m. They knew I had practice. Finally, I was let go at 3
p.m.''
</P>
<P>
   The police said it was not uncommon for someone to spend the
night in jail while the paperwork is being processed through the
system. And Lt. Stephen Biegel, a police department spokesman, said
Wallace's car was not singled out and that officers stopped
everyone that passed through the safety checkpoint early Monday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wallace was asked to produce a license, and he didn't have one
on him so he gave them a passport for identification,'' Biegel
said. Wallace's name was run through a computer that is linked to
the state's Department of Motor Vehicles and his license came up
suspended for failure to answer a summons. Wallace said he never
received a summons and had taken a defensive-driving course Dec. 21
to erase 4 points of the 11 that were on his license for traffic
violations.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace said he was denied the opportunity to make a phone call
when he was arrested. But one police official said Wallace had a
friend with him who had a cell phone. The police allowed the friend
to contact Wallace's lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Although Wallace was vocal in his anger toward the police
department, Biegel said they had not received a complaint from
Wallace about the way his situation was handled.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Wallace wants to make a complaint, he can lodge a
complaint,'' Biegel said. ``He hasn't contacted us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
