<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLANDERS-BRUINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISLANDERS' LUONGO BLANKS BRUINS TO EARN HIS FIRST SHUTOUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JENNY KELLNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ It was a month ago that Roberto Luongo stepped
off the Islanders' flight in Boston, not knowing when he would make
his first start in goal. And it was not until Luongo had eaten
breakfast when Coach Butch Goring told the 20-year-old rookie, who
had been called up six days earlier to replace the injured backup
Wade Flaherty, that he would make his National Hockey League debut
against the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   Since that day, Nov. 28, Luongo has gone from being a highly
regarded prospect to his current status as the Islanders' premier
goaltender in the aftermath of Felix Potvin's trade to Vancouver
and Flaherty's season-ending shoulder injury.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, before a crowd of 9,644, Luongo stopped 34 shots
as the Islanders defeated the Bruins, 3-0, to win consecutive games
for the first time this season. The Islanders (9-19-5) are 3-1-1
over their last five.
</P>
<P>
   Mats Lindgren scored the first goal for the Islanders 38 seconds
into the second period. After Mariusz Czerkawski made a steal at
midice, he spun 360 degrees before putting the puck onto Lindgren's
stick to set up the goal for a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders went up by 2-0 at 11 minutes 55 seconds of the
second period when Bill Muckalt, one of three players acquired in
the Dec. 19 trade for Potvin, picked up the rebound of Gino
Odjick's shot from the left side of the net and put it past Robbie
Tallas for his fifth goal of the season and first as an Islander.
</P>
<P>
   Niklas Andersson scored his third goal of the season at 15:28 of
the third period, unassisted, to put the game out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   As he had been in his debut, Luongo was steady and sometimes
spectacular. He was also lucky, when Darren Van Impe's hard shot
late in the second period went over his glove and clanked off the
right post.
</P>
<P>
   In his debut, Luongo had stopped 43 shots, a franchise record
for saves by a rookie in his first start, in the Islanders' 2-1
victory. He also had become only the fourth goaltender in the 90s
to stop 40 or more shots in his debut.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very special,'' said Luongo, who is 3-4-1 since being
called up from the Lowell Lock Monsters of the American Hockey
League. ``I'll remember it the rest of my life. But I try not to
dwell on the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Luongo, who was the highest-drafted goalie in league history
when the Islanders picked him fourth over all in 1997, launched his
career as the team began a prolonged skid. After the victory in
Boston, the Islanders went nine games without a victory before
defeating the Devils, 5-3, with Luongo stopping 46 shots Dec. 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's mentally a lot better than I first anticipated,'' Goring
said. ``Roberto has impressed us in a lot of ways, but he still
needs to work on a few areas. But he's shown that he's going to be
a big part of this franchise's future. You have to remember we have
Kevin Weekes as well. He has some very good skills as he showed
against the Rangers, where he was excellent. We're not going to let
Roberto go the whole way this season. Both guys are going to get
their playing time and they'll develop.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
