<DOCNO> NYT19991227.0431 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-27 23:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0494 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR &LR;      12-27 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1999 Special for The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is Anne Stephenson's New &AMP; Notable book-review column:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
``PILGRIM'' &QL; 
By Timothy Findley (HarperCollins, $25) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This fascinating novel should bring a whole new audience to its
Canadian author. Findley's story begins in 1912, two days after the
sinking of the Titanic, when a man named Pilgrim hangs himself from
a tree in the garden of his London house. A doctor pronounces him
dead, but a few hours later his heart begins to beat again. It is
Pilgrim's dilemma and curse: He cannot die. He refuses to speak
after this latest of several suicide attempts, so his dear friend,
the enigmatic Lady Sybil Quartermaine, takes him to a psychiatric
hospital in Zurich in the hopes that he might be inspired once
again to embrace life. At the hospital, he comes into the care of
psychologist Carl Jung, who discovers in Pilgrim's journals the
secret of his private agony. Pilgrim has been alive forever. He has
seen feast and famine, the Italian Renaissance, all of the wars
ever fought. He has known Leonardo da Vinci (who is portrayed in
Pilgrim's journals as a tormented brute whose ``Mona Lisa'' has an
ugly secret behind it), Saint Teresa of Avila, Auguste Rodin, Oscar
Wilde and other luminous characters. He is weary of the human
condition, and he wants to die. It's up to Jung to decide: Is
Pilgrim delusional, or do his journals recount what really
happened? Findley mixes fact with fiction, presenting it with such
sure-footedness that we read it as true believers. Pilgrim's story
is not the only one here. There's the complex relationship between
Jung and his wife, Emma; the competitive interplay between doctors
at the hospital; the touching loyalty of Pilgrim's valet, Forster;
and the fate of Lady Quartermaine (the only episode that takes a
wacky turn in this otherwise elegantly imaginative novel). Findley,
a former actor, writes with intelligence and an instinct for
entertainment. His book is a dazzling start to the new year. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``THE COLLECTIBLE GI JOE'' &QL; 
By Derryl DePriest (Running Press, $19.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not being well-versed in Joe's history, New &AMP; Notable was
shocked to see photos of him in the early 1970s, when he had
``Life-Like Hair and Beard'' (as the toy company called it) and
looked vaguely like a Chia Pet. No matter. We were in our
anti-military phase then, and even though the hairy figures were
meant to be conciliatory _ they wore dog tags that looked
suspiciously like peace medallions _ no one was buying GI Joes.
Today, Joe is a nostalgic icon for lots of former little boys. They
will love this book, and so will their own kids. Some lucky guy
sure had fun staging the photos, dressing the Joes in their
camouflage ensembles, posing them around their pup tents, arranging
their weapons, connecting their parachutes and squeezing them into
their little scuba suits. There's even a picture of the rare
Bulletman, a failed attempt to inject a superhero element into GI
Joe, and of another failure (today, she's worth a mint), the 1967
GI Action Girl Nurse, who looks lost amid all this implied
testosterone. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``THE MODEL WIFE'' &QL; 
By Arthur Ollman (Bulfinch, $65) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ollman looks at marriages that also have been photographic
collaborations, with wives serving as ongoing subjects for their
husbands' cameras. You've seen some of these photographs before _
Edward Weston's images of his young wife, Charis; Alfred
Stieglitz's of the angular Georgia O'Keeffe; or Harry Callahan's
innovative shots of his willing Eleanor. But consider the work of
Seiichi Furuya, which shows Christine Gossler as a happy young
woman when they married in 1978, then follows her as she descends
into mental illness. In 1985, she jumped from the top of their
nine-story apartment building. Furuya had come up to look for her,
and he made a photograph of her body on the ground below. That
image, which is almost unbearable to see, is here in miniature,
part of a contact sheet that also includes shots taken before her
death and later from the ground, as her body is covered with a
blanket and guarded by a police officer. Contrast these with Baron
Adolph de Meyer's glamorous portraits of his wife, Olga (he was a
homosexual and their marriage was thought to be chaste _ Olga was,
Ollman writes, his ``passport to credibility and social
acceptability'') or with Nicholas Nixon's intimate, affectionate
photos of Bebe, his wife of 27 years. In the end, this book is as
much about marriage as it is about photography. The images, Ollman
says, ``represent some of the deepest, most passionate
announcements the photographic lexicon allows.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This work is about personal exposure. This is where the camera
shoots in both directions.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
``O.K. YOU MUGS'' &QL; 
Edited by Luc Sante and Melissa Holbrook Pierson (Pantheon, $24) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This odd little anthology sheds some light on what is, if you
think about it, an odd little group. The subject is character
actors, those people who have appeared in film after film until the
familiarity of their faces becomes part of their effect as actors.
Among them: Warren Oates, Timothy Carey, Dana Andrews, J.T. Walsh,
Dan Duryea, Thelma Ritter, Nick Adams, Wallace Beery, William
Bendix, Ralph Bellamy and Leo G. Carroll. They are, Sante and
Pierson say, ``the screen's ordinary Joes, those who therefore
render themselves extraordinary.'' Why, then, have they included a
rogue essay on Elizabeth Taylor, hardly an ``ordinary Joe''? She is
one of those actors, Sante and Pierson say, ``who, with a talent
for reversal, manage to render themselves ordinary by their
insistent wanderings through the realm of the personal.'' We'll
take their word for it. Contributors include Greil Marcus, Mark
Rudman, Chris Offutt and John Updike, who tells of his love for
Doris Day in his much-anthologized 1983 essay, ``Suzie Creamcheese
Speaks.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anne Stephenson is a freelance writer. You can reach her at
amstephenson(at)worldnet.att.net, via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
