<SLUG> BC-HOSPITALS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALLEY FLU-MERGENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By HEATHER ROMERO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A nasty strain of the flu has invaded the Metro Phoenix area,
flooding emergency rooms and forcing many hospitals to send
patients elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just got bombed,'' said Deb Howard, Desert Samaritan
Medical Center's assistant emergency department director.
</P>
<P>
   The Mesa hospital, as well as several others across the Metro
Phoenix area, set records Sunday for numbers treated in the
emergency room. The flu-stricken crowds forced at least six Valley
hospitals to close their emergency rooms Sunday and Monday and
reroute incoming patients to other hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like it's pretty bad this year,'' Lora Dosh,
Thunderbird Samaritan Medical Center assistant emergency room
director, said Monday afternoon. She noted that the hospital was
diverting patients again, after doing so for nearly three hours
during the morning.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital also ran out of space, which caused a backup in the
emergency room with patients who were admitted and waiting for
rooms, Dosh said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times they're sitting in the ER for 12 to 24 hours,''
she said. ``We're having to learn how to be floor nurses as well as
ER nurses.''
</P>
<P>
   Hospital officials urged people to visit their family doctors
first and use emergency rooms as a last resort.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency room visitors can expect to wait an average of two
hours, although a four-hour wait was not unheard of Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people can be frustrated with a wait, but they don't know
that through the ambulance entrance two or three people could have
come in with a heart attack or internal injuries,'' said Kay
Sperduti, Scottsdale Healthcare spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Outside that Scottsdale emergency room Monday, Dale Duckworth,
57, waited for his name to be called.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been through so many boxes of Kleenex,'' the Scottsdale
man said. ``It's not fun stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   But he was unperturbed by the wait, saying the alternative was
to lie in bed miserable.
</P>
<P>
   At Desert Samaritan in Mesa, Penny Bylina rocked her 7-month-old
son in a pediatric emergency room. Baby Jordan had red, puffy eyes,
fever and a nasty cough, and snuggled close to his mother, seeking
relief from his first case of the flu.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctors are full and we couldn't get him in until
tomorrow,'' said Bylina, 34, of Apache Junction, explaining why she
brought him to the emergency room. ``He's been like this since
Christmas Eve.''
</P>
<P>
   Desert Samaritan treated a record 319 people Sunday in its
emergency room. It normally handles about 230 a day. Scottsdale
Healthcare Osborn also set a record Sunday, treating 182 patients,
compared with its average of 110 to 120 a day.
</P>
<P>
   Sperduti said the flu strain seems particularly nasty this year
and has worsened patients' suffering.
</P>
<P>
   ``They feel so horrible,'' she said. ``They feel like they're
going to die and think: What if this isn't the flu?''
</P>
<P>
   So they flock to the emergency room.
</P>
<P>
   Because influenza is caused by viruses that infect the
respiratory tract, antibiotics are not an effective treatment. The
treatments prescribed most are ones that ease the symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mark Rudinsky, an epidemiologist at Good Samaritan Regional
Medical Center, said most influenza cases he's seen so far are of
the Type A strain.
</P>
<P>
   Influenza viruses are divided into three types, A, B and C,
according to the Web site of the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention in Atlanta. Types A and B cause upper respiratory
symptoms and are responsible for the outbreaks that occur almost
every winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``About every nine or 10 years a brand new strain develops that
might not be in the vaccine. That does not seem to be the case so
far this year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's the good news.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news: He predicts it will get worse before it gets
better.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really the beginning of this year's cases,'' he said.
``We'll probably see it for at least another month or two.''
</P>
<P>
   And emergency room workers, often battling their own cases of
the flu, also fear what's ahead: Y2K. But it's not the computer
glitches or power failures they fear. It's the people hazards.
</P>
<P>
   New Year's Eve traditionally brings people injured in drunken
driving accidents and gunshot victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Added on to the flu, it's going to be really busy,''
Thunderbird Samaritan's Lora Dosh said. &QL; 
Heather Romero can be reached at &QL; 
heather.romero(at)arizonarepublic.com or at (602) 444-7981. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
