<SLUG> BC-MANN-THEATER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANN CHAIN AGREES TO SALE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Jason Takenouchi 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- WestStar Cinemas Inc., the bankrupt owner of the
Mann Theatres chain, has agreed to sell its theater holdings for
more than $91 million to WF Cinema Holdings LP, a limited
partnership affiliated with Time Warner Entertainment Co. and
Viacom Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The sale will be completed by Jan. 31 unless another bidder tops
WF Cinema's offer. If a competing bid is received before Jan. 4 the
deadline set by U.S. District Court Judge Joseph J. Farnan Jr.
WestStar's holdings will be auctioned off on Jan. 11.
</P>
<P>
   Encino-based WestStar operates 53 Mann theater complexes in
Colorado and California, including the landmark Mann's Chinese
Theatrein Hollywood. Other area locations include the Plant 16 in
Van Nuys, the six-screen Agoura Mann, the Village 8 in Westlake
Village, the eight-screen Janss Marketplace in Thousand Oaks, the
seven-screen Mann in Valencia and the 10-screen Exchange in
Glendale.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Skislock, an entertainment analyst with Irvine-based
Laguna Research Partners, said several theater companies may be
interested in purchasing the 351-screen Mann chain despite ongoing
concerns over its aging inventory of theaters. One potential
suitor, Pacific Theaters of Los Angeles, said earlier this year
that it had offered to buy Mann.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a very aggressive, very rapid consolidation going
on,'' Skislock said.
</P>
<P>
   Owning the Mann chain could also benefit studios such as Warner
Bros. a unit of Time Warner as they struggle with a
rapidly-consolidating theater industry that is seeking a bigger
share of box office revenues, Skislock said.
</P>
<P>
   WestStar purchased the Mann chain in 1997 from a partnership
that included Warner Bros. and Paramount Studios. Since the
purchase, WestStar has lagged behind its competitors in the
construction of larger megaplexes that now dominate the theater
market. Its only Southern California megaplex is the Plant 16 in
Van Nuys.
</P>
<P>
   The company filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection in
September amid speculation that some underperforming theaters could
close. WestStar officials declined to comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed deal with WF Cinema, WestStar would receive
$46 million up front and another $45 million by Oct. 15, according
to court documents. WF Cinema also would have to take on several
financial obligations, including any sales taxes paid in connection
with the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Viacom and Warner Bros. are listed as the guarantors of the
arrangement, and WF Cinema's mailing address is in care of Warner
Bros. in Burbank.
</P>
<P>
   WF Cinema's $91 million offer is far below the replacement cost
of Mann's 351 movie screens, according to Skislock, the
entertainment analyst. Excluding land costs, construction of new
movie theaters currently runs about $500,000 per screen, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The relatively low purchase price for Mann reflects the
continuing competitive troubles for older theaters including many
Mann theaters as larger, more spacious multiplexes open up across
the country, Skislock said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customers are showing a tendency to gravitate toward the newer
theaters,'' he said. ``It's a risky business buying existing
theaters.''
</P>
<P>
   Any competing buyer will have to bid at least $95 million for
the Mann chain, including $50 million up front, according to the
judge's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
