<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBAL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERBALS' DANGERS IGNORED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KELLY PEARCE  
 and RANDY CORDOVA  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The word is getting around about furanone di-hydro and other
herbal supplements, but coaches and health officials fear it's the
wrong one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids only hear what they want to hear,'' said Ken Jackmann, a
registered nurse at Maricopa Medical Center who has been
weight-training for eight years.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not going to hear that Tom Gugliotta had a seizure
after taking this. They're going to hear that he took it, and that
makes it OK.''
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration has documented one death and
more than 50 adverse effects tied to furanone di-hydro, which
Phoenix Suns forward Gugliotta acknowledged ingesting before
suffering a seizure Dec. 17.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, a 16-year-old Peoria boy collapsed during a
gym class at Centennial High School after taking Verve, one of
several brand names containing furanone di-hydro, which claims to
enhance sleep and help muscles rebuild.
</P>
<P>
   Herbal supplements, which aren't regulated by the FDA, are
available over the Internet and in some health stores, and they're
advertised in magazines. There's also plenty of word-of-mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Americans spend about $4 billion a year on herbal supplements
such as saw palmetto, ginseng and others that promise to do
everything from ease depression, shrink swollen prostates and fight
colds.
</P>
<P>
   A 1997 survey by ``Prevention'' magazine reported that 60
million adults use herbs to treat illnesses. Forty-one percent of
Americans learn about herbal remedies through friends and family,
the No. 1 source of information.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been some members who have asked about it,'' said
Patrick Holloway, a fitness director at the Central Park Square
Athletic Club. ``But it's really nothing to be toyed with. The
danger of it isn't really stressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Although they may be well-intentioned, many who use the compound
don't understand what they're getting into, said Richard Thomas,
director of the Samaritan Regional Poison Center. Sometimes,
appropriate dosages are unclear and different bodies can react
differently to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're looking for any way you can to get an edge,'' Thomas
said. ``Just look at Mark McGwire.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Major League Baseball's home-run star acknowledged
using androstenedione, a testosterone-producing pill that's legal
in baseball but banned in other sports.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the recent publicity over furanone di-hydro results in
the supplement being pulled from the market, these things tend to
be cyclical, Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the poison center received 75 calls from people who had
taken gamma hydroxzybutyric acid, which in various forms has been
sold as a muscle builder and aphrodisiac.
</P>
<P>
   It has been outlawed, Thomas said, but the trend seems to be
that once a substance is made illegal, another one like it takes
its place in the legal world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think it's unfortunate that we still have the mentality
that if it's over the counter and a natural product that it's got
to be safe,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   George Toro, herb department manager at Gentle Strength
Cooperative in Tempe, says herb shoppers must be savvy shoppers.
Scrutinize the labels, he advises.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because something is a natural herb doesn't mean it's
safe,'' he said, adding that his store doesn't stock Verve or other
supplements he calls extreme.
</P>
<P>
   At Advanced Health &AMP; Wellness Center in north Phoenix, customers
are encouraged to undergo an assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to teach you so you can walk out of here and start to
take control of your health,'' said Vimal Patel, a pharmacist and
clinical nutritionist. ``There is no magic pill.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the center is across the street from Paradise Valley
High School, students stroll in and ask about herbal supplements.
He discourages them, because teenage bodies produce an abundance of
hormones.
</P>
<P>
   At Horizon High School in Scottsdale, football coach Doug
Shaffer, who also works with players in the weight room, hasn't yet
heard of herbal supplements among his charges.
</P>
<P>
   However, last year, half his team was taking creatine, similar
to the substance McGwire took. This year, it has fallen out of
favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes in cycles,'' Shaffer said. ``I don't push these
things. It's scary. There's not enough background on them, like
what it does to your body in the long run.''
</P>
<P>
   A sampling of coaches and players across the Metro Phoenix area
revealed that many had heard about herbal supplements, but few
thought they were being used at their schools. However, some of the
youngsters have tried other things.
</P>
<P>
   Marcos de Niza High School senior Eddie Carrillo says he took
creatine for six months before football season this fall and saw
results, not problems. But he has steered clear of herbal
supplements because he doesn't know enough about them.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're an athlete, you want to do better and get
bigger,'' the 18-year-old said. ``If you really want to take that
stuff (herbal supplements), make sure you know all about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Quint Swanberg, a gridder and wrestler at Horizon, has dabbled
in creatine as well as St. John's wort, to give him a mental boost.
</P>
<P>
   However, ``I think you should rely on your own performance,
genetics and all that,'' the 18-year-old senior said.
</P>
<P>
   At Mountain Ridge High School in Phoenix, football coach Jim
Ewan asks his students to tell him if they are using any
supplements so he can monitor their intake. However, if they see
the pitfalls of the products, including what happened to Gugliotta,
they might pause.
</P>
<P>
   ``The negative side can help to educate kids that these are
hazardous,'' Ewan said.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Farrell, football coach at St. Mary's High School in central
Phoenix, has a simple philosophy about ``the edge.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're looking for something beyond hard work, you're going
in the wrong direction,'' he said. &QL; 
Kelly Pearce can be reached at &QL; 
kelly.pearce(at)arizonarepublic.com. or at (602) 444-8979. &QL; 
Randy Cordova can be reached at &QL; 
randy.cordova(at)arizonarepublic.com or at (602) 444-8096. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
